<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE MAN AT MICROSOFT; OR HOW HIGH THE MOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an Editorial Observer for Saturday,
Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, the value of Bill Gates' Microsoft holdings reached
roughly $100 billion. That is a very round number, so round, in
fact, that it would take an American earning the approximate median
income _ $50,000 a year _ 2 million years to equal it. Or, to put
it another way, it would take 2 million Americans earning the
median income to raise the same sum in a single year. It is hard to
see a man when he is surrounded by the corona of that much wealth.
It renders his personality, dark in the best of us, more than
usually opaque and hard to read. It makes Gates, the mere man, an
ironic figure who, no matter how modestly he carries himself, is
always being mocked behind his back by the golem of his wealth.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article, Newsweek portrayed Gates as a scarcely
credible figure plagued with his own brilliance. But the article
also suggests the infantilizing behavior Gates has had to put up
with as his fortune has grown, the sly attention with which people
watch him wherever he appears, waiting to see if he laughs or howls
or lights up with paternal joy when a baby is flung into his arms _
or a pie into his face. Whatever dignity he once may have had his
money has taken from him.
</P>
<P>
   The question $100 billion raises is not ``Does he deserve it?''
but ``Did he intend to earn it?'' Gates has been described as
fiercely competitive, a phrase that, in the '90s, has become the
blandest of compliments. Fiercely competitive does not quite cut it
as a modus operandi for becoming the richest person in the world.
Luck, the ungovernable role of circumstance, has had its way with
this man, and the disparity between intention and chance is one
source of the mystifying air that seems to surround him.
</P>
<P>
   To all appearances Gates is no swashbuckler, though the Justice
Department, in its suit against Microsoft, has argued strongly that
corporate swashbuckling, beyond the limits of the law, was a
frequent occurrence at the Microsoft campus in Redmond, Wash. The
Justice Department suit has done real damage to Gates' chosen
public role of techno-visionary, but it was damage of a kind that
tended merely to confirm what many in the computer industry had
long felt. Microsoft is now another word for ubiquity, and ubiquity
casts a wide shadow.
</P>
<P>
   It is still too soon to tell what effect Gates' philanthropy
will have on his public image. His recent gift of $6 billion, the
largest philanthropic gift ever, places the assets of the Bill and
Melinda Gates Foundation at $17.1 billion, second, temporarily,
only to The Wellcome Trust at $19.2 billion. The Gateses have given
$16 billion to their foundation since January. According to The
Chronicle of Philanthropy, the Gates Foundation will have to give
away $2.3 million a day next year just to meet the federal
requirements that govern private foundations. It will be tempting
to try to read the man in the causes he supports. But that will be
no easier than trying to read him against the domineering edifice
of Microsoft or against his 1 billion shares of Microsoft stock.
Some things are larger than character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
