<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SMART-MICE-NYT &LR;      09-04 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SMART-MICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SMART MICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   The report that scientists have created a smarter strain of mice
by inserting extra copies of a particular gene into fertilized
mouse eggs is a neat technical advance with perplexing
implications. When put through a battery of tests, the mice with
the inserted genes turned out to have superior ability in learning
and memory compared with normal mice. They were better able to
remember the location of a submerged platform, recognize the shape
of objects they had seen before, and associate tones with electric
shocks administered at the same time. The differences were not huge
_ these are no Einstein mice _ but they were measurable.
</P>
<P>
   What the new findings will mean in the long run is uncertain.
Humanity surely has no need for smarter mice _ they are wily enough
already _ so the applications in mouse improvement are apt to be
limited. The next step may well be to experiment with other
mammals, a prospect that opens up some disturbing possibilities.
What if scientists succeed in making chimpanzees smarter than they
already are? Will our vaunted intellectual superiority over other
primates erode to the vanishing point? That could indeed pose a
quandary for the Kansas Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, of course, is whether scientists will be able
to boost human intelligence or at least repair faulty memories
through genetic engineering or new drug therapies. The scientists
who did the mouse study say such gains should eventually be
feasible, but practical results could be years away. At this point,
no one knows whether humans will react the same way as mice, or
whether this particular genetic manipulation is the key to such a
multi-faceted trait as intelligence, or whether manipulating these
genes in humans might cause grave damage in the brain from
unexpected side effects. Such issues will need to be addressed
thoroughly before proceeding _ using, alas, the pokey old brains
that have been given to us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 0011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
