<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: INTRUSIONS ON ELECTRONIC PRIVACY  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   In trying to prevent criminals from using new electronic
technologies in illegal activities, the Clinton administration has
been deaf to the privacy concerns of law-abiding citizens. The
Justice Department argues that electronic surveillance by the
government would hurt only those involved in crime, not the
law-abiding citizen. But erosions of privacy affect all Americans.
As more people use computers and new technology to communicate and
conduct business, balancing the need to protect electronic privacy
against law enforcement requirements is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent examples show the administration's failure to achieve
a good balance. The Justice Department has drafted legislation that
would authorize federal law enforcement officers, with
court-approved warrants, to secretly enter a suspect's home or
office to disable encryption programs on their personal computers
or install devices that can allow investigators to read the
encrypted text. The intent is to thwart the ability of criminals to
conceal information. But the threat to civil liberties may become
substantial as encryption on personal computers becomes common.
</P>
<P>
   Under current wiretap law, law enforcement agencies can seek
court authorization to tap phone lines or to place hidden
microphones in private buildings. More than 1,000 wiretaps are
approved by courts annually, though requests for warrants to use
hidden microphones are rare. Civil liberties groups are worried
that surreptitious entry would become far more common if the
disabling of encryption were to become standard practice whenever a
suspect is thought to use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Federal Communications Commission, at the urging
of the Justice Department, adopted new rules making it easier for
law enforcement agencies to monitor the movement of callers using
cellular phones. The regulations require that phone companies be
capable of providing general location information at the beginning
and end of any cellular call under surveillance with a court order.
Turning cell phones into tracking devices is an unwarranted
expansion of surveillance power.
</P>
<P>
   The new requirements would also give government agents the
ability, applying to both cell phones and ordinary phones, to
continue monitoring conference calls even after the surveillance
target drops off the call and allow them to determine whether a
suspect is using features like call forwarding and call waiting.
Each of these changes may appear limited in scope. But taken
together, these policies unduly erode privacy protections in the
electronic realm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
