<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-04 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
One giant leap for humankind
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Gender equality is still a joke. All you have to do is peruse
the Comets' parking lot. There's hardly a Benz or a Bimmer in the
bunch. Probably half the Rockets own cars that cost more than
Cynthia Cooper, the world's finest women's basketball player, pulls
down in a year.
</P>
<P>
   But progress is progress nonetheless. Women's sports _ make that
women's team sports _ have arrived this golden summer, more than a
generation after Title IX forced a measure of fairness upon us.
First, the U.S. soccer team filled Giants Stadium and the Rose Bowl
en route to its dramatic world championship, creating a genuine
hysteria in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Comets, on the brink of a three-peat in the WNBA, have
shown us exactly how tough, resilient and marketable lady jocks can
be.
</P>
<P>
   When little boys come to games wearing Kim Perrot's jersey, you
almost start believing humankind eventually will get it right.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, 40 minutes shy of being called a dynasty themselves,
aren't the old Chicago Bulls. Coop isn't Michael Jordan. They don't
play way above the rim _ but they don't have to, either, to have
proved, beyond any reasonable doubt, they are made of the same
right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Not better stuff, mind you. Just the same stuff. A professional
athlete is a professional athlete, regardless of the size or shape
of the package he or she comes in. A great middleweight boxer is no
less deserving of respect than a comparable heavyweight, is he?
Pound for pound, so to speak, the Comets are every bit as worthy of
adulation as the Bulls. And perhaps, under these saddest of
circumstances, even more so.
</P>
<P>
   For the Comets to be one victory from another title after what
they've been through the last few weeks makes a powerful statement.
We can't say how a men's team would have coped with the Perrot
tragedy because no men's team ever had to confront the death of a
beloved, highly valued teammate just as the playoffs were about to
get under way.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? Should the Liberty players, perish the
thought, roar back and steal two from the champs on their own
floor, that would make an equally powerful statement about the
strength of their character and will. No matter what happens over
the next 48 hours, it's going to be a win-win deal for the WNBA and
women athletes everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Image-wise anyway, if not financially. In time, though, the
money might come, too. Women CEOs are just now starting to pull
down the seven-figure salaries. And, probably not coincidentally,
it seems most women CEOs played some sort of a team sport when they
were young.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Billie Jean King, then the world's best female tennis
player and arguably sport's most ardent pioneering feminist, told
Sports Illustrated's Frank Deford: ``It really doesn't matter how
much I do, or what Chris Evert does, or Peggy Fleming. Until women
have a successful professional team game, we'll always be
second-class in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean, Mother Freedom, has to be smiling today. There's
nothing second-class about the Comets, whose two-going-on-three
championship banners are tapestries made of discipline,
cooperation, camaraderie, sound basketball fundamentals and no
small amount of God-given ability.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they got game.
</P>
<P>
   Professional also implies adult. Most of the soccer players were
women, not girls. A couple had kids of their own as, of course,
does the Comets' Sheryl Swoopes. And Cooper is 36 years old. You
don't look at Coop and think how cute and huggable she is. Instead,
you see a crafty, battle-tested, take-charge, no-bull leader. You
see someone you want in the foxhole beside you.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Thursday night, she did unto the Liberty what
Jordan always did unto his overmatched rivals. Coop grabbed the
game by the neck and made it hers. She would not let the Comets
even contemplate defeat as an option. We can count on more of the
same from her in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-pubescent gymnasts and ice skaters and teen-age tennis
queens have in some ways hindered our perception of female
athletes. When a sport is dominated by a child or a childlike
person, it's easy to dismiss it as child's play. But there's no
mistaking that the ``W'' in WNBA really does mean woman.
</P>
<P>
   And winner, too. The 3-year-old league offers superb value and
entertainment for male and female fans. The novelty aspect has
mostly worn off. For the regular customers, the real Comets
crazies, it's about the hoops now, nothing else, the same as
watching the Rockets. The Comets might be women, but they are
ballplayers first and foremost.
</P>
<P>
   We have at least come that far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
