<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE PINS HOPE ON N.H. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES AND CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to salvage his foundering campaign, GOP presidential
hopeful Dan Quayle will pour much of his total effort into winning
the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who recently took a licking in the Iowa Straw Poll and
has been stumbling in other statewide and national polls, said
recently he's reshuffling his effort to highlight the Granite
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next couple of months, I'm going to focus on New
Hampshire because I feel if I can win New Hampshire, then I've got
a decent chance of winning the nomination,'' Quayle told ``The
Arizona Republic.'' ``We're going to be spending a lot of time up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Quayle campaign in Iowa, where caucuses in late January or
early February will be the first solid test for the candidates,
will now be mostly a grass-roots effort, said Kyle McSlarrow,
Quayle's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Staff direction and appearances by Quayle and his wife, Marilyn,
will be concentrated in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   One campaign observer said Quayle's focus away from Iowa shows
Quayle is still having trouble gaining traction on the competitive
GOP campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving Iowa smells like a measured retreat,'' said Sherry
Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at Claremont University in
California.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeffe, Quayle has been haunted by the twin demons
of a front-loaded campaign schedule and a damaged personal image.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I think the front-loading (did) was leave
Dan Quayle not nearly enough time to turn his image around,'' Jeffe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire primary, which follows the Iowa contest by a
week, now appears to be Quayle's best chance of scoring well enough
to revive his faltering fund-raising effort, McSlarrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is making several moves to breathe life into the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has moved his press secretary, Jonathan Baron, from Phoenix
to Washington, D.C., to be closer to the New England region.
</P>
<P>
   And he's preparing to rev up his rhetoric, spotlighting such
talking points as his experience in office and his support of big
tax cuts, McSlarrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle will show how he differs on the issues with other
candidates, such as Texas. Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner,
McSlarrow said, but he will not attack them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a slash-and-burn candidate,'' McSlarrow said. ``He's
not going to get personal on George W. Bush. But he is going to
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll also try to ratchet up his fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 14, Quayle suffered a debilitating defeat in the Iowa
Straw Poll, where he came in eighth among the nine candidates who
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   And he's doing poorly in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll this week by Franklin Pierce College and WNDS-TV,
Quayle garnered 4 percent among New Hampshire Republicans. The poll
had a margin of error of 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Iowa Straw Poll, Quayle had put much of his effort
into that state.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is not alone in his sharp focus on New Hampshire. Arizona
Sen. John McCain has also made a push there, recently barnstorming
through the state by bus.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is besting Quayle, however, running second to Bush in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also outdoing Quayle in South Carolina, where Quayle
has essentially folded up shop. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
