<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DOUBTERS GET ONE MORE DAY TO TAKE A REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Here's exactly what you were thinking:
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it. The Rangers are going to blow it. Lose three out of
four to the stinkin' Tigers and now the White Sox, another lousy
team in town, and everyone knows the Rangers play like spit against
bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen's showing its true colors. All that success had to
be too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hits in the clutch. Juan's chasin' those outside
breaking balls again. They can't catch a fly ball. And Oates
doesn't know whether he's comin' or goin.' Nothin' he does turns
out right.''
</P>
<P>
   That about sums it up, right? Did we miss anything?
</P>
<P>
   Relax, Doubting Thomas. Mix yourself a strong Alka-Seltzer on
the rocks and try to be cool. This is the way September is supposed
to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers dangled another potential disaster in their worried
fans' faces last night at The Ballpark in Arlington, then provided
a soothing tonic for the skeptical masses, roaring back from a 4-1
deficit to pound the White Sox, 10-4, in the opener of a six-game
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, we needed that.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, guys, but we need those continued assurances that this
isn't going to be a rerun of 1996 _ or worse _ when the Rangers saw
a nine-game mid-September lead sliced to a single game with a week
to play.
</P>
<P>
   With Oakland's hot breath still sizzling the backs of the
Rangers' necks, there's little room for a meltdown at this stage of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A's are playing well,'' conceded pitcher John Burkett, who
got himself straightened out in time to win his sixth game. ``They
look like they're going to be on our backs the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't ease the minds of the frantic (un)faithful, who have
been known to panic at the drop of a package of sunflower seeds.
Prodded by the Rangers' loss of three of four in Detroit, they've
already began moving supplies into the storm cellar. By the sound
of the e-mails, the bunker mentality is already kicking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about what the fans are thinking,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Or the media, for that matter. The fans get a
lot of their thought patterns from talk shows and other media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the fifth-best record in baseball, we're within a
couple of games of New York and Cleveland for the best record in
the league and yet we have people who think, `That's it, they're
done now,' as soon as we lose two games in a row. Eventually we'll
convince them that you don't throw in the towel until it's soaking
wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I wouldn't count on that.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me, oh dubious one, that you didn't tighten up a bit in the
seventh, when the White Sox, trailing by just a run at 5-4,
threatened against left-hander Mike Venafro, who had just come on
for Burkett. Tell me you weren't wondering why Oates wasn't waving
in a right-hander when Venafro hit Liu Rodriguez with a pitch and
Magglio Ordonez came to the plate with runners at first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Any fingernails left?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you didn't know: Oates had already told struggling
setup man Jeff Zimmerman that he was getting a couple of games off
``to regroup'' after back-to-back shellings in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he didn't touch a baseball tonight,'' Oates said.
``Besides, I liked the way Venafro was throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez, Chicago's best hitter this season, wasn't going to get
a chance to beat the Rangers in that situation. Oates ordered
Venafro to pitch around him, loading the bases for rookie
right-handed hitter Brian Simmons, who then struck out on a 2-2
fastball on the fists.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk one up for Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Venafro's gutsy performance, the Rangers broke the
game open with five more runs in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team is a very comfortable team, a very confident
team,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``We know we're going to
score runs more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody wants us to come out and score 15 runs in the
first inning but it's not that easy. There's a big-league club in
the other dugout, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If the first five months of the season have told us anything,
it's that the Rangers are a good team and probably the best in the
West. Is it still possible for them to blow it in September? You
better believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you've got to think,'' Burkett said. ``There's
still a long way to go, and we've got to win a lot more games.
We've had our rough times recently against teams we're supposed to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to remind us. Around here, long memories are the norm,
not the exception.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
