<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC GETS A CHANCE TO PROVE ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Finally, a game. No more stories about how much
quarterback Carson Palmer has improved. How the defense is better
than people think. How the freshman wide receivers will surprise
teams with their speed.
</P>
<P>
   When USC plays Hawaii tonight (9:30 p.m., PDT) at Aloha Stadium,
the Trojans will be able to release all the pent-up
enthusiasm/frustration that has been bottled up since last
December's loss to Texas Christian in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the key to this year,'' said Palmer,
already raising the stakes in a game most of the nation will sleep
through (Eastern poll voters, how 'bout that 12:30 a.m. kickoff?).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come out and explode,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are brimming with confidence, thanks to their
experience and a year under the belt with coach Paul Hackett.
Outside of these Islands, it might be hard to find someone who
doesn't think they will roll over the hapless Rainbow Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the natives are worried. Just ask new Hawaii coach
June Jones, who is inheriting a program that has an 18-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be playing USC, they're certainly a better team
than we are,'' Jones said. ``There's no question (Hackett) will put
SC back where they want to be. We're overmatched for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii fans don't feel that way. After selling just 158 student
tickets last season, tonight's game is a sellout of 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's the type of situation that makes a coach uneasy, if not
the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure they'll be excited, but we've been to Notre Dame, which
is a more hostile place,'' cornerback Antuan Simmons said. ``I
don't think it will be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett would never say that. He finds himself in the same
position as Purdue did last year when it played the Trojans in the
Pigskin Classic. A new coach with an NFL background has taken over
a program, and no one is quite sure what he will do in his first
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have (had) nothing to look at,'' Hackett said. ``They have
(had) a year to look at us.'
</P>
<P>
   What goes around comes around, but at least Hackett had talent
last season. Jones has barely scrimmaged because he is so worried
about injuries and his team's poor depth. And he has the mental
baggage of that losing streak. But even that scares Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, that streak is going to be over,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   USC's players aren't nearly as, um, paranoid. They can't wait to
take the field, because they feel this year's team is substantially
improved from last season's. They just want a forum to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about anything as long as we go out there and
play like we can,'' offensive tackle Travis Claridge said. ```We'll
be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a near-unanimous decision around USC. Palmer certainly
believes this could be an excellent venue to start the season. The
new artificial turf in Aloha Stadium had the players downright
giddy, thinking about how fast R. Jay Soward and Co. could be on a
friendly surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every advantage with turf because of our speed on
offense and defense,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   After tonight's game, USC hopes these opinions will be
validated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
