<SLUG> BC-BIRDS-SAFECO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM'S OWL `SOLUTION' TO PESKY BIRDS TURNS OUT TO BE A HOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle Mariners broadcaster Dave Niehaus thought he
had it figured out.
</P>
<P>
   The reason you haven't seen sea gulls and pigeons loitering
around Safeco Field, Niehaus told baseball fans, is because
Seattle's Woodland Park Zoo handed over a barn owl to keep a
watchful eye over the Mariners' new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one small problem.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Niehaus knows more about the infield fly rule than he
does about birds.
</P>
<P>
   First, the zoo hasn't supplied the stadium with an owl, said
Ernie Rose, a raptor keeper at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the pest control business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, he said, a barn owl wouldn't do the job. That's
because the owls feed on rodents, not pigeons and gulls.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Mariners searching for answers in what's bound
to become a problem now that they're playing outside.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, pigeons and sea gulls will discover the hot
dogs, pizza, peanuts and other goodies left behind by fans and help
themselves to a feast before workers get a chance to clean it all
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you don't want them doing their business all over
the seats,'' said Rebecca Hale, a spokeswoman with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners worry that, though the birds haven't been a
problem, it's only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a legitimate fear, says Chip Lydum, director of sports
facilities at the University of Washington in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Husky stadium has had problems with sea gulls
invading the stadium once the crowd leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have learned,'' Lydum said of the sea gulls. ``Toward the
end of the game, as the crowd is leaving, they circle the stadium
and swoop in en masse to dine on what's left.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews at Husky Stadium have placed pointed objects at some of
the pigeon's favored perching places, but that's just diverted the
pigeons to other places, Lydum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had a better idea to deter, especially the pigeons,
we'd love to hear about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, work crews simply clean up after the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Lydum sympathizes with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have six home games,'' he said. ``At Safeco, that's
different. They have 81 home games.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will the Mariners do?
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners originally asked the zoo about a peregrine falcon.
But the Mariners quickly lost interest when they learned that the
falcon was on the endangered species list at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That raised the alarming possibility that the stadium might be
barred by law from opening or closing the stadium roof.
</P>
<P>
   The peregrines have since been removed from the endangered list.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't likely to be the answer anyway, says Greg
Toffic, curator of birds at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peregrines can eat a pigeon a day _ how much of a dent is that
going to make?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   And peregrines, he said, don't eat sea gulls.
</P>
<P>
   As for Niehaus' confusion, it probably arose because of a
``sketchy'' report that a worker in recent weeks might have seen an
owl or owl's nest at the stadium, Hale said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Mariners did talk to Rose and another zoo raptor
keeper last year about trying to attract a predator to set up
housekeeping at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is at least a nugget of information there that is on the
right track,'' Hale said. ``It just kind of went off the track. I'm
not sure how that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Niehaus was not at work when the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
called Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hale said the Mariners have a meeting scheduled with the zoo
soon to talk about ways of getting raptors to take up residence at
Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose, the zoo's raptor keeper, said the zoo will be
explaining that it cannot solve the Mariners' potential problem
with sea gulls and pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   The same message was delivered last year, after Rose toured the
stadium and told the Mariners it was unlikely the stadium could
attract a predatory bird.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said he was mortified by Niehaus' mistaken suggestion that
barn owls hunt birds _ ``if it flies, it dies,'' he told fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, within the biology community, it looks like we don't know
what we're talking about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, business owners have been contacting the zoo asking for
the same service provided to the Mariners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
