<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS USE USUAL CURE, TURN ON THE POWER TO RALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ There was a time when 800 runs scored was the
mark of a good offensive team. If a team crossed the plate 800
times over 162 games, it stood a good chance of leading the league
in runs scored and reaching the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. Standards have been raised in this era of
mind-boggling numbers. So has the Rangers' offensive output.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers blew past the 800-run mark last night in their 136th
game, pounding the Chicago White Sox, 10-4, at The Ballpark in
Arlington. It was the 17th time this year the Rangers have scored
at least 10 runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're capable of scoring a lot of runs,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``When you put all those guys together, that's a
pretty good lineup. They put the pressure on the other team every
single inning. Every single inning you look up, there's a guy with
90 RBI staring you in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have scored 805 runs, second in the American League
behind Cleveland's 838. They're on pace to score 958 this season,
which would break the club record of 940 set last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another club record seemingly destined to fall is the one for
home runs. The Rangers hit four last night _ one each by Lee
Stevens, Todd Zeile, Juan Gonzalez and Ivan Rodriguez _ giving them
10 in their past three games.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves them with 195, the third-highest total in club
history. They're on pace to finish with 232, which would smash the
club record of 221, set in 1996. The Rangers' current slugging
percentage of .477 would also be a club record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously that's not our goal, to set a club record for runs
scored or home runs,'' Stevens said. ``You still have to go out and
win games. It doesn't do any good to hit two or three homers and
lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But offense gives them a chance, even when the starting pitcher
is getting battered early. Last night, John Burkett allowed eight
hits to the White Sox's first 17 hitters and trailed 4-1 in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez's 32nd home run sparked a three-run fourth off
White Sox starter James Baldwin, Stevens broke a 4-4 tie with his
career-high 22nd home run in the sixth and Rodriguez's 31st home
run got a five-run rally going in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team does a lot of things well,'' said Zeile, who homered
in the second. ``But the thing that's impressive about the offense
is how quickly we change the scope of the game, and it can happen
at any point in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, having watched this offense for four years, knows that
as well as anybody. That's why he knew he still had a chance
despite trailing 4-1 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but feel confident with the bats in those guys
hands,'' Burkett said. ``That's what I was thinking, give those
guys a chance. Get a little rhythm and get on a roll and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox found out what can happen, as if they didn't
already know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left a lot of pitches up, and they punched them,'' Baldwin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Added White Sox manager Jerry Manuel, ``Against a team like
this, when you make mistakes they do damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' mentor, the late Cal Ripken Sr., was the one who told him
800 runs should be the goal of a good offensive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a couple of years ago we visited again,'' Oates said.
``He said, `Oatesy, it's time to turn it up to 900.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They did, and, by the latest measure, the Rangers remain an
impressive offensive team.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
