<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LOSE A TOUGH ONE TO ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck McElroy was trying to tidy up Turk Wendell's
mess Friday night, trying to keep the Mets breathing in extra
innings and trying to do it against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of tense spot that gave the Mets their daily
dose of pennant fever. Bases loaded, two out, tie score, 10th
inning, McElroy facing the Colorado team that traded him to New
York five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   McElroy looked as if he might navigate through the minefield,
but one high fastball to Jeff Barry wound up destroying him and the
Mets. Barry belted McElroy's fat pitch over right fielder Roger
Cedeno for a three-run double that lifted the Rockies to a 5-2
victory over the Mets at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to nitpick with the bases loaded,'' McElroy
said. ``I just got beat with my best pitch. It was hit the opposite
way. There is nothing you can do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a distressing loss for the Mets, who wasted a decent
start by Orel Hershiser, who used six pitchers and who went 4 for
20 with men on base. So the Mets succumbed to an underachieving
team whose most important news has been that Jim Leyland, the
manager, probably does not want to manage the club next season.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Bobby Valentine scribbled ``darn'' across his desk
calendar after the Mets slipped to 4 1/2 games behind first-place
Atlanta in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was darn,'' Valentine said. ``We couldn't put an
offensive stroke together. We left guys at third. Orel did fine and
the bullpen did fine up until the end. Two runs just wasn't
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who lead Cincinnati by four games for the wild-card
playoff spot, rely so heavily on their bullpen that they look
stunned whenever the relievers struggle. Wendell pitched for just
the second time in 10 days Friday night, allowed two of three
batters to reach base against him and then complained about being
rested. The reliever said he had lost the touch on his slider and
did not feel smooth in his mechanics without consistent work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the week off killed me,'' Wendell said. ``I'm not
saying Bobby did the wrong thing. I know that there was concern
about us being tired. I was never asked if I was tired. It's
obvious I have to pitch to stay strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell delighted the fans by slamming the resin bag behind the
mound at the start of the 10th _ his signature move _ but it was
one of the few things he gave them to cheer. The quirky reliever
did not want to challenge Larry Walker, who leads the league in
hitting, and wound up walking him. Walker's athleticism also
crushed Wendell because he was savvy enough and quick enough to
scoot from first to third on Dante Bichette's looping single to
left. Wendell trudged back to the dugout and was fuming after the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing for me,'' he said. ``It's embarrassing for
the team. It's frustrating. I pitched like garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy replaced Wendell and struck out Todd Helton for the
second out. Since Vinny Castilla was 0 for 7 off McElroy, Valentine
left the reliever in the game. Castilla walked on a 3-2 pitch to
fill the bases. While the Mets' fans were excited during the tense
at-bat, that turned to exasperation when Barry, a switch-hitter who
had a higher average from the right side, batted from the right
side and slapped McElroy's first pitch to right field.
</P>
<P>
   When McElroy was asked if he knew a lot about his former
teammate, he said: ``Who? Not really. I played against him. He's up
there to swing. He did what he's supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser pitched six innings that were emblematic of one of his
starts. He permitted two earned runs on five hits while striking
out three and walking one. It never looked as if Hershiser was
stifling batters because his fastball did not exceed 85 mph, but he
stopped Colorado on one hit in six at-bats with men on base to
limit the damage.
</P>
<P>
   But, as efficient as Hershiser was, 24-year-old Jamey Wright was
much more durable over eight innings. The Mets scored in the fourth
and the fifth on run-scoring hits from Edgardo Alfonzo and Robin
Ventura, but they had runners on in six other innings against
Wright and did not score. No wonder Valentine wrote ``darn'' next
to September on his desk calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to stay there all month,'' Valentine said, which
is how long the Mets might think about this lost opportunity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
