<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SERVICE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMBERS OF UNITEDHEALTHCARE CAN'T GET COVERAGE AT HEALTH MIDWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Members of UnitedHealthcare of the Midwest
health plans can no longer receive full coverage for services at
Health Midwest hospitals and surgery centers in the Kansas City
area.
</P>
<P>
   The change in coverage, which took effect Wednesday, affects
about 184,000 health plan participants in UnitedHealthcare's
19-county Kansas City region, company spokeswoman Mary Nowotny
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowotny and Health Midwest spokesman Dennis McClatchey said
contract negotiations between the two organizations had reached a
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a series of good faith negotiations, the parties have
been unable to reach a mutually acceptable agreement, but the door
remains open,'' McClatchey said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowotny said UnitedHealthcare ``continues to seek contracts with
Health Midwest hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   The change affects six Health Midwest facilities: Overland Park
(Kan.) Regional Medical Center, Independence (Mo.) Regional Health
Center, Medical Center of Independence, Lafayette Regional Health
Center in Missouri, Surgicenter of Kansas City, Mo., and
Surgicenter of Johnson County in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   The change also may affect patients' access to doctors who have
admitting privileges at those Health Midwest facilities, unless the
doctors also affiliate with hospitals that remain in
UnitedHealthcare's network.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealthcare members have never had full access to Health
Midwest's entire network of 16 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The change affects members of all UnitedHealthcare plans,
including health maintenance organizations, point-of-service plans
and preferred provider organizations. The impact of the change
depends on which type of plan you are in. For more details, call
the company's toll-free member services number at (800) 627-0607.
</P>
<P>
   Nowotny said UnitedHealthcare members retain full access to 25
hospitals and 2,600 physicians in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Health Midwest is the Kansas City area's biggest health system.
UnitedHealthcare of the Midwest is based in St. Louis and is part
of the Minneapolis-based UnitedHealth Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
