<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-VIKINGS-NYT &LR;      09-04 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHREBET TO MISS 6 WEEKS WITH BROKEN FOOT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It was supposed to be a critical look at
a backup quarterback, but Friday night's final preseason game
turned out to be costly for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chrebet, one of the top receivers in the National Football
League, was lost for six weeks when he broke his left foot during
the Jets' 38-17 victory over the Minnesota Vikings. Chrebet was
injured when he tried to cut on the artificial turf. Chrebet, who
has never missed a regular season game in four years, limped to the
sidelines and was take to the locker room, where his parents met
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the preseason is over, glad to end on a good note, a
victory,'' coach Bill Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Parcells would not speculate on who would replace
Chrebet, it will probably be the Quinn Early, who caught 3 passes
for 124 yards, including a 79-yard touchdown and who will share
time with Dedric Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde said Chrebet was ``a little bummed out, a
little upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rick Mirer, getting a big chance to back up
Testaverde, engineered the Jets to four straight touchdown drives _
three by passes _ after entering the game in the third quarter. It
was Mirer's first Jets appearance in more than a mop-up role and,
because of his greater experience, probably solidified his position
as the club's No. 2 quarterback if Testaverde were sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who had never enjoyed consecutive winning exhibition
seasons until last year, finished the preseason with three
victories in a row, and they now have a preseason record of 10-2
under Parcells. His overall exhibition record is 45-16.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the first half Friday night the Jets' offense and
defense found themselves in rare circumstances: they were being
outplayed. The swift Vikings' defense pressured Testaverde from the
opening drive. Often, Pro Bowl defensive lineman John Randle was in
the backfield after having outmaneuvered rookie guard Randy Thomas.
Randle was incessant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Vikings' offense made its patented big play, the
type that helped set a league scoring record last season. In taking
a 10-9 halftime lead, the Vikings made the most of the Randy
Moss-Aaron Glenn mismatch. Moss is a 6-foot 4-inch, 202-pound
receiver, and a Pro Bowl player. Glenn is the 5-9, 185-pound Pro
Bowl cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Moss took full advantage of his 7-inch, 17-pound differential in
the opening quarter. As the pair entered the end zone, Moss nudged
Glenn enough to throw him off balance. Moss got in front of Glenn
and reached for, and snared, Randall Cunningham's 28-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson showed his mettle Friday night. On one play he
grabbed a Testaverde pass, was hit hard by linebacker Orlando
Thomas, lost his helmet and came up smiling. It was Thomas who had
to be helped off the field in a daze.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also missed Testaverde end-zone passes on alley-oop
plays on two separate drives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jets did get three field goals in the half from John
Hall and outstanding receptions in crowds from backup receivers
Early and Dwight Stone. The Vikings' other score of the half was
positioned after Chad Cascadden was flagged for running into the
punter. The infraction kept alive a drive that led to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer reacted quickly to his final chance as the Jets' backup
when he started the second half. He benefited from having the
first-team offensive line at his disposal. He was 2-4 on his
opening drive, but one of those was a 15-yard touchdown pass to
F-back Keith Byars that lifted the Jets to their first lead. On the
march, Leon Johnson produced a 23-yard run, but the Jets failed to
convert the 2-point attempt and led by 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   After Leon Johnson had returned a punt 42 yards, Mirer needed
only one pass to generate still another touchdown. He connected on
a 28-yarder with Stone. Then Early made a nice grab in the end zone
for a 2-point conversion and a 23-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mirer closed out the quarter by directing still another
touchdown drive that ended with a 2-yard Johnson run to put the
game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Year 3 of the Parcells era officially begins next weekend here
against the Patriots. By then, the T-shirts reading ``Start Over''
will have become collectors' items. The T-shirts were for training
camp. The starting over will have started.
</P>
<P>
   In Parcells' first year running the Jets he inherited a team in
such dire straits that he decided to come up with a motto to erase
the 1-15 record of 1996 _ along with various ghosts, myths and
negative realities about the Jets. He came up with a T-shirt that
read ``Who says we can't?''
</P>
<P>
   And they could, going 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells did not let up on the Jets in last year's preseason,
though. Following the stunning record of 1997, Parcells brought
everyone to camp and showed them the new theme: ``Take the next
step.'' All his coaches and scouts and ball boys and equipment
people wore those T-shirts. It said to the players, last year was
nice, but not far enough.
</P>
<P>
   They went 3-1, the first time in club history the Jets had put
together winning exhibition seasons. And, of course, they produced
a 12-4 regular season that brought them to the American Conference
championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
