<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T WORRY ABOUT NO. 9999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There's going to be a lot of hype next week
about the ``string of nines'' factor. Ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   Some wonk who must have looked at computer code for too long
decided a while back that the world was going to have a bad day
Thursday because the date will be 9-9-99. After all, the reasoning
goes, a string of four or six or more 9s was used by some computer
programmers to signal computers to purge a program or to shut a
program down.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is based on flawed thinking, not flawed computer
code.
</P>
<P>
   Because computers look for six numbers in the date field,
they'll read the date as 09-09-99, not as a string of nines.
</P>
<P>
   We're betting the day goes by with nary a glitch.
</P>
<P>
   However, at least three Year 2000 monitors are using Thursday as
a dry-run test of their abilities to track the bug:
</P>
<P>
   - The United Nations-backed International Y2K Cooperation
Center, a global clearinghouse for computer bug data, will rehearse
a plan aimed at keeping up-to-the-minute tabs on how the world is
faring as it enters 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Reports will be updated in real time on the center's Web site _
www.iy2kcc.org _ and ultimately will reflect information from 170
or more national Y2K coordinators. During the test, 15 countries
will take part.
</P>
<P>
   - U.S. officials will get a first look at a $40 million Y2K
Information Coordinating Center designed to give federal agencies a
round-the-clock view of potential problems. The center also will
share Y2K information with the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
   - The North American Electric Reliability Council, a trade
organization, will rehearse an emergency drill to test operating,
communications and contingency plans.
Bomb plot
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest threats looming at the end of the year comes
from those who want something bad to happen, experts say. Case in
point: Alfred Reumayr of New Westminster, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Canadian is suspected of a Y2K bomb plot. He is
charged with attempting to hire a U.S. citizen to blow up energy
supply systems in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in both countries said the man planned to have
explosives detonate at the end of the year to cover his tracks and
throw suspicion on the Y2K bug.
Tidbit
</P>
<P>
   One reader called to ask where she could find the full Y2K
sermon being distributed by the American Bankers Association that
we wrote about last week. Here's a Web site:
www.charlotte.com//banking//docs//0816sermon.htm.
Thanks for the memos
</P>
<P>
   Here's what one major Kansas City law firm is telling its
employees to do to ``minimize possible business interruptions
caused by the Year 2000 computer bug.''
</P>
<P>
   1. Schedule no depositions, conferences, conference calls or
meetings for the first week of January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   2. File any legal documents that must be filed in January before
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   3. Print and copy critical documents to a floppy disk for use
outside the firm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Take laptops out of the office by Dec. 31 to continue work
away from the firm. The firm's computer network will be shut down
from Dec. 31 to Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   5. Plan no travel for the firm for the first week of January
2000. Avoid foreign travel between Dec. 25 and Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   6. Don't rely on quick courier services.
</P>
<P>
   7. Do not leave your car in the building garage in case the card
readers or doors do not operate.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the memo. We are always looking for local stories
about what people and businesses are _ or aren't _ doing to battle
the bug. Keep those cards and letters coming.
Weapons plan scrapped
</P>
<P>
   In Orange City, Iowa, some people think the sheriff would have
done better to call upon church elders rather than people holding
permits for concealed weapons as a way to mobilize a special Y2K
reserve force.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jim Schwiesow recently sent letters to the county's 396
registered concealed-weapon permit holders, asking them to help his
department in case of Y2K emergencies. ``This would be strictly a
volunteer pool of trustworthy people that I could summon in dire
times,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Sioux County Board of Supervisors nixed the idea, saying the
county would be liable for the actions of any reserve force.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeff Sajdak, pastor of Immanuel Christian Reformed
Church, said the sheriff would have been better off calling on a
coalition of people in education, law enforcement and social
services to battle the bug ``than to find everybody with a weapons
permit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
