<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF TAX CUTS, A BOY'S BOOK AND SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ What better way to say adieu to the
traditional summer season than by allowing the readers to write
today's column and thus give Uncle Fearless the full benefit of a
long holiday weekend?
</P>
<P>
   First up is a reader with a tax-relief proposal that makes a lot
more sense than most anything else you've heard:
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (budget) surplus results from overpayment of Social
Security taxes, why not just cut the Social Security tax? That
would give all the people, poor and rich, an equal tax cut. Of
course the politicians would have to finally tell the truth about
the bogus Social Security Trust Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sensible: This would indeed be the best possible tax cut.
It won't happen, though, because Congress likes the extra money. By
the way, while you're right about such a cut being equal for all,
it would help lower-income workers more than the rich. Most
low-income workers don't benefit from income-tax relief because
they don't pay much in income taxes. They would, however, get
significant relief from Social Security cuts because this tax hits
the first dollar of income.
</P>
<P>
   The following inquiry about money management may be of interest
to others similarly situated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months ago you wrote an article in which you
referenced a book that you had read when you were a young boy
(about) the power of savings and investments. I am about to start
working with my kids on financial management (and) would like to
know the title and author.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Wondering: It has been nearly a year since I wrote about
the book to which you refer and its profound influence, not on me
but on a valued contributor. The book is The Richest Man in
Babylon, by George S. Clason.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of such matters, another reader isn't sure he's done
the smart thing by avoiding the febrile world of Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say fools rush in while greater fools watch from the
(sidelines)...When asked by friends if I've made money in the
Internet stocks, I simply respond that I'm unfortunately not smart
enough to understand their concept of value.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Cautious: Smart people know that one of the most valuable
things in the world is adequate rest, and thus manage their money
so as to ensure a good night's sleep. Meanwhile, if you're kicking
yourself for not getting rich from the dotcom craze, read some
histories of the 1929-30 market crash. These chronicles are
chockablock with stories of hotshots who got rich quick and then
got poor even quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Space is running out, so we'll wind things up with this
interesting perspective:
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, property taxes need to be abolished. ... In an
agricultural society, where the majority of the people own
property, this is a viable tax. But in the post-industrial,
information society, this tax is an anachronism.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Outspoken: My view has always been that a community's
property owners have the biggest stake in creating a local society
able to provide basic needs such as schools, public safety,
common-area upkeep, and the like. Therefore, the landed gentry
ought to shoulder the biggest responsibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
