<HEADLINE>
SQUABBLE CON TINUES OVER WILDERNESS ACRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday, the 35th anniversary of the federal Wilderness ct,
Arizona environmentalists questioned if that is enough.
</P>
<P>
   As Arizona's population doubles over the next few decades, they
say, so should the land placed off limits to roads, vehicles,
buildings and commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of wilderness epitomizes what environmental
protection is all about,'' said Martos Hoffman, executive director
of the Flagstaff-based Southwest Forest Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   For Darlene Slusher, there is no justification for preserving
more land in Arizona as wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Why, she asks, when the potentially developable private property
in Arizona makes up less than 18 percent of the state, would anyone
want to lock up more of the federal lands, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's God's plan,'' said Slusher, Arizona
spokeswoman for People for the USA, a national group that advocates
ranching, mining and timber cutting on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work with the land. We have to make it produce
something. Otherwise, why is it there?'' Slusher said.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are less cattle grazing and timber cutting than a
decade ago, she said, and it is becoming more difficult for
developers, in both rural and urban areas, to plan and build
without being challenged by their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use it, don't abuse it,'' Slusher said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's wilderness areas include the Superstition Mountains,
east of Mesa; Pusch Ridge, north of Tucson and Red Rock-Secret
Mountain, northwest of Sedona. But environmentalists find it
inconceivable that places like northern Arizona's Grand Canyon and
eastern Arizona's Blue Range Primitive Area are not part of the
wilderness system.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's coalition of 70,000 environmentalists will do an
inventory of the state in the coming months, presenting to Congress
what they hope is a scientifically defensible plan to increase the
amount of wilderness in the state by as much as 6 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean nearly 14 percent of the state would exclude any
motorized vehicles or permanent structures.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Congress is in Slusher's camp.
</P>
<P>
   No new wilderness has been added to Arizona since 1990.
Nationwide, only one wilderness area, Oregon's 20,000-acre Opal
Creek Wilderness, has been added to the National Wilderness
Preservation System since Republicans took control of Congress in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, U.S. Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., announced the formation
of a new bipartisan ``wilderness caucus'' in the U.S. Senate.
Feingold was joined by former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, the founder of
Earth Day, in pursuing a new generation of nature-savvy lawmakers _
akin to Arizona's late Barry Goldwater and Mo Udall _ who will
consider more lands for permanent protection.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the wilderness system consists of nearly 105 million
acres, or less than 5 percent of the nation. More than half of the
nation's wilderness is in isolated parts of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Wilderness Act was passed in 1964, much of the land in
Arizona was protected as wilderness for its scenic value: the tops
of mountains and the bottoms of canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, whose Forest Alliance includes more than 50 groups from
Arizona and New Mexico, said more lands should be considered for
wilderness designation because of their value as habitat for
threatened and endangered wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The fragmented parcels of wilderness do not reflect the larger
areas most wildlife species need to survive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now beginning to be concerned about preserving
wilderness . . . for its ecosystem and biodiversity potential,''
Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   It's time, he said, to connect the dots. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
