<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSSEXUAL-RESTROOM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLAINT CHALLENGES USE OF WOMEN'S REST ROOM BY MAN UNDERGOING
HORMONE THERAPY FOR SEX CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A group of women in a city engineering office
has filed a complaint with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission over whether an employee who was once a man _ but now
identifies herself as a female _ may use the women's rest room.
</P>
<P>
   The eight women in the Kansas City (Mo.) Public Works
Engineering Field Office mailed their complaint Friday to the
federal EEOC office in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether an engineering technician, who according to
the complaint has started hormonal sex reassignment therapy but has
not yet had a sex-change operation, may use the one women's rest
room in the field office.
</P>
<P>
   The women, who say the city's handling of the rest room
situation is creating an ``intimidating, hostile or offensive work
environment,'' declined to comment further Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleges that the technician worked for the
engineering division as a contract employee for five or more years
before being hired full-time this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in late 1998 or early 1999, he made it known to
several people that he was going to have a sex change operation,''
the complaint stated. ``By his own admission, he has not done so
yet and it may be quite awhile before he does.''
</P>
<P>
   The technician requested Friday not to be identified. The
technician also declined to comment, except to say: ``As far as I
can tell, everything has been adequately resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary O'Bannon, deputy director of the city's Human Resources
Department, said Friday he had not seen the EEOC complaint and
could not comment. Law Department officials could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A similar case surfaced recently in Minneapolis over whether a
school librarian, who was once named David but is now called Debra,
can use the women's rest room. Another teacher filed a complaint
with the state about having to share the rest room.
</P>
<P>
   The American Center for Law and Justice, founded by religious
broadcaster Pat Robertson, is asking the Minnesota Human Rights
Department to ban the librarian from the rest room.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Frevert, deputy director of Kansas City's Public Works
Department, said officials had met with all the employees involved
in the dispute. He said the city had tried to accommodate both
sides and was spending $30,000 to remodel the rest room.
</P>
<P>
   Frevert said the stalls were to have been made completely
private, with doors from ceiling to floor. But when he visited the
facility recently he said the doors did not reach the floor.
Frevert ordered new doors that will provide ventilation but still
make the stalls private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staff will meet with the employees as early as Tuesday
morning and let them know the doors will be replaced at full height
to provide more privacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Documents show the employee's name and gender were legally
changed on the birth certificate in May 1998, saying the employee
was transsexual and had begun living and working as a woman since
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC complaint stated that the technician began using the
women's rest room in the building, to the consternation of the
other women employees. They reported their concerns, and those of
their husbands, to their supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings with the city's law and human resources
departments, the city began the rest room remodeling. The
technician has temporarily stopped using it, but the women say that
isn't sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the females employed at that time reported that we did
indeed have a problem sharing the female facilities with an
anatomically correct male regardless of what name they went
by....If we were forced to share the rest room we would leave the
building and seek a rest room somewhere else,'' the complaint
stated. ``We requested a separate or unisex rest room be
constructed.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the field say that a transsexual's transition to
becoming a woman occurs before surgery. Many doctors require that
the patient first undergo two years of dressing the part and taking
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Most employment complaints, however, are filed by transsexuals
when they feel discriminated against, such as being told they can't
use the rest room that matches their sexual identity, said Sam
Marcosson, a law professor at the University of Louisville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
