<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VOTE-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR VOTES TO BREAK FROM INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS reaction in grafs 5-8)  (lh) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ After 24 years of brutal occupation by
Indonesia, the people of East Timor, defying a campaign of terror
instigated by the military, have voted overwhelmingly to become an
independent nation, the United Nations announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan told the Security Council that
voters in the referendum on Monday rejected by 78.5 percent a
proposal by the government of a new autonomous status within
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the totals in the voting were 344,580 against
autonomy, and thus in favor of independence, and 94,388 for
autonomy within Indonesia, which invaded East Timor in 1975 and
annexed it the next year as its 27th province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of East Timor have thus rejected the proposed
special autonomy and expressed their wish to begin a process of
transition toward independence,'' Annan said. In January, President
B.J. Habibie announced that if autonomy was rejected, Indonesia
would end its claims on the former Portuguese colony and simply let
it go free, after a generation of separatist guerrilla warfare in
which 200,000 people have died. The referendum results are not
binding, however. Technically, the referendum was a ``popular
consultation'' whose outcome would have to be endorsed by the
Indonesian Parliament at the end of the year. But most analysts
said political realities would circumscribe the Parliament's
ability to reject the outcome of the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   On television Saturday morning, Habibie said he accepted the
results of the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie called on his forces in East Timor ``to uphold law,
security, safety and public order,'' and said: ``I also instruct
the entire ranks of the Indonesian armed forces to take firm action
against all sides who attempt to sully the pride of the nation,
undermine the authority of the government and security and public
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Violence has swept through the territory of 800,000 people since
the vote. Its continuation could turn a new East Timorese state
into the scene of a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   A militia leader, Eurico Guterres, told reporters in Dili, ``We
are de- feated diplomatically, but we are not giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York, Annan said, ``What is
important is in the next couple of months that we need to ensure
security and law and order and make sure things do not get out of
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   He again called on Indonesia to ensure security in East Timor.
He said it was too early to say whether a U.N. peacekeeping force
might be needed, but he said ``contingency plans'' were under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the results are out, and the vote is clear as to what the
people of East Timor want,'' he said. ``They have spoken. I hope
that with this message the prointegrationists will realize that
they are at the end of the road and there is no need for any more
senseless violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence and fear, the successful holding of the
referendum and its unequivocal result were a heady moment of
accomplishment for the East Timorese, an impoverished and poorly
educated people who have not had control of their territory for
hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   Under Portuguese rule, they formed the least valued and least
developed part of an empire, of interest mainly to Catholic
missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   When Portugal set East Timor free in 1975, along with the rest
of its colonies, there was only a brief interlude of local disarray
before Indonesia, a new foreign power bringing a new foreign
language, again took control of the tiny region.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast with Portugal, Indonesia poured resources into East
Timor, but the bulk of the resources went to support the huge
military presence that was needed to subdue a separatist rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In Dili, East Timor's capital, the announcement of the result
Saturday morning was held in an atmosphere of intense threat as
truckloads of anti-independence militiamen, armed and organized by
the Indonesian military, set up roadblocks and took control of
access to the airport, according to residents.
</P>
<P>
   After months of promising and failing to ensure security, the
Indonesian government had made a new promise on Friday and sent
1,400 more troops from its Strategic Command.
</P>
<P>
   But the shooting, burning, killing and terror of the ragtag
militia gangs may be beyond the control even of the Indonesian
military that created them this year as surrogate spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are burning everything,'' said one of 54 U.N. officials
who reached Dili on Friday after having evacuated the southwestern
town of Maliana, which the militias have taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and witnesses said more than 12 East
Timorese had been killed since the referendum. A spokesman for the
United Nations in Dili, David Wimhurst, said that at least four
local U.N. staff members had been killed since Monday and that six
were missing.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear to what extent the violence has been centrally
controlled and organized or what its purpose is. Assuming that the
militias were the creation of the military, which has been
reluctant to cede its hard-fought battleground, they may have
rampaged beyond the control of their masters, said Jusuf Wanandi,
director of the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a
policy institute in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   But if the militias had really intended to derail the
referendum, it is notable that they did not take any of possible
high-profile actions that might have accomplished that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they would have had to do was kill a couple of foreigners
working for the United Nations to halt the referendum in its
tracks,'' said Donald K. Emmerson, an Indonesia specialist at the
University of Wisconsin at Madison. ``So why didn't they?''
</P>
<P>
   After months of intimidation and violence, the militias fell
suddenly silent on voting day, when they could have been severely
disruptive. Instead, nearly 99 percent of the registered voters
turned out in a largely peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Then the killings and intimidation were redoubled. Although the
atmosphere of threat was intense, important targets like the Dili
Museum, where the ballots were counted, were left untouched.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the United States was worried about the
possibility of an evacuation of foreigners from East Timor, the
Navy placed two ships in the South Pacific on alert, ordering them
to be prepared to move within 72 hours' notice, a military official
said. The ships, the cruiser Mobile Bay, which is off Australia,
and the cargo ship Kilauea, have helicopter landing pads and could
be used to ferry evacuees short distances.
</P>
<P>
   Although foreigners and journalists were targets of the
militias' anger and threats, most of the violence appears to
involve local hatreds over the divisive issue of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke rose on Friday once again in Dili from burning houses in
the largely pro-independence Becora neighborhood, which has been
the target of repeated militia attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are running for their lives,'' a resident told The
Associated Press by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse violence was reported from rural areas, including
reprisals against people who had helped the United Nations conduct
the referendum. In Maliana, which has been the scene of some of the
most brutal militia violence, the United Nations reported on Friday
that two of its drivers were killed overnight and that five other
staff members were missing. Thirty-three foreign and local U.N.
workers spent the night in a police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that the militias are in control,'' said
Wimhurst of the United Nations. ``The militias are running rampant
in the town, and no effort is being made to stop them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
