<HEADLINE>
SLAYING IN EAST KANSAS CITY STARTS GORE-SPATTERED CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN AND GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 76-year-old woman was slain Friday in her
home, touching off a wild foot chase through eastern Kansas City
that ended with the arrest of the alleged attacker.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half an hour and more than a mile, a man suffering
multiple stab wounds chased his assailant through afternoon
congestion down quiet residential streets. The commotion unfolded
before astonished residents, and drew in other motorists who joined
the pursuit and helped lead police to the assailant.
</P>
<P>
   The chase ended about three houses from where an 83-year-old man
was found slain Thursday. Investigators are trying to find a link
between that death and the woman killed Friday. Police are
investigating both as homicides, but have not released a cause of
death in either case, pending autopsy results.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed in either case, and police have
established no motives. Police withheld the name of the woman
killed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to police statements and witness accounts, this is
what unfolded Friday:
</P>
<P>
   Officers were summoned at 12:47 p.m. to a house on a report of a
prowler.
</P>
<P>
   As police were responding, a man who lived at the house
returned. He later told police that he found the woman dead inside,
along with an intruder, who was standing near her. The two men
struggled and continued to fight outside, where witnesses said they
saw the suspect stab the other man in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas spilled onto a road. The suspect broke free and ran
north, armed with a screwdriver for at least a portion of the
chase. The other man, who was bleeding from wounds on his chest and
head, continued the chase.
</P>
<P>
   A woman driving through the area saw the commotion and dialed
911 on her cellular phone. She drove along behind and relayed
information to police dispatchers.
</P>
<P>
   David Krantz, who was returning to his home, spotted the men
running near 11th Street and Belmont Avenue. Krantz jumped out of
his minivan to assist, leaving his frightened wife in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   After the suspect unsuccessfully banged on front doors trying to
get into houses, Krantz and the man with the stab wounds chased him
down an alley and through back yards to the 900 block of Fuller
Avenue. There, the suspect jumped into a truck traveling south on
Fuller. The suspect pleaded for a ride, but Krantz and the wounded
man yelled warnings to the driver, who stopped his truck and jumped
out.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived moments later and were directed to the suspect by
the woman with the cell phone. An officer captured the suspect as
he tried to flee over a fence in a nearby back yard.
</P>
<P>
   The stabbing victim collapsed, and at 1:10 p.m. an ambulance was
called. Police didn't think his injuries were life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz, 30, said he was going to follow the suspect, despite the
bloody wounds he saw on the stabbing victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to get too close,'' he said. ``I had a cell
phone and was just planning on calling the police.''
</P>
<P>
   At the scene of the initial call, police knocked on the door,
but there was no response. Officers broke through the chain-locked
door and found the body of the woman who lived there, sprawled
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Officers found traces of blood and other evidence that they
believed linked the suspect to the woman's death.
</P>
<P>
   Residents described the woman as a quiet and friendly neighbor
who often spoke to them as they walked past her white, two-story
bungalow. She was often seen gardening, watering her plants or
picking up litter near her front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The chased ended near the scene of another slaying just a day
earlier. On Thursday, police found the body of Frank Holcer, who
was discovered by a friend. Holcer was killed in the home where he
was born in 1915 and had lived ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Police were trying to determine whether the cases were
connected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we are looking at but it's too early for us
to speculate,'' said Officer Russ Dykstra, a police spokesman.
``There may be some parallels with that case and this one.''
</P>
<P>
   One resident said she was troubled by the killings that have
occurred near her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand this,'' said Esther Southern, who lives
across the street from the woman who was killed. ``It's been too
close to home; there's no reason for murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors living near Ninth and Fuller echoed the same concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too much for me,'' said Merlene Shaw, who watched
police gather on her corner for the second straight day. ``I think
it's time to move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
