<SLUG> BC-LABORDAY-FESTIVITIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY AREA OFFERS VARIETY OF LABOR DAY WEEKEND EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Renaissance atmosphere, oldies music and
seniors playing golf _ could Kansas City ask more of a Labor Day
weekend?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. Perfect weather in which to enjoy it all might seem
in order, as would cheap gas to get to your destination. One out of
two isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday travelers can expect to pay much higher gas prices this
Labor Day weekend than last year, with average Missouri self-serve
prices up 20 cents a gallon to $1.14, and average Kansas prices up
18 cents to $1.18.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Right, spokesman for AAA in Missouri, said a 61 percent
increase in the price of crude oil from a year ago is resulting in
higher prices at the pump. Higher crude oil prices are a result of
the decision earlier this year by the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries to reduce production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems they are sticking to their resolve,'' Right said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the weather is mostly good news. With the
exception of some heavy storms Sunday morning, the long weekend's
weather should be suitable for taking in the host of area festivals
and activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Saturday to early Sunday a storm front will move in,''
said David Beusterien, a National Weather Service meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, he said, ``it looks to be dry again, with high
temperatures around 80 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, not bad.
</P>
<P>
   Those leaving the metropolitan area will see extra officers
patrolling highways in Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Trooper Doug Alexander, public information officer with Troop A
in Lee's Summit, said Missouri troopers would be concentrating on
highways between Kansas City and the lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to have enough of a presence on the roads that
people will see us and slow down, drive more safely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Highway Patrol will be stepping up enforcement, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some additional administrative staff, who are
typically behind a desk, out handling regular patrol duties,'' said
Sgt. Mark Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol will be on the lookout for people who are
drinking and driving and those who are not using their seat belts
or proper child seats.
</P>
<P>
   Highway officials in both states said motorists should not
encounter road construction problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Interstate 70 west of Columbia, a site of recent construction
work, all lanes of traffic will be open for fans going to the
University of Missouri for its football opener this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And in Kansas, construction ``will have a very minimal impact on
holiday traffic,'' said Mick Halter, metro engineer for the Kansas
Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Holst of the Missouri Department of Natural Resources said
state campgrounds, at least in the Kansas City area, are expected
to be full. For more information on camping call (800) 334-6946.
</P>
<P>
   She added that even with full campgrounds, there is a lot
available at the parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hiking trails and beaches and beautiful picnic
areas,'' she said. ``And Watkins Mill has a fabulous museum.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the festivals and other events,
including the PGA Senior Tour's stop in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   - The second and third rounds of the TD Waterhouse Championship
golf tournament will be today and Sunday at Tiffany Greens Golf
Club. Play will begin at 8 a.m. both days. ESPN will begin its
television coverage of the event at 2 p.m. today and 4:30 p.m.
Sunday. Among the 84 senior golfers _ age 50 or older _ who have
committed to play are Hale Irwin, Gay Brewer, Bob Charles, Jim
Colbert, Don January, Jim Thorpe and Kermit Zarley.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the event are $20 per day. They may be bought at Hen
House supermarkets or at the Tiffany Greens gate.
</P>
<P>
   - The annual Renaissance Festival of Kansas City begins its 23rd
year today in Bonner Springs. The festival will run from 10 a.m. to
6:30 p.m. on weekends (including Labor Day and Columbus Day)
through Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to old favorites, such as turkey legs and wandering
minstrels, the festival this year will offer a vegetable toss and
human chess match. Admission is $12.95 for adults and $5.95 for
children ages 5-12. Children younger than 5 are admitted free.
Parking is also free. The festival is just off Interstate 70 and
Kansas 7.
</P>
<P>
   - In the heart of the city, the 1999 Spirit Festival continues
today and Sunday evening. The festival, which opened Friday, runs
from 4 p.m. until midnight both nights. It features a collection of
bands, ranging in styles from country western to Christian to
disco. A few of the names include KC &AMP; the Sunshine Band, Rick
Springfield and the Violent Femmes.
</P>
<P>
   The festival takes place around the Liberty Memorial in Penn
Valley Park. Admission is $10, although children younger than 12
and adults older than 62 get in free.
</P>
<P>
   - In Independence, Mo., Santa-Cali-Gon Days continue through
Monday on the Independence Square.
</P>
<P>
   The festival gets its name from the fact that Independence was
once the trail head for the Santa Fe, California and Oregon trails.
It's open between 10 a.m. and 11 p.m. today and Sunday, and until 6
p.m. Monday. Admission is free, although there are charges for
carnival rides.
</P>
<P>
   The festival offers music shows, arts and crafts booths,
historic re-enactments and dance demonstrations. In addition, the
festival offers contests in ice-cream eating, watermelon-seed
spitting and root beer chugging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
