<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGSELL-BEACHES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIAN TO FLOW INTO BEACHES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A little bit of the French Alps may be coming
soon to a beach near you.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Board of Supervisors is set to vote to approve a
two-year contract with Evian Natural Spring Water, making it the
``Official Bottled Water Sponsor of the Los Angeles County
Beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract includes an optional three-year extension and board
approval is expected, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For Evian, it's less about tapping into the allure of Southern
California's sun-drenched, bikini-flecked beaches, and more about
profiting from the dry climate and Californians'
health-consciousness, said Evian spokesman Michael Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no `Baywatch' fantasy going on here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   California is the largest bottled water market in the United
States, consuming one-quarter of all bottled water sold in the
country, Neuwirth said. Evian is the largest supplier of imported
bottled water in the United States and the largest bottled water
company in the world, selling 1.4 billion liters a year in 120
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' beaches, with 60 million thirsty visitors a year,
are logical places to sell bottled water, Neuwirth said. The liter
bottles of Evian, which is bottled unfiltered at the source in the
French Alps, probably will sell for around $1.
</P>
<P>
   This deal is far from a first for the county, which has long
traded off the marketing value of its beaches. Other bottled water
companies that have paid for the official title in recent years
include Canadian-based NAYA and Arrowhead Mountain Spring Water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking advantage of the popularity of our beaches,''
said John Wallace, spokesman for Supervisor Don Knabe. ``If we can
generate revenues for recreational opportunities for the public, we
need to go after those.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong approach, said Martin Schlageter of the Sierra Club.
``It's only destroying our open space and our public resources,''
he said of the proliferation of advertising on public property.
</P>
<P>
   Local governments should be pushing for revisions in tax laws
that now force them to scramble for alternative sources of
revenues, Schlageter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles County is strong and powerful and should be at the
forefront of reforming state tax laws that have starved so many
municipalities of revenues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Evian deal, the Department of Beaches and Harbors sent
out letters to 61 companies that sell bottled water and/or fruit
drinks and advertised in six local newspapers. Evian and Coca Cola
submitted similar bids but Evian offered a greater annual cash
sponsorship fee, department director Stan Wisniewski said in a
report to the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the official designation and the right to plunk
down 30 bottled water vending machines along the beach boardwalk,
Evian will pour $75,000 a year into the county's coffers. The
company also will:
</P>
<P>
   Donate 200 boards showing the time and temperature, valued at
$15,000, for the county's 155 lifeguard stations (the number
includes spares).
</P>
<P>
   Donate 50 volleyball nets, valued at $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Pay 35 percent of its gross sales revenues to the county
Department of Beaches and Harbors, a sum estimated to be at least
$10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   If the contract runs the full five years, it will be worth about
$587,000 to the county in goods and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations and business entities since the mid-1980s have vied
for the right to link their product officially to the county's
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce-based Authentic Fitness Co. signed a three-year
contract with the county in February 1998 to provide $358,000 worth
of Speedo swimsuits and volleyball nets in exchange for rights to
refer to itself as the ``official swimwear sponsor of the Los
Angeles County beach lifeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   Local Ford dealers for years have donated as many as 60 trucks
for lifeguard and youth programs. The dealers in return can
advertise the Ford trucks as the ``official vehicle of Los Angeles
County Beaches.'' This contract is still in place, Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of selling a city's or a county's name is not
unique to Los Angeles, of course. The city of San Diego has put
together a deal, which its City Council is scheduled to vote on
shortly, that would make Pepsi the city's official soft drink.
Pepsi would pay millions of dollars over the 12-year contract for
the right to install its vending machines on city property. The
value to the city will depend on the number of machines installed
but could be as high as $23.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
