<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, September 4.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LAUNDER-SWISS (Geneva) _ Swiss prosecutors probing
suspected money laundering by officials at high levels of the
Russian government have ordered Swiss banks to provide information
on two dozen Russians who may have accounts here and have frozen at
least 59 bank accounts over the past two months. By John Tagliabue.
1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SOCIALISTS (Saarbrucken, Germany) _ In this coal and
steel-producing area with a strong labor union tradition, the
conviction that Social Democracy must stand for solidarity, for
workers' rights, for the downtrodden and for a comprehensive
welfare state lives on. So strongly that the small Saarland region,
which holds a critical state election Sunday, has become an
unlikely focus of the identity crisis of Gerhard Schroeder's
136-year-old Social Democratic party and of the ideological battles
of the European left as a whole. By Roger Cohen. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-GOVS (Denver) _ As each new high-profile shooting roils the
national debate over gun ownership rights, advocates for greater
gun control are winning support from an unlikely source: Republican
governors. After several tragedies in recent years, including the
mass shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., almost
a third of the nation's 31 Republican governors have taken
positions to strengthen gun control in their states. By Michael
Janofsky. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS-NSA (San Francisco) _ A cryptographer for a Canadian
software firm, dissecting a piece of Microsoft security software,
made an unexpected find: an element in the Windows operating system
labeled ``NSAKey.'' When his discovery was made known on his
company's Web site, it set off a firestorm of Orwellian visions in
Internet discussion groups. Was the buried software component a
Trojan horse that gave the National Security Agency a hidden back
door into the world's computers? Or was it merely a Microsoft
programmer's remarkably bad choice of language in a software system
designed to protect electronic communications and commerce? By John
Markoff. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WILL-TO-LIVE (Undated) _ Proponents of a right to assisted
suicide argue that choosing death can be a rational response to
intolerable suffering, while opponents caution that inadequate
treatment for pain, depression or other conditions can color the
decision to die. Yet scientists are only beginning to investigate
what leads some patients in the grips of a grave illness to give up
the will to live. By Erica Goode. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SHUTTLE (Washington) _ The nation's fleet of four space
shuttles will be grounded at least until the end of October while
technicians continue detailed inspections that have already turned
up numerous cases of wiring damage, NASA officials say. By Warren
E. Leary. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-UHAUL (Boston) _ A national journal: Every year, right
around now, Boston finds its arteries and veins hopelessly clogged
by the bright orange bulks of what residents believe to be the
greatest convergence of U-hauls in the country. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MCAULIFFE (Washington) _ This is not the first time that
Terry McAuliffe, who so generously put up $1.3 million to help the
Clintons buy their house, has come to the aid of the First Couple.
He's their fund-raiser par excellence, raising millions for their
legal defense fund, their house in Hope, Ark., the presidential
library and Hillary Clinton's Senate race. By Richard W. Stevenson
and Katharine Q. Seelye. 1,200 words. With sidebar,
CLINTONS-HOUSE-DEAL.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-LETTER (Washington) _ Fund-raising letters
postmarked in this city have always used language that is
hyperbolic, but a recent ``urgent'' letter went beyond that. It
asked for contributions of $25 or more to help protect the United
States from a looming nuclear attack. By Don Van Natta Jr. (The
story has moved in ``w'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-RENO (Washington) _ A look at the attorney general under
scrutiny: in the glare of TV lights, she seems remarkably calm. By
Melinda Henneberger.
