<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST MARINER GOES SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was a bush league move _ literally _ and Denny
Stark knew it. On a hook in his locker at Safeco Field Friday was a
black and teal New Haven Ravens cap. When a visitor pointed it out
to him, Stark quickly disposed of the evidence, dropping the hat
behind a small locker cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old right-hander has put Class AA behind him for
now, but he's still learning big-league fashion.
</P>
<P>
   When Stark got the call to the majors on Wednesday, he was in
Binghamton, N.Y., at the end of a six-game road trip. It was a
joyous moment, but it also put Stark on the clock: The Mariners
told him he had 90 minutes to gather his things and get on a plane
for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem. Stark had been wearing jeans the whole
trip, and his first day as a big-leaguer would be a travel day,
when jeans are forbidden and jackets required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to pick up some khakis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stark called his parents and his girlfriend, then made a quick
stop at the Gap in a mall in Binghamton. He couldn't find a jacket,
but he got the khakis, got on the plane, and arrived at Comiskey
Park _ in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, who had a 2{-hour drive from their Ohio home near
the Indiana border, beat him to the ballpark. The day ended in
Seattle at 2:30 a.m., when Stark and the M's landed back home.
</P>
<P>
   It was a whirlwind day for a pitcher who didn't think he'd make
it to Seattle this year. But after throwing complete games in two
of his last three starts to finish 9-11, Stark was invited for a
late-season look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't worry too much about it,'' said Stark, whom
the M's named as one of their top six pitching prospects this
spring. ``I started out a little slow this season, but the main
thing was looking forward to the end, to start improving what I'd
done. I made great steps toward pitching better, but I wasn't
looking at a shot at the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to Seattle, though, Stark knew what he had to do
first:
</P>
<P>
   He went to Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to pick up some clothes, because most of the things I
had were dirty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HENRY HEALTHY: As expected, the Mariners activated left-hander
Butch Henry from the disabled list before Friday night's game.
After going 2-0 in four April starts, Henry had surgery to repair a
torn labrum and missed four months.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is one of two left-handers in the Mariners' bullpen;
rookie Robert Ramsay is the other. Manager Lou Piniella is waiting
to see Henry before he makes him his No. 1 left-handed option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he pitches and how he bounces back,'' Piniella
said, ``but he's ready to contribute right now.''
</P>
<P>
   BAD BREAK: To Charles Gipson, who rejoined the Mariners this
week, there was irony in the separated shoulder he suffered during
the Mariners' brawl at Los Angeles that caused him to miss almost
two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird, because I was in a lot of fights throughout my
life as a kid,'' said the reserve outfielder/infielder. ``Finally,
the one I'm not starting and I'm just trying to be a mediator in is
the one where I get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson has an option remaining for next year _ meaning the
Mariners can send him up and down as often as they like _ but
Piniella is hoping Gipson can stick as a utility player in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to look at Gipson a little bit and see how he fits
in for next year,'' Piniella said. ``I'd like to see Charlie
establish himself as a good role-type player who plays some
outfield and some infield.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: The newest feature at Safeco Field is a two-tiered
billboard on the facing of a stairwell high above right-center,
marking the countdown to Ken Griffey Jr.'s 400th home run. The top
board reads, ``Chasing 400'' and includes Griffey's picture, and
the bottom board is a running countdown of his lifetime home runs.
Griffey had 391 entering Friday night's game. ... First baseman
Mike Blowers dropped jersey No. 4 after one game, getting his old
No. 16 from first-base coach Sam Mejias. Mejias switched to No. 57.
... Second baseman David Bell had grounded into only two double
plays through Aug. 28, but hit into his second in six games Friday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
