<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS RETURNS AS YANKEES FALL TO ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The phone call will come and Scott Brosius
believes it will be soon. Cancer is ravaging Maury Brosius, the
father of the Yankees' third baseman, and over the last five days
Scott Brosius left the team to be at the bedside of his parent in
Oregon, to talk, to trade thoughts and memories, to say goodbye.
The son felt blessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad and I had the chance to say the things we wanted to say
and have the conversations we wanted to have,'' said Brosius, after
rejoining the Yankees before Friday night's game with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius found comfort in being among friends, among his
teammates, who have prayed for his family, he said, before the
Yankees lost to the Angels, 8-2, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Angels manager Terry Collins resigned, feeling
he could no longer compel his players to perform, with a month
remaining in what has been a disastrous season for Anaheim. But the
Angels _ who have played well against the Yankees _ assumed a lead
quickly, under the direction of the interim manager, Joe Maddon.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte likes to pitch without distraction. But Joe
Girardi, the catcher who usually works with Pettitte, was in New
York for the birth of his first child Friday morning, and Jorge
Posada started behind the plate and spent the early innings trying
to align thoughts and signals with his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored a run in the second, two in the third. Posada
hammered a 440-foot home run in the fifth inning, cutting Anaheim's
advantage to a run. But Mark Petkovsek pitched out of a
seventh-inning jam, striking out Derek Jeter with the bases loaded
and two out, and Mo Vaughn's two-run homer highlighted the Angels'
five-run seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed six runs in six-plus innings, with two walks
and five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius was 1 for 3 with a double; he was caught off second base
in the fourth inning, after he either lost track of a fly ball or
forgot how many outs there were.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius is soft-spoken with a Mayberry geniality, and deeply
religious. He loves baseball, but he is more suited to small towns
than to big lights; he does not enjoy the celebrity his job affords
him. After he was named the most valuable player of World Series
last fall, baseball officials shuttled Brosius from one television
interview to the next, much to his dismay. An impatient Brosius
wanted to celebrate with teammates or family, and at the first
possible moment, he broke away from the news media and met his
father in a side room at San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius was offered the usual array of off-season endorsements
and rejected them all in order to go back to Oregon. Once Brosius
retires _ he is a millionaire many times over _ he intends to stay
home to watch his children grow, and look into the possibility of
coaching baseball at a local college.
</P>
<P>
   His voice and manner were steady Friday , as Brosius sat in
front of his locker and spoke serenely with reporters about his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Brosius' colon cancer was thought to be in remission last
year, but it returned. By this spring, Scott Brosius' hope for his
father was that his pain would be diminished. They have talked
almost every night after games, conversations facilitated by the
time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Brosius watched on television as the Yankees played on the
East Coast, and before it was too late on the West Coast, Scott
would call and monitor his father's voice. Sometimes he sounded
good, his voice strong. When Scott Brosius decided to wear his
uniform pant legs high, to just below the knee, Maury Brosius told
him it was a good look. You're wearing them just the way I taught
you, the father told the son.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Brosius received a phone call from home, word
that his father had taken a turn for the worse, and General Manager
Brian Cashman and manager Joe Torre told him to take as much time
as he needed. Girardi ferried the Brosius family to the airport
and, later that day, the Yankees who meet to share in religion
prayed Scott would have time with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Brosius has found a way to be comfortable while lying in
bed, and he is coping with the pain. ``He's shown me some
unbelievable strength, battling this thing,'' said Scott Brosius.
``He refuses to take the Valium, because he wants to be alert and
be able to talk to everybody. He wants to be aware of what's going
on. He's battled to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius was at his father's home and bedside for five days
and they spoke about all the joy they had been able to share in the
last year. Maury Brosius taught his son baseball and, last summer,
he had watched Scott play an integral role for a team with the most
victories in the history of the big leagues. He was in San Diego
last October to see him round the bases jubilantly, arms and fists
outstretched after Brosius slugged the home run that all but
clinched the Yankees' championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has done some great things for us,'' Scott Brosius said,
reflecting on their time together in the last year, in the last
week. ``I'm pretty sure that going home when I did was the right
time to go, and today was the right time to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Before flying here Thursday, Brosius saw his father for the last
time, he believes. ``Yesterday was the hardest day, by far,'' said
Brosius, ``having to say our goodbyes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was glad to be around his teammates again. Brosius walked
into Edison Field Friday afternoon with Pettitte, among his closest
friends on the team, and Brosius smiled when he heard the good news
about how Girardi and his wife, Kim, had their first child, a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius and Maury Brosius spoke by phone Friday afternoon.
They will talk as often as they can, in the days to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
