<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS COME ALIVE IN WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Terry Collins was asked during a news conference
announcing his resignation Friday why he decided to leave now.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and said: ``The Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The team had lost nine in a row, and with the defending World
Series champs in town, it was safe to assume things would only get
worse.
</P>
<P>
   But with Collins watching from his home in Seal Beach, the
Angels did everything he wanted them to do all season. For new
manager Joe Maddon, the Angels got two-out hits, solid pitching and
defense and took an 8-2 victory before 35,782 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, Collins said all he wanted to read
in the newspapers today was how the Angels won. He got his wish,
even if it was too late to help his cause.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the Angels were on course to continue a
strange trend that started last season beating the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In '98, the Angels were the only team in baseball with a winning
record against the eventual World Series champs, winning six of 11.
With a victory Friday, the Angels improved to 5-2 against New York
this season, including a three-game sweep at Yankee Stadium May
11-13.
</P>
<P>
   At certain points during Friday's game, many Angels players were
off the bench and leaning over the dugout railing encouraging
teammates, a rare sight during this horrible season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels pounded out 12 of their 15 hits against Yankees
starter Andy Pettitte (12-10). Mo Vaughn hit his 23rd home run of
the season. Garret Anderson, Gary DiSarcina and Todd Greene each
had three hits. Tim Salmon and Troy Glaus had two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starting pitcher Tim Belcher (6-8) gave up two runs in
51/3 innings, striking out six, and got considerable help from the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees closed to 3-2 in the fifth on Jorge Posada's solo
homer with one out, his 12th. But New York, which lost for the
third time in four games, left the bases loaded in the seventh when
reliever Mark Petkovsek struck out Derek Jeter, who had hit safely
his first three times up.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ben Molina threw out Jeter in the first inning and Ricky
Ledee in the second trying to steal. Salmon doubled up Scott
Brosius at second base after catching a fly ball in right field in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher survived solo homers by Posada and Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Darryl Strawberry, who went 0-for-2 against Oakland
on Thursday in his first game back from colon cancer and a drug
suspension, pinch-hit in the ninth and walked.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped a streak of 14 series in which the Yankees won
the opening game, a franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Angels gave reliever Mike James, who had elbow and
shoulder surgery and has not pitched this year, his unconditional
release. Anaheim also activated outfielder Matt Luke from the
disabled list. Luke tore a muscle below his right rib cage making a
throw in a game against Oakland on June 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
