<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS TAKES ONE FOR THE TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ I'm so angry I could quit. My editor admonishes me
when I miss deadline, he holds me accountable for my factual
errors, he stays on me like a tailgating driver.
</P>
<P>
   I can't take it anymore. He's a cloud in my cafe latte.
</P>
<P>
   To heck with that. From this point forward I'm not going to
bother trying to write poetic prose. No Pulitzers for me, no siree.
I'm just going to mail it in. Some days I may not even send a
column at all.
</P>
<P>
   The more I mess up, the worse it'll reflect on my editor. He'll
take so much heat he'll have no recourse but to resign. Either that
or he'll get fired. Either way, I win.
</P>
<P>
   You see, all I know about professionalism I learned from our
L.A. sports teams. Let's face it, for our professional athletes it
truly is a dog's life. They can make a mess all over Southern
California and nobody expects them to clean up after themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I want I want to come back in my next career as a
Laker or an Angel. That way I can stubbornly refuse to heel and the
person on the other end of the leash will wind up in the doghouse,
not me.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Lakers fired Del Harris because head coaches are
easier to find than seven-foot centers. And Friday, Angels manager
Terry Collins quit _ mind you, a good two months after his
sniveling players did.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, to be a professional athlete here and now means never
having to say you're culpable.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, 50, was kind enough to show up for his funeral,
fielding questions through a veil of tears four hours before the
Angels' game against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Who said there's no crying in baseball? On Wednesday, 22 umpires
weeped and 48 hours later Collins' eyes grew all watery. What's
next, ``Crying Towel Night''?
</P>
<P>
   Like Harris before him, Collins departed with class. He offered
no excuses and steadfastly refused to rat out the Judases, wherever
they were hiding.
</P>
<P>
   If only his players could have worn their dirty laundry the same
as Collins _ as undergarments instead of outerwear _ this sorry
season might never have come to this.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, from avowed team leader Mo Vaughn on down, the Angels were
finger-pointing poseurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in clubhouses where the players didn't necessarily
care for each other,'' said Collins, who was in his third season as
the Angel manager. ``The bottom line is, they went out and played
together. That's what you've got to do. I had reached the last
thing I could think of to get (the players) going.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it was the best sacrifice play executed by any Angel
in quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real hard to walk away,'' Collins said, his voice
cracking. ``These jobs are hard to get. I had a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he awoke Friday _ in his own home after eight days
(and seven losses) on the road _ with his immediate future
amorphous as a dream. His course of action was crystallized later
in the morning when he met with vice president and general manager
Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, Collins' staunchest ally in the organization, sized up
the situation and invoked the mercy rule.
</P>
<P>
   It was the best call, Bavasi said, ``a little bit for the club
but mostly for Terry. If he's your friend, I'm not sure you want to
ram (staying on) down the guy's throat.''
</P>
<P>
   If Collins was resigned to his fate, Bavasi was repulsed. Asked
how he imagined the players were taking the news, Bavasi retorted,
``I'd be less than honest with you if I told you I cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he said, ``Terry said he's not bitter. He's a bigger man
than I. It's a bitter pill for me. I put together a team that had
every reason to respond well and didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   I would have liked to have been able to gauge the players'
reactions to Collins' resignation for myself. But by Bavasi's
decree the Angels' clubhouse was closed to reporters before and
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   When all else fails, control the press, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably just as well the clubhouse doors stayed shut. It
would have sickened me to see a bunch of players who have exhibited
so little heart all summer try to manufacture an ounce of
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he treated his players like grown men. Well, no
wonder things ended badly. It's pretty obvious the 1999 Angels are
a Disney remake of Peter Pan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 0154EDT &QL; 
