<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0778 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SELICHOT-SERVICE-LADN     09-04 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELICHOT-SERVICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELICHOT SERVICES PREPARE JEWS FOR HIGH HOLY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY HOLLY J. ANDRES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Imagine sitting with a roomful of people praying
at midnight when suddenly the heavens shake and open, revealing a
forgiving God who is listening to the words of repentance.
</P>
<P>
   That's the image Rabbi Richard Camras of Shomrei Torah Synagogue
believes Jews might benefit from visualizing during Selichot
services.
</P>
<P>
   Selichot means ``forgiveness,'' and the penitential prayers said
first at this service will be recited every day through Yom Kippur,
except on Shabbat, said Camras, who leads the Conservative
congregation in the West Hills community of Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Repentance, renewal, starting over and God's forgiveness are
major themes of this somber service in which the synagogue's Torah
mantles will be white to symbolize purity, and the shofar, a ram's
horn, will be blown near the end of the service to awaken Jews to
the spiritual work they need to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service is based around the Bible passage Exodus 33. This
passage is where Moses asks God for forgiveness after the
worshiping of the golden calf,'' Camras said.
</P>
<P>
   The Selichot service dates from the second century, but
typically, it draws smaller crowds than Rosh Hashana, Yom Kippur
and other holy days because of the late hour.
</P>
<P>
   Micah Caplan, a 10-year member of Shomrei Torah, said, ``It's a
powerful service. It's a time for me to prepare for the High Holy
Days. It's a time to better myself. It's a time to start asking God
for forgiveness and asking others to forgive us. I really dig deep
into myself to plan for the coming year.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sharlene Blau, the Selichot service means keeping a
tradition she grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from a traditional background. I was exposed to it. It
sets the tone for the High Holy Days for me. I start thinking about
the meaning behind those days. The service starts giving you the
taste and gives you the mood for the holidays. There's a week to
prepare yourself. It's a time of reflection, and it does something
for me spiritually,'' said Blau, an 11-year member of the
synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The service will start at 11:30 p.m. and will include prayers,
readings and choral singing. Although most of the prayers will be
in Hebrew, many of the readings will be in English.
</P>
<P>
   A Selichot program at 8:30 p.m. will include a panel of speakers
sharing what the service means to them. Following refreshments,
Camras will lead a workshop on personal repentance and suggest
steps to personal change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an important service to go to if we are serious about
self-examination and changing the way we live, how we treat family
and friends and to work on our relationship with God,'' Camras
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take appropriate steps, and Selichot is the
beginning of our commitment to make these changes. No more
procrastination. We have to start today.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
