A0786 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-04 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON DINGS RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ David Bell had one goal as he ran from first to second
in the seventh inning Friday night against the Boston Red Sox:
distract Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lampkin, who hit the ground ball to second that would force
out Bell, had one thought: I'm going to be out by 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin was wrong, because Bell made good on his effort.
</P>
<P>
   If Garciaparra had sent his relay throw swiftly to first, Boston
would have had a double play and escaped the inning with a 1-0
lead. Instead, Bell slid in high, Garciaparra's throw sailed,
Lampkin was safe at first and the tying run had scored.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Dan Wilson's single drove in pinch-runner
Charles Gipson for a stirring 2-1 Mariners win that moved the M's
to 6{ games behind the Red Sox in the wild-card standings.
Left-hander Jamie Moyer pitched his second complete game in five
starts and improved to 13-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to distract him any way I could,'' Bell said
of his slide. ``I wanted it to be a legal slide. After I slid I
could still touch the base, and that's what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin said he was surprised Bell got to Garciaparra as quickly
as he did, because his grounder was hit hard, and right at second
baseman Jose Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing you know, David's right on him,'' Lampkin said
of Garciaparra. ``He made him jump to get the throw over him, so he
must have gotten down there quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed also showed up from an unlikely source Friday night. Edgar
Martinez, who beat out an infield single in the sixth inning,
started the ninth with another one, on a ball that trickled down
the third base line. Third baseman Wilton Veras waited for it to
roll foul, but it bumped the bag _ fair ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of strange,'' Martinez said of his
two-infield-hit night. ``I don't think I ever had two in a row,
even in Little League.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gipson pinch-ran for Martinez, and after Jay Buhner
popped up on a bunt attempt, Gipson stole second as Russ Davis
swung through a hit-and-run. Then Wilson singled off former Mariner
Derek Lowe (5-3) to give the M's their fifth consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected him to come at me with a sinker,'' Wilson said.
``He came hard, but he was up in the zone and it ran in a little on
me. I knew I just needed to get it in the outfield with Gipson on
second.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Mariners were energized by the series-opening victory
_ ``The first game is the most important. We'd like to win this
series, at least take three,'' Martinez said _ the Red Sox were
irritated.
</P>
<P>
   First base umpire Brian O'Nora ejected three Red Sox on one play
in the eighth inning after Damon Buford was called out at first
after trying to bunt for a hit. Buford, manager Jimy Williams and
first base coach Dave Jauss all were tossed, but the more pivotal
play was the one an inning earlier involving Lampkin.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's throw pulled first baseman Mike Stanley off the
bag, but Stanley leaped and caught the ball, then swiped to tag
Lampkin. Lampkin said he felt some contact, though he wasn't sure
whether he had reached first base by then. Stanley made a factual
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was up the line, I tagged to my left,'' Stanley said.
``It's got to be before he hits the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no such intrigue when the Red Sox batted, because
Moyer put so few runners on base. He yielded two singles in the
first inning, a walk in the fifth and a leadoff homer by
Garciaparra in the seventh. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer has thrived since starting the Safeco Field opener on July
15. He has lasted at least six innings while allowing no more than
three earned runs in eight of his last nine starts, and has a 2.28
earned-run average since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can keep your pitch count down, good things can
happen,'' Moyer said. ``But if you're at 100 pitches in the fifth
and sixth inning, you're not going to last too much longer. Tonight
I was able to do it _ they were swinging the bats and aggressive,
and that allowed me to keep my pitch count down. I had no idea what
it was (during the game), but I know I threw 101 pitches, which is
kind of nice.''
</P>
<P>
   For 44,471 fans at Safeco Field, it was a nice way to open a
homestand that should determine if the Mariners put on a true
pennant drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are making (this) out to be a big series, but every
series is big as far as I'm concerned,'' Moyer said. ``Looking at
the next 30 days, you say, we've got to do something here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
