 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for Sunday,
Sept. 5, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN (New York) _ U.S. Open lede. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ARATON-COLUMN (New York) _ On the U.S. Open. By Harvey
Araton.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-BORIS-STEFFI (Berlin) _ Before Boris Becker and Steffi Graf
came on the scene, Germans admired their celebrities from a polite
distance. As Becker and Graf rose to the top of their professions,
however, they became Boris and Steffi, German cultural exports and
symbols of national pride. Thanks to them, Germany is now a
tennis-loving country. By Alan Maimon.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ No wonder people are excited. New
York has not come this close to a subway series since 1956, because
when the Mets were up, the Yankees were generally down, and vice
versa. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ANGELS (Anaheim, Calif.) _ Yankees at Anaheim, 4:05
p.m. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-ROCKIES (New York) _ Colorado at Mets, 7:10 p.m. By
Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-COLUMN (Undated) _ On Baseball on the Mets. By Jack
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Baseball notebook. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ NFL notebook. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   BKL-LIBERTY-COMETS (Houston) _ Game 2 of the WNBA finals. By
Timothy W. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-U.S.-IRELAND (Foxboro, Mass.) _ U.S. women vs. Ireland, 4:30
p.m. By Alex Yannis.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NOTREDAME-MICHIGAN (Ann Arbor, Mich.) _ Notre Dame at
Michigan, 3:30 p.m. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-RUTGERS-CALIF (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Rutgers at California,
5:30 p.m. By Gregg Bell.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Al Capone was sitting in a
steambath in Chicago one day when a stranger struck up a
conversation. The stranger talked glowingly of an impending
business deal and said that if mum were the word, Scarface, er, Al,
could make a quick killing, so to speak. All Capone had to do was
lend the stranger $2,000 until later. Capone gave the man the
money, but later never arrived. The stranger was named Harry
Morgan, called Swifty, but better known as the original Lemon Drop
Kid, whose namesake, a 3-year-old colt won the Travers Stakes at
Saratoga on Saturday, earning $600,000, following his triumph in
the Belmont Stakes in June. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-FISHING (Undated) _ Here was Eric Leiser of Wappingers
Falls, N.Y., a devotee of trout and a guru of fly-fishing, sitting
in a 14-foot rowboat with a six-horsepower engine, joyously pumping
a spinning rod _ a spinning rod! What was the world of fly-fishing
purists coming to? ``A good time,'' said Eric, and that's true. By
Robert H. Boyle.
</P>
