   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-SWEDEN-LINK (Copenhagen, Denmark) _ A new 9.5-mile, $2
billion tunnel and bridge connection called the Oresund Fixed Link
is being completed that will tie Sweden to the continent of Europe
for the first time and create a new European trade and marketing
center surpassing Stockholm and equal to cities like Berlin,
Hamburg, Zurich and Amsterdam. By Warren Hoge. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-TV-POLITICS (Moscow) _ If television is, as it
increasingly seems to be, the weapon of choice in Russia's intense
and ugly political battles, then Sunday night will offer Russian
viewers, on two of the country's major channels, a journalistic
rendition of ``Gunfight at the O.K. Corral.'' By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-VIOLENCE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ East Timor entered a
dangerous period Saturday as swaggering thugs intensified their
violence and menace following an early-morning announcement that
the tiny territory had voted overwhelmingly for independence from
Indonesia. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-SYRIA (Damascus, Syria) _ In an effort to move another
piece of the Middle East peace puzzle into place, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright arrived here Saturday for the first visit
by a senior Clinton administration official in two years. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-DEMOCRACY (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Since its election on
July 25, a Constitutional Assembly loyal to President Hugo Chavez
has not only stripped the opposition-controlled Congress of all its
powers, but also taken control of Venezuela's judicial system.
Though those actions have generated much criticism abroad that
democracy is being endangered here, Venezuela's 23 million people
have largely hailed the moves. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ELECTIONS (Nauen, Germany) _ The extreme-right Deutsche
Volksunion party, backed by a millionaire Bavarian publisher named
Gerhard Frey, is hoping to benefit from disillusionment with the
center-left government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in elections
on Sunday. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FOR-RENT (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ All over Pristina,
there is building and the noise of electric drills and cement
mixers from every direction. Pedestrians walk an obstacle course
over and around piles of sand, boards and scaffolding. The main aim
seems to be to redo a house and rent it to foreigners. By Carlotta
Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-SLOVAK-BARRIERS (Prague, Czech Republic) _ It has been
less than seven years since the Czech and Slovak republics
peacefully split up after some 70 years together as Czechoslovakia.
But recent surveys indicate that, although Czech and Slovak are
among the closest of languages in the family of Slavic tongues, and
the two peoples can communicate without difficulty, the youngest of
Czech schoolchildren now have difficulty understanding their Slovak
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ELECTIONS (New Delhi, India) _ Indian national elections
begin Sunday, and, as always, they are likely to be a great, if
unwieldy, display of democracy for the 605 million people eligible
to cast a ballot. But as impressive as Indian elections may be,
they are becoming too much of a good thing. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires, Argentina) _ It is not the
best year to be the presidential candidate of the governing
Justicialist Party, with the country sinking into recession, crime
soaring and polls showing that voters believe government corruption
is rife. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ISLAND-NATIONS (United Nations) _ For more than a decade,
several dozen small island nations threatened by rising seas and
increasingly violent weather have been awaiting the world's
attention as they face forces well beyond their control. On Sept.
27 and 28, they will get a chance to air their fears. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOOP-ETHICS-FLAP-L _ During the eight years he held the post of
U.S. surgeon general, Dr. C. Everett Koop became one of the
country's most authoritative and recognizable public figures on the
subject of health. But more than a decade after leaving office,
Koop, now 82, is facing criticism about his Web site, DrKoop.com.
By Holcomb B. Noble. (EDS: Two versions of this story will move: a
full-length version and an abridged one slugged
KOOP-ETHICS-FLAP-S.)
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-DEPRESSION (Boston) _ The 92-year-old woman was sitting
in her wheelchair, talking with her psychiatrist at the Hebrew
Rehabilitation Center for Aged, when the phone she carries in a
black canvas bag rang. She unzipped the bag and greeted her niece
on the line: ``Hello, Myrna. I'm in a meeting now. Can I call you
back?'' The psychiatrist, Dr. Eran Metzger, smiled. A year ago, the
woman was so depressed that she had not only lost interest in
talking to anyone, she had stopped eating. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH (New York) _ Organizers of the Million Youth
March promise a peaceful rally. (EDS: Story will move after 4 p.m.
ET when event is over. With sidebars as warranted.)
</P>
<P>
   FALWELL-GAYS-MEETING _ If all goes as agreed, the Rev. Mel
White, an outspoken supporter of gay rights, will take 200 people
to Lynchburg, Va., next month, to meet with the Rev. Jerry Falwell,
an outspoken critic of homosexual activity, and 200 people he has
invited, to talk about the issue dividing them. By Gustav Niebuhr.
(With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-GAYS _ A Roman Catholic priest, ordered by the Vatican to
end his ministry to gay and lesbian Catholics, has resumed public
speaking, saying he can do so, within limits, and still respect the
church's directive. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA (Washington) _ Fighting any suggestions of a
lame-duck presidency, President Clinton on Saturday challenged
Republicans to approve an ambitious fall agenda that includes
gun-control proposals, a patient's bill of rights and various
education proposals like measures to fix up old schools, hire more
teachers and end social promotions. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOLS-THREATS (Denver) _ Grappling with the aftermath of
the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton,
education officials say five other high schools in the same
district have received letters threatening violence in the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   VAIL-HOUSING-DISPUTE (Vail, Colo.) _ Battles over growth bedevil
communities throughout the country, but rarely have they generated
such fury as they have here in one of Colorado's premier ski
resorts. By Michael Janofsky. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   KING-COUNTY-DEBATE (Seattle) _ King County Council member Larry
Gossett believes Seattle and its surrounding county have a great
secret to share with the rest of the nation. ``We're living here in
Martin Luther King Jr. County, and nobody seems to know it,'' said
Gossett, a Democrat. Actually, the issue of the county's name is
not quite that simple. By Sam Howe Verhovek. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INCOME-CHASM _ The gap between rich and poor has grown into an
economic chasm so wide that this year the richest 2.7 million
Americans, the top 1 percent, will have as many after-tax dollars
to spend as the bottom 100 million. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICAL &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Items on politics from around the nation. By
B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
