<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-DENMARK-SWEDEN-LINK-A     09-04 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-SWEDEN-LINK-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINK TO TIE SWEDEN TO A NEW EUROPE, BREAKING OLD DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark _ Swedes may share history, culture and some
language with the Danes, but they haven't always been welcome when
they have crossed the Baltic channel that separates the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the nations have fought a series of bloody wars over
the centuries, usually with the Danes on the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in a move symbolic of how the new Europe is breaking
down its age-old divisions, the Danes are about to make it easier
than ever for Swedes to come calling, and far from fearing the
consequences, they view the occasion as a chance to bury hatchets,
raise future prospects and smooth over clashing national
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   A new 9.5-mile, $2 billion tunnel and bridge connection called
the Oresund Fixed Link is being completed that will tie Sweden to
the continent of Europe for the first time and create a new
European trade and marketing center that will surpass Stockholm and
equal those of cities like Berlin; Hamburg, Germany; Zurich,
Switzerland, and Amsterdam, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   When the four-lane highway and dual-track railroad is opened to
traffic next July 1, Copenhagen, Denmark's capital, will be only an
11-minute ride from Malmo, Sweden's third-largest city, and a
single metropolitan region with a population of 3.2 million people
will be born.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th and 18th centuries, the Swedes won a series of wars
with the Danes and kept walking off with territories that had been
Danish.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Danes were more prosperous and powerful than
the Swedes but a lot less lucky. When Swedish royalty cast covetous
eyes this way in 1658, the harshest winter in history promptly
arrived, allowing a march across the frozen sea. The Swedes caught
the enemy by surprise and diminished Denmark a little more. By the
19th century, the two nations were still fighting, and the
conquering Swedes made the Danes cede to them all of what is now
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the moment of bonding provided by the new link has
become a chance for Denmark and Sweden to put to rest their
belligerent old relationship, and this time the Danes finally seem
to be on the winning side. ``We love the Danes more than the Danes
love us,'' conceded Per Olov Enquist, 65, the Swedish novelist and
playwright who lived here during the 15 years he was married to a
Danish woman.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while he never encountered ``aggressive
anti-Swedish feelings,'' he felt that Danes are generally
appreciated more than Swedes. ``For example, when a Swede speaks
Danish, it sounds stupid, but when a Dane speaks Swedish, it's
considered cute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the judgment is a stereotype popular in Copenhagen and
largely undisputed in Malmo of Swedes as stiff, formal, reserved,
humorless, collective-minded and ever obedient to intrusive state
rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danes will say, `Oh you Swedes, you have laws against
everything,''' Enquist said. ``They make it sound as if we have
barbed wire around the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Danes, by contrast, are thought of as the Southerners of
Northern Europe, cosmopolitan, individualistic, extroverted, high
spirited and fun-loving, and they are quite content to feed the
image. ``When I go to the Nordic Council,'' said Magrethe Auken,
54, a member of Parliament, ``you can be sure that where there is
laughing, celebrating and drinking, that's where the Danes are.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbro Reinestrand and her husband, Hans, both 56-year-old
Swedes from the southwestern town of Kungalv, stood on the Malmo
shore one recent afternoon and looked admiringly out at the bridge
melting into the mists above the Oresund on its curving trajectory
to Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to go over there,'' Mrs. Reinestrand said. She raised
her arms in a folk dancer's pose and tapped her feet. ``Danes are
so happy, and Swedes are so moody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Swedes in Scania, the southern province of the country, are
willing to accept this unflattering picture of their national
character because they're really talking about Swedes in the North,
particularly in the area of Stockholm, the national capital 400
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live in Scania think of themselves as more Danish
than Swedish, and they think of Stockholmers as gray and dull, more
like Russians,'' said Fredrik Nilsson, a Swedish anthropologist
from the University of Lund who conducted a study of attitudes on
either side of the Oresund and published his conclusions in a book
called ``When One Hour Became 10 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that, as in other parts of Europe where centuries-old
conflicts affect present day senses of identity, many Scanians
still think of themselves as former Danes. The province was annexed
by Sweden 341 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Scanians, who often fly their own distinctive red and yellow
flag in place of the blue and yellow national standard, refer to
residents of the capital scornfully as ``Zero-Eights,'' a reference
to the city's telephone area code.
</P>
<P>
   Scanians resent being caricatured by other Swedes as provincial
lowlanders, and they feel neglected by the national government.
``For a lot of people in Scania, the bridge is their exit from the
Swedish nation state'' Nilsson said. ``They feel that they're going
home to Denmark.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reinestrand gently patted her own backside and confirmed
the sentiment. ``We call ourselves the rump of Sweden,'' she said
brightly, ``and we feel much closer to Copenhagen than to
Stockholm.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson added: ``The people behind the bridge like to say we are
uniting Sweden and Denmark, but to ordinary people here it is a
question of uniting Scania and Denmark. People don't think about
two countries, they think about one region.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the state-backed investment promotion and tourism
development agencies have been focusing on in the run-up to the
bridge's opening. It is their hope that Denmark will not become
simply a ``footprint'' for Swedish transports on their way to
Germany and the European heartland but that the 8,000-square-mile
Oresund area will become a place unto itself as regionality and
nation-to-nation cooperation become more important, and national
identity less.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While the European Union, of which both Denmark and Sweden are
members, has broken down trade and currency barriers, it has lagged
in building transportation connections like the Oresund link to
make come true its hopes of a continental community that is
geographically rational and accessible.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lars Kolind, 52, a manufacturing executive who is one of
Denmark's most innovative business leaders, believes that there are
complementary resources on either side of the Oresund that are
particularly well suited for the region's specialities like
pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, medical research, environmental
science and information technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of business depend on networking, close
communication and exchange of knowledge, and though I'm fully aware
of the advantages of the Internet, there is no substitute for
physical contact,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A country with real industrial might, Sweden has businesses that
are large and muscular where Danish businesses rely on their
centuries-old skills in international commerce. ``Swedish business
is more powerful than ours, but we are the traders, the
manipulators, the ultimate pragmatists,'' said Michael
Christiansen, 54, the director general of the Royal Danish Theater
who is chairman of the consortium that built the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The collaborative possibilities are inviting, but the divisions
between the two like-minded countries could still stall progress.
Christiansen said he believed that Denmark and Sweden had drawn
farther apart in the last 20 years, and he recalled that at the
time the decision was taken to construct the Oresund link in 1991,
majorities of both populations were against the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two areas are like bears just sitting sleeping,'' he said.
``The question is, are they ready to move. We're not quite sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
