<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0807 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TRADEMARKS-REVIEW-NYT     09-04 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADEMARKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACRED OR PROFANE, ODD OR MUNDANE, IT HAS A TRADEMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (Eds: Replace (TM) with superscript trademark symbol)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boom times have a trademarked feel. Literally. It is harder and
harder to get through the day without tripping over the little
``TM'' sign that is the equivalent of a ``No Trespassing _
Violators Will Be Prosecuted'' sign in an empty swath of New
England woods. It is not always clear who owns the property in
question, but it is abundantly clear that you don't. Tread on it at
your risk.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest signs of TM-ing, as noted by The New York
Observer, popped up at the end of Cindy Adams' gossip column in The
New York Post. After years of signing off with the phrase ``Only in
New York, kids, only in New York,'' Ms. Adams has applied for a
trademark. She has also fenced off the word gossip, at least for
use in perfumes and cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Trademarks flourish in a strong economy, and the boom of the
late 1990s has seen an increase in the trademarking of words,
images and sounds by at least 10 percent annually in three of the
last four years, according to figures from the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the rate of increase (Increase(TM) was registered by
Enrich Corp. for shampoos and nutritional supplements) is
turbocharged (Turbocharge(TM) is used by U S West Communications
Inc. for its credit-card validation services). If applications
continue at the current pace (Pace(TM) applied for or registered to
more than 250 entities), there will be 25 percent more in 1999 than
1998. One clue to the spike: The words ``dot com'' figure in 222
pending or registered trademarks on the government's trademark data
base.
</P>
<P>
   Trademarks differ from copyrights, which protect works of
creative expression _ books, artwork, music, commuter software and
the like. Businesses or individuals register trademarks to
establish the source of a product or service. It costs $245 to
register a trademark for a single class of goods.
</P>
<P>
   Even trademark is trademarked. Resistance is futile (Paramount
Pictures trademarked that Star Trekism for everything from pinball
machines to wrapping paper). As soon as some phrases catch on, they
get taken. Comedian Jerry Seinfeld may have put Yadda Yadda Yadda
into the vernacular, but Custom Tees Inc., a Connecticut sportswear
company, registered it for clothing and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that Seinfeld objects. Comedian Johnny
Carson, however, fought back. It took him 10 years, but a federal
appeals court ruled in 1987 that Here's Johnny Portable Toilets
Inc. had violated the star's ``right of publicity'' and owed him
$31,661.96. During the legal proceedings, Carson trademarked
``Heeere's Johnny.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record (16 trademarks), newspapers, magazines and news
shows have long since protected their features. The ``60 Minutes''
ticking stopwatch is a trademark, as is the slogan of The New York
Times, ``All the News That's Fit to Print,'' and the names of some
of its sections like ``Circuits'' and ``House and Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities like Oprah and Madonna have also registered their
names. Elvis Presley Enterprises, Inc. holds dozens of trademarks.
Still, Diagnostic Hybrids Inc. of Ohio somehow slipped through and
got Elvis for use on, of all things, ``diagnostic preparations for
clinical and medical use.''
</P>
<P>
   The roar of the MGM lion has been trademarked. Even skylines. In
New York, the Empire State Building, the Chrysler Building and
Rockefeller Center have all staked claims to their images.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seems to be sacred. Nearly 500 trademarks on Christmas
(from Papa Noel's Cajun Christmas Cap to Special Christmas Brew
Beer) have been issued or are pending. Nothing seems to be profane.
Six trademark applications have recently been filed for barnyard
words that are unprintable in this newspaper. In the world of
trademarks, there is little shame (only seven trademarks contain
the word shame) and much integrity (the word is part of 279
trademarks).
</P>
<P>
   Mary Donovan, a partner in the law firm of Donovan &AMP; Yee, said,
``Everybody has realized that there is money to be made. While I am
all for protection of one's intellectual proprietary rights, I
think there needs to be some balance so that freedom of expression
isn't squashed.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the balance that U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard
Gesell tried to strike in 1985, when he rejected Lucasfilm Ltd.'s
claim that political commercials sparring over President Ronald
Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative would dilute the company's
trademark if allowed to call SDI ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws do not reach into the realm of public discourse to
regulate the use of terms used outside the context of trade,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At least, not most places. Maybe only in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
