<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sept. 5 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS-2000 (Los Angeles) _ The future never looked brighter than
in 1988 when the class of 2000 entered kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Now the future is here and it bears scant resemblance to what
district officials, parents and even students envisioned. By Sherry
Joe Crosby. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MTA-ZONE (Los Angeles) _ By the numbers and surveys of riders,
bus service in the San Fernando Valley is sadly lacking. As a
transit zone, locally run, it would better serve residents,
according to proponents. By Douglas Haberman. (Will move in the
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NOKILL-STRAYS (Los Angeles) _ In an ambitious move to save the
lives of thousands of stray dogs and cats, city officials said they
will partner with animal activists to find homes for every
adoptable pet brought to the pound. By Harrison Sheppard. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTHY-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ A 95-year-old blind man and his
grandson visit twice weekly a la ``Tuesdays with Morrie,'' the
best-selling book. By Dennis McCarthy. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-MAPS (Oxnard) _ Computer nerds, pilots Gary Petrowski and
Mark Gassaway created a real-time display of the streets they were
flying over, and law enforcement agencies in search of the
``seamless mapping technology'' have beaten a path to Petrowski and
Gassaway's Oxnard hangar, home of the company they since started,
AeroComputers Inc. By Jeremy Bagott. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
