<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     09-04 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE SPENDS TIME WITH A HERO - HIS GRANDPA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- His grandfather's 90th birthday was coming up and
the whole family would be gathering to celebrate. It was the
perfect time to let Grandpa know exactly how he felt about him.
</P>
<P>
   So, 25-year-old Jon Banks sits at his home computer and lets the
memories flow _ tries to put into words all the warm feelings and
life lessons he's learned from his grandfather, Morrie Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Author Mitch Albom had his ``Tuesdays with Morrie'' _ a best
selling, poignant book about the writer's experiences with his aged
former professor.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Banks has his Saturday's and Sunday's with Morrie, which are
much the same.
</P>
<P>
   A student or a grandson, it doesn't make any difference because
the underlying theme of their days together with a grandfather or
elderly teacher are the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heroes inspire you and lead you to live a better life,''
Jon Banks begins. ``My hero is Grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrie Carr sat surrounded by family on his 90th birthday,
feeling proud and honored as his grandson read his tribute to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit home, all of it,'' Morrie would say later. ``All the
stories and lessons you try to teach your grandkids about right and
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   All that advice he handed out to his grandkids with sticks of
Wrigley's spearmint gum as they took long rides in his Oldsmobile
on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked plain, from the heart,'' Morrie says, like it was
only yesterday. ``And we had a good time.''Jon smiles as he looks
over at his mother, Penny Marson, and continues reading his tribute
to Morrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Grandpa lost his vision, he couldn't drive anymore, which
made it pretty difficult for him to be a good traveling salesman,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While most of us would have packed it in, he soldiered on, and
Jenni, Brian, and I were recruited to help him with his business.
We would take turns helping him out with his furniture catalogs,
and we got bribed with some cash and a free lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my driver's license, one responsibility that went
hand in hand with my Buick station wagon was taking Grandpa out to
run errands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing happened on the way to being a good grandson,''
Jon said. ``While I loved him with all my heart, I discovered that
I had never really known who Grandpa was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or more likely, by that time, I had grown old enough to
appreciate him as a person rather than as a grandpa. He became a
flesh and blood man to me, a hero with an unending amount of quirky
and endearing personality traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great times together. Our list of errands that we'd run
together would grow and grow. During those trips, I heard story
after story about his life and why he made the choices he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``These anecdotes became guideposts to my own self-discovery as
I learned how I became the person I am,'' Jon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did I learn right from wrong? Where did I learn what a
man should do and how a man should act? Where did I learn that
family is truly all that's important?
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer became clear _ from my grandparents and through my
mom,'' Jon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa is legally blind. He can only see shapes and sometimes
he's not particularly adept at that. However, I dare you to back up
50 yards from him and do something that he wouldn't approve of.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll see, oh yeah, he'll see, and he'll let you know that he
doesn't approve,'' Jon said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time has slowed him down some. Grandpa no longer bounds to my
car like he did a few years ago. If the seat is too far back, he
might have trouble getting in and out. It's always too cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``And unfortunately, the passage of time has meant that we don't
go out as much as we used to. Work isn't like college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highlight of our week now is getting together on Saturday
or Sunday, and going back on the road _ picking up the dry
cleaning, looking for batteries at Radio Shack and going to a
restaurant with good lighting and a strong cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa is not a great man. He's not famous and his
accomplishments won't be debated by historians. He is merely a good
and decent man who loves his family above all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the kind of man I try to be,'' Jon Banks says, walking
over to hug his grandfather on his 90th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays and Sundays with Morrie _ a nice story to remind us
that Grandparent's Day is coming up this month on Sunday, Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
