<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0836 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-1     09-04 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-1,015&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE RISES AS EAST TIMOR FACES FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ East Timor entered a dangerous period
Saturday as swaggering thugs intensified their violence and menace
following an early morning announcement that the tiny territory had
voted overwhelmingly for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   With Indonesian policemen standing back, organized
anti-independence militias threatened and shot at U.N. officials
and foreign journalists who were taking refuge in a seafront hotel
in the capital, Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Dili, the United Nations reported stepped-up attacks
that forced the closing of four of its offices and the evacuation
to Dili of 96 foreign U.N. workers, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   One American working as a police adviser for the United Nations
in the small town of Liquica was shot and evacuated by a U.N.
helicopter that itself came under threat from armed men. His
condition was described as not serious.
</P>
<P>
   In the vote, taken on Monday and announced Saturday, residents
rejected an offer of a new autonomous status within Indonesia,
which invaded East Timor in 1975 and has fought a separatist
insurgency ever since, with the loss of some 200,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   With this rejection by 78.5 percent of registered voters, East
Timor will be allowed to go free, President B.J. Habibie has said.
Their vote must be ratified by the Indonesian Parliament in a
session that begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie said Saturday that Indonesia would honor the vote and
most analysts believe that the lopsided outcome would be very
difficult for Parliament to overturn. But it is this period of
limbo, between the vote and its ratification, that many analysts
say poses the greatest danger of disruption.
</P>
<P>
   The violence brought condemnation from around the world Saturday
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright warned of an
international backlash if Indonesia continues to break its promises
to provide security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia has continuing obligations and must live up to
them,'' she said in a statement issued in Damascus. ``To do
otherwise risks disaster and will have lasting effects on
Indonesia's status in the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite months of violence and intimidation, nearly 99 percent
of East Timor's 450,000 registered voters cast their ballots on
Monday in what U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan called an act of
courage.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, East Timor becomes a strange and dangerous
no-man's-land, still technically a part of Indonesia but
potentially without effective administration or security during its
period of danger.
</P>
<P>
   This has given rise to intensified calls for the United Nations
to send armed peacekeepers to the former Portuguese colony of
800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian police have been responsible for security during
the referendum but _ as happened Saturday _ they have stood aside
as the military-backed thugs stage their attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameramen taking refuge in the seaside Mahkota Hotel
on Saturday filmed armed thugs approaching the foyer as a dozen
police officers stood back. The thugs smashed a glass door with a
sword and fired shots toward the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the streets of Dili were nearly deserted as open
garbage trucks drove along the seafront carrying armed men waving
guns and machetes.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell, residents said that gunshots could be heard in
the empty streets and that there were no policemen to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-independence leaders have said they would not accept
the vote, asserting that the United Nations was biased against
them. But an independent three-member commission set up to oversee
the referendum certified its conduct Saturday as acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most anti-independence leaders have boycotted the
formation of a 25-member reconciliation commission that is part of
the agreed plan for a transition of power.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of reconciliation seemed to be a difficult one for
Eurico Guterres, one of the most flamboyant and feared of the
militia leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are winners and losers now,'' he said. ``But how can we
reconCile the two sides? It is very difficult. Even the U.N. will
not be able to settle this. I am a citizen of Indonesia and it is
impossible for me to betray my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterres, whose armed men have been preventing some East
Timorese from boarding planes to leave the territory, spoke at the
airport as he prepared to depart for the island of Bali. ``I need
to take care of my family,'' he explained to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Among those appealing for armed help from the United Nations was
Jose Alexandre Gusmao, the man most likely to become the leader of
a new East Timor, who has been in prison since 1992. The government
said Saturday that it intended to release him within about a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We foresee chaos,'' Gusmao said. ``We foresee a new genocide
in East Timor. We foresee total destruction in a desperate and last
attempt by the Indonesian generals, and politicians maybe as well,
to deny the people of East Timor their freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the result Saturday morning, Annan said that
contingency plans were in place but that there was no immediate
plan to seek approval from the Security Council for a deployment of
a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Indonesian government completes its formalities and
East Timor becomes free, he said, armed peacekeepers would be part
of a promised U.N. administering authority. That authority would
attempt to provide a buffer of time for East Timor as it seeks to
set up a new government.
</P>
<P>
   During its years of occupation, Indonesia provided the
territory's administration, schools, utilities and police force.
East Timor has few people with the education or training to perform
these tasks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Annan also warned of the instability in the months to come.
``After 24 years of conflict, East Timor now stands on the
threshold of what we all hope will be a process of the orderly and
peaceful transition of power,'' he said. ``The coming days will
require patience and calm from the people of East Timor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the surge in violence was simply an
angry backlash by military-backed militias that have tried to
derail the vote or whether it was intended somehow to block
implementation of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Some militia leaders have spoken of trying to create their own
Indonesian enclave in the western part of the territory. Neither
the United Nations nor Indonesia has taken that idea seriously,
although the Indonesian military, which has been virtually
autonomous in its years of occupation, might support it.
</P>
<P>
   With representatives of some 70 nations participating in the
U.N. vote process, condemnation of the violence was widespread and
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   European Union foreign ministers, meeting in Finland, issued a
statement saying they were ``deeply concerned about the
deteriorating security situation in East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's representative for East Timor, Foreign Minister
David Andrews of Ireland, used even stronger language that
reflected growing international frustration over Indonesia's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled by the failure of the Indonesian authorities,
despite repeated representations to them, to fulfill their
obligation to provide adequate security,'' he said. ``The people of
East Timor are now entering a period of great uncertainty and great
danger. It would be tragic if they were left unprotected against
murderous thugs now out of control in many areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0837 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-REVIEW-ART-     09-04 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S MANY FACES REFLECT ONE NATION, DIVISIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ ``One country. One people. One language.''
</P>
<P>
   As a national credo, displayed on banners and placards, it
sounds simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   But in this scattered archipelago of 13,000 islands, roiling
with an untamed mix of cultures, ethnic groups, histories,
rivalries, gods and spoken tongues, it begins to seem almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   These days, some people say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous nation with well
over 200 million people, is deep in a crisis of economics, politics
and national identity. Its leaders and institutions have lost much
of their popular standing and legitimacy. The forces that most
overtly held Indonesia together _ the grip of a dictator and the
harshness of his military _ have retreated since the forced
resignation 15 months ago of Suharto as president.
</P>
<P>
   A country so unsure of its unity that it has made oneness an
obsession is being forced to rediscover the logic of its
nationhood. The challenge as it steps gingerly into an era of
democracy is to want to be a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The violence that ravaged the former Portuguese colony of East
Timor last week as it was voting for independence from Indonesia
came as a reminder to the outside world of the diversity and
tenuousness of this scattered nation. Perhaps the fears it has
aroused _ of centrifugal forces that could pull Indonesia apart _
are exaggerated. Still, it points up the counterproductiveness of
enforced union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to have an Indonesia in which the constituent
parts sit happily together as a republic and not because they are
held together by bayonets, you are going to have to have a system
where the constituent parts come together because they want to be
together,'' said James Dunn, a former Australian diplomat who is an
expert on Indonesia. ``Since the founding of Indonesia, the
military has seen itself as the guardian of national integrity. In
a democracy national integrity has to be held together by the
national will.''
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of this, the post-Suharto government _ which is
still taking shape _ is exploring ways to devolve some economic and
political control to the provinces. An extreme possibility, one
that would demand a constitutional amendment, would be to shift
power into a federal structure.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian rule has sometimes been likened to a colonial
structure, with the dominant Javanese on their relatively small
island asserting their rule over the larger and more resource-rich
outer islands. A fairer distribution of the national wealth along
with greater political empowerment could go a long way toward
mollifying Indonesia's restive provinces.
</P>
<P>
   But the loosening of a grip always carries the risk of loss of
control. After 32 years of Suharto's policy of enforced national
harmony, the vacuum created by his departure and the humbling of
the military has been quickly filled by all the repressed passions
of political, religious and ethnic differences that strain
Indonesia's fabric.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, separatist movements have been energized in
several areas, highlighted by East Timor, which Indonesia invaded
in 1975 but which never accepted integration as the country's 27th
province.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Indonesian capital, Jakarta _ and particularly in
the military _ fear that freedom for East Timor could be the start
of a process of national disintegration. Other analysts point to
that territory's unique place as a national afterthought and argue
that a line can be drawn between East Timor and the rest of
Indonesia. It is the only part of the country to have been
colonized by the Portuguese rather than by the Dutch and it is the
only part to have been been dragged into union by invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The most potentially destabilizing separatist movement is in the
strongly Islamic, natural gas-rich province of Aceh, where the loss
of life this year has been far greater than in East Timor. A former
Islamic kingdom with its own proud past, Aceh is an integral part
of Indonesia's history and self-definition and its loss could deal
a severe blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very worried,'' a senior Western diplomat said. ``If
Aceh begins to take off, they will really have problems with the
integrity of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   A smaller, less unified separatist movement has flared in the
remote mountains of Irian Jaya, whose primitive people are as
strange and exotic to residents of modern Jakarta as they are to
New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Vicious bloodletting has also continued in the Moluccas (the
former Spice Islands that first attracted traders to the
archipelago) and in West Kalimantan on the island of Borneo. But
these eruptions, for the moment at least, have more to do with
local feuds, and with Jakarta's inability to impose order, than
with serious separatist threats.
</P>
<P>
   Though they may not pull the nation apart, the declarations of
individuality by the separatists offer a reminder that Indonesia is
an artificial geographical conglomeration inherited from its Dutch
colonizers.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant, taciturn princes of Java seem to have little in
common with the otherworldly dancers of Hindu Bali, the long-eared
Dayak tribesmen of Borneo, the seagoing pirates of the Spice
Islands or the Chinese traders who control the country's ports and
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   What brings them all together as Indonesians?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an idea, as in other big, diverse countries like
India and the United States,'' said James Clad, a professor of
Southeast Asian studies at Georgetown University. ``It is an idea
of an archipelagic country, a concept that goes back to pre-Islamic
times.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
