drop since 1996 in applications to the 125 schools accredited by
the American Medical Association. But there is still no shortage of
candidates. The 41,004 applicants last year vied for 16,000 spots.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Big Drop in AIDS Deaths Begins to Slow
</P>
<P>
   The substantial decline in AIDS deaths that began after newer
combinations of drugs were introduced nearly four years ago has
slowed _ to 20 percent from 1997 to 1998 compared to 42 percent
from 1996 to 1997, federal health officials reported. The newer
therapies are benefiting many people infected with the AIDS virus,
but have led many others to think that drugs alone will wipe out
AIDS, experts said. They urged renewed efforts at prevention to
overcome the complacency.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   Retiring the Beanie Babies
</P>
<P>
   In what toy industry experts say may be a publicity stunt, Ty
Inc., the maker of Beanie Babies, announced on its World Wide Web
site that ``all Beanies will be retired'' as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   No one really believes that Beanies Babies will go the way of
the pet rock.
</P>
<P>
   The company may have made the announcement to drum up sales for
a product that has lost some of its appeal as youngsters have moved
on to other toys, such as Pokemon. The announcement created a
frenzy on Web site chat rooms and left customers confused. The
company, which has been known to ignore customers and retailers (Ty
even has an unlisted phone number), has declined to comment on the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DANA CANEDY
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnay's Shameful Past
</P>
<P>
   The long arm of DNA that reached back into Thomas Jefferson's
family history has drawn attention to another scandalous liaison,
but this time in the family history of the chardonnay, one of the
world's best-known grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a DNA fingerprinting technique, geneticists at the
University of California, Davis, have shown that chardonnay is not
a kind of pinot, as believed by some experts, but rather is a cross
between pinot and gouais blanc.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing is surprising because pinot is a highly regarded
grape but gouais, common in the Middle Ages, became so despised
that it is no longer cultivated in France. The geneticists
discovered that 15 other French wines are also the progeny of the
pinot-gouais liaison, including gamay, the grape from which
beaujolais is made, and melon, the source of muscadet.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Bush Outlines Plan To Fine Failing School
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush has worked hard in his presidential
campaign to sound conservative but pragmatic, a line he tried to
toe again in his first major address on education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush excoriated most federal education programs as ineffective,
but he also called for a big expansion of the Education Department.
He said schools should be controlled by local boards, but insisted
on federally mandated testing of children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to use the word ``voucher,'' but said federal money
should be taken from public schools where children perform poorly
and given to parents to use at private or other schools. ``Public
funds must be spent on things that work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
