<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ELDERLY-DEPRESSION-AR     09-04 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DEPRESSION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAPS IN TREATMENT OF DEPRESSION AMONG ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Dr. Eran Metzger with a patient is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 92-year-old woman was sitting in her wheelchair,
talking with her psychiatrist at the Hebrew Rehabilitation Center
for Aged, when the phone she carries in a black canvas bag rang.
She unzipped the bag and greeted her niece on the line: ``Hello,
Myrna. I'm in a meeting now. Can I call you back?''
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrist, Dr. Eran Metzger, smiled. A year ago, the
woman was so depressed that she had not only lost interest in
talking to anyone, she had stopped eating. But not long after he
started her on an anti-depressant, her mood began to improve. The
ringing telephone, he said, was as good an indication as any that
she was again engaged in life.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, a 92-year-old former business executive, had suffered
a series of griefs that might seem to define old age: the deaths of
her husband and her five sisters; the loss of her vision and her
ability to walk; then, crushingly, the death of her only child, a
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I didn't want to live,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But this woman was one of the luckier older Americans who suffer
from what doctors call major depression, a condition in which the
brain chemistry is altered: Her home for the aged had a geriatric
specialist on staff, Metzger, who could recognize her symptoms and
not confuse them with old age itself. Most nursing homes and
residences for the aged do not.
</P>
<P>
   Just as medicine is more able than ever to treat depression,
experts worry that the nation's health care system is not prepared
to deal with a surge in cases as baby boomers approach old age _
eventually doubling the population 65 and older _ and encounter the
chronic diseases and losses that can make a person vulnerable to
depression.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the growing treatment of depression among the old also
raises questions about the quality of the last stage of life and
its emotional complexities _ the mingling of grief at the loss of a
spouse, for example, with the anticipation of seeing a grandchild _
that younger people, who mostly fear old age and disability, find
difficult to understand.
</P>
<P>
   While doctors say there is no question that depression can be
safely treated, they also debate where sadness ends and depression
begins _ and what realistic expectations for the final years are.
</P>
<P>
   Poets and philosophers have always spoken of the despair _ ``the
tragic sense of life,'' the Spanish philosopher Miguel de Unamuno
called it _ that the very old experience as they confront the
dwindling of their days. Some experts on aging worry that modern
medicine may end up trivializing that despair, trying to medicate
away the deep sadness that comes with losses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some despair is inevitable as you recognize that time is
short, that you don't have the opportunity to work out a different
life,'' said Rose Dobrof, 74, the Brookdale Center on Aging's
professor of gerontology at Hunter College.
</P>
<P>
   ``What too often happens is that because the family doctor
doesn't have time to talk, he prescribes medication,'' Ms. Dobrof
said. ``It's the easiest thing to do. What people need are human
connections.'' People, she said, need to talk, to doctors, clergy
and social workers, and to family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Dobrof said, medication _ particularly
newer anti-depressants like Zoloft, Paxil and Prozac that have
fewer side effects than older ones _ is needed to ease depression
in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Medication undoubtedly played a major role in the recovery of
the 92-year-old woman (many old people talk freely, even eagerly,
about their ailments, but depression is not considered a subject
for open discussion; the woman, like other patients interviewed for
this article, did not want to be named). She had attended weekly
group therapy sessions, Metzger said, but until she began taking
anti-depressants she could only sit by helplessly and cry. Now she
joins in.
</P>
<P>
   But Metzger said her recovery was also helped by a psychiatric
nurse, Phyllis Cronin, who recognized the woman's isolation and
made an effort to form a close relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of treatment, Metzger said, was not to erase her
sadness, nor to transform her into a different person. ``We're not
trying to make everyone conform to our stereotypes of aging,'' he
said. Most of the cases he treats, he said, are people with major
depression, a condition that can inhibit recovery from disease and
strokes and increase pain.
</P>
<P>
   Though the woman no longer talks of wanting to die, Metzger
said, she still cries over her son, and she still gets angry about
living in an institution. He is mindful of how she put it the other
day: ``The doctor and the medicine help you, but the pain in your
heart will live forever.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, to the extent that doctors thought
about depression and the elderly at all, it was to say that
depression among the elderly was understandable, even to be
expected. But geriatric psychiatrists and other experts see no
reason that the old and infirm should not find some fulfillment in
life.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, ``Another Country _ Navigating the Emotional
Terrain of Our Elders'' (Riverhead, 1999), Mary Pipher explored the
psychological growth that many old people experience as they
decline. ``There is an amazing calculus,'' she wrote. ``Anyone who
isn't an idiot becomes a philosopher.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is important, experts say, that younger people not impose
their fears and stereotypes about old age on the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people find new relationships and new interests,'' said
Dr. Ira Katz, director of geriatric psychiatry at the University of
Pennsylvania School of Medicine. ``I truly believe that even in a
nursing home, even in someone with heart failure, even with
disabling arthritis, with Parkinsonism, with any number of
disabling conditions, it really is possible to have pleasure in
life and to have a meaningful life if only one isn't depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Katz and other geriatric psychiatrists report that
increasing numbers of people are recovering from depression with
the help of new medications, experts say the great majority of
depressed older Americans are not getting adequate treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The health care system, they say, has not trained physicians to
look for depression in older people; managed care gives doctors
little time to explore what can be a difficult diagnosis (geriatric
psychiatrists often talk with a patient for an hour before
prescribing anything), and the newer anti-depressant medications
are expensive and require follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``More than one in six older patients who go to a primary-care
doctor's office have a clinically significant degree of
depression,'' Katz said. ``But only one in six of those get
adequate treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the National Institute of Mental Health,
depression among the elderly drives up health care costs, because
depression aggravates other conditions and depressed people visit
doctors more often. And, the institute said, there is the human
cost of going without treatment:
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our senior citizens will live their final years in
despair and suffering without any appreciation of their affliction
or the understanding and comfort of those most dear to them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the institute, major depression is found among 3
percent of the population over 65 living in their own homes, but it
is estimated that 5 percent to 10 percent of those who visit
primary care doctors have major depression. In nursing homes, an
even-larger proportion of the residents have major depression.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts fear that rates will skyrocket as baby boomers
encounter major medical conditions. As a generation, they already
have higher rates of depression than those ahead of them. In
response, several national projects to improve treatment are under
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even have to invent anything new,'' said Dr. Jurgen
Unutzer, a geriatric psychiatrist at the University of California,
Los Angeles, who is coordinating a project, financed by the John A.
Hartford Foundation in New York, to help doctors treat the elderly
who suffer from depression. ``We just have to use what we already
know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not age itself that can make a person vulnerable to
depression, but age-related diseases and disabilities that can
alter brain chemistry, along with blows like the loss of a spouse.
The point of treatment, experts say, is to make it possible to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want people to be numb to their sadness _ that's not
what depression treatment is about,'' Katz said. ``It's about
helping people enjoy what is there to be enjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   One barrier to treatment is the persistent myth that depression
in old age is natural. But experts say another is a health care
system in which doctors rush through, on average, 15-minute visits
with elderly patients who may be suffering from a number of chronic
health problems, many of which have symptoms that mimic depression.
</P>
<P>
   Then, even when a doctor is alert for depression and diagnoses
it, medication dosages must be closely monitored and must be
continued for at least eight or nine months to be effective. In
most cases, neither happens, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most managed-care systems restrict access to mental
health care and do not provide geriatric mental health specialists.
About 15 percent of older people with Medicare are enrolled in
managed-care plans, and about 80 percent of all mental health care
in managed care is provided by three or four extremely large
for-profit organizations, according to Dr. Gary Gottlieb, a
professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and chairman of
psychiatry and mental health for the Partners Health Care System, a
health care provider group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb, who led a panel that analyzed data from a study of
mental health care for older people provided by managed care, said,
``In evaluating the manuals, credentialing materials and
requirements of those organizations, virtually none of them have
mention of requiring special expertise in handling older adults.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There have been few studies on treatment of depression among the
elderly, but there is evidence that the use of anti-depressants
among older people has increased considerably in the last 10 years
or so. One study of people living in their own homes in North
Carolina, conducted by Dr. Dan Blazer, a professor of psychiatry at
Duke University, showed that the use had nearly doubled, to 8
percent, between 1986 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But still many more people who might benefit from it are not
getting treatment, and the barriers include the high cost of
psychotherapy, and of the newer anti-depressants, which can easily
cost $60 to $100 a month _ on top of the other medications many
older people take regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare offers no outpatient medication benefit, though
President Clinton has proposed creating one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are older people who go to the pharmacy,''
Unutzer said, ``and the pharmacist says `That will be $80 for the
first month,' and they say, `I'm sorry, I don't need it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rate of major depression among the elderly in the community
is slightly lower than among younger people, and geriatric
psychiatrists say they are struck by the resiliency and stoicism of
their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Blazer began seeing a 78-year-old man who had
been depressed for four or five years. ``He lost his wife about
eight years ago, and he thought all his problems were related to
the fact that he couldn't adapt to his wife being dead,'' Blazer
said. ``I told him I thought he was depressed, this wasn't just
grief.''
</P>
<P>
   The man's primary care physician had apparently made the
judgment that it was ``just grief,'' Blazer said. Blazer prescribed
Paxil and a brief course of psychotherapy. The depression has
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Doctor, I can't remember when I felt this
good,''' Blazer said. While his intense grief has abated, his wife
is hardly forgotten. ``He said, `When I think of my wife, I still
have pain.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
