<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST REBUKED BY VATICAN RESUMES PUBLIC SPEAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic priest, ordered by the Vatican to end his
ministry to gay and lesbian Catholics, has resumed public speaking,
saying he could do so, within limits, and still respect the
church's directive.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, the Rev. Robert Nugent of Maryland, had worked for
nearly three decades with Sister Jeannine Gramick, also of
Maryland, in reaching out to gay Catholics. But the church's
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith told them on July 13
that they were permanently prohibited from further pastoral work
with gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation, in charge of safeguarding doctrine, said
Nugent and Sister Gramick had not sufficiently emphasized church
teaching that homosexual acts are ``intrinsically disordered'' and
evil.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before he was to participate in a public forum
on homosexuals and religion at Northeastern University in Boston
last week, Nugent said he and leaders of his religious order
concluded that the Vatican directive did not bar him from public
speaking, such as giving lectures in an academic setting, even if
he could no longer hold workshops, retreats and discussions for gay
Catholics or their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' Nugent said, ``I'm not prohibited
from speaking, as long as it's not associated with a pastoral
setting'' and is open to a general audience.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent added that he had not been silenced, a punishment the
Vatican has applied against certain theologians that it considered
to have strayed from church doctrine. He can continue to write, he
said, although the directive states that he must seek approval from
his religious superiors before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent described his participation in the Boston event as his
first speaking engagement since receiving the Vatican directive. He
said he had thought and prayed about it before accepting the
invitation, because of the attention it might focus on him, not
because he thought it would violate the directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the effects of these things is self-censorship,''
Nugent said. ``Canon lawyers tell me these things must be
interpreted very narrowly.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I don't want to spend the rest of my life watching
everything I say and every step I take.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks in Boston, at a forum sponsored by the National
Conference for Community and Justice, an interfaith organization,
Nugent described the history of his and Sister Gramick's work, the
investigation by Catholic authorities and the Vatican's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Gramick has not spoken publicly about her response to the
directive. She said she had sent her thoughts about it to officials
of her order, the Baltimore Province of the School Sisters of Notre
Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now they're reflecting on my reflections,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
