<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: VIVA LAS VEGAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, Vegas _ I'm strolling down a cobblestone street, beneath
a cloud-speckled Paris sky. Past Le Village Buffet, past Napoleon's
cigar and cognac lounge, past Parcage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such word as `Parcage.' In France, we call it
`Parking,''' sniffs Francois, a French journalist covering the
opening of Paris, the $785 million hotel-casino that clones the
classy city of lights in the no-class city of neon.
</P>
<P>
   It boasts a Mini-Moi Eiffel Tower, half the size of the
original.
</P>
<P>
   Francois grimaces as a ``citizen,'' as the 4,000 Paris employees
are known, bicycles past with a basket of baguettes. He's wearing a
beret, a striped T-shirt and a red kerchief, and singing
``Alouette.''
</P>
<P>
   The French journalist continues le rant: ``It doesn't look like
a French building. The color of the roof is blue. In Paris, the
roofs are slate gray. And the gendarmes here are not in police
uniforms _ they're in Foreign Legion uniforms. And we don't put an
article in front of everything _ Le Journal, Le Cafe. It's not La
Boutique, it's Boutique. Everything is too shiny, too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Too shiny? Too much? Hey, Frenchie, it's Vegas!
</P>
<P>
   I came not to bury Caesars Palace, but to praise it. I loved the
old Vegas, the louche Vegas, the un-Disneyfied Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Casino chiefs began feminizing their hotels after focus groups
showed that men might decide to come to Vegas, but women choose
where to stay. More romance and shopping, less ring-a-ding-ding and
ka-ching, ka-ching.
</P>
<P>
   I was skeptical about the new fake European hotels: the
Venetian, with gondoliers crooning ``That's Amore!'' in a grand
canal in a mall; the Bellagio, with an eight-acre Lake Como adorned
with transplanted Italian trees, and fountains syncopated to Gene
Kelly songs; and now Paris, with the Arc de Triomphe and the
Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the old raffish Elvis/Rat Pack Vegas, more Scotch than
espresso, more steak than foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellagio has pink, flowered, fringed awnings over the gaming
tables. The Paris has Faberge-egg slot machines with Jacquepots and
gardenia-covered Eiffel Towers by the baccarat tables.
</P>
<P>
   What would Bugsy Siegel think of the Busch Gardenization of his
macho playground?
</P>
<P>
   But after two days in this world capital of unreality, I melted.
Its vices may be less straight-up, but it remains the most
deliciously deranged place on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of the cool city on the Seine with the brash city in
the desert is hilarious. Camus meets Andrew Dice Clay.
</P>
<P>
   It's the American way, really. If you don't have it, buy it.
Think of William Randolph Hearst, shipping boatloads of Renaissance
and Baroque artifacts to San Simeon. London Bridge, falling down,
was crated and sent to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Paris, Vegas, flies over its croissants from Paris, France,
daily.
</P>
<P>
   We can recreate France along our own fantasy lines, without its
bad plumbing and snooty airs. The hotel has Jilbere hair dryers,
and they're on the right electrical current.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone _ from the beefy trainer in the gym to the guy in a
black beret vacuuming the halls _ has been trained to speak a
soupcon of French. But they do it badly, nicely. So the tourist
feels superior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bone jer, come on tally view?'' sing-songs the maid, with a
big grin. ``That means `How are you?'''
</P>
<P>
   You never have to worry, as you do in the real Paris, about
feeling guilty that you are not cultivated enough. Paris, Vegas, is
the Inspector Clouseau of hotels. (``Have you seen my moonkey???'')
</P>
<P>
   It is one humongous Gallic cliche. Juggling mimes, accordion
players, street artists in red berets. Edith Piaf and Maurice
Chevalier on the sound system. Everything but a Vichy pavilion,
with tiny fake collaborators in Claude Rains trench coats.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that you can buy culture, the hotel paid French stars to
say nice things. At the opening party, Charles Aznavour and Michel
Legrand sang and Catherine Deneuve sparkled. (In a treasonous
moment, Ms. Deneuve snuck off to check out the Bellagio's more
upscale shops.)
</P>
<P>
   Let the real Parisians treat the casino with amused disdain. I
think it's positively magnifique to stand on the Lido and see the
Eiffel Tower rising along the banks of Lake Como.
</P>
<P>
   Call it globalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
