<HEADLINE>
GERMAN STATE VOTES SUNDAY, AND RIGHTISTS HOPE TO GAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAUEN, Germany _ ``And then,'' said Rene Farbig, 21, ``there is
the question of foreigners. It's not that we are against them, but
they don't adapt to German habits, they don't behave as they
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Farbig is an apprentice carpenter in this small town in the
eastern state of Brandenburg, where voting takes place Sunday in an
election heavily marked by the presence of the free-spending,
extreme-right Deutsche Volksunion.
</P>
<P>
   The party, backed by a millionaire Bavarian publisher, Gerhard
Frey, is hoping to benefit from disillusionment with the
center-left government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, which has
proved unable to dent an unemployment rate still running close to
20 percent in the former East German states, about double the
national level.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the eastern state of Saxony Anhalt last year, the
Volks-union showed its potential appeal, taking 13 percent of the
vote. In Brandenburg, the largest of the states of former East
Germany, it is unlikely to fare that well, but may qualify for the
state legislature for the first time by gaining over 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Farbig would not say if he intended to vote for the party, but
said he was disturbed by the number of foreigners in Brandenburg,
particularly Turks. ``The number is excessive, especially with our
unemployment,'' he remarked.
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, a small plane passed overhead trailing a banner
advertising the Volksunion, which has plastered towns throughout
Brandenburg with slogans like ``Criminal Foreigners Out,'' ``German
Money for German Jobs,'' ``Defend Yourself on Election Day'' and
``Less Money Abroad, More for Brandenburg.''
</P>
<P>
   Neo-Nazi violence has surged in Brandenburg recently. The
state's interior minister, Alwin Ziel, said last week that there
were 33 serious far-right attacks in the first half of this year, a
rise of 50 percent over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the year, an Algerian youth died in Guben while fleeing
a rightist mob, and in June, 11 African refugees were beaten by
thugs in the town of Cottbus. An African soccer player was forced
to leave the Cottbus club after being relentlessly taunted.
</P>
<P>
   Brandenburg has been a Social Democratic stronghold since East
Germany collapsed, and Schroeder's party won an absolute majority
of 54.1 percent in the last state elections in 1994. But that was
when the conservative Chancellor Helmut Kohl was still in power
nationally, and the Social Democrats could blame him for
Brandenburg's woes. Now the Social Democrats control the federal
government. Schroeder's popularity is at an ebb _ recent polls have
shown that less than 30 percent of the country approves of his
performance _ and the party's support is expected to fall by at
least 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Christian Democrats are widely expected to
gain ground. Polls give Kohl's party about 25 percent of the vote,
compared with 18.7 percent in 1994. The Party of Democratic
Socialism _ the former East German Communists _ is also expected to
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still vote Social Democrat because I'm a worker and I
believe it to be the workers' party,'' said Wilhelm Lussel, who
works in a machinery factory in Nauen. ``But Mr. Schroeder is
promoting this aggressive `elbow society' where money alone counts,
and we are not happy with him.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Social Democrats are punished in Brandenburg, and fail to
hang on to power in the western state of Saarbruecken, where voting
also takes place Sunday, Schroeder will look severely weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe that his hold on power is threatened, because his
coalition with the Greens appears firm for the moment. But with
elections in Saxony, Thuringia and Berlin looming in the next
several weeks, and an ambitious program of budget cuts and economic
reform awaiting application, Schroeder is by no means the ebullient
politician who swept to power a year ago under the slogan ``I am
ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
