<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-ELECTIONS-1100(     09-04 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-ELECTIONS-1100(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A RAMBLING SHOW OF INDIAN DEMOCRACY, NATIONAL ELECTIONS BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Indian national elections begin on Sunday,
and, as always, they are likely to be a great, if unwieldy, display
of democracy, this time requiring a month of voting and 800,000
polling locations for the 605 million people eligible to cast a
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But as impressive as Indian elections may be, they are becoming
too much of a good thing, with this being the third vote in 40
months, a result of fragmented and sometimes treacherous politics
that produce easy-to-disassemble coalition governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without one-party rule, I don't think any government will last
for long,'' said Mohammad Idris, a taxi driver interviewed in the
city of Hyderabad, expressing a common view among Indian voters.
</P>
<P>
   The current round of parliamentary elections became necessary
last April when an alliance headed by the Hindu nationalist
Bharatiya Janata Party lost its majority by a single vote. At the
time, it seemed that the Congress Party, the BJP's strongest
opponent, would be able to cobble together a majority of its own,
but that notion proved chimerical.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of the BJP has
been running an interim government, awaiting the elections, which
will require five stages. Voting will also take place on Sept. 11,
18 and 25 and on Oct. 3. Counting will begin only after the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   If pre-election polls are correct, the Hindu nationalists will
again end up leading a patchwork coalition, though one with more
seats in Parliament than before. Vajpayee will remain in charge. He
has succeeded in providing a kinder, gentler face for the BJP,
which has a longtime association with militant Hindu chauvinists.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the campaign has been without much Hindu-Muslim
friction, an ugly staple of Indian society. As in the last
election, the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party has set
aside the more controversial parts of its agenda _ for example
their call for the construction of a Hindu temple on the site of a
demolished mosque _ with an eye toward mustering a majority
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Akhtar Angadi, 21, a Muslim who works in a village tea stall,
said he intended to vote for the political party that is allied
with the BJP in the state of Andhra Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vajpayee is taking welfare measures,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   The electioneering has not been short on the incendiary,
however. Personal insults, impugned patriotism and general bombast
are in overabundant supply, so much so that on Thursday the chief
election commissioner, M.S. Gill, called for ``a cease-fire'' and
asked politicians ``to turn their attention to issues that matter
to us as a people.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born head of the Congress Party and
the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, has been ridiculed
for not being sufficiently Indian.
</P>
<P>
   In the most repeated of many verbal taunts, George Fernandes, a
BJP confederate and the nation's defense minister, asked: ``What is
her contribution to the nation _ the two children she gave birth
to? She has contributed two people to the 100 crore population of
our country. Is there anything else?'' (A hundred crore is 1
billion.)
</P>
<P>
   Pramod Mahajan, the minister of information and broadcasting,
was widely quoted with this barb: ``If we are so keen on having a
foreigner as PM, why not have Tony Blair, Bill Clinton or even
Monica Lewinsky?''
</P>
<P>
   Recent counterattacks by the Congress Party have focused on
Vajpayee's integrity. One allegation _ made so far with scant proof
_ is that he connived with the prime minister of Pakistan, the
nation that is India's archenemy, to import $214 million of
unneeded sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Kapil Sibal, a Congress Party spokesman, called the matter
``Sugargate'' and ``the scandal of the century,'' berating Vajpayee
for putting money into Pakistani pockets.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the maligning of personalities, commentators frequently
and sarcastically point out, actually comes from a dearth of
disagreement on more substantial matters. The two major parties hum
very similar tunes when it comes to economics and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is hard for politicians to find a message
with equally strong resonance across so varied a nation _ a country
of 1 billion people and a society made all the more complex by the
distinctions of caste and ethnicity and mother tongue. Seventeen
major languages are spoken in India in addition to an estimated
22,000 dialects. Four major religions began here.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 percent of the population lives in villages. News often
travels in stutter steps because of illiteracy and inaccessibility.
Parochial needs frequently predominate. Votes in a national
election are often cast because of a widened road or an extra food
subsidy. Regional parties have become kingmakers. Seventeen parties
currently have at least five members in the 545-seat Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be voting for the TDP,'' said S. Shankar, 40, a man who
washes clothes for a living in the city of Hyderabad. He was
referring to a state party allied with the BJP. ``The TDP
constructed a washing platform for us,'' he explained gratefully.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This year, only one issue seems to cut across all of India's
dividing lines. That is Kargil, the shorthand name for a 10-week
military operation in the frigid peaks of Kashmir that ended in
late July. The Indian army and air force overcame hundreds of
Pakistani-backed soldiers who had crossed into India and taken
mountaintop positions. The rugged terrain had to be recaptured foot
by foot.
</P>
<P>
   Heroic deeds fed national pride, and the BJP commends itself for
the victory. Vajpayee has tried to use Kargil to rally the diverse
electorate under the Hindu nationalist banner. ``The soldiers were
from all religions and regions, fought together and shed blood
together and everybody's blood was red,'' he said in a speech last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party candidates, for their part, praise the soldiers
while reproving the government, charging that there would have been
no need for heroism had there been proper surveillance of enemy
infiltration. Vajpayee is flayed for having made a bus trip last
February to Pakistan, once viewed here as a master stroke of
statesmanship but now widely seen as a sucker's bet that played
into the hands of Pakistani betrayers.
</P>
<P>
   The BJP is trying to fight the criticism head on. Its ads show
the 73-year-old prime minister at his grandfatherly best, staring
calmly, if resolutely, into the heavens. The wording says that
while he ``can travel far to shake a hand,'' he can also ``crush it
with a Kargil.'' He has ``the swiftness to nip mischief,'' it says,
and he has readied India with nuclear weapons and the missiles to
deliver them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1332EDT &QL; 
