u a BC-COLO-SCHOOLS-THREATS-     09-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOLS-THREATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE SCHOOLS NEAR LITTLETON GET LETTERS WITH THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: No byline) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Grappling with the aftermath of the April 20 massacre
at Columbine High School in Littleton, education officials say five
other high schools in the same district have received letters
threatening violence in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   And with the largest charitable fund for victims of the
shootings closing this week, the families of some victims say they
are dissatisfied with their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The new problems are only the latest to confront officials since
an attack by two teen-age gunmen left 15 people dead and dozens
injured in Littleton, a suburb of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   When classes at Columbine began on Aug. 16, swastikas were found
scratched into brick and paint at the school. Later in the week
officials found 4/20 scrawled on a bathroom wall. It was on that
date, Hitler's birthday, that two students, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, went on their fatal shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pranks are not just pranks,'' said Marilyn Saltzman, a
spokeswoman for Jefferson County school district. ``They're
serious. We are being very cautious this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, school officials sent a letter home with the 90,000
students in the school district alerting parents that five of the
17 high schools had received anonymous threats. Ms. Saltzman said
she could not discuss the contents of the threatening letters, but
one local newspaper reported that the letters warned, ``Columbine
was just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Ms. Saltzman said, security guards were added at
the five schools, the sheriff's department was asked to step up
patrols around all schools and parents and staff members were asked
to talk to students about the seriousness of threats.
</P>
<P>
   But as life at Columbine settles into a semblance of normality,
the threats at the other high schools were no cause for concern for
some who survived the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that everywhere, isn't it?'' said Richard Castaldo,
17. ``It doesn't really bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Castaldo, who uses a wheelchair after suffering a spinal cord
injury in the shooting, is returning to school on Tuesday for the
first time since the April 20 attack.
</P>
<P>
   Castaldo and his family will be among the final recipients of
money from the Healing Fund, the largest of about 30 charities
created to help victims after the shootings. It collected $4.4
million of the estimated $6 million that was donated to all the
funds. The bulk of the money collected by the Healing Fund has
already been distributed, and it will distribute the remaining $1.4
million this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never intended to be a perennial fund,'' said Kelley
Cahill, spokeswoman for Mile High United Way, which ran the Healing
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the families of the 12 students and one teacher slain
in the school received $50,000 each from the Healing Fund, and
relatives of four students left paralyzed or with brain injuries
received $150,000 each. Twenty-five other injured students received
$10,000 each. Community and service organizations received $1.6
million to assist with services like counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Any future donations to the Healing Fund will be forwarded to
the Colorado Organization for Victim Assistance, and a Jefferson
County school district Web site (www.spiritofcolumbine.org) is
providing a list of specific funds where donations can be sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that particular needs are understood, we know which
victims need certain kinds of care,'' Ms. Cahill said. ``The four
students with brain or spinal cord injuries will have lifelong
needs in terms of medical care. Money will go into trusts to meet
their future needs. In addition to those folks, some students face
more surgeries, such as one young man who has a bullet lodged near
his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some parents, it was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kirklin, whose 16-year-old son Lance was shot in the face,
said he did not have the money to pay the $229,000 medical bills
for the 28 days his son spent in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has been a real joke so far,'' he said of the
Healing Fund. ``The first payment of $5,000 was split between me
and my ex-wife, and the second went directly into a trust for
him.'' Kirklin is self-employed and did not have health insurance
at the time of the shootings. Lance has to undergo at least five
more surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Some criticism of the school district has come from within. Last
week, school board members complained when they learned that the
district was not participating in a study by the National Centers
for Disease Control of school-related homicides and suicides.
``We've had so many requests for documentaries, plays, studies, but
we believe this one has merit and we will review it again,'' Ms.
Saltzman said. ``Our goal has been to get back to normal operating
mode.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
