<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VAIL-HOUSING-DISPUTE-     09-04 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAIL-HOUSING-DISPUTE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING FOR POORER NEIGHBORS OFFENDS VAIL'S RICH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich, Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Battles over growth bedevil communities throughout
the country, but rarely have they generated such fury as they have
here in one of Colorado's premier ski resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Objections over plans to build affordable housing for people who
work in local hotels, shops and restaurants grew so heated this
summer that Mayor Rob Ford quit, two years before his term expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some of the meetings we had, things got so bad that I was
uncomfortable without an undercover police officer there to protect
me,'' Ford said. ``At times I thought guys were going to pop me
right there in Town Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is familiar in upscale resort towns. With Vail's
winter popularity sagging in recent years because of aging hotels
and intense competition from other ski resorts in Colorado and
beyond, officials outlined an economic plan to revitalize the town
center. The centerpiece is a new Marriott hotel, scheduled for
groundbreaking next summer. Other projects are under way.
</P>
<P>
   But new amenities mean more employees. And having more employees
means creating living space for them, a daunting challenge in a
town that is already 98 percent developed and where homes typically
cost $500,000 and more. When workers in resorts like Vail are
forced to find cheaper housing many miles away, the long commutes
persuade many of them to seek jobs closer to home, causing huge
employment needs at the resort during peak season.
</P>
<P>
   To reverse trends that allowed Breckenridge to overtake Vail
last year as Colorado's leading ski resort, Ford and the City
Council sought suggestions from the Vail community and later
identified about seven sites around town for new housing that would
cost under $200,000 per dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the trouble began, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   People living in the area of the planned construction began
objecting, he said, fearing that their property values would
plummet. Three groups have sued the city, all contending that town
officials are violating local tax laws by buying open land for the
new housing. One plaintiff, Charles Bernhardt, a carpenter, lives
adjacent to a prospective housing site but insisted, in an
interview, that his proximity to the site had nothing to do with
his decision to sue.
</P>
<P>
   At least lawsuits confront problems in a civil manner, contrary
to the demeanor of some other town residents, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one Christmas party, one of the Grand Dames of Vail came up
and lit into me,'' he said, without identifying her. ``She screamed
so loud that spit was going out of her mouth. I couldn't even
understand what she was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Other town residents have also made their feelings known, Ford
said. Recounting a conversation with Jack F. Kemp, the former
housing secretary who owns a home in Vail and was the 1996
Republican vice-presidential nominee, the mayor said Kemp
``expressed displeasure'' that any new housing might be located
near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Kemp said in an interview. Describing himself as a
strong supporter of affordable housing in Vail, he insisted that he
had never spoken with Ford about the housing issue and called the
mayor ``rather disingenuous'' for saying that they had talked.
``I've never said anything publicly or privately about this,'' Kemp
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also said John Glenn , the former Democratic senator from
Ohio and a Vail homeowner since 1980, complained to officials that
some of the housing might be located near him. ``It was
disgusting,'' Ford said of his letter.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn conceded that his letter was ``reasonably tough.'' But he
said his objections were solely based on assurances given when he
bought his mountainside condominium that the open area beside it
would not be developed. And even now, he added, he did not oppose a
housing project on the land so long as it did not block his view of
the valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought I was being snookered,'' Glenn said. ``I
thought they were changing the ground rules on me, and I wanted
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 48, said he came to Vail 25 years ago from Michigan for
the skiing and never left. He worked as a bartender and hotel clerk
and now sells real estate. He was elected to the seven-member City
Council in 1995, and in 1997 the Council voted him to be the mayor
for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Before the turmoil over affordable housing, he estimated that he
skied 75 to 80 days a year. For the last two years, skiing days are
down to 30. He plans to step down in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a politician,'' he insisted. ``I said I would be mayor
because I thought I could address Vail's problems, and I feel I
have met the objectives we set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the level of incivility is more than I'm willing to put up
with,'' he said. ``I like to ski, then sit down at the bar to drink
a beer and not have someone come up to me and complain. I want to
go back to skiing and being a nice guy again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
