<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Locally heavy rain will fall near the center of the remnants of
Tropical Storm Dennis as it moves north into central Virginia.
Moisture-laden air from over the Atlantic will be drawn into the
storm's circulation Sunday resulting in widespread rain amounts of
1 to 3 inches from northeastern North Carolina to eastern Virginia
and Maryland. Imbedded thunderstorms will result in flooding
downpours in some areas. Winds will be strong at times, especially
near exposed coastal locations where gusts over 35 miles an hour
will be common. High surf will exacerbate beach erosion near the
Middle Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, periods of rain will spread across Pennsylvania
to near the southern New England coast during the day. Clouds will
thicken elsewhere in New England and upstate New York. By Sunday
night and early Monday, locally heavy rain will reach central and
eastern Pennsylvania while lighter showers expand northward.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and unseasonably warm conditions will persist from Michigan
through most of the Ohio Valley and Southeastern states. Farther
west, a slow-moving cold front will be accompanied by a 100-mile
wide band of clouds and thundershowers from the western Great Lakes
to the southern Mississippi Valley and parts of the Southern
Plains. Behind the front, breezy and cool conditions will cover the
northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Tranquil weather and near seasonal afternoon temperatures will
cover most of the Western states. An approaching cold front will
bring clouds and few showers to the Washington Coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE END OF SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   Tradition designates the Labor Day weekend as the end of the
summer season. Because of the building reservoir of ocean warmth,
summer heat lingers long after June 22, the day when the sun is
highest in the northern hemisphere's sky. Astronomers will not
declare an end to summer until 7:31 a.m. EDT on Sept. 23 when the
direct rays of the noontime sun shift into the southern hemisphere.
Among the official keepers of climatological records, summer in the
northern hemisphere ended on Aug. 31, the last day of the three
warmest months of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
