<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-BORIS-STEFFI-2TAK     09-04 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BORIS-STEFFI-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECKER AND GRAF LEAVE BIG SHOES TO FILL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ More than just dominant tennis players, Boris Becker
and Steffi Graf were global phenomena, the rarest of athletes who
symbolized nationality and transcended it at the same time. Before
Becker and Graf came on the scene, Germans admired their
celebrities from a polite distance. As Becker and Graf rose to the
top of their professions, however, they became Boris and Steffi,
German cultural exports and symbols of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent editorial, a Berlin newspaper credited Becker and
Graf with nothing less than altering the self-image of Germans.
``Their success on the tennis court made Germans feel more like
individuals,'' Tagesspiegel wrote. ``Can tennis ever be the same
without them?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the unpleasant question that many Germans are asking.
Thanks to Boris and Steffi, Germany is now a tennis-loving country.
</P>
<P>
   Since Becker's first victory at Wimbledon in 1985, membership in
the German Tennis Federation has risen by almost 25 percent to 2.2
million in a country with a population of 80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the pro circuits, the ATP and the WTA, are also eager to
see Germany maintain its tennis tradition. Both invested a lot in
Germany during the Becker and Graf era.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP brought its World Championships, a tournament featuring
the best eight players of the year, to Germany 10 years ago at the
peak of Beckermania. Next year, the ATP moves the tournament from
Hanover to Portugal, and subsequently to rotating locations around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to move the tournament out of Hanover has nothing
to do with a lack of fan interest in Germany,'' said Nicola Arzani
of the ATP. ``We just felt that a world championship needed to play
in different places in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the other 12 ATP and WTA tournaments that take place in
Germany, six came into existence after Becker and Graf became
stars. Neither association is worried about the financial health of
these tournaments now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these tournaments are sold out,'' Arzani said.
``Germans loved Becker, but knew that his career was winding down.
The bigger test will be for the WTA tournaments, because Steffi was
still at the top of her game when she left.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, German stations broadcast an astounding 2,700 hours of
tennis. This year, that amount will sink to about 1,000 hours.
Germans no longer require an oversaturation of tennis. They are
already hooked. But they do require a winner.
</P>
<P>
   This year's U.S. Open, the first Grand Slam in the post-Becker
and Graf era, is a test of whether German tennis can maintain
momentum now that its two legends are gone.
</P>
<P>
   The men's game would not appear to be in crisis. Germany has a
pair of 21-year-olds ranked in the top 20, Tommy Haas at 14th and
Nicolas Kiefer at 15th. Both are on pace to qualify for the ATP
World Championships in November, a tournament featuring the best 14
players of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haas has what it takes to be a household name,'' said Joe
Favorito of the United States Tennis Association. ``His good looks
and tremendous game could take him as far as Becker.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrappy Kiefer is also on the ascent. But strong showings in
Toronto and Washington last month have been overshadowed at home by
his role in a verbal free-for-all that threatens to tear apart the
powerful German federation. The dispute involves the ever-present
Becker, who is manager of the German Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the team captain, Carl-Uwe Steeb, Becker has been
entrusted with maintaining the status of German tennis after his
retirement. A loss in the relegation series against Romania at the
end of September would thwart that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer sparked controversy when he announced last month that he
would not participate in the Romania series. Becker was furious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiefer's worldview begins and ends with himself,'' Becker
said. ``Everybody needs to pull themselves together and forget
their ego.''
</P>
<P>
   The animosity Becker and Kiefer feel toward each other dates
back several years to when the teen-age Kiefer quit Becker's junior
team. Since that time, the legend and his would-be successor have
not been on speaking terms. Those who know both men well say that
the problem stems from the fact that they are too similar, that
Kiefer shares the same stubborn individualism that Becker
practically invented 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tension was palpable when Becker thrashed Kiefer in straight
sets on center court at Wimbledon this year in what would prove to
be his penultimate victory before retirement. But since Wimbledon,
it is Kiefer who has given Becker fits.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the professional rivalry between Becker and Michael
Stich, which developed after Stich's Wimbledon victory over Becker
in 1991, the feud between Kiefer and Becker has exposed deeper
cracks within the infrastructure of German tennis. Even Haas and
Kiefer have stopped talking to each other. Wary of associating
himself with his controversial peer, Haas has chosen to speak out
for the honor of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why Kiefer backed out of the Romania
series,'' Haas said. ``I am always proud to play for Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas then uttered the words that show he understands the real
backdrop to the story: ``I guess Kiefer just can't come to terms
with the Becker clan.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer is not the only one. Dirk Horndorff, former vice
president of the German federation, also felt that Becker had
disproportionate control over German tennis. Horndorff wondered out
loud about Becker's duties as Davis Cup team manager. Irate that
his role was being questioned, Becker thrust a copy of his contract
into Horndorff's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see your contract,'' Horndorff shot back. ``I
want to know what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker gave the federation president, Karl Weber, an ultimatum:
discharge Horndorff or he will go. Although Weber acknowledged that
he and Becker have had problems recently, he dismissed Horndorff.
More awkwardness ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Rainer Schuettler, the player expected to replace Kiefer on the
Davis Cup team, is coached by Horndorff.
</P>
<P>
   A veil of silence has fallen over the federation as adversaries
and allies by convenience struggle for the soul of German tennis.
Two weeks ago, mass resignations among the group's executive
council over the Horndorff affair were narrowly averted when the
council decided to delay acting until after the Davis Cup matches
in September. Things remain Orwellian behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internal problems need to be settled internally,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The German women's game has been spared the ego clashes, but
harmony does not make up for the fact that Germany is plagued by a
serious talent gap now that Graf is gone.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of injuries, Anke Huber, 24, has climbed back to
27th in the WTA ranking, after peaking at fourth in the world in
1996. It is highly improbable, however, that Huber will be able to
fill the void left by Graf. As the only German woman ranked in the
top 50, Huber has not fared well at Flushing Meadows, losing in the
first round of the U.S. Open in two of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can replace Graf and Anke knows that,'' Weber said.
``She just has to play her game and not worry about being in
anyone's shadow anymore.'`
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of talent must rebuild Germany's reputation
on the women's circuit. Although she plans to work with several
talented juniors, Graf is not expected to take as much of a
leadership role at the professional level as Becker.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing junior is 13th-ranked Scarlett Werner, 15.
Weber said she has the talent _ not to mention the catchy first
name _ to bring her international attention in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is Kiefer and Haas who will chase hopes of filling
the vacated throne in German men's tennis. Haas is the darling of
the moment in Germany and Kiefer the villain. But a glimpse into
Becker's past should give Kiefer hope that lost image points can be
regained.
</P>
<P>
   Becker also feuded early in his career with his Davis Cup
captain, Jiri Bilic. His history teaches that winning can do
wonders for public relations. Still, it is hard to imagine that
either Haas or Kiefer will ever be treated like a hometown hero at
Wimbledon. They are not Boris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
