<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE CHIEF'S TEPID STAND HOBBLES HIS PARTY'S CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ It is not the best year to be the
presidential candidate of the governing Justicialist Party, with
Argentina sinking into recession, crime soaring and polls showing
that voters believe government corruption is rife.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the problems facing the candidate, Eduardo Duhalde,
who is now governor of Buenos Aires Province, is the ambiguous
support, if it can be called that, he is receiving from President
Carlos Saul Menem, the party's head.
</P>
<P>
   Lagging far behind his competitor, Mayor Fernando de la Rua of
Buenos Aires, in the polls, Duhalde said last week that the
opposition Alianza coalition had a secret plan to devalue the
Argentine peso that would destroy the economy. De la Rua denied
that he had devaluation in mind, saying he was committed to
Argentina's eight-year-old policy of pegging the peso one-to-one to
the American dollar.
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical heated campaign exchange with little import
until Menem said publicly that he believed de la Rua, putting an
end to the rumor and embarrassing Duhalde.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to recover, Duhalde assembled all the Justicialist
governors and party chiefs at a Buenos Aires convention hall last
week to propose an economic plan that would cut the value-added tax
from 21 percent to 15 percent, reduce taxes for businesses that
suspend planned layoffs, and give subsidies to small- and
medium-sized businesses. He challenged the opposition to join with
the Justicialists to approve the plan before the Oct. 24 election
because the country's economy was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's initial reaction was decidedly tepid. ``It deserves
consideration, but that's all,'' he said. ``We'll see whether it
should be implemented.'' After party leaders complained that Menem
appeared to be sabotaging the ticket, he grudgingly endorsed the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Even more embarrassing to Justicialist leaders have been press
reports that Menem's senior aides and top congressional supporters
have called reporters in recent weeks to suggest that Duhalde would
resign as the Justicialist candidate and be replaced by someone
with a better chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to the reports, but they underscored Duhalde's
weakness and the divisions in the party, which has had a stormy
history since it was founded by Juan Peron.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Menem and members of his Cabinet insist that they
fully support Duhalde, a contention many experts contest. ``Menem
has done all he can to damage Duhalde,'' said Joaquin Morales Sola,
a columnist for the paper La Nacion.
</P>
<P>
   Menem challenged Duhalde for the Justicialist nomination for
months until the courts and Congress resisted his attempts to
overturn a constitutional ban on his running for a third
consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   Menem has since announced that he would like to return to the
presidential palace in 2003, and his aides say he is willing to
challenge Duhalde in a primary to do it.
</P>
<P>
   A poll made public last week by Mora y Araujo and Associates, a
respected Argentine polling company, showed de La Rua, who is
running a cautious campaign with little flair, with 48 percent
backing to 29 percent for Duhalde. Domingo Cavallo, a former
economy minister running on a conservative third-party ticket,
received 9 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Media coverage of the campaign has been dominated in recent days
by accounts of how the Duhalde forces are trying to regroup and
find a winning message. Many articles have been suffused with
sarcasm, especially when it became public that Duhalde's running
mate, Sen. Ramon Palito Ortega, made a panicked trip to Israel to
seek spiritual guidance from a rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde was vice president during Menem's first term, but the
two have not been close for years. Duhalde rose in the polls
earlier in the year while distancing himself from Menem's
free-market economic policies, but more recently he has had nice
things to say about the president as he has attempted to unite the
Justicialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Menem has said he supports Duhalde, and he embraced him at a
recent public meeting. But Menem continues to tell reporters that
if he could have run for re-election, ``I would be the best
candidate of all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
