<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-HOLOCAUST-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS BANKS MAY BE FACING MORE HOLOCAUST PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Anxiety appears to be rising in Swiss banking circles
that a long-awaited report from a commission seeking Holocaust-era
accounts may recommend that banks pay out more than the $1.25
billion agreed to in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss newspaper reported Saturday that a letter signed last
month by two high-level bankers reflected fears that the
commission, headed by the former Federal Reserve chairman, Paul
Volcker, would call for a new program to restore unclaimed funds
from Swiss bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   This would be in addition to the August 1998 deal agreed on by
Switzerland's two largest banks to settle claims that they had
profited from dealings with Nazi Germany and from holding onto
accounts of Jews killed in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was set up in 1996 in the wake of charges that
the Swiss banking community had hoarded money stashed in
Switzerland, a neutral country, by Jews who were later killed by
Hitler's henchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last week, the Volcker commission indicated that it
would wrap up its search and issue a final report by the end of
November, the same time that an independent commission of
historians is supposed to release its findings on the country's
treatment of wartime refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland has been accused of turning refugees away at its
borders, thus sending them to a certain death in Nazi Germany, and
the upcoming report is expected to review all historical records
and come to some conclusions about Switzerland's role.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, the Volcker commission's four
auditing groups have checked millions of names for possible links
to accounts that had been established in Swiss banks between 1933
and 1945. It has investigated 61 banks, provoking complaints by
some banks earlier this year that the search was too expensive and
had gone on too long.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The commission's activities are separate from the billion-dollar
1998 settlement between Holocaust victims and Switzerland's two
largest banks, UBS A.G. and the Credit Suisse group. That accord,
generally unpopular in Switzerland, was viewed as bowing to threats
of boycotts of the Swiss banking sector, an important part of the
country's economy and prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss disdain for the deal, coupled with the high price tag, has
made bankers particularly anxious that the Volcker commission might
add to their debt. Working out arrangements, under the supervision
of a U.S. district court judge, for the disbursement of the $1.25
billion took months. At the end of June, a campaign to inform
victims of Nazi persecution, began in 40 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss newspaper, Le Temps, said that top-level bankers from
UBS and Credit Suisse, together with the head of the Swiss banking
association, had sent the letter on Aug. 27 to Volcker, expressing
concern that he and his aide, Michael Bradfield, would put in place
a program parallel to the $1.25 billion settlement, and that a
Jewish organization was considering it.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, the newspaper said, was signed by Marcel Ospel, who
heads the UBS group, and Lukas Muhlemann, his counterpart at Credit
Suisse group, and George Krayer, president of the Swiss Banking
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the letter was not available, and the letter's
signers could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Volcker commission, officially called the Independent
Committee of Eminent Persons, has uncovered 62,000 accounts with
possible links to Nazi-era victims, the newspaper reported. Of
these, 2,800 have been matched with the names of Holocaust victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-ISLAND-NATIONS-4     09-04 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ISLAND-NATIONS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A U.N. SPECIAL SESSION ON CLIMATIC THREATS TO ISLAND NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ For more than a decade, several dozen small
island nations threatened by rising seas and increasingly violent
weather have been awaiting the world's attention as they face
forces well beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27 and 28, they will get a chance to air their fears in
a special session of the General Assembly. Their leaders say the
time has come to go beyond reciting statistics to demonstrate the
human toll that climate changes are already taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learn from the scientific community does not give us a
great deal of comfort,'' said Tuiloma Neroni Slade, Samoa's
representative at the United Nations and chairman of the Alliance
of Small Island States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we certainly know is that in the low-lying areas,
the sea has claimed our burial grounds,'' he said. ``That, of
course, reflects the smallness of the available territory. But it
also says that areas that are so very close to families and
communities are being invaded. It is the beginning of that loss to
communities that we fear.''
</P>
<P>
   To compound the natural disasters, Slade said, the smallest
nations now face a loss of trade concessions that sustained their
agricultural economies. Recent World Trade Organization rulings
made in the name of liberalization are cutting trade preferences,
especially in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism, which many island nations turned to as a rapid money
earner, is no longer a panacea for several reasons, cultural and
environmental. But the greatest threat to this industry may also be
coming from the sea, Slade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no escaping a hurricane that decides to hover over a
relatively small land mass,'' he said. ``In an industry like
tourism, hotels are often destroyed. It takes a long time to
rehabilitate.'' Beaches and reefs are also disappearing, and
biodiversity is being lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Climate change is already taking effect in terms of some of
the life support systems,'' he added. ``For instance, in the
Maldives, there is infiltration of fresh-water reserves by sea
water. In many places, there is a degree of brackishness in the
drinking water. You can see this in the Caribbean. You can
certainly see this in the Pacific. Fresh-water reserves have been
contaminated. Whether it is a storm surge or the sea rising, the
waters get into the fresh water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Climate change is the type of global issue not of our making,
so it raises questions of equity and ethics,'' he said, adding that
the island nations will once again ask that larger nations cut back
on their use of fossil fuels that heat the atmosphere.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Slade said that the island nations, often guided by
international experts, initially tried to build barriers against
the oceans. This is no longer realistic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural protective action is to set up walls against an
invading sea,'' he said. ``It is quite physically impossible and
also economically impossible for any one country or group of
countries to undertake this. There are certain things we can do to
adapt, but we cannot hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Several envoys of island nations said that global economic
liberalization is hitting them just after they have diversified
agricultural economies and begun to introduce small-scale
industries, including textiles. These small-volume farming and
factory products cannot compete in world markets. The 42 nations
and territories represented this month at the special session,
occurring five years after the first conference on small island
states in Barbados, are expected to ask for better advice and
concrete relief measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
