<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-2000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EARLY START FOR THE POLITICAL PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   For some, the year 2000 campaign season is starting one Labor
Day too soon. In this conventional view, all political races,
especially on the presidential level, are overly protracted. The
electoral process wearies the citizenry, we are told. Voters are
said to be tired of a permanent campaign kept on life support by
the news media, political consultants, pollsters and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point in 1999, New Yorkers and Americans in general
seem to be enjoying a political parade featuring Rudy versus
Hillary, the meteoric rise of the latest Bush and the low-charisma
showdown between Al Gore and Bill Bradley. It may also be that,
especially in the presidential nominating race, there is a good
civic purpose in getting interested early. In six months, it could
be over. In campaign time, that half-year will be shortened by the
holidays in December and the hurrah over the new millennium in
January.
</P>
<P>
   This ``big bang'' theory of presidential primary politics was
created by the vigorous me-first competition among the primary
states. The scramble to be an early primary led to
``front-loading,'' meaning a knot of early primaries tilting the
whole process to the start of the season. The race to be first
became so intense that the New Hampshire Legislature recently
decided to maintain the state's position as the first 2000 primary
even if they had to move their Election Day into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This early cluster of votes has also driven an early stampede of
fund-raising. The Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, is expected to amass more than $50 million by the end of
September, freeing him from public money and its limits. Four years
ago, the eventual Republican nominee, Bob Dole, had raised about
$19 million.
</P>
<P>
   Being early has always counted for something in presidential
politics, although not all early candidates do well on energy
alone. Tennessee's Lamar Alexander, who recently ended his run as a
semipermanent GOP candidate, comes to mind here. More successful
early risers include Jimmy Carter, who locked in the Iowa caucuses
before most voters had even heard he was in the race. Ronald Reagan
started his winning 1980 campaign shortly after he lost the
nomination in 1976. President Clinton's 1996 general election
campaign really began in the summer of 1995, spending mostly soft
money in what ultimately became a $50 million ad campaign. By the
time the Republicans got their act together, it was really too
late.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Labor Day 1999. This is the time to inspect
the choices. In New York's Senate race, the public might as well
start vetting the candidates, because neither Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani nor first lady Hillary Clinton is likely to be tested by
primary opposition. On the presidential side, it is time to start
asking Bush about more than his youthful cavorting. Potential
voters need to know how he would tackle health care, trade issues,
the next Kosovo. This is also the time to sort out the Democratic
differences between Gore and Bradley. The National Association of
Secretaries of State, one group trying to stop the primary
front-loading, has suggested that each party hold at least one
presidential debate this fall. For this year, at least, that does
not feel too soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
