<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KING-COUNTY-DEBATE-AR     09-04 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-COUNTY-DEBATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SYMBOLIC IDEA, BUT AT WHAT COST? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ King County Council member Larry Gossett believes
Seattle and its surrounding county have a great secret to share
with the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living here in Martin Luther King Jr. County, and nobody
seems to know it,'' said Gossett, a Democrat. ``When I tell
visitors who this county is named for, I cannot begin to tell you
the joy and excitement that people feel, the surprise and
disbelief, also. It's, `Wow! We didn't know that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the issue of the county's name, which is 147 years
old, is not quite that simple. And a recent proposal by Gossett to
change the county's logo to include a likeness of King, the civil
rights leader who was slain in 1968, has revived a debate over an
unusual action taken by the County Council 13 years ago, when it
officially voted to change the county's namesake, but not its name.
</P>
<P>
   As Council member Chris Vance, a Republican who is skeptical of
Gossett's proposal, put it: ``This county is not named after Martin
Luther King Jr. We all like to pretend it is, but it's really
not.''
</P>
<P>
   King County was originally named in 1852 for William Rufus
Devane King, a slaveholding senator from Alabama who, by all
historical indications, never got anywhere near the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to curry favor in its bid for statehood with the
incoming White House, the Oregon Territorial Legislature gave a
territorial division where Tacoma is located the name Pierce
County, after the new president-elect, Franklin Pierce. And it
named the county to the north after King, the vice president-elect.
</P>
<P>
   King was seriously ill with tuberculosis during the campaign,
and he never even made it to Washington, D.C., for his swearing-in.
He went to Havana, for convalescence, and under a special act of
Congress, he was sworn into office there by the American consul. A
few weeks later, he went to his plantation in Alabama, where he
died on April 18, 1853.
</P>
<P>
   A historian of the nation's No.-2 office, Sol Barzman, once
wrote of King: ``Of all the inglorious and unknown vice presidents,
the 13th must surely lead the list.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remained that the county in which Seattle and a
considerable ring of suburbs are located was named for this
forgettable figure, whom even Vance referred to once as ``William
Rufus Whatever Devane King.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the case until 1986, when the County Council,
on a 5-4 vote, passed a resolution decreeing that King County
should henceforth be considered named for Martin Luther King, not
William King.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over that vote grew a bit raucous, as one opposing
Council member urged her colleagues to ``leave the historical
record alone'' and a few Seattle residents even attended the
Council meeting to speak up for the late Alabamian. One called him
a ``marvelous man'' who cared deeply about adequate housing and
``proper nutrition'' for his slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also said that King County residents believed
that ``the ownership of another human being is an injustice against
humanity'' and indicated that the county did not wish to be named
for a slaveholder anymore. But opponents questioned that part of
the resolution as well, noting that the state of Washington is
itself named for a slaveholder, President George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution had little practical effect, and no change was
made in the county's logo, which, evoking the word ``king,''
depicts a gold crown.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to 1999, and the recent proposal by Gossett, the
only African-American on the 13-member Council, to revise the logo
to include a depiction of the civil rights leader and Nobel Peace
Prize winner.
</P>
<P>
   That means an image of King would appear on the logo, the flag,
on county cars and buses, and on official documents and stationery.
</P>
<P>
   Just how the Council, which consists of seven Republicans and
six Democrats, will handle the matter remains unclear. So far,
there is no strong opposition: Even Vance said he might well vote
in favor of the change _ if it can be phased in to minimize its
cost and if the state Legislature, which he contends is the proper
authority to approve any changes in the county name (or namesake)
to begin with, passes some sort of measure certifying that the
county is, indeed, named for Martin Luther King.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, there does not seem to be wild enthusiasm
for the idea, at least not yet. Several Council members raised the
issue of the cost of the logo change, to pay for things like new
stationery and repainting buses, and noted that the county could be
in for a major round of budget cuts if a controversial statewide
tax-reduction measure known as Initiative 695 is approved by voters
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``As important as symbols are, this could wind up being a very
low priority compared to the delivery of services,'' said Maggi
Fimia, a Democratic Council member. ``The ones that could be most
affected by budget cuts are the very people that Martin Luther King
spoke for.''
</P>
<P>
   And King County Executive Ron Sims, who is black and was a chief
proponent of the namesake change in 1986, is noncommittal on the
proposal as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to take a look at what it all means,'' said a
spokeswoman for Sims, considered a likely candidate for statewide
office in the future. ``Cost is definitely an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gossett is forging ahead, and, as his proposal notes,
changing the logo means that Seattle would fly three flags
representing the community's diversity, with images of ``President
Washington, an Anglo-American; Chief Sealth, a Native American, and
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., an African-American'' on the
state, city and county flags, respectively. There are about 1.7
million people in King County, 5.5 percent of them black.
</P>
<P>
   And even as he frets over the legalities and historical
revisionism involved, Vance concedes that he finds the proposal
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if we could start all over from scratch, I'd wish
this county were named for Martin Luther King Jr.,'' he said.
``Clearly, he's a much more important historical figure, a better
role model, a better symbol for these times than William Rufus
Devane King.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
