<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     09-04 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LEGENDARY LEMON DROP KID LIVES ON THROUGH A
3-YEAR-OLD COLT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Capone was sitting in a steambath in Chicago one day when a
stranger struck up a conversation. The stranger talked glowingly of
an impending business deal and said that if mum was the word,
Scarface, er, Al, could make a quick killing, so to speak. All
Capone had to do was lend the stranger $2,000 until later.
</P>
<P>
   Capone gave the man the money, but later he never arrived.
Capone sent two men to locate the con man and bring him back to
Capone's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you pick on me?'' asked the incredulous Capone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pick on you,'' replied the stranger. ``You picked on
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Capone was supposedly so charmed that he called to his wife,
``Mae, set another plate for dinner. We've got a guest.''
</P>
<P>
   The stranger was a man named Harry Morgan, called Swifty, but
better known as the original Lemon Drop Kid, whose namesake, a
3-year-old colt, won the Travers Stakes at Saratoga last Saturday,
earning $600,000, after his triumph in the Belmont Stakes in June.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan flourished from the 1930s to the '60s. Jimmy the Greek,
in his autobiography of the same name, wrote that Morgan was ``one
of the premier con artists of my time, and the time before that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like con men generally, Morgan was a charming extrovert. A man
of wit and dash. A short man's man, a ladies' man, debonaire and
daring. ``It seemed,'' said a friend, producer Dave Siegel, ``that
people liked giving Swifty money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember once we were at a race track and the financier Lou
Wolfson walked by and stuffed $500 in Swifty's pocket,'' Siegel
said. ``He was funny, Swifty was, and fun to be around, and listen
to.'' (The guess here is that Wolfson, rather than be intrigued by
a Swifty scam, took the easy way out.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Morgan known among marks and the con cognoscenti,
but the Kid had also been featured on stage, screen and in
literature. The short story ``The Lemon Drop Kid'' by Damon Runyon
related the tale of a race-track tout.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, Runyon wrote that the Kid's tales were compelling
even to ``prominent citizens,'' ``especially if the tale has any
larceny in it, because it is only human nature to be deeply
interested in larceny.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyon's short story was later made into a movie starring Bob
Hope as Swifty (who snacked from an ever-present bag of lemon drops
in his pocket). The Kid was also a featured character in Runyon's
``Guys and Dolls,'' and in the autobiographical movie of Joe E.
Lewis, ``The Joker Is Wild,'' starring Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   When Sinatra, struggling to make a comeback in the early 1950s,
was producing ``Joker,'' he asked Swifty how much money he wanted
for rights to use his character. Swifty said with magnanimity and
foresight, ``Take care of me when you can.'' Sinatra did, for many
years paying for a room for him in the exclusive Beverly Wilshire.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Vance, owner of the current Lemon Drop Kid, said she had
admired a show horse in the 1950s named Lemon Drop Kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was named for the character in the Runyon story,'' she
said. ``I thought that my horse resembled the other not in color _
the first one was a chestnut, mine's a bay _ but in personality.
They're both kind, but don't push 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Vance said she did not know the original, Swifty Morgan. But
this correspondent had made his acquaintance, as the saying goes.
It was in a nursing home in Los Angeles in 1975. The Kid was then
91 years old, lying in the middle of three beds in the convalescent
room. He was small and frail and on public welfare. He wore a
little white beard, and had few teeth left, but his eyes were still
alert.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the time he asked actor George Raft for a pair of
his initialed cuff links on loan. Raft agreed, though he didn't
know why Swifty wanted them. That night, Raft had a date with a
rich woman. Swifty showed up at their table, and when Raft excused
himself for a moment Swifty sold the woman the ``GR'' cuff links so
she could give them to George as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   But for a man who lived with the elan he had, who had traveled
first class to Europe and back 38 times on ocean liners, it must
have been an indignity to be told that he must use toilet paper
instead of the more costly tissue paper to wipe his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Swifty had learned to make the best of any situation. At one
point in my visit, he pointed to the fire extinguisher on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open that bottle of Scotch and take a drink,'' said the Lemon
Drop Kid, with customary charm. ``Pour one for the nurse, too.''
</P>
<P>
   While Swifty Morgan is no longer with us, he would have surely
enjoyed knowing that the Lemon Drop Kid is still having his way at
the track.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
