old men sitting on shady street corners, filling the radio
airwaves, cropping up in news articles on everything from politics
to business and culture. Mainland Americans call it the
``statehood'' issue because they think it's a simple question of
whether Puerto Rico should become the 51st state. For Puerto
Ricans, boiling things down to a simple up or down vote on
statehood doesn't do justice to the complex mix of history,
culture, principles and emotions that most of this vibrant island's
residents bring to the discussion of what they call ``status.''
(Williams, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED TUESDAY.
