<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONGRESS TO ACT ON BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fighting any suggestions of a lame-duck presidency,
Bill Clinton challenged Republicans Saturday to approve an
ambitious fall agenda that includes gun-control proposals, a
patients' bill of rights and measures to fix up old schools, hire
more teachers and end the practice of promoting children to the
next grade even if they are failing.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton cast the Congress, which
returns to Washington after Labor Day, as sitting on all of these
matters while the nation waits.
</P>
<P>
   He made the argument most pointedly on the matter of gun
control. Noting that nearly five months have passed since the
school shootings at Columbine High School in Colorado, Clinton
said: ``I'm still waiting, and America is still waiting, for
Congress to act. It shouldn't take another tragedy to shake them
from the summer slumber.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would send a letter Saturday to the Republican
leaders in Congress urging them to approve ``a balanced, bipartisan
juvenile crime bill that closes the gun-show loophole, requires
child safety locks for guns, and bans the importation of
large-capacity ammunition clips.''
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential campaign begins to heat up, many candidates
are putting education at the top of their agendas, and Clinton is
staking out the same turf. He taped his radio address at the
Waterman Elementary School in Skaneateles, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
