u a BC-CALIF-TEXAS-SMOG-NYT &LR;      09-04 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TEXAS-SMOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES LOSES DUBIOUS DISTINCTION: WORST SUMMER SMOG DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A brown haze persistently shrouds the downtown
skyline, an ever-present reminder of the pollution that chokes this
city. But this year residents are breathing a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in decades _ going back at least 25 years to
when records were first kept _ there have been no full-blown smog
alerts in the four-county South Coast Air Basin, and the area has
relinquished its hold on having the worst smog day of the summer.
That title went to Texas City, Texas, which was followed closely by
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of the long-term trend of reducing
emissions from all sources as well as the weather,'' said Sam
Atwood, a spokesman with the South Coast Air Quality Management
District, the pollution control agency that covers two-thirds of
Los Angeles County, all of Orange County and the western sections
of Riverside and San Bernardino Counties. ``This summer, unlike the
rest of the country, has been pretty darn nice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, that means relatively cool with few temperature
inversions that trap the gases that help make the region the
smoggiest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice news for people that breathe in Los Angeles. They
deserve a break,'' said Felicia Marcus, administrator for the
Environmental Protection Agency region that includes California.
``But it's not something I would get that excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles still has the worst air in the country, exceeding
the federal standard regulating ozone, or smog, on 62 days this
year as of Sept. 1. Still, there has been a steady decline of air
pollutants in the region.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Environmental Protection Agency found that
Texas City, about 30 miles east of Houston, had the highest
one-hour concentration of ozone, which is created when hydrocarbons
and nitrogen oxides are heated by sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Texas City, which had a one-hour concentration of ozone of .206
parts per million, was followed closely by Houston. Then came
Westport, Conn.; Galveston, Texas; White Plains, N.Y., and
Crestline, Calif., in the Los Angeles region. Federal health
standards mandate that the ozone concentration be no more than .120
parts per million, with health advisories issued when the level
reaches .150 and a Stage 1 alert at .200.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from this year, the Los Angeles basin typically leads the
country in both the number of bad air days and the worst day.
</P>
<P>
   The South Coast Basin faces serious challenges when it comes to
air pollution. It has more cars traveling more miles than in any
other part of the country, in a warm, sunny environment that
fosters the creation of smog. The problem is complicated further by
the basin's geography, with mountains on three inland sides.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the population between 1980 and 1997 increased
37 percent to more than 14 million. The number of miles being
traveled on roadways increased 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those increases, the South Coast Basin has been able to
reduce emissions significantly, leading to decreases in ozone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take credit and be pleased with the progress we've
made,'' said Tim Carmichael, executive director of the Coalition
for Clean Air, an environmental group based in Los Angeles. ``We
also have to remember we're a long way from clean air, and it's
going to take considerable effort from individuals as well as
businesses to get clean air in this region and, for that matter,
all the metropolitan regions of this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1440EDT &QL; 
