<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-04 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TAKING THE MENTAL SUBWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not that New Yorkers need any excuse to indulge in feverish
hyperbole, but we are discussing a Subway Series as if it were our
divine right.
</P>
<P>
   The very phrase ``Subway Series'' tells you everything you need
to know about New Yorkers. We are the center of the universe. You
got a problem with that?
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in very early September and the Mets have no
guarantee that they will hold on to a wild-card position, what with
six games left against Atlanta. And the subway doesn't run to
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no wonder people are excited. New York has not come this
close to a Subway Series since 1956, because when the Mets were up,
the Yankees were generally down, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   The general assumption from old geezers (that is to say, anybody
six months older than me) is that baseball was better back in 1949
through 1956, when there were six _ count 'em, six _ Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   Back in those glory days, legend has it, New Yorkers congregated
jovially on street corners and argued the relative merits of
Charlie Silvera, Sal Yvars and Rube Walker (second-string catchers;
you thought I was going to resort to the Mickey-Willie-and-the-Duke
cliche?).
</P>
<P>
   My own opinion about a 1999 Subway Series is that it would beat
anything from that hallowed age. It says here that the collective
buzz from the goofy guys making asinine puns on the television
sports centers and the new breed of yappers on talk radio (Imagine:
``Dawg, dey gotta get dat Hodges outta dere. He's killin' duh
Dodgers!'') and the blizzard of sites on the Web would whip New
York into a baseball frenzy it has never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Real New Yorkers with no particular affinity for baseball would
nevertheless be flicking Mets or Yankees ball caps onto their
noggins faster than some carpetbagger senatorial candidate.
</P>
<P>
   People would get all pumped about a Subway Series, because they
would be instructed that it is huge.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that kids in New York would experience a
smaller portion of the Subway Series than we did when they played
the World Series in daylight in early October. (Which is why they
call them the good old days.) We would rush home from school and
catch the last four or five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the geniuses who run baseball start World Series games
after 8 p.m. Eastern time, even when Eastern teams (Toronto and
Philadelphia, Cleveland and Florida, Atlanta and the Yankees) are
playing. Given the wretched four-hour trudge of baseball games
these days, this guarantees that New York kids would be nodding off
by the fourth inning, and would never get to see Mariano Rivera
pitching to John Olerud with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The kids would have to play catch-up in the morning,
understanding that a Subway Series is special, even if cleverly put
beyond their bedtimes by baseball's marketeers.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand the sense of entitlement in New York. From
1921 through 1956, there were 13 Subway Series involving the
Yankees and either the Giants or the Dodgers. Chicago, by contrast,
has had exactly one Subway Series _ in 1906 _ and had to resort to
inventing Michael Jordan to make up for this deficit. Philadelphia
and Boston have subways but never had a Subway Series when they had
two teams. The Bay Area had a Bay Area Rapid Transit series in 1989
that was so good, the earth shook.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and what was the first World Series totally west of the
Mississippi River? Trick question. It was the Browns and the
Cardinals in 1944. And St. Louis did not have a subway back then.
</P>
<P>
   Given the history, you can understand why New Yorkers
automatically think Cleveland and Arizona and all those other
poseurs are going to fall flat into a swoon. A Subway Series may
not be inevitable, but there is every reason to think the earth
would shake. The Subway Series is a big deal, although it does
require a certain amount of masochism to dredge up personal
memories from the golden age.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, I was a tyke raking leaves li3tening to Red Barber on
the radio when Cookie Lavagetto broke up Bill Bevens' no-hitter
with a game-winning double. I was too young to remember who won
that Series.
</P>
<P>
   I do remember the 1949 Series, rushing home from school to hear
Tommy Henrich's game-winning homer off Don Newcombe, but the rest
of the Series is a blur.
</P>
<P>
   My 1951 memories are stuck on Oct. 3, the single most epic
baseball game played between New York teams. Maybe it wasn't a
Subway Series, but it surely was judgment day.
</P>
<P>
   All of 34,320 fans bought their way into the Polo Grounds as the
Giants played the Dodgers in the third game of the National League
playoff. That's right. There were 20,000 empty seats that weekday
afternoon, although a dozen collectors will sell you Bobby
Thomson's home run ball, complete with Ralph Branca's fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   Giants fans and Dodgers fans fought over that game, while Yankee
fans, perennially smug, sat back and said, wasn't it a shame about
Don Mueller's broken ankle and the chewed-up Giant pitching staff?
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, I vaguely recall Billy Martin making a racing catch of
Jackie Robinson's elusive popup in the seventh inning of the
seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, my father got me a ticket for my first World Series
game. Seated in the center-field bleachers of Ebbets Field, I saw
Mickey Mantle's grand slam get bigger and bigger and bigger. ...
aw, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 4, 1955, I was benched at halftime so I sat on the
Jamaica High bench at Bushwick High in Brooklyn and listened to
bells going off all over the borough of churches. Finally, there
was a Subway Series in which the good guys won.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, I listened to a car radio as Dale Mitchell took a
called third strike to complete Don Larsen's perfect game. From my
perfect vantage point, that ball was outside the strike zone.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They haven't had a Subway Series since, which makes New Yorkers
fantasize in this season of Derek Jeter and Robin Ventura, this
year of El Duque and Fonzie.
</P>
<P>
   Subway Series? Given the fat-cat profile of people who wangle
strips of expensive tickets for the World Series, this will be a
limousine series. But alliteration is nice, so go with it. Subway
Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
