<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: HANDS-ON EXECUTIVE RAISES METS' PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Phillips is easy to find on the field before
the Mets play at Shea Stadium and easier to find in Manager Bobby
Valentine's office after games. The general manager is predictable
in these ways and in how he likes to maintain control and keep
track of what is lurking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Phillips will initiate interviews even if no
reporters request one. He takes pains to wait for virtually every
reporter to assemble before he speaks. It is part of the way
Phillips assures that his voice, not Bob Murphy's, is the voice of
the Mets (with some room for utterances from Valentine).
</P>
<P>
   These are rewarding times for Phillips, who helped mold the Mets
into an impressive team that should qualify for the postseason for
the first time since 1988. The Mets have the best infield in the
major leagues. They have one of the best bullpens. They have
superstars in Mike Piazza, Robin Ventura and the still-improving
Edgardo Alfonzo, and they have a manager whose decisions in games
are well conceived.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Mets have a general manager who is shrewd and
who has put them in position to snare a World Series. Phillips
constantly praised his scouts and his assistants as he reviewed the
moves that have worked splendidly in 1999, but he was being too
humble. If Ventura were batting .220 or Alfonzo flopped at second
or Rickey Henderson strained another hamstring, the scouts would
not be roasted. Phillips would be. When the Mets are lauded,
Phillips deserves plaudits, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to watch now,'' Phillips said. ``But at this point,
you don't take the games personally. You take them for the
organization. I think that's the way everybody feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, in the midst of revamping the Mets, Phillips
could not be sure if he would ever be part of the results. He had
larger issues. Phillips had to take a leave of absence to deal with
an allegation of a sexual harassment and the repercussions of a
series of extramarital affairs. It was a painful time for Phillips
and his wife, Marni, and an awkward time for the Mets, who brought
back Frank Cashen, their former general manager, to handle
Phillips' duties.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-day leave in which Phillips underwent ``extensive
personal counseling'' and admitted that he had caused ``a
significant wound in my family life,'' he returned. But Phillips
emphasized that his return did not mean his family situations had
been mended and admitted that it would be a ``lengthy process''
with uncertain results.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips does not want to elaborate on the process or the
results. With the Mets churning toward games in October, Phillips
was asked if he felt good about making it back to this point after
such a public display of his personal problems. The man who speaks
in paragraphs edited himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is not to comment on it,'' Phillips said. ``It
just opens it up completely. I regret having answered a question
about it a couple of months ago, and I don't think I want to go
back down that road.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Phillips' prerogative. Those issues are really between
him and his wife. It is hoped, for their sake, they have found
peace and somehow strengthened their relationship. It is hoped that
these are happier times.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips started the Mets' off-season by aggressively pursuing
Piazza and then signing him to a seven-year, $91 million contract.
The Mets probably overpaid, but Piazza meant more to them than he
would have to any other team. They had to have him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it really has helped change the perception of the
organization,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Piazza suddenly fell in love with New York, some other
crucial pieces were added. The Mets signed Al Leiter and Dennis
Cook, and they used Todd Hundley to obtain Armando Benitez from
Baltimore and Roger Cedeno from Los Angeles in a three-team trade.
When Hundley's aching elbow prevented him from playing much as a
catcher in the spring, Phillips looked smart for not clinging to
him.
</P>
<P>
   A day after trading Hundley, the Mets made perhaps the best
free-agent signing of this season or any other by giving Ventura a
four-year, $32 million deal. It enabled the Mets to switch Alfonzo
to second base, where his offensive numbers glow, and gave them a
Gold Glove third baseman with a sweet swing. Both Alfonzo and
Ventura are serious candidates for the Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it ended up falling for us and the way that we ended
up being configured, it couldn't have worked out any better,''
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Some other additions have produced, from Henderson to Pat
Mahomes to Orel Hershiser. Phillips also acquired Darryl Hamilton,
Kenny Rogers, Shawon Dunston, Chuck McElroy and Billy Taylor for
the pennant push, which is three good and two bad. Instead of
getting Bobby Bonilla for Mel Rojas, Phillips should have eaten
Rojas' contract.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is difficult to watch the Mets and not see Phillips'
influence. This is Valentine's team, but it is the team Phillips
was instrumental in giving him and the team they discuss in the
manager's office after each game. You can count on it. Phillips
will be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
