<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HOPING REPLACEMENTS FOR CHREBET CATCH ON FAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now the Jets will find out about their depth.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six weeks of the season, they will be without
Wayne Chrebet, their 1,000-yard receiver, who broke a bone in his
left foot Friday during the Jets' final preseason game, a 38-17
victory over the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells had been hoping to use the game to assess
the squad's depth and determine who the No. 2 quarterback would be.
He probably decided the quarterback issue when Rick Mirer directed
four touchdown drives after replacing Vinny Testaverde at the start
of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' backup wide receivers, Quinn Early and Dwight Stone,
produced big performances, each catching a touchdown pass from
Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, Early and Stone were signed within the last month _
filling potential holes that Parcells, also the team's general
manager, had worried about. Faster than he expected, each player
has become important.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet's injury means that Dedric Ward will join Keyshawn
Johnson as a starting receiver, said Parcells, whose post-game
comments on Chrebet were terse. Parcells does not dwell on
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet never missed a game in his previous four seasons, and
had formed a durable, formidable duo with the irrepressible
Johnson. The injury occurred as Chrebet was trying to change
direction, just slightly, in the opening quarter. He was running on
the Giants Stadium artificial turf, which was being used the first
time this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's game, the Jets and the Giants had agreed to play
the preseason on a grass surface that is being considered for
regular-season use next year. The artificial surface was back in
play since that is what will be used starting next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet broken the fifth metatarsal in his left foot. He limped
off the field by himself, but was soon visited in the locker room
by his parents. Saturday, a screw was surgically implanted to help
repair the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ward conceded after the game that he is not familiar with some
of the receiving routes Chrebet had run so well. Nor does Ward have
Chrebet's blocking talent or his proven ability to catch in a crowd
_ especially in the clutch. Chrebet is perennially among the league
leaders in third-down receptions.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ward is the team's big-play receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to use every weapon we can,'' he said. ``I'm very
confident I can do the things it takes to become a starting
receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Early and Stone will at least provide options that will enable
the offensive coordinator, Charlie Weis, to keep the defenses
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 34-year-old Early is listed as Johnson's backup, he
said he has also played Chrebet's flanker position. On Friday, his
three receptions included a 74-yard score from Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Early said he went into the game thinking that he needed to
impress his teammates. ``I'm an older player, and they might wonder
whether I still have it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Did he believe he had proved he still had it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, 35, also snared three passes, one a 24-yard touchdown
from Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer directed touchdowns in the three drives he led in the
third quarter, added another score in the fourth and then relaxed
as Ray Lucas did mop-up duty.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he liked Mirer's mobility (he had an 18-yard
scamper), but said he did not like something Mirer had done on one
play. He would not be more specific than that.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer benefited from having the first-team offensive line in
front of him against many of the Vikings' second-stringers. He
completed 5 of 8 passes for 145 yards and 3 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet's injury means the Jets will be missing two starters for
their home opener next Sunday against the New England Patriots.
Right cornerback Otis Smith remains sidelined with a broken
collarbone. Inside linebacker Marvin Jones did not play Friday as
he recovered from a sprained ankle, but he is expected to suit up
for the opener.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The Jets showed a marked improvement in punt returns. For the
first time in the preseason, LEON JOHNSON broke a pair for
double-digit yardage. His long return was for 42 yards. Johnson
also amassed 56 rushing yards on 11 carries.
</P>
<P>
   _ In winding up the preseason with a 3-1 record, the Jets have
made it three straight winning summers. Before Coach BILL PARCELLS'
arrival in 1997, the Jets never put together successive winning
exhibition seasons. They are 10-2 under Parcells, whose overall
exhibition record is 45-16.
</P>
<P>
   _ With 3-for-3 field-goal kicking, JOHN HALL finished 8 for 10
in the preseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
