<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKING PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS; MCCAIN'S BOOK; HISPANICS AND
REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Texas, N.M.)  (js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCKS, THEN BACKING TO BUSH CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   The money just keeps on rolling in for George W. Bush, close to
$50 million now, or more than any other presidential candidate has
ever raised, even figuring in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   But money isn't the only thing that the Texas governor is piling
up. Endorsements by top elected officials around the country are
also rolling in, too, especially endorsements by governors and
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   By the Bush campaign's count, 23 of the 31 Republican governors
(24 including the candidate) have come out in support of Bush,
along with 169 of the 277 Republicans in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, even though Election Day is still more than a
year off, Bush already has won the support of roughly two of every
three Republican governors and Republican members of Congress. The
other Republican presidential candidates can claim only a handful
of endorsements _ all added together.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the endorsement game go over on the Democratic side
for Vice President Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere near as well.
</P>
<P>
   He is leagues ahead of his only Democratic challenger, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, just as Bush is leagues ahead of
his Republican challengers. But equally important, who is the
stronger candidate within his own party?
</P>
<P>
   Bush, going away.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Gore lags Bush in polls of the grass roots, he also lags
Bush in winning early top-level endorsements. By his latest count,
he has commitments from only 6 of 17 Democratic governors and only
69 of the 256 congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, while Bush has the support of more than
two-thirds of all Republican governors and members of Congress,
Gore has the support of less than one-third of all Democratic
governors and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Political pros say that such top-level endorsements seldom sway
a lot of votes down below. But endorsements are nevertheless
important because the officials often follow up by putting their
own political organizations to work for the favored candidates. ``I
believe in endorsements,'' Tony Coelho, Gore's campaign chairman,
said the other day. ``I don't believe in anything else. They're
tremendous validators.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Gore plans to make a high-profile push in coming
months to add as many endorsements as possible, not just more from
top elected officials but also from ethnic leaders and leaders of
major national organizations, like labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is trying to take the early-commitment race to another
level.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, on a trip to Des Moines, he collected the
endorsements of 31 of the 56 Republicans in the Iowa House and 16
of the 30 Republicans in the Iowa Senate.
</P>
<P>
   NO SALT NEEDED WITH MCCAIN BOOK
</P>
<P>
   One of the hoary givens in presidential politics is that any
book by a candidate that comes out at campaign time, especially an
autobiography or memoir, should be read with a full shaker of salt
nearby, or maybe not at all. The sole aim of such books, of course,
is to sell the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Faith of My Fathers,'' the newly published ``family
memoir'' by Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who is seeking the
Republican nomination and who, before getting into politics in 1982
was a Navy pilot for 22 years, spending five and a half of them
enduring torture and privation in North Vietnamese prisons after
being shot down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith of My Fathers'' (Random House) is a book about strong
character _ the strong character of McCain's father and
grandfather, both Naval heroes, and the strong character McCain saw
displayed by fellow pilots while in prison in Hanoi. His own strong
character also becomes evident in the book _ over the years, other
survivors of the ordeal have described him as among the toughest of
the tough _ but he modestly insists he was no hero, only ``among
heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally evident about McCain is this: As he sees Election 2000,
strong character is what Americans now long for most in their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The early buzz in both political and publishing circles is that
``Faith of My Fathers'' just might be the exception in campaign
books, the self-serving tome that not only is a well-turned good
read but also has enough modesty, warts-and-all honesty and genuine
substance to maybe give the candidate a boost. A review by
Publishers Weekly says ``Faith of My Fathers'' is ``too good to be
dismissed as simply another campaign book'' and Kirkus Reviews
calls it ``impressive and inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're hot, you're hot, in politics as in publishing, so
come Tuesday McCain will set off on a 17-day national tour to
promote his book (read, candidacy), trying to not only increase
sales but also the growing perception among some political pros
that he might be best positioned to pick up the Republican gonfalon
should George W. Bush somehow falter. In between stops at book
stores from New York to Los Angeles, he will show up on just about
all of the big early-morning, mid-afternoon and late-evening news
and talk shows, as well as on local news and talk shows without
number.
</P>
<P>
   Many asked him to appear. Usually with such book tours, it's the
other way around.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; REPUBLICAN SEEKING HISPANIC CANDIDATES &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 31 million Hispanic people now account for almost
11 percent of its population, and more and more of them are voting.
In the past five years, according to the Southwest Voter
Registration Education Project in San Antonio, the registration of
Hispanic voters has increased almost 30 percent nationwide, while
registration in general around the country has increased only 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-dozen or so states, the Hispanic vote is at or near
the point that when it is cohesive, it can tip a close election.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade or so, Democratic candidates have gotten
more of the Hispanic vote than Republican candidates, and Hispanic
Democrats have fared better as candidates than have Hispanic
Republicans. For example, there are now 18 Hispanic Democrats in
Congress but only three Hispanic Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans took heart after the 1998 elections. Though the
Hispanic vote went against them in the biggest state, California,
where Republicans had led several efforts to toughen immigration
restrictions, Republican candidates won heavy Hispanic backing when
they actively went after it.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, that backing helped Gov. George W. Bush win
re-election in Texas and it helped his brother, Jeb, capture the
governor's office in Florida. Further, in Arizona the Hispanic vote
helped another Republican, Sen. John McCain, win re-election
easily.
</P>
<P>
   One of McCain's Southwestern neighbors, Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, says it is now time for Republicans to begin fielding
more Hispanic candidates rather than concentrating mainly on
getting Hispanics to vote for non-Hispanic Republicans. He contends
that in the past the party has paid little more than lip service to
recruitment of Hispanic candidates and has lost much Hispanic
support as a result.
</P>
<P>
   So a few days ago, he announced the formation of Pete's PAC, a
political action committee that will help finance Hispanic
Republican campaigns around the country for national, state and
local offices. His hope, he said, is to raise $300,000 for the PAC
by early next year, probably not an insurmountable goal given that
he is chairman of the Senate Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics need to be encouraged to run,'' Domenici said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
