<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-HOUSE-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPPAQUA SORTS THROUGH MIX OF EMOTIONS OVER PASSING THE CLINTON
TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Last week was a strange one for Chappaqua,
where life usually revolves around train schedules, soccer
practice, book clubs and cocktail parties.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, there was a frisson of excitement when
Vanessa Williams, still a resident, was crowned Miss America and
then disappointment when she was dethroned. In the late 1980s, the
spotlight returned when FBI agents staked out Felix Bloch, who had
holed up in his daughter's house here after he was suspected of
being a spy.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1990s had been quiet. At least until the president
decided to move in.
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement that President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton had signed a contract to buy a Dutch Colonial at 15 Old
House Lane, many residents here were a jumble of emotions: proud to
be judged the fairest suburb of them all, fearful of the
implications and, mostly, tired of the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of dreading it,'' said Kathy Kiernan-Johnston,
summing up a widely expressed sentiment, as reporters canvassed the
usually sleepy business district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice quiet town, and that was the whole point of moving
here,'' she said. ``I have a feeling there will be another brouhaha
when they actually move in _ with Chelsea taking her first walk in
the town and Bill playing golf for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, were relishing the moment. Len Savanella, the
owner of Chappaqua Stationery, posted a sign on his storefront that
read: ``Bye Bye Beanie Babies. Hello Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Gerry Gorman, a pharmaceutical company executive
and father of three who is sure to have the ultimate cocktail party
boast, living as he does three doors down from the Clintons' home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, it's fun, it's different,'' he said with a big
grin.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Gorman seemed not all that worried about the traffic
on Old House Lane, a tiny slip of a street with only a half-dozen
houses. On Friday, it looked like an airport runway, with cars
streaming up and around the cul-de-sac for a glimpse of the house
and television satellite trucks vying for position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the cars, but that's temporary,'' he said. ``I
think it will all subside.''
</P>
<P>
   A hamlet in the Town of New Castle, Chappaqua was once
predominantly Republican, but it has shifted in recent years; all
five members of the New Castle town board, as well as the town
supervisor, are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Since they are moving to friendly territory, can the Clintons
expect a parade or a big banner across the town hall?
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Chappaqua, Tom and Maxine Baker?'' mused the town
supervisor, Clinton B. Smith, referring to hypothetical newcomers.
``There's no difference between Tom and Maxine Baker and Bill and
Hillary Clinton, so the answer is no.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Often, the most adamant reactions here to the president's move
came from people who also had the strongest reactions to his
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Those like Dr. Rami Mosseri, who twice voted for President
Clinton, were delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Clintons,'' said Mosseri, who oversees treatment
programs in Westchester County for emotionally disturbed children
for the Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services. ``I like
what they stand for, and I'm flattered that they think of Chappaqua
as a town they would like to live in.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any upheaval the Clintons' presence may cause, he said,
``Chappaqua can use a little action.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Portlock, who said Clinton had ``brought shame to the
presidency,'' wondered how residents would get their children to
school in the mornings when the Clintons and their entourage are in
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody drives their kids to the high school, and there are
already massive traffic jams,'' said Ms. Portlock, a saleswoman at
Bloomingdale's in White Plains and a Chappaqua resident for four
years. ``Will they close the streets? How will you get through?''
</P>
<P>
   But Pat Miller, a fiction writer and grandmother who has lived
here for 23 years, blamed the news media for making much ado over
what she called a ``nonevent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mrs. Clinton gets elected,'' she said, referring to her
expected run for the U.S. Senate, ``she'll be here 12 days a
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
