<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY LIE THE HELMETS THAT WEAR THE BRONCOS' LOGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems to be a tradition: Team wins National Football League
championship. Team celebrates. Calamities strike team.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency tears team apart. Or drugs. Or arrests. Or
controversial personnel moves. Maybe a retirement or two. Or, in
the case of the Denver Broncos, some variation of all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   First John Elway said a teary goodbye, which led to Coach Mike
Shanahan naming Bubby Brister as Elway's replacement at
quarterback. But Brister did what many thought he would: He played
terribly. He was so bad in the preseason, twice throwing
interceptions on the first pass play of a game, that last week
Shanahan made the controversial decision to bench Brister for the
second-year quarterback Brian Griese.
</P>
<P>
   Now Shanahan must deal with the consequences. The Broncos might
indeed be better for the move, but there may be some players who
wonder whether they can trust Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the quarterback controversy, the Broncos have had to
deal with a series of other distractions. The talented defensive
player John Mobley got into a serious automobile accident that
could have killed him; luckily, he is fine. Tight end Shannon
Sharpe blasted the league for forcing the Broncos to play a
preseason game in Australia. Then when the news media blasted back,
calling Sharpe a crybaby, he boycotted them. So far Sharpe is
sticking to his stance.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest Rocky Mountain headache surfaced late last week.
Linebacker Bill Romanowski, a fitness guru who takes dozens of
vitamins and nutritional supplements each day, is being
investigated for illegally obtaining a prescription drug by the
Douglas County sheriff's department in Colorado and the Drug
Enforcement Administration. Those agencies have asked that two
felony counts and one misdemeanor count be filed against
Romanowski. If convicted, he could face a prison term of up to
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski, through his lawyer, Jeff Springer, denied any
wrongdoing. Springer called the allegations ``scandalous.'' No
charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Romanowski's wife, Julie, and another woman
obtained prescriptions for Phentermine from a doctor and then gave
the drug to Romanowski. Phentermine is usually given to people with
severe obesity and can act as a stimulant. The National Football
League does not have a prohibition against it.
</P>
<P>
   The case could have serious repercussions for Romanowski and the
Broncos. If convicted of misuse of prescription drugs, Romanowski
would be in violation of the league's substance-abuse policy and
would be subject to a suspension and/or a fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have long been known as a team that does whatever it
takes to win. In part, that simply means hard work _ they won the
last two Super Bowls largely because Elway remained in great
physical shape, as did running back Terrell Davis, who takes part
in excruciating off-season workouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the league has recently kept a close eye on the Broncos, and
in particular on their relationship with EAS, a Colorado company
that makes nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the NFL sent a memo to each of its teams about the
use of Andro-6, which is supposed to boost testosterone levels and
thus increase strength and muscle mass. In the memo Dr. John
Lombardo, the league's adviser on anabolic steroids, said that
using Andro-6 would violate the league's substance-abuse policy
because it included two banned items, androstenedione and
dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA).
</P>
<P>
   What was unusual about Lombardo's warning was that while other
companies make products that contain the banned substances, the
only company he mentioned was EAS, which has a close relationship
with the Broncos. A number of Denver players use EAS products.
</P>
<P>
   While Lombardo's memo was circulated to each team, league
officials said privately at the time that they hoped the Broncos
took special notice since so many of their players were said to be
using Andro-6.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that when the Broncos look back over this season come
January, the Romanowski incident will have been nothing more than a
blip in what could be another great year.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most repeated words in a football locker room is
distraction. When one comes along, coaches and players act as if
they are not bothered, even though it may be sitting on their
shoulders. The Broncos have not one, but several of these pesky
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan is such a good coach, despite how poorly he handled the
Brister situation, that he will get the Broncos at least 10 or 11
victories. They have too much talent to get any fewer. And since
Brister appears to be better coming off the bench than as a
starter, Shanahan's decision may in the end be a wise one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a reason no team has won three consecutive Super
Bowls. A lot of these little things, these distractions, can add
up, and pretty soon the Broncos may not be fighting only other
teams, but also themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Costly Exhibitions
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants and Jets lost two key players to injury on
Friday, it provided more support to the critics of the preseason
system.
</P>
<P>
   Four preseason games in the highly violent world of professional
football seem like too many. Injuries to the Giants' Gary Brown
(sprained knee) and the Jets' Wayne Chrebet (broken foot) are the
latest in a growing number of hurt bodies left in the wake of
another preseason. St. Louis lost quarterback Trent Green for the
season last weekend after he severely hurt his knee. This
off-season the team had signed Green to an $11 million contract.
The New Orleans rookie Ricky Williams hurt his ankle, and the
Saints saw two other players injured as well.
</P>
<P>
   No team has been as devastated as the Miami Dolphins. Miami is
missing more than a dozen players to injuries, including the rookie
defensive lineman Dimitrius Underwood (shoulder). Coach Jimmy
Johnson has watched his once large group of running backs decimated
by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is simple: Cut the number of preseason games to
two. It would give coaches less game time to evaluate their
players, but the injuries would be drastically reduced. And the
preseason games would become more important, not meaningless as
they are now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HAYNES-MIRACLE05-COX     09-04 1756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYNES-MIRACLE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A `Pearl' at high tide
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A dozen years ago, Melinda Haynes was a preacher's
daughter who thought she had run out of miracles.
</P>
<P>
   A high school dropout who suffered from a panic disorder, Haynes
was in the middle of a bankruptcy and a rapidly disintegrating
marriage. Her husband had lost his job, and the bank had foreclosed
on their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had nothing to live for,'' says the 44-year-old
Alabama author. ``I believed I had let everybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   When she couldn't stand it any longer, she attempted suicide by
taking an overdose of antidepressants.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the miracles began happening.
</P>
<P>
   A chance encounter with a priest in a small Catholic church
landed her a job as a reporter for The Catholic Week. That resulted
in an assignment covering relief organizations in Jamaica. And that
led to a short story, a new husband and a book contract.
</P>
<P>
   Then the big miracle happened.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Oprah Winfrey called to say she had selected Haynes'
debut novel, ``Mother of Pearl'' (Hyperion, $23.95), for her TV
book club. (The taped segment airs this week, although at press
time producers had not settled on a firm date.)
</P>
<P>
   When Haynes first got the call, she didn't recognize Winfrey's
voice. ``She was talking so softly, I thought she was an office
worker who didn't want to be overheard. After a while, I
</P>
<P>
   asked her who she was. When she said, `This is Oprah Winfrey,' I
dropped the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The book that captivated the talk-show host is set in Petal,
Miss., during the 1950s. It explores the intersecting lives of Even
Grade, a black man who was orphaned as a child; Valuable Korner, a
fatherless teen-age girl who is the daughter of the town whore; and
Joody Two Sun, the local soothsayer.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Conroy called the book ``a novel of staggering power'' and
The New York Times described Haynes' prose as being ``as profuse
and vigorous'' as kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   Before Winfrey's announcement, Hyperion expected to sell about
10,000 copies of the novel. Now the publisher has gone back to
press twice for a total of 700,000 copies. Paperback and foreign
rights have been sold, a movie deal is in the works and the book is
No. 7 on this week's New York Times Best Seller List.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the whirlwind, Haynes is trying to remain calm.
``I'm trying to keep my life simple,'' she says. ``We live out in
the country in Grand Bay (Ala.) in a trailer. It's very peaceful,
very quiet. We have another place on the river, a fish camp. Now I
can keep writing; I don't have to worry about going out and getting
a job.''
</P>
<P>
   She does, however, have to worry about facing the public. For
someone who has suffered for years from agoraphobia, that prospect
is frightening.
</P>
<P>
   The first panic attacks began when she was in seventh grade.
``Suddenly everyone in the room seemed to be getting closer and I
could hear my heart in my ear and I actually fell out of my desk,''
she recalls. ``It began to happen more and more at school.''
</P>
<P>
   As the daughter of a Baptist preacher, Haynes couldn't hide. She
was always called on to pray in Sunday school, and she was expected
to attend all church functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began missing a lot of school,'' she says. ``They took me to
a psychiatrist, but there was not a lot of information about the
disorder. Then the attacks began to happen in church, and then in
stores. I finally quit school in the 11th grade and was tutored at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as she got her diploma at 18, she married and started a
family. ``I was trying to find something,'' she says. ``I don't
know what. For a while, I felt safe.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 23, she had three daughters and a husband
who found it increasingly difficult to make ends meet at
blue-collar jobs. To supplement their meager income, Haynes began
painting portraits. Trained by her grandfather, Opie Braswell, a
Hattiesburg, Miss., artist known for his baptism scenes, Haynes
began to earn $5,000 to $6,000 per painting.
</P>
<P>
   But even that was not enough. When her husband lost his job, the
panic attacks returned and Haynes, unable to deal with her clients,
quit painting. The couple lost their house and filed for bankruptcy
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   That's when she tried to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like if I had been a better painter I could have saved
us. That's the trick of depression. You start to believe everyone
would be better off without you.''
</P>
<P>
   After the suicide attempt, Haynes was driving and crying one day
when she stopped and went into a small church, which turned out to
be Catholic. ``This man came in and sat down beside me while I was
crying,'' she says. ``He wasn't dressed like a priest, but he began
explaining what the different things in the church were. I decided
then and there I was going to convert. It saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Haynes realized that perfection was not possible, she began
to recover. Until then, she was always concerned about her weight,
or the way she looked, or how well she did in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was nothing that my parents ever tried to put on me,''
she says. ``It was some standard that I set for myself at an early
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Converting to Catholicism proved to be a turning point in her
career as well. After divorcing her first husband, Haynes took a
job as a typesetter for The Catholic Week newspaper in Mobile. Nine
months later, she was assigned to cover relief organizations in
Kingston, Jamaica. Her photographs won the Mobile Press Club's
Award of Excellence but, more importantly, her essay was read by
co-worker Ray Haynes, 56, a retired Marine captain and Vietnam
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first thing I had read that really brought tears to
my eyes,'' Ray Haynes says. ``She's only about 5 feet tall, but I
told her she wrote like a tall woman. I also told her she was too
good for this place. Shortly thereafter, we started going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, they married and moved to Grand Bay, where
she began writing her first short story, ``Strange Dirt.''
Meanwhile, a friend had recommended that she subscribe to Poets &AMP;
Writers magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the first issue arrived, I read it from cover to cover
and then cried for two hours. The odds seemed impossible. Contest
fees, book recommendations, retreats I couldn't afford. ... There
didn't seem to be a profile of an undereducated Southern woman who
had grown up out in the middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There didn't seem to be a slot for a middle-aged grandmother
who had put away her paintbrushes and fallen in love with her
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged, she gave the magazine to her husband and went back
to her day job as production manager at The Catholic Week. Every
night she wrote until 3 a.m. on her novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 75 pages into the book and felt as though I had
wandered, by some sort of strange accident, into a world of
possibilities,'' she says. ``It was the most incredible time of
self-awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   As she wrote, her husband bundled up her stories and sent them
to literary magazines. Eight weeks later, she got a call saying two
of her stories had been accepted by The Crescent Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray began an aggressive course where my writing was concerned.
He cleaned out a bedroom, screened my calls and researched the
possibilities for a literary agent.''
</P>
<P>
   After reading a profile of agent Wendy Weil in Poets &AMP; Writers,
he sent her 104 pages of the novel. Sixteen days later, she called
Haynes at work and asked to see more. Six months after that,
Hyperion bought the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Weil says it was Haynes' cover letter that made her manuscript
stand out in a huge slush pile. ``It was very heartfelt. And then
we started reading the story and immediately fell in love with Even
and the other characters. She is a natural writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Levin, Haynes' editor at Hyperion, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melinda is a writer who is passionate about language,'' Levin
says. ``She's in love with it the same way writers such as Toni
Morrison are. Her writing combines a childlike innocence with a
very sophisticated manipulation of the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes derived her love of words from reading the works of James
Joyce and Flannery O'Connor, but she attributes her talent for
description to her training in art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I know how to paint scenes, I can make a translation
from what I was seeing into words very easily. And I've always been
able to anticipate moods, see emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her writing, Haynes possesses a certain kind of innocence.
``She's like a child in the way she looks at things,'' her husband
says. ``Her agent said she hoped she didn't lose that quality in
all this. I don't think she will. Neither of us is very
materialistic. We both like to fish and ride motorcycles. The
biggest thing we want to do is build a house on the river one of
these days and get out of the trailer. Every time a thunderstorm
comes through, she gets worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes has no intention of changing, even with the promise of
more money than she ever imagined and the pressure that comes with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for me as a writer is to make sure
that I'm trying to please me, nobody else. I don't want to please
someone for commercial reasons. I feel like I'm the guardian of the
characters. I just want to be true and honest.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An excerpt from ``Mother of Pearl''
</P>
<P>
   Even Grade walked past the spot on the bridge where Canaan had
caught the bottle with his head and saw the blood mark was still
there, but just barely. The two-week bake of August sun beginning
to mask its humiliation, blending the old man's emission to a color
like that of rusted girder. On a day not spent dealing with death,
Even would have stopped one more time to wonder over the bigger
insult: that Canaan's middle-aged forehead got split by glass and
bled out, or that the bottle bearing skin and blood soared over a
rail and dropped into the water that he loved. Death or no, Even's
suspicion was the same as two weeks back: both. Both were equally
bad. ...
</P>
<P>
   When Even passed under the caution light at Central and Main, he
saw Canaan sitting on the warm deck of the loading dock of the Feed
and Seed. Leaning against the wall, his shades on his bony nose,
Canaan had put aside the bandage he'd worn for two weeks. ...
Canaan didn't stop reading. Just said from behind newsprint as Even
approached. ``I do say, Even Grade, somebody dead?'' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody dead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
