<HEADER>
A0928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-HOMERS-N     09-04 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-HOMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERPOWERING YOUR TEAM; CAN'T KEEP UP THAT PACE; NOWHERE TO GO BUT
OUT; PHILLIES IN FREE FALL; JAHA DELIVERS FOR A'S; FIGHTING FOR
LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (SEE also BBO-NOTEBOOK-TRADES) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire has hit more home runs in losing efforts than any
player in history. He has slugged 34 of his 54 home runs this year
in games the St. Louis Cardinals have lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Sammy Sosa, his partner in historic home run races, has a
chance to do something no one ever has _ hit 50 or more home runs
and wind up with more home runs than his team has victories.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa took a 57-55 lead over McGwire into the Chicago Cubs' game
Saturday. He clouted his 53rd home run in the Cubs' 53rd victory
and 54th in their 54th. But then he connected for No. 55 in the
team's 7-3 loss at San Diego last Tuesday, and the Cubs haven't
been able to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Berger, Ralph Kiner and the original Frank Thomas (not the
one playing now) have come closest to achieving the odd feat.
Berger hit 34 home runs when the Boston Braves won 38 games in
1935, Kiner hit 37 when Pittsburgh won 42 games in 1952 and Thomas
connected for 34 when the rookie Mets dazzled the baseball world
with 40 victories in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-homer plateau had been reached 27 times before this
season. The closest finish in those 27 instances came in 1947 when
Kiner hit 51 home runs and the Pirates won 62 games. McGwire came
close to that difference last season, hitting 70 as the Cardinals
won 83 games.
</P>
<P>
   Can't Keep Up That Pace
</P>
<P>
   When Jose Canseco hit his 31st home run July 8, he was only one
behind Sammy Sosa and he was four home runs ahead of Mark McGwire.
But he played only one more game for Tampa Bay before he went on
the disabled list with a back injury. Since returning Aug. 20,
Canseco had played 11 games before Saturday night, and he still had
31 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 55 relief appearances for Texas, Jeff Zimmerman
allowed 10 earned runs in 771/3 innings for a 1.16 earned run
average. In two outings in Detroit last week, Zimmerman faced 13
batters. Nine of them got hits and eight scored, ballooning his ERA
to 2.06.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere to Go but Out
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Terry Collins as the Anaheim Angels' manager
could hardly have surprised anyone. The players might have deserved
to be fired more than Collins, but the Disney team wasn't going to
be the first to make that move.
</P>
<P>
   Between the first game after the All-Star Game break and
Collins' resignation Friday, the Angels endured losing streaks of
11 games, seven games and nine games. The first streak is the
longest in the American League this season, and the league's 13
other teams have a total of eight losing streaks as long as seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   No team has fallen faster than the Angels did in July. After
winning the first post-break game, the Angels plummeted 13 games in
the standings in the span of 18 games, 16 of which they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies in Free Fall
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies weren't ready to contend for the
playoffs this season, but they made a valiant effort, going as far
as their young talent and a healthy Curt Schilling could take them.
They were only 5 1/2 games out of first place and four games from
the wild-card lead as recently as a month ago, but they lost 18 of
24 games before breaking a seven-game losing streak Friday night
and tumbling 17 games from the division leader, Atlanta, and 13{
games from the wild-card hopeful Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling pitched the first game of that 24-game stretch but
then went on the disabled list with a sore shoulder. He returned
Friday, in time to stop the losing streak but not in time to stop
the fatal fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jaha Delivers for A's
</P>
<P>
   Teams stayed away in droves. John Jaha was a free agent, but he
was also a patient, recovering from major foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a whole lot of choices,'' said Jaha, a first
baseman, who spent his first seven seasons with the Milwaukee
Brewers. ``Nobody really was willing to take a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaha, 33, thought teams were ignoring a good opportunity. ``I
thought I could play,'' he said. ``I work pretty hard in the
wintertime. It was just a matter of someone giving me a chance to
come to spring training and let me work into shape and get my
confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland gave Jaha that chance, signing him on the eve of spring
training for a $400,000 salary. The Athletics included a bonus of
$75,000 if he is named the comeback player of the year. They might
as well pay the man now.
</P>
<P>
   Serving mostly as the designated hitter, Jaha entered Saturday's
game with Detroit tied for the team lead in home runs with 32 and
second in runs batted in with 96, two good reasons the Athletics
are competing for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the funnest time I've had in my career,'' Jaha said.
``I haven't been playing for much when September came around in
past years.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting for Luck
</P>
<P>
   Considering the overreaction to the brief bus scuffle between
the Mets' Rey Ordonez and Luis Lopez, some people must think two
teammates never had a fight before. Why it wasn't even novel for
the Mets (see Tim Foli and Ed Kranepool in 1971 for one precedent).
</P>
<P>
   Teams like the Oakland Athletics in the early '70s and the Los
Angeles Dodgers in the later '70s had intramural fisticuffs and won
pennants. Maybe the cut over Ordonez's eye is a harbinger of good
things to come for the Mets. Maybe that's the element of the fight
that should be viewed seriously, not the fight itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
