<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0929 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-COL05-COX     09-04 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-COL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Possible Buchanan defection has GOP sounding alarms
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Voters such as Joe McCutchen of Ellijay, Ga., are the
reason Republican leaders worry that presidential candidate Pat
Buchanan will take his campaign to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   McCutchen, a Republican activist, said he and his band of North
Georgians who are backing Buchanan will happily follow the
three-time candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's going to do it,'' McCutchen said. ``But
if he does, I'll be with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is back in the pack of Republican candidates, and the
social and foreign policy issues that are central to his campaign
are not getting heard as they did in 1992 and 1996, when he won the
New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   But if he runs as a third-party candidate, Republicans fear he
will drain enough votes from the GOP nominee to ensure the election
of a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich urged the Reform Party on
Friday to nominate whomever Republicans choose and run as a team in
2000. ``Because the alternative would be to offer assistance to Al
Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point to 1992 to bolster their position. Ross Perot,
who left the GOP, was the Reform candidate and Bill Clinton won the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll shows that, in a hypothetical
matchup, Buchanan takes almost all his support from Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. While Bush still finishes ahead of Vice President
Al Gore in the poll, it is a much closer contest than a two-man
race.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
said he will meet with Buchanan and try to persuade him that he has
a place in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's firm opposition to abortion rights and hard-line
stance on other social issues may make it difficult for him to win
the nomination of the Reform Party, which tends to attract people
with more moderate views on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   But if he could capture the nomination, Buchanan would have
access to more than $12 million that the party will receive in
federal funds for the 2000 campaign, far more money than he expects
to raise.
</P>
<P>
   Gore criticized over Russia role
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's leading role in U.S.-Russian relations
is leaving him open to criticism from his presidential competitors
over allegations that Russian gangsters stole up to $200 million in
international loans and other foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a long history as the administration's point man in
U.S.-Russian relations, and the vice president's foreign policy
experience is one of the selling points in his campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Steve Forbes and Elizabeth Dole have said that Gore
bears special responsibility for the scandal because of his
prominent role.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Bill Bradley last week chided the Clinton and Bush
administrations _ but not Gore in particular _ in his assessment
that ``American assistance and lending policies toward Russia have
been misdirected and ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign press secretary Kiki Moore said Gore ``is not
going to play partisan politics'' with the Russian money-laundering
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides have said the vice president was not aware that
loans from the International Monetary Fund may have been taken by
the Russian mafia and laundered through the Bank of New York into
U.S. accounts.
</P>
<P>
   They also have said that Gore has used his prominence to push
the Russians to crack down on corruption as a condition for the
continuation of foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has vowed to keep the issue front and center, and already
has aired a radio ad in which he says Gore's aides said the vice
president ``was out of the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase was the same one used by then-Vice President George
Bush in response to critics of the Iran-contra scandal of the
Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates take S.C. Primary seriously
</P>
<P>
   You can forgive J. Sam Daniels for his exuberance when he says,
in all apparent sincerity, that South Carolina boasts the nation's
``most important primary.''
</P>
<P>
   As the state Republican Party's executive director, Daniels gets
paid to promote all things South Carolina and Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But his comment is more than mere bluster and as proof, he
offers the campaigns of Republicans Steve Forbes and George W.
Bush, who are spending part of the Labor Day Arizona Sen. John
McCain has made South Carolina and New Hampshire the focal points
of his campaign. Dole also has made several trips to the state,
next door to her native North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina does not hold the first primary and it is not
rich in delegates to the nominating convention. But it holds its
primary early enough, Feb. 19 in 2000, and first among Southern
states. Since 1980, every Republican who has finished first in
South Carolina has won his party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The state is deep with religious conservatives, yet presidential
primary voters have stood as a bulwark against insurgent
candidacies from the party's right wing and in support of the
mainstream candidate.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolinians helped Bob Dole stop Buchanan in 1996 and Bush
shut off Pat Robertson's momentum in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's plan to capture the GOP nomination is built around
using strong showings in New Hampshire and South Carolina, and a
decisive win in Arizona, to narrow the Republican field to a
one-on-one contest in California against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush does well in the Iowa caucuses and in New Hampshire, he
could use South Carolina to effectively end any serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Dole and Forbes would like to use South Carolina as a
springboard to the round of early March primaries that include
Georgia, but also the big prizes in California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be 11 days between us and New Hampshire,'' said
Daniels, who worked on Guy Millner's campaign for Georgia governor
last year. ``I think you'll see candidates spending a lot of time
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky race has Democrats excited
</P>
<P>
   Five seats will determine who controls the House of
Representatives after next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats were practically giddy last week when former Rep.
Scotty Baesler of Kentucky said he would run for his old seat in
the Lexington area.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler lost a race for the U.S. Senate last year to Republican
Jim Bunning by 6,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   But his election is no sure thing against freshman Rep. Ernie
Fletcher, who has amassed $533,000 in campaign funds to defend his
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Cook, a Washington political analyst, said a
Baesler-Fletcher contest would be ``one of the most competitive
races in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Baesler, then an incumbent, beat Fletcher in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party expects more than a handful of seats to change
hands anywhere in the South, meaning both sides intend to pour as
much as they can into any campaign that appears competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
