<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING IS EVERYTHING ON TEAMS' TRAVELS TO THE POSTSEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (SEE also BBO-NOTEBOOK-HOMERS) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks were busier making trades and spending
money in the off-season, and the Oakland Athletics changed their
roster a bit more with midseason deals, but no team was more active
than the Mets at both times of the year in making changes they
hoped would catapult them to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks engaged in such a massive roster turnover last
winter, acquiring such players as Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre,
Luis Gonzalez, Steve Finley and Tony Womack, and played so well in
the first half of the season, that the only spot they felt they had
to shore up at midseason was their closing relief role. They
accomplished that goal by obtaining Matt Mantei from the Florida
Marlins just before the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, the Athletics had no thoughts, other than in their
wildest fantasies, of contending for a playoff spot so they signed
a couple of veteran free agents, Tony Phillips and John Jaha,
hoping they would add to the team's offense. But when the Athletics
reached the July 31 no-waiver trading deadline, they found
themselves in the wild-card race, and General Manager Billy Beane
went on an all-out blitz to ensure that they stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   First, he traded Kenny Rogers to the Mets, then added two
starting pitchers, Kevin Appier and Omar Olivares; two relievers,
Jason Isringhausen and Greg McMichael, and a second baseman, Randy
Velarde. A couple of weeks later, when Phillips broke his leg,
Beane acquired Rich Becker to play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, on the other hand,
completed a series of significant transactions during the winter,
then went back to business before the trading deadline. Did his
midseason work mean he hadn't completed the job in the winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more timing that it's done in season than the job
not being complete,'' Phillips said. ``It's a dynamic process that
doesn't start or finish at a specific time.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Phillips cited the Mets' desire after the 1997
season to acquire a marquee-type player. ``That sort of guy didn't
become available for the right deal until we were able to acquire
Mike in May '98,'' he said, referring to Mike Piazza. ``Often you
identify your need, but for whatever reason, you're not able to
fill it, whether it's not being able to sign a free agent or not
having the right fit for a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the Mets snared two free agents they wanted,
third baseman Robin Ventura and left fielder Rickey Henderson, two
players without whom the Mets would not be contending. The same day
he reached agreement with Ventura, Phillips executed a three-way
trade with Los Angeles and Baltimore. From the Orioles came Armando
Benitez, who was on hand to become the Mets' closer when John
Franco went on the disabled list two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   From the Dodgers came Roger Cedeno, who was on hand to fill in
for Henderson when he injured a knee in April. Benitez proceeded to
blow away hitters with his fastball, and Cedeno proceeded to take
off on a stolen-base tear that sent him to the head of the league.
Henderson, when healthy, has played like a rejuvenated player, and
Ventura is having a most valuable player-type season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mets were playing well as the trading deadline
approached, Phillips was not content; he wanted to make the team
even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking to improve,'' the general manager said. ``That
is the challenge that our staff looks at every day. What can we do
to improve? In parentheses you say within the confines of your
budget and not giving away too much of the future. The trading
deadline just happens to motivate people to make deals. We would
have liked to have upgraded with a second left-hander in the
bullpen much earlier in the year, but that time of year makes it
easier to make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Working shrewdly ahead of the competition, Phillips grabbed
Rogers a week before the deadline for the starting rotation. Then,
on deadline day, he secured the left-handed reliever he wanted,
Chuck McElroy; added another reliever, Oakland's closer, Billy
Taylor; obtained a veteran, the versatile Shawon Dunston; and
swapped center fielders, Brian McRae for Darryl Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   All in a day's work.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some teams, the Mets did not add any players last
Tuesday, the last day players could get onto the roster and be
eligible for postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Houston obtained Stan Javier for their outfield decimated by
injuries; Atlanta added a backup catcher, Jorge Fabregas; the
Diamondbacks picked up Lenny Harris, a versatile utility player the
Mets had last season; Cleveland acquired Tyler Houston, another
versatile player, four days after trading for Harold Baines, a
veteran designated hitter; and Boston tried to solve its closer
problem by securing Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some moves have helped teams win, others have
not been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day,'' Phillips said, ``if you look at where you are on
that given day, you feel good or bad about your acquisition. Of
course, you don't draw a final conclusion until the season is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt that day, Phillips said, ``I feel pretty good
today. I think we've been right more than we've been wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
