<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BERTELSMANN-2TAKES     09-04 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BERTELSMANN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA COMPANY WALKS AWAY FROM TAX DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bertelsmann AG, the third-largest media company in
the world, has decided to walk away from $28 million in tax breaks
for the new headquarters for its Random House publishing division
rather than comply with a last-minute city request to conduct a
full environmental review of the $300 million project.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the company will proceed with construction of the
31-story tower on Broadway, between 55th and 56th streets.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent more than two years looking for a suitable
location, and a year negotiating with city officials over an
incentive package. Construction is to begin Nov. 1, and the company
recently learned that to obtain the subsidies it would have to
conduct the environmental review, a process that could take a year.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to incur any additional delays, Bertelsmann balked
last week. Some executives said they suspected that the city's
last-minute demand was being used to renege on the tax breaks, and
city officials countered that they were not asking for anything out
of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city's zoning law does not require an environmental
review in this case, Bertelsmann has decided to forgo the $28
million in tax breaks and proceed with what will be called the
Random House Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incentive package is not as important as our need to
consolidate our employees at Random House into one state-of-the-art
building,'' said Robert Sorrentino, president of Bertelsmann Inc.
``We did not ask the city for any special treatment. We respect the
mayor's decision, but we'll go ahead without the city's incentive
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorrentino said his company would conduct its own environmental
analysis and resolve any problems, like traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden turnabout by Bertelsmann raises a critical question
about the city's policy of granting tax breaks to some of the
largest, most profitable corporations in the world: If Bertelsmann
can proceed without the tax breaks, why did Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's administration offer them in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning down a tax break is pretty good evidence that the
subsidy wasn't ever needed,'' said Diana Fortuna, president of the
Citizens Budget Commission, a nonprofit organization. ``I'm sure a
lot of these projects could fly without government support.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban planners, anti-tax groups, labor unions, liberal analysts
and good-government groups like the Citizens Budget Commission have
long criticized the tax breaks as a form of corporate welfare,
particularly when the economy is strong. They say the deals shift
the tax burden to small and medium-sized companies, while depriving
the city of needed tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Bertelsmann decision gives credibility to their contention
that companies choose to expand or relocate for business reasons,
not because city officials offer a special tax bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that they should be trying to create a good
business environment for all businesses, large and small,'' Ms.
Fortuna said. ``That can be done by improving schools and public
transportation and lowering taxes across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the New York economy surged in recent years, the
Giuliani administration provided more than $2 billion in tax breaks
for 50 companies, including Viacom, Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber,
the New York Stock Exchange, and News Corp. Under the state law
governing such subsidies, the tenant must sign an agreement saying
that if it were not for the tax breaks, it would have moved out of
the city or been unable to build a new skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
   So-called corporate retention deals have become so common that
Bear Stearns, CBS and others did not even threaten to leave New
York before getting tens of millions of dollars in tax incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our policy of providing incentives has been
enormously successful,'' Deputy Mayor Randy Levine said. ``In this
case, Bertelsmann was in a time bind. Their need to get into the
building on time outweighed their need for incentives. So the city
gets the best of both worlds: It gets a new building, and it gets
to save money for taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Bertelsmann had completed its acquisition of Random
House in July 1998, the German company had been looking for a home
for both Random House and its Bantam Doubleday Dell consumer
publishing group. The company spent more than seven months last
year negotiating over a site in Times Square across the street from
Bertelsmann's headquarters at 1540 Broadway, but the deal fell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Bertelsmann opened talks with Steve Ross of Related
Cos., who needed a tenant for an 860,000-square-foot building he
planned to build on the west side of Broadway, between 55th and
56th streets. By May, the two sides had come to terms: Bertelsmann
would own and occupy 640,000 square feet of the building and move
in more than 1,500 employees. Retail space and about 130 apartments
would take up the rest of the building. The project did not need
any city approvals.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Levine agreed to provide Bertelsmann with
$28 million in tax breaks, a bit less than what the company had
asked. In the meantime, Ross completed most of the demolition on
the Bertelsmann site.
</P>
<P>
   But before the deal could be approved by the city's Industrial
Development Agency, city officials unexpectedly told Bertelsmann in
early August that to get the tax breaks it had to conduct a full
environmental review, rather than the more perfunctory analysis
that is usually done at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The demand took Bertelsmann by surprise because city officials
had not mentioned that requirement in more than a year of talks on
an incentive package. City officials said the company's lawyers
should have anticipated the request.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the review could kill the project altogether,
while Levine and Michael Carey, the president of the city's
Economic Development Corp., said the city was not asking for
special treatment, according to people on both sides of the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came up at the last minute,'' said one person involved in
the Bertelsmann project. ``It looked like the city was hiding
behind the technicality to pull the tax breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine denied that the Giuliani administration's real motive was
to withdraw the incentive package. Rather, he said, it feared that
the absence of a full environmental review might arouse
neighborhood opposition. ``We didn't want the project delayed by
lawsuits,'' he said. ``We wanted it to go forward.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassment for the Giuliani administration, the state
Supreme Court recently struck down a year-old zoning rule that
allowed Broadway theaters to sell air rights above the theaters to
nearby developers, saying that the city should have conducted an
environmental-impact statement.
</P>
<P>
   Two people familiar with the Bertelsmann project suggested that
the Giuliani administration was now gun-shy. But they said the
city's decision also raised the dangerous possibility that all new
projects might have to conduct what many regard as a torturous
environmental review to obtain tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Several real estate lawyers said that most deals approved by the
Industrial Development Agency involved existing office space, not
new buildings like the Bertelsmann project, and did not require a
full environmental review.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, said Richard Leland, who heads the environmental
practice group at the Rosenman &AMP; Colin law firm, it is reasonable
to assume that a building will be built at Broadway and 55th
Street, whether or not there are tax breaks. ``So there is no real
environmental impact from the tax abatement,'' said Leland, who did
the environmental work for the Bear Stearns tower, which is being
built on Madison Avenue with a city tax break. ``In those
circumstances, it's unusual to require an environmental review.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
