<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILLION-YOUTH-HARLEM-     09-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-HARLEM-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUCK IN MIDDLE, HARLEM LOSES A QUIET WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH) 
(lh) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The White Man Is the Devil'' buttons were on sale
near an antidrug van labeled Mr. Crack, bow-tied men calling
themselves ``messengers of Allah'' hawked Muslim newspapers, and as
many as 30 of New York's finest guarded deserted corners as a
sparse troupe of black teen-agers chanted: ``Whose street? Our
street!''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbert W.D. Love II, an undertaker in Harlem for 47 years, kept
his distance. That was not hard to do on the seven blocks of
Malcolm X Boulevard that had been set aside Saturday for the
Million Youth March, where shortly after the noon starting time,
the crowds on the six-lane boulevard were so thin that frustrated
vendors began packing up almost immediately. Love, wearing a straw
hat, black waistcoat and high-collared white shirt, declared the
rally's organizer, Khallid Abdul Muhammad, ``ignorant and
pompous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole bunch of mess _ a waste of time and money,''
Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the neighborhood have felt caught between Muhammad
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and seemed to blame both leaders
equally for the fact that central Harlem had lost a peaceful summer
weekend for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Even with what appeared to be a far smaller crowd than last
year, they felt their neighborhood was being occupied. Anthony W.
Bowman, 47, who was holding a barbecue in his backyard and said he
did not know anyone who went to the rally, was one of many who
contended that Giuliani had promoted Muhammad's event by denying
him a permit, prompting a widely covered court fight that the city
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being invaded,'' said Bowman, who conducts walking and
bus tours of Harlem. ``Khallid Muhammad and Mayor Giuliani have a
grudge match, and our children are being put on the front line.''
</P>
<P>
   Some participants, however, contended that the event was in
keeping with Harlem's heritage as a center of black culture and
political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of Harlem _ that's where black people belong,'' said
Ronnie Hodge, 40, the superintendent of a five-story apartment
building, who was standing near the stage. ``There was a time you
couldn't move into the white man's neighborhood. But now they come
here, and we don't say nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Diop, 19, a high school senior who has lived on Malcolm X
Boulevard for five years, said all the attacks on Muhammad made him
even more determined to show up, and he skipped a soccer game to
hear the speeches. ``When white people see a crew of blacks
together, they think it's a gang,'' he said. ``This is about peace
and love, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Muhammad who live near the rally site said they
feared that publicity about him would negate the strides Harlem has
made toward redevelopment. Several longtime residents said
Muhammad's anti-Semitic remarks seemed especially out of place
since many of the churches in the area were once synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's rally, many neighborhood leaders and local
ministers canceled vacations so they could offer health and safety
services to rally participants in an effort that one organizer
likened to ``the Red Cross in a hostile zone.'' Six churches opened
to supply water and emergency haven, while 300 volunteers donned
T-shirts saying ``Harlem Community Observer'' and fanned out with
walkie-talkies to try to keep the rally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, as part of Harlem leaders' repudiation of the
rally, many of those organizers and ministers left for the Labor
Day weekend, and no such network was set up. ``It was our actions
last year that gave Muhammad any credibility at all,'' said Terence
D. Tolbert, who was one of the last year's coordinators. ``What's
the expression? `Fool me twice, shame on me.' We were not going to
put ourselves in harm's way for Muhammad's inciting rhetoric.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Saturday's event shut down a summer school program that usually
serves about 125 neighborhood young people on a summer Saturday.
Geoffrey Canada, president of the Rheedlen Centers for Children and
Families, closed three training sites near the march zone because
he feared for the safety of his participants, and because he said
he did not want the comings and goings at his centers to add to the
perceived size of the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Canada's group held what it called a Children's
March for Peace, with an attendance estimated by organizers at
3,200. Supporters noted wryly that the march produced no violence,
no bigotry and little media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Selina Stinson, who heads a neighborhood group called
Looking Forward Tomorrow, spent all week trolling beauty parlors,
grocery stores and soup kitchens, urging residents to stay away
from the rally. ``Please don't be fooled,'' she said over and over.
``Our children don't need to be taught to be hateful. They need to
be taught to go to the library.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Johnson, 40, a school security guard who has lived in
the neighborhood all her life, took her 13-year-old son, Jonathan,
shopping for sneakers during the speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right before school starts, they're getting these kids all
riled up,'' she said. ``They're going to get in trouble, and then
they're going to say, `At the peace march, they told me I should
have free speech.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
