<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCARLIFE-GRAY-C     09-04 1924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARLIFE-GRAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henley Gray: Driven by love of the chase
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Ga. _ Henley Gray speaks of his life in two distinct
chapters: before the wreck and after.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just two different lives, really,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the wreck, Gray, now 66, was one of stock-car racing's
nomads. From 1964 to 1977, he drove in 374 NASCAR Grand National
races.
</P>
<P>
   But that life hit the wall Sept. 14, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   He was coming into the pits at Michigan Speedway after a
pre-qualifying practice run. The car hit a bump and broke the right
front ball joint. Suddenly, the car took a hard left turn and
headed for the wall at 125 mph.
</P>
<P>
   An independent owner-driver who had to make his only race car
last, Gray didn't even consider what might happen to him. ``Before
I hit, I'm thinking: `How am I going to get this car back together
for the race?'''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been in a race car since, nearly 22 years. He keeps a
picture of the remains of that car in a drawer. But he lives that
moment every day. It's like time stopped on that September morning.
The truck he used to haul his car to races is in the back yard,
rotting in the grass. ``I used to think I'd want to be buried in
that truck,'' Gray said, ``but it's in worse shape than me.''
</P>
<P>
   He lives in the same frame house he has for 37 years. He can
point to the spot in the dining room where he and some friends
rebuilt a blown engine on a race weekend at Atlanta. That was
before he built the race shop out back. ``My wife stayed down
there; she didn't know what we were doing, rolling that engine over
on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray gets around gingerly. The wreck nearly took off his left
leg. He walks with a slight limp, and his joints are a barometer.
``I can tell you when it's gonna rain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His feet bear the scars of the acid that sprayed everywhere when
the battery in the Chevelle exploded against the wall. ``The doctor
wanted to know how I'd gotten this blue paint all over my feet,''
he said. The feet are discolored. ``To this day, I wouldn't go
swimming in a public place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still available to help
</P>
<P>
   He's got a shop full of race cars and equipment that might or
might not be for sale; he wants to be ready in case someone calls
him to help out a race team. Gray owned a car that made three races
in 1993; his last try was in 1995, but the car wrecked in
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Steve, works on the Winston Cup team of the No. 4
Chevrolet driven by Bobby Hamilton. When Steve calls and tells his
dad what's going on in the shop, he takes notes. Never know when
they'll come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through it so many times, thinking we were going to
get a deal,'' he said. ``It would go all the way to the last man
and fall through. That's a big letdown, when you think you're
getting ready to get some money to go race on and don't get it.
I've been talking to a guy with a lot of money. Until I see the
money, I won't let it bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife get by on minimum Social Security. ``It's not a
lot, but I didn't pay in a lot over the years,'' Gray said.
``Working for myself, there wasn't that much profit at the end of
the year. It was hard work. But we got by and paid all the bills. I
made a living all them years.''
</P>
<P>
   To race car drivers, especially from the early days, a
retirement fund was like a part for a foreign car. ``It was a case
of, `I'll take care of that next year,''' Gray said. ``If I could
have took 10 percent of all the money I handled and put it back (in
the bank), I'd have a decent retirement fund. I just spent it on
the car.''
</P>
<P>
   If it hadn't been for some inheritance money his wife came into,
some money donated by the racing wives' auxiliary and a $15,000
NASCAR insurance policy, Gray would have had trouble paying the
$20,000 bill for his 2 1/2-month hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't take care of their people,'' Gray said about
NASCAR. ``As far as they're concerned, you're just something
they've got to make money with. If they take care of their own,
it's because the drivers take care of each other, not because
NASCAR took care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray has no trouble recalling the wreck that changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the cars are made, the roll bars and the seat, when it
hit that concrete wall, it just acted like a big knife going down
the left hand side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just peeled the roll bars and the seat right out of the car
and just slung me out of the car against the concrete retaining
wall. I didn't go but about two car lengths before it stopped. I
didn't have any idea that I was really hurt. (But) it didn't take
long for the pain to start. It separated my left knee joint, just
tore it all loose. It was just dangling. When they picked me up, I
couldn't see my leg and I thought that it was gone. I remember
saying, `Well, a lot of people just have one leg; that won't be a
problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   During the years, he has come to terms with how close he was to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two inches,'' Gray said. ``I feel like two inches was the
difference in me living and dying. That's how close that wall was
to me. I mean, I don't know how close it come to me, but right at
my left foot is right where the battery set. And the battery was
disintegrated. The wall hit that battery dead center. If I had hit
the wall, well, that would have been it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was months before Gray realized he'd never drive again. He
returned to simply being a car owner, hiring for a late 1977 race a
young Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnhardt was just getting started,'' Gray said. ``He drove
our car at Charlotte. Had a hard time making the race. And look
what's he's done now and where I am. I was having too much fun
driving, and I should have been working on sponsorships.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray began racing in 1956, winning more than 100 Sportsman
races, including the 1962 Dixie 400 in Atlanta, before moving up to
the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from a quarter-mile dirt race to Daytona. It scared to
me death,'' he said. ``I don't know how you can be that scared and
having that much fun at the same time. Didn't run but 150 mph; I
thought I was going a thousand.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 374 races as a driver and another 118 races as a car
owner, 1964-95, he never won a Grand National _ later Winston Cup _
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way to do that,'' Gray said. ``It took a lot of
money to do that. I had to run the best I could with what money I
had. I did whatever it took to survive and be around at the end of
the year: Slowing down a little bit to finish or using a higher
gear in the car to make the motor last.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple game plan: Do well enough to recover the entry
fee and be running at the end to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to my first race at Nashville, if you bought one
tire for $55, they'd give you another tire. So I bought a set of
tires up there, cost me $110 for four new tires. They only paid
$100 to start, so I was going in the hole to start with. If it was
a hundred-mile race, they paid $100 to start. If it was a 500-mile
race, they paid $500 to start. I had to go by the starting money,
that's what I knew I had made. Everything made above that was
extra.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of times, he had to race on the best used tires he
could afford and nurse his car along, to be there at the end. Or
know when to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darlington in '71 paid $550 to start the race. You had to
finish 21st to make $150. It paid $175 for finishing 12th. You
gotta run a long time, a lot of laps, and it wasn't worth the
difference in the money. Sometimes, I'd just have to park. I had to
decide whether I could make the most money running or parking it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did finish fourth in the Winston Cup points race once, in
1966, by saving his car. ``I done it by running miles, finishing
races,'' Gray said. ``Just backing off going into the turns, not
turning quite as many rpms, I'd make sure the engine would live
till the end. You cannot race hard with no money. You have to race
by whatever your pocketbook will let you.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsponsored and without much funding, Gray found out quickly
that there was honor and money in making the field and just
finishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 25 of us that were called independents,'' Gray
said. ``We had one car that we carried everywhere. If we wrecked
it, we had to have that thing fixed by the next week or we didn't
have any money coming in. I used to make the statement if that
thing gets cut in half this week, I'd better have it put back
together by the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it felt like a great adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running all the races, going all over the United States,
getting to see the country, getting paid for it. I was really
enjoying it. Every week was a new experience going somewhere else
I'd never been before, getting on a different race track. It was
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loaded the family up and went on the road every week during
the summer. There was five of us. We had to find a motel with a
good pool for the kids (Cheryl, Pam and Steve). Pam said the other
kids at school only got to go someplace once a year. She got to
where she wouldn't even talk about it because she felt guilty, like
she'd be braggin' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   He was racing so often, 52 times a year, a friend told him,
``You must have ball bearings in your brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Raced everywhere
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a record book that says I went to Savannah three
times,'' Gray said. ``I don't remember going to Savannah but once.
See, every week you just went somewhere. I always had that fear I
was going to go to the wrong race track.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest headline he made in his career read: ``Henley Gray
Fined By NASCAR Heads.'' He was caught using nitrous oxide to juice
his Chevrolet to 186.521 mph in qualifying at Talladega in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just spray it right in the air cleaner,'' he said. ``If
you spray enough of it, it could make 100 horsepower more. A lot of
people were using it. You didn't want to get caught because you
didn't want to quit using it. If you was using that and had it
where it really worked right, you could make every race with no
trouble. I used it for a year solid before I finally got caught
(and fined $1,000.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the nitrous oxide is laughing gas. I had one guy
call me and ask, `What does it do to you? Does it make you brave?'
He thought it was something I was taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing left Henley Gray with a lot of pictures, some trophies
and a bum leg. But the warm memories, like the newspaper clippings,
have faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back now, I can't understand where the excitement
was,'' Gray said. ``I mean, I can't get that enthused. I'd like to,
but I just can't do it. One time we went to California on vacation,
back when I was running them dirt races, probably 1960. I had a
25-lap dirt race here that weekend. I wanted to be here for that. I
drove all the way straight through from California to run that
25-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't walk across the street to sit down in a car now. I
done it so much and seen so much of it that I guess I just wore out
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE 1970s: THE HENLEY GRAY FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 66.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia connection: Born in Rome, where he still lives.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR career: 14 years, 1964-77; career ended after a
practice-lap crash at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Career highlights: 374 starts, no wins, no poles, one
fourth-place finish, four fifth-place finishes, 55 other finishes
in the top 10; of 76,045 laps run, led two laps in one event; won
$265,687.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
