<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HENDLEY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hendley's spot near perfect in history
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ The letter arrived from Augusta, Maine, and was
postmarked Sept. 9, 1985 _ the 20th anniversary of the only
major-league game with just one hit.
</P>
<P>
   The younger son of Bob Hendley _ the forgotten pitcher in that
game _ excitedly tore open the envelope and marveled at the
contents. Inside was an autographed newspaper clipping, two signed
index cards and a personal note:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please say hello to your dad for me,'' it read. ``Sincerely,
Sandy Koufax.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart Hendley, now 28, still can't believe he got a response from
the reclusive Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wrote him, I really didn't think I'd hear back,''
Hendley said. ``It meant a lot to me. I think it did to my dad,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Koufax won three Cy Young Awards, pitched four no-hitters
and was a first-ballot inductee to the Hall of Fame. But even at
the top of his career, Koufax had to be perfect to beat another
left-hander on a September evening in Los Angeles almost 34 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant pitcher of the mid-1960s beat Macon native Bob
Hendley and the Chicago Cubs 1-0 in a pitching duel for the ages.
Koufax pitched a perfect game, striking out 14. Hendley allowed
only one hit _ a bloop double by Lou Johnson with two out in the
seventh inning. The Dodgers' run scored on a throwing error in the
fifth inning after Hendley's only walk.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Koufax told reporters, ``It's a shame Hendley
had to lose a game like that. But I'm glad we got that run, or we
might have been out there all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later in Chicago, Hendley got a little revenge. He
pitched a four-hitter to beat Koufax and the Dodgers 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know about that,'' Bob Hendley said, smiling.
``All they remember is the other game. But I guess it's good to at
least be remembered for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Once hailed as the next Warren Spahn by Milwaukee Braves manager
Bobby Bragan, Hendley hurt his arm in the minors after reporting
late to spring training because of Army duty. He was only 48-52 in
seven major-league seasons with four teams. After a second elbow
surgery in 1969, he retired at age 30 and began a long coaching and
teaching career in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Hendley attended Mercer University in the offseason while
playing baseball and graduated in the spring of 1970. This year is
his 18th at Stratford Academy, after he had coached at Tattnall and
River North, also private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one to live in the past,'' said Hendley, 60. ``Who
knows what would have happened if I hadn't got hurt? What good does
it do to look back and think about it anyway? I've had a good life.
I really enjoyed getting a chance to coach my sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent, 31, and Bart, 28, were hard-hitting first basemen at
Stratford Academy and went on to play at Georgia Southern and
Georgia College, respectively. Brent also played three seasons in
the Oakland A's farm system.
</P>
<P>
   Hendley's school office has no memorabilia from his playing
career, and the items he has at home are tucked away out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd never know my dad had been a major-league pitcher,''
Bart said. ``He just doesn't like to show off or anything. I used
to have to get out baseball cards to show my friends that he really
had been a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendley did attend one old-timers' game in Atlanta in the 1980s,
but it mainly was to let his sons soak up the experience of being
in a major-league clubhouse. ``I was afraid the other players
wouldn't remember me,'' Hendley said. ``But they did. It was
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could forget Hendley, who saw the 6-foot-3 left-hander
match Koufax almost pitch for pitch. Just recently recalled from
the minors, Hendley did not give up one hard-hit ball against the
Dodgers. Johnson's bloop hit to right field came on a slip pitch,
Hendley's change-up.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had scored the game's only run two innings earlier. He
walked, was sacrificed to second by Ron Fairly, who also was born
in Macon, and then tried to steal third. Rookie catcher Chris
Krug's throw sailed into left field, and Johnson trotted home with
the game's only run.
</P>
<P>
   Given a lead, Koufax became even more dominant. He struck out
the last six batters he faced. Harvey Kuenn, pinch-hitting for
Hendley, whiffed to end the game, which was played in 1:43. Hall of
Famer Ernie Banks struck out three times. Koufax finished 26-8 in
1965 and struck out 382 _ a National League record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy had great stuff that night,'' Hendley said. ``I should
know. He struck me out twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hendley also was on the top of his game, he insists it
was not the best game of his career. Pitching for the Milwaukee
Braves in 1963, he had a no-hitter until Curt Flood of St. Louis
tripled with two out in the ninth inning. Hendley ended up winning
9-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing that no-hitter hurt,'' Hendley said. ``I was really
locked in and focused. That's the game I remember most.''
</P>
<P>
   BOB HENDLEY FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 60.
</P>
<P>
   Job: Assistant head baseball coach and physical-eduation teacher
at Stratford Academy in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married to the former Runette Harris for 35 years. Sons
Brent, 31, and Bart, 28; both played college baseball, and Brent
spent three season in Oakland A's farm system.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball career: Left-handed pitcher with 48-52 record over
seven major-league seasons (1961-67). Played for Milwaukee Braves,
San Francisco Giants, Chicago Cubs and New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Highlight: On Sept. 9, 1965, faced Sandy Koufax of Dodgers in
the only major-league game to feature just one hit. Koufax pitched
a perfect game, and the Cubs lost 1-0 on an unearned run. Hendley
allowed one hit and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
