<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-KNOW05-     09-04 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-KNOW05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 things you should know about hockey
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fred Shero, late coach of Philadelphia's ``Broad
Street Bullies,'' once defined his hockey philosophy as follows:
``Take the shortest route to the puck and arrive in ill humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shero's words give some clue as to hockey's nature, but they
don't fully define what separates the sport from those with the
``ball'' suffix _ as in baseball, football, basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, as a primer for the NHL's return to Atlanta, we offer
this list of 10 things that make hockey different:
</P>
<P>
   1: ICE
</P>
<P>
   The NFL can claim some January playoff games in Green Bay and
Buffalo, but even the clumsiest of NHL goons is more graceful than
a nose tackle on frozen sod. According to legend, hockey has its
roots in England and France in the 1400s, when players of field
hockey or a facsimile sought an activity when lakes froze in the
winter. The French word ``hoquet'' means ``bent stick.'' Some
people felt the sport should be banned because it disrupted
peaceful skaters. Les Wimps.
</P>
<P>
   2: ZAMBONI
</P>
<P>
   Where there's ice, there's the funky tractor-like vehicle that
scrapes, cleans and floods the ice between periods. People have
become so fascinated with the machine that there is now a Web site
and a ``Zamboni Driver of the Year'' contest. And take this,
Canadians: The machine was invented by rink owner Frank Zamboni _
in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   3: PUCK
</P>
<P>
   A character in Shakespeare's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
Anybody seriously defining puck that way instead of as hockey's
version of a ball _ a 3-inch-disk of hard, frozen rubber _ gets a
faceful of Tie Domi (No. 28, taunting Sandy McCarthy).
</P>
<P>
   4: FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, basketball and football most often eject fighters.
Hockey either embraces it or turns the other way, depending on what
seems politically correct at the moment. Fighting majors draw a
five-minute penalty. Translation: Players are thrown out for 1/12th
of a game. It's worth noting that Rule 52, ``Deliberate injury of
opponents,'' states as an example: ``A player with taped hands
injures an opponent in a fight. During the same fight, he is also
called for head-butting his opponent. The referee must assess a
match penalty (which includes a suspension) for injuring the
opponent with tape on his hands. A major and a game misconduct
shall be assessed to the player for head-butting.'' It contains a
lesson for younger players out there who want to avoid a
suspension: When in doubt, only head-butt your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   5: STICK
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a baseball player gets to use a stick, too. But it's
usually to hit the ball. A hockey player can find multiple uses for
his stick. For example, we have the ``butt-ending'' penalty, in
which the knob of the stick is jabbed into an opponent's rib cage.
We offer Ulf Samuelsson as an expert stickman, who, when asked his
opinion of the NHL's dirtiest player, responded, ``Can I vote for
myself?''
</P>
<P>
   6: PENALTY BOXES
</P>
<P>
   How much would you have paid to see Conrad Dobler in a penalty
box? Or Dennis Rodman? No other sport includes an incarceration
station. The Thrashers already have asked Matt Johnson for
decorating preferences in the home box at Philips Arena. Kidding,
Matt.
</P>
<P>
   7: POWER PLAY
</P>
<P>
   No other league allows a team to play short-handed, unless you
count the Clippers. When one team has a player in the penalty box,
the other team goes on the ``power play'' and more often than not
spends the next two minutes passing the puck 27 times but fails to
get off a shot. It is completely appropriate for fans to yell
something derogatory at the coach of the team that squandered the
scoring opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   8: CHANGING ON THE FLY
</P>
<P>
   No, it has nothing to do with the woman in seat 2A deciding to
go with the Halston instead of the Versace while somewhere over Des
Moines. It's a team making substitutions during play. All other
sports require a stoppage in play _ and, in the case of baseball, a
20-minute dissertation from the manager to the home-plate umpire.
</P>
<P>
   9: GOALIE MASKS
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has face masks. The NHL has works of art. Football's
togs police ensure that all helmets and masks conform to league
artistic standards. The NHL puts no limits on how goalies paint
their masks, within reason. The first goalie to decorate his mask
was Boston's Gerry Cheevers, who painted stitch marks to indicate
the cuts he would have received without the mask. At the other end
of the spectrum: Gump Worsley, the last mask-less goalie who
received more than 200 facial stitches in his career. Vancouver's
Corey Hirsch, a reflection of his sometimes flaky fraternity,
saluted ``Psycho'' by having a ``Bates Motel'' replica painted on
his mask.
</P>
<P>
   10: EUROPEANS
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has a Europe League. The NHL has a European flavor. No
other sport's top athletes _ Hasek, Jaromir Jagr, Peter Forsberg,
Alexei Yashin, Teemu Selanne _ carry a foreign passport. However,
that fact does not go over well in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
