<HEADER>
A0948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERSTART05-C     09-04 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERSTART05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers on the (b)rink of debut
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Now, they are like every other NHL team. No more
mock expansion drafts, no more choreographed jersey unveilings, no
more blur of breakfasts with men's clubs from the local church and
synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this morning, when 65 players ranging in age from 18
to 35 and in dimensions from 5 feet 8, 185 pounds to 6-5, 232, and
hometowns from St. Paul, Minn., to Pribham, Czech Republic, step
into an Orlando ice rink, the Thrashers are just like everybody
else _ a hockey team in search of an identity, a roster and a power
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this is the climax to what we've been building the
last 13, 14 months,'' said the team's general manager and chief
architect, Don Waddell. ``We're 2 years old at this point, but
we're getting ready to kick off our second life.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't officially begin until Oct. 2, when the NHL expansion
team opens its regular season against the New Jersey Devils at
Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Waddell and coach Curt Fraser have more player
grading, trimming and molding to do than any other GM-coach duo in
the league. The 65 players represent 10 to 15 more than most NHL
teams will bring to camp, in large part because the Thrashers are
the league's closest thing to a ``help wanted'' sign. There are no
fan favorites yet, no players who will be retained merely for
salary or political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers have more jobs to fill than anybody else:
Twenty-three will make the NHL team; an additional 12 to 15 will be
kept and assigned to the top farm team, the IHL's Orlando Solar
Bears; and a few will be placed on the ECHL's Greenville Grrrowl.
The rest will be cut, traded or returned to their respective junior
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches will be looking to change a few roster spots and
maybe shuffle forward line combinations and defensive pairings.
Fraser's immediate concern is getting across to his players
elements of the big picture: rules, attitude, philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Like rule No. 1: No golf. Although, as Fraser said, ``If any of
our guys feel up to golfing, we're probably not doing our jobs as
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely going to lay out what I expect and what I need
out of everybody,'' Fraser said. ``We have guys coming from a lot
of different camps. Some of these guys probably feel like they've
been going to training camp for 100 years. But our work ethic has
to be second to none; our intensity has to be way above average.
This is the time to prove yourself and get a jump on other teams.
This is no country club.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected camp to be more physical than normal,
Fraser said, ``I'm sure some guys are going to try to show their
stuff. I don't want anybody getting hurt. I don't want anybody
getting hit from behind. But I do want them to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 65 players in camp, 10 are being given free-agent tryouts
and four are invitees of the Solar Bears. But the majority of the
Thrashers' roster will comprise players acquired in the expansion
draft (forwards Kelly Buchberger, Terry Yake and Matt Johnson, for
example), those picked up in pre- or post-expansion draft trades
(goalie Damian Rhodes, defenseman Gord Murphy) and free-agent
acquisitions (forwards Nelson Emerson and Ray Ferraro).
</P>
<P>
   The lone draft pick who will make the final roster will be
center Patrik Stefan, although rookie center Andreas Karlsson, a
former Calgary draft pick who has been playing in Sweden, also is
given a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will rely on goaltending, defense and
aggressiveness in its first season, because skilled scorers are in
short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Based on last year's NHL statistics, the Thrashers' major
goal-scorers will be Ferraro (13), Emerson (13), Andrew Brunette
(11), Terry Yake (9), Mike Stapleton (9), Johan Garpenlov (8).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams can be skilled, and everybody can try to work
hard,'' Fraser said. ``But if we can have an edge to our hockey
club, work hard and pay attention to details, we can be
competitive. And we're going to have to be physical. My philosophy
is to be aggressive offensively and entertaining. I want to attack,
force the other team in mistakes. I want a team that energizes the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, the oldest player on the roster at 35, says he is
looking forward to a new atmosphere after Los Angeles decided he
could not return to 20-goal form because of injuries and age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel L.A. made a mistake not re-signing me? Yeah, I do,''
Ferraro said. ``I know I can still play. I'm disappointed they
didn't give me an opportunity to come back. But to be honest, I'm
excited to go to Atlanta. I'm excited to go to a team that wants me
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   As to what he expects in camp, Ferraro said, ``I'm good friends
with one of the assistant coaches in Nashville, Brent Peterson, who
I used to play with in Hartford. He really liked what went on in
Nashville. He liked the enthusiasm everybody had. Nashville became
a tough team for everybody to play because they were enthusiastic
and they worked hard and all the players wanted to show everybody
that they belonged. Our biggest challenge will be to show everybody
we belong and that we can compete.''
</P>
<P>
   It holds true not just for the players but also for the general
manager and the coach. Waddell and Fraser have proved their
abilities at the Class AAA level, the IHL, but not in the NHL. The
fate of Ted Turner's $80 million investment is in their hands. But
both men will stick with the formulas that got them where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, not blessed with an abundance of natural ability to play
hockey, nonetheless accumulated 193 goals and 433 points in 12
seasons and left his imprint on a number of imposing chins,
collecting 1,306 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, who also built independent expansion franchises in San
Diego and Orlando into league finalists, has excelled at the
business side of the sport and thinks that player evaluation is his
strength. That this is the NHL doesn't make a difference, he says.
The same thing that makes a player successful at one level _
talent, character, discipline, effort _ makes him successful at
another.
</P>
<P>
   In Waddell's blueprint, the team will be equal parts dash and
crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing we wanted to do was create a foundation for the
future,'' he said. ``This is not a short-term project; it's a
long-term project. You lay the groundwork, you hire good people
and, when the puck drops, you start to move in another direction.
You look for ways to improve. You identify who are are, what you're
about, who are your leaders. It's not important what our record is
after five games but how we're doing three to five years from now.
That starts Oct. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, who has a one-year contract plus an option, knows he
isn't here for the five-year plan. The transition must be quick and
painless, even if going to camp with an expansion team ``is a
complete unknown for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the guys personally, but in camp I'll have a lot
of time to get to know everybody a little bit,'' Ferraro said.
``It's going to be interesting. We're all starting on the ground
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
