<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-WHATHOCKEY05-COX     09-04 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WHATHOCKEY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's happening in the NHL
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Need to get up to date on the NHL? Here are some
things to remember:
</P>
<P>
   Who are the rivals?
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers, who open the regular season Oct. 2 against New
Jersey at Philips Arena, are the NHL's 28th team. Two more
expansion teams, Minnesota and Columbus, will begin play in the
2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will play in the Southeast Division with Carolina,
Florida, Tampa Bay and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MVP eyes retirement
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek didn't retire, but he announced his
desire to do so after the season. Hasek, who almost single-handedly
won an Olympic gold medal for the Czech Republic and led the Sabres
to the Cup finals, said he wants his children to grow up in his
homeland, remarks that will not be amplified by the Buffalo Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the money?
</P>
<P>
   Right now, several NHL veterans don't plan to retire, but their
asking prices are scaring off buyers. Among the available
unrestricted free agents going into training camps: Ulf Samuelsson,
Joe Murphy, Pat Verbeek. Further, Boston granted Dmitri Khristich
``walkaway'' free-agency rather than accept a $2.8 million
arbitration decision.
</P>
<P>
   New season begins
</P>
<P>
   The regular season opens with two games Oct. 1: The defending
Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars will host Jaromir Jagr and the
Pittsburgh Penguins, who did not change addresses because they were
rescued in bankruptcy court by Mario Lemieux. In the other game,
the New York Rangers visit the Edmonton Oilers in a meeting between
the teams that bookend Wayne Gretzky's resume. Appropriately,
Gretzky, who retired after last season, will be honored in pregame
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers open wallet
</P>
<P>
   OK, not everybody is practicing fiscal responsibility. The
Rangers assaulted the free-agent market as if it were the
``seconds'' bin at Wal-Mart. They bought five players for $62.85
million, including Theo Fleury, whom Colorado chose not to re-sign
after his playoff fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   In the crease
</P>
<P>
   The NHL, red-faced after last year's Stanley Cup final ended on
a disputed goal by Brett Hull, moved quickly to chuck the
``skate-in-the-crease'' video rule. Video replays now will be used
only for determining whether a puck crossed the goal line. On-ice
officials will determine whether an attacking player has his skate
in the crease or causes interference during a goal.
</P>
<P>
   New overtime look
</P>
<P>
   League officials got a little gimmick-crazy in the offseason.
Determined to reduce the number of tie games _ 162 last year _ the
league decided that teams tied after regulation will be guaranteed
a point in the standings, no matter what happens in overtime.
Further, the teams will play four on four (not counting
goaltenders) during the five-minute overtime. Apparently, the NHL
has no plans to make anybody skate blind-folded.
</P>
<P>
   Twin-less in Vancouver
</P>
<P>
   While the first overall pick in the draft, the Thrashers' Patrik
Stefan, will play in the NHL this year, the second and third picks
won't. Vancouver's Daniel and Henrik Sedin decided to return to
Sweden to play with their team, MoDo, finish their last year of
high school and, presumably, attend their Swedish prom, which is
said to be killer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
