<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-BEATING-TRI     09-04 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BEATING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL SET FOR OFFICERS LINKED TO ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early on the morning of Dec. 19, 1997, a 36-year-old
Brooklyn man, Reginald Bannerman, was struck and killed by a No. 2
subway train rumbling into the Sterling Street station in Crown
Heights. The city medical examiner's office called his death a
suicide, although other investigators said they could not rule out
the possibility that he had accidentally fallen onto the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   His death might have remained an obscure misfortune, except for
what law enforcement officials say happened less than an hour
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   They said Bannerman, a recreation specialist in an after-school
youth program who also worked as a porter in a Crown Heights
restaurant, had been kicked and beaten by at least two off-duty New
York City police detectives outside the restaurant. The authorities
said a group of detectives had become disorderly during a
liquor-fueled birthday party in the restaurant, and Bannerman was
attacked after he had tried to quiet them down. The assailants also
fired their guns over Bannerman's head as he ran away from them,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 minutes later, Bannerman was struck and killed by the
train. In the interval, investigators say, a deeply upset Bannerman
had stopped at a friend's house, where he had refused the friend's
offer to take him to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of some or all of the four detectives is scheduled to
begin Tuesday in state Supreme Court in Brooklyn. None have been
charged in connection with Bannerman's death. Rather, they are
accused of crimes including assault and tampering with evidence
stemming from the confrontation with Bannerman outside the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear how many are to go to trial this week,
defense lawyers and prosecutors said, because the judge, Albert
Tomei, has not yet ruled on defense motions for separate trials and
for dismissal of the charges against one detective. The judge is
expected to issue his rulings Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trial is expected to illuminate the violent
encounter outside the BBB Soul and Seafood Restaurant at Bedford
Avenue and Crown Street, lawyers in the case say it is not expected
to establish definitively what propelled Bannerman onto the subway
tracks less than an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   After Bannerman's death, his relatives said they had been told
by witnesses that the detectives had beaten Bannerman at the subway
station until he had jumped onto the tracks to escape. But the
investigators said witnesses they had spoken to had rebutted that
account.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have witnesses seeing him come into the station,'' one
investigator said last week, and ``nobody sees anybody pursuing him
to the station.'' The investigator said no witnesses saw any
detectives at the station.
</P>
<P>
   Other investigators have quoted a passenger at the station as
saying that Bannerman had been alone, pacing back and forth on the
platform. And the authorities also quoted the motorman of the train
that hit Bannerman as saying he had jumped.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Bannerman's family, Ronald L. Kuby, agreed last
week that there was no evidence that the detectives had chased
Bannerman to the station. But Kuby also rejected the theory that
Bannerman had committed suicide, insisting that the detectives were
responsible for the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most likely thing that happened is that he was
injured so badly, about the head and one of his eyes, which was
protruding from its socket, that he accidentally fell in front of
the train because he was incapable of seeing where he was
walking,'' Kuby said. ``But for the beating, that would have never
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the indictments last year, the Brooklyn district
attorney, Charles Hynes, took a similar tack. While there was no
evidence to support murder or manslaughter charges, he said, ``if
Bannerman had not been assaulted in this manner, he would probably
be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the indicted detectives, who at the time of the
incident were all members of the Brooklyn South narcotics unit,
said their clients were not guilty of any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the detectives, Lloyd Barnaby, 38, and Mark Cooper, 29,
are charged with second-degree assault, prohibited use of weapons
and reckless endangerment. Court papers indicate that the
prosecutors _ Charles M. Guria and Lance Ogiste, executive
assistant district attorneys in Brooklyn, and Matthew Greenberg, an
assistant district attorney _ will argue that Barnaby and Cooper
kicked and stomped Bannerman, beat him with a bottle and fired
shots over his head as he staggered to his feet and fled.
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby is also charged with intimidating a witness, Cooper is
charged with menacing Bannerman's brother with a gun, and both are
accused _ along with Detective Edward Howard, 31 _ of tampering
with evidence by picking up and hiding the spent shell casings to
thwart investigators. The fourth detective, Orice Connor, 30, is
charged with official misconduct, accused of failing to report the
actions of the others. Connor's lawyer is seeking to have the
charges against him dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby's lawyer, Dino J. Lombardi, said the detectives had
``felt themselves threatened by a couple of individuals who were
for some reason taking a negative attitude,'' and Bannerman had
``continued to provoke the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's lawyer, Alan I. Friess, said he was confident that the
jury would acquit his client.
</P>
<P>
   And Marvyn M. Kornberg, the lawyer representing Howard and
Connor, said, ``There's no question in my mind they will be
vindicated because they did nothing wrong.'' Kornberg said his
clients would forgo a jury trial, so that Tomei would render a
verdict for them while the jury rendered a verdict on the other
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, who are free on bail, are on restricted duty
pending the outcome of the case. The most serious charge,
second-degree assault, is punishable by up to seven years in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
