<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TO A FATHER, `MARTINA AND SERENA ARE JUST KIDS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sitting on a golf cart Saturday morning, puffing
contentedly on a thin cigarette, Richard Williams did not hesitate
when asked what his big-picture goals were for his fast-moving
daughters, Venus and Serena, in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep them sane until they are 25 years old,'' one of America's
most famous fathers said with the slightest of bemused smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Venus was on one of the nearby practice courts, hammering serve
after 100 mph serve. Serena was off resting for her third-round
match later in the day against Kim Clijsters. Behind Richard
Williams and family, he hoped, was the latest so-called tennis
controversy, an old-fashioned cafeteria food fight between Serena
and Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Martina to Serena: ``Big mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena to Martina: ``Bird brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Pete Sampras' withdrawal, this is what passed for
headlines during a mighty slow first week of the U.S. Open. And
when you really think about it, when you compare this to what
consistently stains the pro and college sports environment, we
should be accessed a penalty point and threatened with default of
news media privileges for so much as insinuating the
Williams-Hingis tiff as ``controversy.'' Abuse of concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said a couple of things that should never have been
said,'' Richard Williams said. ``Martina and Serena are just kids.
How many times do you tell your kids, `Don't say that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, unwittingly, it was Richard Williams who knocked over
the first glass, when he confidently raised the notion of an
all-Williams final, which naturally got under Hingis' thin,
competitive skin. He said he was postulating more than he was
forecasting. Either way, it wasn't a crime, not even an insult. It
was just another harmless observation that drew smoke from
sensitive teen-age ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to raise your kids in front of the world out
here, and at the same time you want them to win,'' Richard Williams
said. ``You're bound to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, degrees of teen-age separation and tennis
family dysfunction. Practicing alongside Venus Williams Saturday
was Mary Pierce, whose father had to be legally severed from her
side, if not her psyche. And first on in the Arthur Ashe Stadium
Saturday was Jennifer Capriati, overpowering 11th-seeded Nathalie
Tauziat, 6-3, 1-6, 6-1, adding another stitch to the tatters that
the unfettered pressures of teen-age tennis made of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the extreme cases, the Hingis and Williams families
could collaborate on the how-to manual. The parents of these
players _ and throw in Lindsay Davenport's, too _ never seem to get
enough credit for the jobs they've done, under the most oppressive
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina's a good kid,'' said Richard Williams, who Friday had
his shirt signed by Hingis in a staged peace process. ``She's No.
1, and that creates a whole new set of problems because everybody
is nipping at you, and it's only natural, especially for a kid, to
feel threatened. I can already see that Venus and Serena made
better decisions on certain things when they were younger than they
do now. These kids are out there trying to please the media, the
sponsors and their parents. I wouldn't be surprised if we see some
kid go nuts out here one day. It's rough, and that's why I kept my
daughters away from this for as long as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   wo years ago, more than a few tennis people were willing to
wonder if Richard Williams' girls, schooled away from the junior
tennis grind, faced the possibility of being colossal flops. Now,
every day at the Open is Williams Family Day. The sisters are
energetic, engaging, edgy. They appear to have it all, except Grand
Slam victories, and those are obviously coming.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has five Grand Slam titles, but she is naturally wary of
the Williams sisters, the new girls strutting down the halls of her
school. Hingis isn't the first 18-year-old to be threatened by the
calamity of less attention. She'll survive these occasional,
inevitable eye-poking contests. Her nasty remarks last winter about
Amelie Mauresmo's lesbian lifestyle were not so easy to laugh off,
even if they were less scornful, more snide.
</P>
<P>
   When Billie Jean King heard that Hingis had called Mauresmo
``half a man,'' she said she would have to call Chris Evert, who is
Hingis' tour mentor. Zina Garrison and Pam Shriver serve in similar
capacities to Venus and Serena, as part of a Women's Tennis
Association player development program that, in Richard Williams'
typically expressed opinion, doesn't really work.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have any effect, it has to be about more than tennis,'' he
said. ``It has to be about family, about education.''
</P>
<P>
   Father or friend, mother or mentor, they all face the same
eternal obstacles of adolescence. There are always concessions,
bearable conditions in the interests of granting teen-agers their
space. Melanie Molitor's daughter, Hingis, had a rebellious early
summer, but what 18-year-old doesn't occasionally tell her parents
to get lost? Formal education or not, Hingis arrived on tour
thoughtful and well-spoken in a third language. She's talented and
smart, and with any luck, she'll survive being a kid. She'll be 25,
and then she and the Williams sisters can insult each other in more
mature ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-SYRIA-1STLD-     09-04 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-SYRIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING ON TO SYRIA, ALBRIGHT WIDENS HER EFFORT FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS top 14 grafs to rewrite with U.S. official's assessment of
Albright-Assad meeting and to add details.) (js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ A widely anticipated meeting here Saturday
between Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the Syrian
leader, Hafez al-Assad, failed to yield anything that would lead to
the immediate resumption of talks between Israel and Syria, a
Clinton administration official said after the session.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the official said, the meeting between Albright and
Assad, their first in two years, was encouraging in laying the
groundwork for new Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who attended the meeting and has dealt with Assad
in the past, said that the Syrian leader stuck to his public demand
that Israel must recognize the 1967 border between the two
countries before talks can resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I heard any movement on that,'' the official said
of Assad's position.
</P>
<P>
   But in a general sense the encounter had been encouraging
because Assad said he recognized the new Israeli prime minister,
Ehud Barak, as a ``serious and honorable'' man, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived here a day after announcing a new peace deal
between the Israelis and the Palestinians that the Clinton
administration hopes will boost the chances of a broader Middle
East settlement, including peace between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who is in failing health, appeared to be in no worse
condition than expected Saturday, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian leader, who met with Albright; Dennis Ross, the
administration's top Middle East negotiator, and other U.S.
officials, appeared to recognize the improved atmosphere for peace
in the region, according to the account given to reporters
traveling with Ms. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   But both Israel and Syria hold different views on how the talks
should begin, and the United States would work to bridge the
differences, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries wanted the United States to play a role in
bringing them together in a way that would produce a final
agreement rather than arranging talks for the sake of talks, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' role would be that of a ``facilitator,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides want us to play a role to find a way for them to
get together in a way that would produce a result,'' said the
official. The Syrians have said that once negotiations begin, they
can be completed in a matter of months. The Israelis have not
disagreed with this.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with the Syrian foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa,
the official said that Albright had raised the issue of Syria as a
country that is annually listed by the Clinton administration as a
terrorist state. In apparent preparation for making peace with the
Israelis, the Syrians have told Palestinian groups in Syria that
they should deal only with political matters and stop their
terrorist activities. The official said that Sharaa had confirmed
that directive.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before sitting down with Assad at his palace here, Albright said
at a news conference that she had brought ``some assessments'' made
by the United States on the particulars of the Israel-Syria
negotiations before they stopped in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that Washington was the depository of record for
the past talks, which involved Warren M. Christopher, the former
secretary of state, and that finding a formula for restarting the
negotiations on the basis of that record was the key to unlocking
the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Syrian leader has insisted on what Damascus has
called an agreement by Yitzhak Rabin, made when he was Israeli
prime minister, to a full withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which
Israel captured during the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has specifically said that he will agree to restart
negotiations only if the Israelis take as a baseline the return of
the Golan Heights to the boundary of June 4, 1967, meaning that
Syria's border with Israel would go to the shore of the Sea of
Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has also said that Rabin promised this in the last round
of negotiations if security measures for Israel, including the end
of hostilities in Southern Lebanon, were met. But the Israelis have
said that Rabin never made such a definitive pledge and that as a
new boundary, they want a border agreed to internationally in 1923,
which does not reach to the Galilee shore.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By demanding that Barak accept the 1967 line as a starting point
for the talks, Assad is leaving the Israeli prime minister with
little leverage, Israeli officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Saturday that the United States was willing to
help Israel and Syria again. President Clinton and Assad exchanged
letters in July on the prospect of resumed talks between the
Israelis and the Syrians, and they have spoken once on the
telephone since Barak's visit to Washington in July, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Albright stressed that the announcement of an
agreement on Friday night between the Israelis and the Palestinians
should spur on the Syrians. ``We have a window of opportunity, and
the light that came from yesterday's agreement should illuminate
the whole region,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharaa, the Syrian foreign minister, repeated Saturday after a
joint news conference with Albright that Syria would like to
``resume the talks at the point where they left off,'' indicating
that the June 1967 line remains the Syrian starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hope that will bring some good news from Israel,'' the
foreign minister added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the picture for the United States, according to
U.S. officials, was the effort over the last several years by
Ronald S. Lauder, a former U.S. ambassador to Austria, to negotiate
with the Syrians on behalf of the previous Israeli prime minister,
Benjamin Netanyahu. Clinton administration officials said that they
had not been briefed on what Lauder had done but were concerned
about the message that his talks had left with the Syrian leader.
Lauder has not commented on his talks with Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Itamar Rabinovitch, who conducted the Israeli side of the talks
with the Syrians from 1993 to 1996, said that Albright's trip was
vital for Barak's goal of completing a peace deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The new Israeli prime minister has said he wants to pursue two
tracks of the peace process _ with the Palestinians and the Syrians
_ at the same time, an ambitious plan that has not been
successfully pursued by former Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak needs to know whether the Syrian track is feasible,''
Rabinovitch said. ``Her trip could be an opportunity to see if it
is feasible.'' Rabinovitch said that Assad's ``cordial music''
toward Barak immediately after Israeli elections had been replaced
by ``critical tones, but not inimical tones.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rabinovitch said that Assad's failing health and his
desire to have a peace deal with Israel in hand before his son,
Bashar, succeeds him was a driving force for the Syrian leader.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Syria, Albright made a quick and unscheduled stop
in Beirut, the first secretary of state to fly in to the Lebanese
capital on an official plane since George Schultz in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Her visit was intended to demonstrate two important points,
administration officials said: that the Lebanese government was
making strides in normalizing life in the country and that the time
was right to widen the Middle East peace process to include
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met with the Lebanese prime minister, Selim Hoss, and
expressed the desire of the United States to see talks resumed
between Israel and Lebanon, her aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government is crucial to a successful negotiating
track between the Syrians and the Israelis because terrorist
groups, chiefly Hezbollah, operate in Southern Lebanon under the
control of the Syrians and with Lebanese acquiescence.
</P>
<P>
   One of Syria's conditions for negotiating with Israel is that a
negotiating track also begin with the Lebanese, an administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   While security conditions have improved substantially at the
Beirut airport, they have not improved sufficiently for U.S.
commercial aircraft to land there. A U.S. travel ban on American
citizens' visiting Beirut was lifted two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
