<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS ON FAST PACE TO SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you do not count the volunteers who sneaked on the track
after midnight for a run and a well-deserved giggle, the last race
contested at this year's world track and field championships in
Seville, Spain, was won by Michael Johnson and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That victory in the 4x400-meter relay last Sunday was an
appropriate finish. Johnson had been the only athlete to break a
world record in Seville, running the 400 in 43.18 seconds, and the
United States was again the leading nation at the biennial
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it won its lowest total of medals, 17, since the
event began in 1983, 11 of the medals were gold, which was five
more than any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lingering paradox that Americans are dominant in this
global sport in which the American public takes scant interest,
except for a few days every four years at the Olympics. Imagine
what sort of greeting would have awaited Johnson at home if he were
an Italian; or what might have awaited Maurice Greene, a triple
gold medalist, if he were Swedish or South African.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' continuing success is a tribute to its vast
depth of athletic ability, the enduring strength of scholastic
programs and the expertise and energy of thousands of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most visible of those coaches _ John Smith, who
coaches Greene, and Joe Douglas, Carl Lewis' former coach and
manager _ are guardedly optimistic about their sport's future in
the United States, after a season in which the number of domestic
meets and the level of domestic television exposure increased along
with revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some good responses; we're starting somewhere,''
Smith said. ``We've got a new chief executive officer taking over,
and we're trying to change a sport in one year that's been run
another way for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, the former miler who is USA Track and Field's new
chief executive officer, expressed particular delight with the fact
that for the first time at a world championship, both the American
men and women finished first overall, based on points acquired by
the top eight finishers in each event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a good thing, as is the breakthrough by Inger Miller
in the sprints, C.J. Hunter in the shot-put, Anthony Washington in
the discus and the confirmations by Maurice Greene, Michael Johnson
and Marion Jones,'' Masback said. ``But there is also plenty of
room for improvement. We had what seemed to be an unfortunate
number of mishaps here.''
</P>
<P>
   Those included John Godina's unexpected struggles in the shot
put and discus; Jeff Hartwig's failure to qualify for the pole
vault final; Mark Crear's disqualification for two false starts in
the heats of the 110-meter hurdles; and Jones' season-ending back
injury in the 200 semifinal, which held her to one gold medal and
one bronze in Seville instead of the multiple golds she had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Her ability to achieve her even more ambitious goal of five gold
medals at next year's Olympics in Sydney, Australia, will depend on
her health and her ability to improve in the long jump. Several
experts, including Carl Lewis' sister Carole, who won a bronze in
the long jump at the world championship in 1983, believe that
Jones' back problems are linked to her jumping technique.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' awkward landings put considerable stress on her knees, as
well, and while Carl Lewis rarely needed to use all his jumps in
competitions where he was also sprinting, Jones had to use all six
of hers to acquire her bronze medal in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Lewis thinks that Jones needs to hire a long jump coach
to work alongside her coach Trevor Graham, whose specialty is the
sprints. But that will be for Jones and her entourage to decide,
and if her back problems are not new _ as Austrian agent Robert
Wagner has indicated and Jones' agent Charlie Wells has denied _
then even more reflection is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, at age 23, is the world's dominant sprinter, a dominance
he underscored by bolting past Dwain Chambers of Britain with great
ease on the anchor leg of the 4x100 relay last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had around a two-meter lead, but that is not enough if I go
into the last leg knowing I'm racing against superman,'' Chambers
said wryly.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Masback's mind, in addition to the United States'
fortunes, were the doping and corruption scandals that have plagued
track and other sports recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much more we need to do and do better,'' Masback said.
``But we are doing something, unlike professional baseball and
unlike many other professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question needs to be asked of FIFA, what are you doing?
What are you spending on doping and what is your budget for it and
how many out-of-competition tests did you do last year? Because
that's good for the youth of the world that those questions are
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And frankly as an administrator of sport, I feel that if we
need to take the hit so that all other sports begin to do what they
are supposed to do, then ultimately in the scheme of things, it
will be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lingering doubts, there was much to value. There was
Hicham el-Guerrouj of Morocco floating more than running on his way
to the fastest 1,500 meters in major championship history.
</P>
<P>
   There was the wide-eyed Greene practically pawing the track
before running the second-fastest 100 meters in history. There was
the cancer patient Ludmila Engquist of Sweden covering her eyes and
crying after qualifying for the final of the 100 hurdles; Wilson
Kipketer diving across the finish line to preserve his dominance in
the 800; Inger Miller lying on her back after winning the women's
200 in the absence of Jones and kicking her legs in the air like a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Johnson hunched over next to the clock just past
the finish line, posing for photographers as his 43.18 glowed
behind him. But by Sunday night, there were no more numbers on
display on that device, only a farewell message: ``Adios Sevilla.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time to turn the clock ahead to Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
