A0959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOWN-GOWN-MAKEOVER-AR     09-04 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWN-GOWN-MAKEOVER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 TOWNS COLUMN: GOWN TRIES TO DRESS UP THE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, N.Y. _ Poor Canton, so close to Canada, so far from any
really decent malls. How is it going to get college students to
come all the way up here?
</P>
<P>
   St. Lawrence University, Canton's biggest employer, worries
about those kids and that problem, and it thinks one answer is to
get the old farm village to spruce up a bit, put a little modern
gloss on the aging Main Street, something Starbucky, maybe,
something GAPpy. Anything that _ in the words of Tom Coakley, the
university's vice president _ creates a sense of ``retail
vibrancy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail vibrancy is important for the social atmosphere of a
university,'' said Coakley as he showed off an example of what he
means, the university's new bookstore, whose dark wood and
slate-green accents mimic Barnes &AMP; Noble right down to the category
signs on the bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping is entertainment; these kids have been raised being
entertained in malls, and that goes to this atmosphere, but dressed
up in a book-oriented, liberal arts environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even a 100-year-old university with 600 well-paid jobs has
to tread softly when it comes to telling people up here that they
should follow its lead to make Main Street more appealing to
prospective students and _ more important, Coakley believes _ to
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Albany and Syracuse are downstate to people in St. Lawrence
County, and New York City, seven hours away by car, may as well be
in Virginia. So when the campus basically tells the locals to wash
their faces and tuck in their shirts for the visitors, some people
get their backs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the North Country are very independent, always have
been,'' said Marilyn I. Mintener, a former mayor and the owner of
the Pear Tree gift shop on Main. ``So sometimes they don't like
being told what to do, and maybe the university has been pushing a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Kingston, owner of Josie's Little Pizzeria, calls the
university ``the company,'' and puts the friction down to class.
``It's just two different classes of people, the university and
everybody else, and they just think differently, and they have
different agendas.'' She paused, then added, ``But they bring a lot
of culture. If the university wasn't here, we'd have nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The campus is hardly struggling. Enrollment has dropped from
2,400 in the mid-1980s to 1,900, but only because the university is
choosier, Coakley said. It has been spending $20 million a year on
physical improvements for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the university is trying to look ahead, and it would help if
Main Street had a little more of Chapel Hill or Harvard Square
about it, and a little less deep-woods-barely-hangin'-on.
</P>
<P>
   So St. Lawrence has already handed out tens of thousands of
dollars in low-interest loans to help merchants improve their
storefronts. In exchange for closing Leigh Street through campus,
the university has promised $300,000 to open up more parking behind
Main Street ``to give the village a more mall-like feeling,''
Coakley said.
</P>
<P>
   But the village is balking, and who knows when anything will be
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in the village think St. Lawrence is trying to
run the place,'' said David Curry, the owner of a no-name bar on
Main and a village trustee who opposed closing Leigh Street. ``But
if it wasn't for them, no one would have heard of Canton.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can move Canton in the right direction, it ought to be
Tommy Coakley. He grew up here, played hockey for Canton High and
went to Brown on a hockey scholarship. He lost a leg in an ambush
in Vietnam and married a nurse from the amputee ward. He earned a
master's in economics at Wharton, and, in the timeless pattern of
North Country kids who leave for a while, he found himself headed
home.
</P>
<P>
   Now he worries about making sure young people who visit Canton
and St. Lawrence see what he sees _ the clean air, the quiet, and
the friendly people, even if they do get a little crusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban campuses worry about urban blight, and rural campuses
worry about isolation,'' Coakley said. ``In terms of running a
successful university, having a little isolation and being a little
behind the rest of the world is OK The important thing is not
getting a lot behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
