<P>
   AUTO RACING
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-LIFE _ Life After The Fast Lane. The 1970s: Henley Gray _
For 14 years, Henley Gray raced against the best NASCAR could
muster, but he seldom had the speed to make a big splash on the
track. And now, with the exception of his beat-up body, he doesn't
have much to show for his career _ few trophies, not much money.
``Raced all over the country,'' said Gray. ``And I can't for the
life of me figure out why.'' (Levine, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
54. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE _ Drivers talk about mysteries of Darlington
_ what makes the place so special _ before today's 50th Southern
500. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 20.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-NOTES _ NASCAR notebook. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HENDLEY _ MACON, Ga. _ Once hailed as the next Warren Spahn,
Bob Hendley never lived up to that billing. But for one game in
September, 1965, he was nearly perfect. Unfortunately, Sandy Koufax
was. In the only major-league game to feature just one hit, Koufax
pitched a perfect game as the Dodgers beat Hendley and the Cubs
1-0. Hendley's career was cut short by elbow surgery and he
returned to his native Macon, where he his entering his 30th year
as a teacher and coach. Hendley, 60, says he doesn't live in the
past and doesn't wonder, ``What if?'' (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
