<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISASTER-CLEANUP-REAL     09-04 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-CLEANUP-REAL-730(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: BATTLING BACK AFTER HOUSEHOLD DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BEVERLY SOLOCHEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For four days last spring, Eve and Stanley Queler
lived in an occupied zone, their sprawling Upper West Side
apartment taken over by a small platoon of workers with ladders,
steam-cleaning machines, vacuums and crates stuffed with rags,
sponges and brushes. Streaked with soot and reeking of rubber _ the
residue of a baby-bottle burn-down atop the stove _ the apartment
had been rendered useless.
</P>
<P>
   In Montrose, Gregory Fucheck and his family similarly shared
their home for five days with six former strangers, all workers
dispatched to undo a storm of soot from a malfunctioning furnace.
On the Upper East Side, Maryell Semal lived briefly with a small
group of workers and then for 19 months with the equipment
necessary to dry out a flooded apartment.
</P>
<P>
   And in Chelsea, Kieran McGonnell and Gregg Driben welcomed five
workers who, over four days, performed a miracle of cleanup after a
fire swept through their ground-floor co-op.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these cases, the workers and equipment came from
companies that undertake the nightmarish tasks of cleanup, repair
and restoration when homeowners or renters are hit with household
disasters: floods, fires, foul odors, soot and other kinds of
calamities.
</P>
<P>
   Usually referred to the site by insurance companies, these
specialists in household disasters labor to save as much property
as possible in an emergency so that losses to both the insurers and
the residents are minimal. But that they exist at all is the big
surprise _ and relief _ to the householder in the midst of
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would have to clean the house myself,'' said
McGonnell, an artist and scenic designer whose fire-blackened
apartment held more than 70 of his oils and watercolors.
Envisioning endless trips to the hardware store for buckets and
brooms _ ``my brain kind of stopped working,'' he said _ he planned
to spend two to three weeks cleaning. But by the next day, Maxons
Restorations Inc., a large local property-restoration company, was
on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come in at peoples' worst moments and try to turn a
negative into a positive,'' said Damon Gersh, president of Maxons,
which works on both commercial and residential properties. With a
staff of 25 that responds to emergencies around the clock, Gersh
also taps into a network of 500 other specialists who attend to
everything from fine arts and antiques to damaged books to
chandeliers, silver sets or oriental rugs.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 1,200 such companies worldwide, 115 of which
are in the New York metropolitan region, according to Kimberly
Howard, executive director of the Association of Specialists in
Cleaning and Restoration, one of several trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   Most provide full disaster-restoration services, although some
specialize in one kind only, such as water damage. Yet, Ms. Howard
said, ``Most people are not familiar at all with their services;
after all, most people don't like to think about disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster was the last thing on Fucheck's mind when he woke up
one morning last winter to find black soot in his tissue when he
sneezed. For two days he had noticed but ignored some soot on the
walls of his newly built four-bedroom colonial. But now, he said,
the soot was everywhere. The smell of oil pervaded his home, which
is heated by forced air in open grates in the floors.
</P>
<P>
   A call to his oil company produced an inspector who called
Fucheck's insurance broker. He, in turn, reached for Westfair
Restoration Services of Thornwood. The Fucheck's malfunctioning
furnace was producing ``puff-back,'' an industry term for a
houseful of soot. The soot not only blackened the hems of the white
curtains skirting the heat registers on the floors but also fell
like a veil over every surface and object in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the house of our dreams,'' Fucheck said. ``We thought
everything was ruined. We felt terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Goomrigian, one of four project managers at Westfair,
quickly arranged for six people to be at the Fucheck home from 8:30
a.m. to 5:30 p.m. for five days to methodically scour, polish,
vacuum or shampoo each object in the house. Clothing was picked up
for dry cleaning. Every dish, every knickknack, every toy, was
individually hand-washed. Each room was deodorized. ``It looked
like a brand-new house,'' Fucheck said. ``It had never been so
clean before.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Soot, smoke and a powerful, noxious stench greeted the Quelers
one mild April morning when they returned home from a stroll with
their grandson, for whom they were baby-sitting. A forgotten potful
of rubber nipple rings and a plastic baby bottle being sterilized
on top of the stove had melted and burned in their absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a stupor,'' Ms. Queler said. ``I could not breathe.
We kept thinking that if we opened windows and put on the ceiling
fans, it would help. But we didn't realize it was going into the
carpets and upholstery.'' By the time Maxons was called more than
36 hours later, the soot was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The large Queler apartment, brimming with family photos, art
work, memorabilia from their international travels, oriental rugs,
colorful textiles and musical and office equipment, needed over
$8,000 worth of cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical damage to the naked eye was not apparent, except
in the kitchen,'' said Howard White, a vice president of Maxons who
supervised the systematic work. The odor, however, was
``overwhelming,'' he said, ``and on closer inspection, you could
see the fine residue of soot that had settled everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Queler, the conductor who leads the Opera Orchestra of New
York, was especially worried about her music. ``I have essential
work that I keep here,'' she said. Aside from a grand piano that
she feared would rust, she had records and books, stereo and CD
equipment, and endless materials from her 30-year-career as an
international musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she said, ``I had nothing to worry about. They took
every book out and cleaned it; every record album. They cleaned my
fax, my word processor. They washed curtains. It was just
amazing.'' The piano was cleaned inside and out. Radiators were
dismantled and vacuumed. Item by item, room by room, the house was
sanitized and deodorized. ``The apartment needed a painting
before,'' Ms. Queler said. ``It doesn't anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every household mishap is as extensive or costly as those
that befell these residents. Indeed, according to a 1997 study by
the Insurance Research Council, average national residential
property claims, including thefts, range from $2,000 to $4,000. For
New York City, the average was $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Some accidents _ a spill of merlot on the sofa, a toaster fire _
might be handled by the occupants themselves, with a boost from
Good Housekeeping. But according to Michael Griggs, president of
the National Institute of Disaster Restoration, most restoration
companies handle small problems and large, even if householders
prefer to pay themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gilbert, president of Westfair Restoration Services,
said it is largely when the insurance deductible is high, about
$1,000, and the damage relatively small that people prefer this
option.
</P>
<P>
   The most common situation, Gilbert said, is a water-damaged
carpet in a small flooded room, which would run $400 to $450 to
extract water, remove the padding, apply anti-microbial agents,
dehumidify, provide fans and then return to install new padding and
clean the rug. Cost estimates are provided free.
</P>
<P>
   When the restoration specialists are hired, insurance companies
and individual householders typically receive itemized accounts of
the work performed. One such 15-page report by Maxons for fire
damage in a SoHo loft included these items: cleaning of three frame
mirrors at $5 each; dismantling and cleaning of a toaster oven, $5;
painting the spiral staircase of 13 steps, front and back, plus
banister, using oil-based metal paint, $195; cleaning 300 CDs, 25
cents each, and a 10 percent ozone-decontamination charge on the
dry cleaning of a host of furs, linens and other fine materials,
$91.15.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Howard of the restoration association,
insurance companies often work with preferred vendors and send one
they trust to a site after they have been notified. Indeed, Ralph
Chardavoyne, an insurance broker with Cernese, Pomerantz, Kirtman
in Croton-on-Hudson, who represents Fucheck, said he almost always
calls Westfair in an emergency. ``My clients,'' he said, ``are
looking for immediate help.''
</P>
<P>
   Others prefer to let clients pick their restoration companies.
Either way, policyholders are typically covered for restoration and
cleaning services if that is what is needed. ``It is the
responsibility of the insurance company to make you whole,'' said
Jeanne Salvatore, vice president of consumer affairs at the
Insurance Information Institute in New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When William B. Martin, the claim section manager for State Farm
Insurance in Jericho, gets an emergency call, he sends out an
adjuster who makes an immediate assessment at the scene and lets
the policyholder decide whom to call. Knowing that homeowners may
well be in shock, the adjuster will offer names, if asked. But,
Martin said: ``People are sometimes touchy, and rightfully so. A
certain percentage want to be directly involved in picking their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   When clients choose their own restoration companies, Martin
recommends that they check with the local consumer affairs
departments or Better Business Bureaus for complaints and that the
chosen company be licensed, bonded and willing to provide
references. Another useful benchmark, specialists say, is an
affiliation with professional associations or the employment of
workers certified by the associations.
</P>
<P>
   And when clients pick their own restoration companies, Martin
suggests a conversation between the companies and the insurance
adjusters to be sure there is agreement on pricing.
</P>
<P>
   How much residents end up paying out-of-pocket _ deductible
notwithstanding _ depends on how much and what kind of coverage
they buy.
</P>
<P>
   It is wise, brokers say, to choose replacement coverage rather
than actual cash value, even though premiums might be 10 percent to
15 percent higher. With cash value coverage, depreciation is
deducted on everything from carpeting to computers and that can
make a huge difference should a loss occur.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and renters alike need to be covered for personal
property and liability. Homeowners should be covered for the total
cost of rebuilding their home, Ms. Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   Co-op and condominium owners need coverage for improvements and
alterations like new kitchen stoves or built-in storage cabinets.
Most basic policies cover damage caused by fire, smoke and water
problems stemming, say, from plumbing breakdowns. But brokers warn
that flooding is not covered in standard policies and also
recommend that homeowners check to see if they are covered for
backups of sewers or drains.
</P>
<P>
   While water damage is the most common kind of problem that
restoration companies face, they also encounter the unusual.
Gilbert of Westfair recalls the vandal-like damage caused by three
wild turkeys in one Pound Ridge home. And every year, he said, his
company is called to as many as 25 homes that have been visited by
spraying skunks (which is not covered in most insurance policies).
Timing is critical in all cleanup jobs. Once eau de skunk
infiltrates fabrics, Gilbert said, it is ``very difficult'' to
remove.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring books is a particular challenge. It is not that they
cannot be saved; libraries and bookstores confer accolades on
companies that have rescued large collections. But water damage can
be fatal to books.
</P>
<P>
   Gersh of Maxons said, ``They warp, pages dry as a sodden mass,
ink runs and paper yellows.'' Yet if the book is valuable _ an
assessment that can sometimes be intensely personal _ the volume
can be freeze-dried and reborn in a frozen environment. This is a
very expensive process and more often done for commercial or
institutional clients. Despite the elaborate process, the results,
Gersh said, ``may not be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Ms. Semall's books were salvaged from a devastating flood
she lived through several years ago after firefighters put out a
blaze that claimed the life of a tenant in the apartment directly
above her own two-bedroom Manhattan co-op.
</P>
<P>
   The water first soaked the master bedroom, where she had quickly
propped an umbrella to protect a new computer. With the help of the
superintendent and her son, who lived nearby, she put out pails and
drop cloths and watched as the water, which travels slowly,
mysteriously and relentlessly, continued to saturate her home for
more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Maxons arrived the day after the fire and immediately lifted and
removed the wall-to-wall carpeting throughout the apartment, all of
which was ruined. Using blowers and commercial-grade dehumidifiers
that pull 200 pints of moisture out of the air a day, the company
started a process that ultimately saved Ms. Semall's handsome
herringbone-patterned oak floors, and indeed, almost her entire
home.
</P>
<P>
   But it took an unusual amount of time. The apartment above was
sealed and off limits for months as the estate was being settled,
so no one could get to the source of the problem. ``Every room
upstairs was piled with debris that had been hosed down by
firefighters,'' Gersh said. Even when the dripping stopped, the
moisture, trapped in the floors and walls, was unyielding, and
created a constantly high humidity level in Ms. Semall's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year she lived in chaos, occupying just a small
slice of the living room. She slept on the sofa. Painters,
plasterers, electricians and other workers, all deployed by Maxons,
were regular visitors. ``All I did was give them coffee and cake,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Three elegant antique wooden chests were removed so specialists
could repair their warped and loosened veneers and joints. Window
frames were replaced. The contents from a corridor of dampened
closets were dry-cleaned, boxed and stored. All surfaces, as well
as her books and objets d'art, were treated with mildewcide to
prevent mold and mildew.
</P>
<P>
   Seated now in her comfortable and dry living room, she points
out, with gratitude, that she lost nothing she cared about. Two
dresses, maybe. A few blankets. And yes, the drapes disintegrated.
More important, her ceiling did not collapse and the walls
eventually stopped cracking. And her precious books and other items
of real value to her were saved, treated ``with love and care.''
</P>
<P>
   McGonnell, the artist whose home burned in Chelsea, said he
feared that his richly colored oils, swathed in soot, could not
possibly be restored ``to their glory.'' But he watched ``in
fascination,'' he said, as their vibrant colors re-emerged at the
gentle hands of skilled cleaners applying chemical sponges.
</P>
<P>
   Grateful that his losses were limited, he also acknowledges the
psychological role that the restoration company played in the
ordeal. ``They were not just courteous, but so sensitive to our
needs,'' he said. ``It was extremely comforting to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
