<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-585&AMP;ADD-     09-04 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: RULES ON PERMITS VARY WIDELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your home is your castle, right? Just try building a moat
without getting permission from the plumbing inspector first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're here to ensure the safety of the occupants of
a home,'' said Brian Webster, code enforcement officer for the town
of Vestal in Broome County, N.Y. ``And if you tell me, `Hey, it's
my house, I can do what I want,' I'll tell you, `That's fine while
you live in it, but what about future owners who will have to live
with your mistakes?'''
</P>
<P>
   That sums up the rationale behind the millions of words
contained in the volumes of building, electrical, plumbing and
construction codes found in code-enforcement officers' offices in
cities, towns and villages across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And while the laws of physics ensure that the rules of proper
construction are basically the same wherever you live, the manner
in which those rules are applied and enforced varies _ sometimes
significantly _ from place to place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some towns around here require you to get a permit when you
put new siding on your house,'' Webster said. ``But we count siding
as a property-maintenance thing, so we have no permit
requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the building and construction rules that apply to
owners of commercial properties and residential rental dwellings
are fairly strict; most local governments require building,
plumbing or electrical permits for any work that could even
remotely affect the health or safety of occupants. The rules for
owner-occupied one-family and sometimes two-family houses, on the
other hand, range from permissive to prohibitive, depending on the
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only way you're going to be able to find out for sure
what rules apply to you,'' Webster said, ``is to call the local
building inspector.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, for example, owner-occupants of one-family houses
can perform just about any type of work imaginable on their
buildings, subject to certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a one-family house, a homeowner can do almost everything,''
said Louis Scala, the construction official for North Bergen, N.J.
``All you have to do is demonstrate that you have the knowledge and
ability to do it.'' And that can be done, he said, by a simple
question-and-answer session with the appropriate inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Because a homeowner can do work in a house, however, that does
not mean the homeowner's work will escape the scrutiny of local
officials. Scala explained that under New Jersey's Uniform
Construction Code, building, plumbing or electrical permits are
generally required whenever a property owner intends to build,
repair, renovate, alter, reconstruct, demolish or change the use of
a structure.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Scala said, permits are generally required whenever
any electrical work is being done, and for any mechanical work that
could affect public health or general safety. And whenever permits
are issued, Scala said, one or more inspections are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Scala said that if a new doorway is cut in an exterior wall, the
inspector will likely require a framing inspection to determine
whether the support beam above the new opening is of adequate
strength and size, an insulation inspection to determine whether
adequate insulation is installed in the exterior wall, and a final
inspection after all work has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   And if electrical or plumbing work was performed as part of the
project, he said, an inspection of the work must be performed both
before and after the walls are plasterboarded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In New York City, homeowners generally do not have to worry
about working on their electrical or plumbing systems because, by
law, they are not allowed to touch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules here for electrical work are pretty simple,'' said
Ilyse Fink, a spokeswoman for the New York City Department of
Buildings. ``For anything other than plugging something into an
outlet, you have to hire a licensed electrician.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fink said that the installation of things like
waste-disposal units, ceiling fans and even light switches
typically required the services of a licensed electrician because
it is necessary to tap into the house's electrical system to
perform the work. And while that may seem like overkill, she said,
the rules are intended to protect residents' safety by ensuring
that everything connected to the electrical system is properly
wired and grounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a ceiling fan installed by a licensed
electrician,'' she said. ``I ended up paying more for the
electrician than I did for the fan, but I have the peace of mind of
knowing it was installed properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Satish Babbar, acting deputy commissioner for technical affairs
for the Department of Buildings, said that while a homeowner could
do some minor plumbing work in a single-family home without having
to obtain a permit, the law typically required a licensed plumber
for any work for which a permit was required.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to change a faucet or retile the bathroom walls,
you don't need a permit,'' Babbar said. ``But if you want to move
the sink across the room, you need a permit, and only a licensed
plumber can take out a plumbing permit.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, unlike places that require
inspections by local officials, New York permits licensed
professionals to inspect and sign off on their own work. For
example, he said, a plumber who remodels a kitchen can provide the
Department of Buildings with a certification that all work has been
completed according to applicable codes.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that homeowners in New York City can do
themselves, Babbar said, is construction work. However, he said,
permits are generally required for any work that alters or enlarges
the structure or changes the use of the building _ a broad caveat
covering everything from adding new doorways in load-bearing walls
to adding new walls that create additional rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And whenever a permit is required for a construction project,
Babbar said, a registered architect or professional engineer must
submit plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you want to build a deck yourself,'' Babbar said.
``Well, you can do that. But first you have to hire an architect or
engineer to submit plans with the application for the permit and
you have to file a certification saying that you're not employing
other people to do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, New York's building code allows the professional _ in
this case, the architect or engineer _ to inspect the finished work
and then submit a certification to the department that the work has
been completed in accordance with the plans and the code.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut homeowners, like those in New Jersey, are generally
allowed to perform most work in their homes themselves. And while
permits are typically required for anything other than minor
repairs, it is not necessary to hire a licensed architect or
registered engineer to draft them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most towns in Connecticut, anybody can draw up your
plans,'' said Aris George Crist, a licensed architect in Greenwich,
``but a good architect will enter into a dialogue with an owner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
