<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOWNTOWN-SILICONVALLE     09-04 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-SILICONVALLEY-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN SAN JOSE, HOPES FOR A MORE LIVABLE DOWNTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By MORRIS NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Two high-density residential developments,
one a rental building and the other a condominium project, are the
latest expressions of a 20-year effort to create a vital downtown
in the largest city in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The projects represent the city's attempt to introduce new
housing into a thinly populated urban center. With 900,000 people,
San Jose is the third-largest city in California, but less than 1
percent of its residents live downtown.
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of the new apartment and condominium
complexes, the city will have built only a quarter of the 8,000
units it hopes to complete by 2010, when it expects the population
of downtown San Jose to have swollen to 19,000, from 6,585 today.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders hope that the two new projects, with 424 housing
units, and projects with 1,200 more housing units in the planning
stage will bring hundreds of new residents into the downtown area,
where extensive redevelopment has already brought new office
buildings, parks, cultural venues and historic preservation
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those new developments were either created by or heavily
subsidized by the San Jose Redevelopment Agency, which is sprucing
up the downtown area to compete with better-established office
locations throughout suburban Santa Clara County _ the region
popularly known as Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the largest urban center in Santa Clara County,
downtown San Jose is still coming from behind in the competition
for high-tech tenants in Silicon Valley. Smaller, more suburban
cities like Palo Alto, Menlo Park, Mountain View and Cupertino have
been the main beneficiaries of the phenomenal expansion of computer
and Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   Until World War II, San Jose was an unremarkable farming
community whose greatest distinction was being the seat of Santa
Clara County. Surrounded by fruit orchards, the city was a center
for the canning of pears, prunes, cherries and apricots. After the
war, it grew as a bedroom community for the region's computer- and
defense-related businesses. In the 1950s, city officials saw
homebuilding and annexation as sources of growth, and the city
expanded by 47 square miles during that decade.
</P>
<P>
   The small downtown area was suffering from the loss of major
employers, however, many of them leaving for the suburbs. And it
sustained a severe symbolic loss in 1954, when the city government
left downtown for peripheral neighborhoods. The image of a
depressed downtown became even more dismal in the 1960s, when
entire blocks of aging buildings were bulldozed in the name of
urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Korabiak, downtown coordinator for the Redevelopment
Agency, recalled the dismay he felt when walking through downtown
in 1982, shortly after joining the organization. ``I walked down
First Street and said, `What have I got myself into?' '' he
recalled. ``It was that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, San Jose was just starting a long-term
redevelopment program, funded principally by a portion of the
property taxes levied on newer, suburban-style business parks on
the city's northern and southern edges. The success of those
business parks provides downtown San Jose with the richest flow of
tax increment financing available to any California city, about $90
million annually, Korabiak said. (In tax increment financing, a
portion of property tax revenues is used for redevelopment.)
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Redevelopment Agency has assisted or
provided partial funding for so many downtown projects that it
would be only a slight exaggeration to say that San Jose's new
downtown is the agency's creation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the projects that the agency assisted are the Children's
Discovery Museum, the San Jose Arena, the San Jose Convention
Center, the San Jose Repertory Theater, the Tech Museum of
Innovation, the Biblioteca/Youth Center and the Mexican Cultural
Heritage Gardens. It also helped restore the Civic Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The city has also provided big subsidies to businesses willing
to relocate downtown. Adobe Systems, the software maker, moved into
a new downtown building in 1994 after receiving a $35 million
subsidy from the city. (Much of the subsidy paid for a parking
garage.)
</P>
<P>
   The Redevelopment Agency has also paid for most of an extensive
landscaping program that has turned the banks of the Guadalupe
River into a 20-mile regional park. The riverfront was a selling
point for the Adobe deal, according to Korabiak, who added that the
riverfront is now so popular that the city no longer provides
incentives to companies willing to relocate along it.
</P>
<P>
   The single most ambitious project of the Redevelopment Agency is
the San Jose Civic Plaza, a seven-block redevelopment project that
would bring City Hall back to downtown San Jose, together with a
new Symphony Hall, a new elementary school, a renovated
supermarket, a multitiered public parking structure and 50 housing
units. The City Council approved the project in June.
</P>
<P>
   But downtown housing remains an unrealized ambition. Elsewhere
in Santa Clara County and in San Jose, the expansion of
computer-related businesses has stimulated home development and
prices. At the end of July, existing single-family houses in San
Jose were selling for an average of $400,657, while condominiums
were selling for an average of $228,576, according to the Santa
Clara County Association of Realtors. In 1994, the average
single-family house sold for $238,258; the average condominium
price was $150,575.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, the 104-unit Paseo Villas condominium complex,
currently under construction, is being built by Goldrich &AMP; Kest
Inc. of Los Angeles with the assistance of the Redevelopment
Agency. The agency contributed the land and is a partner in the
venture. Completion is expected next March.
</P>
<P>
   Although the developer has not yet set prices for the units,
comparable condominiums in the area are selling for $250 to $300 a
square foot, ``which is not that high for the area,'' according to
Korabiak. The condos, all two-bedrooms, will range from 1,600 to
1,900 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The 320-unit apartment complex, known as 101 San Fernando, is
being built by Forest City Enterprises Inc. of Cleveland.
Completion is expected in fall 2000. Rents have not been announced,
although city officials say they expect the apartments to rent for
about $1.85 per square foot. The apartments will range from a
421-square-foot studio to a 1,390-square-foot three-bedroom. The
city agency assisted the project by buying the land from the
developer and leasing it back for 55 years, which gave the
developer cash to build the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of people with well-paying jobs looking for
places to live that are closer to where they work,'' said Greg
Anderson, vice president for development at Forest City. ``We are
responding to that with this project.''
</P>
<P>
   The city allowed the developer to build up to 107 units per
acre, making 101 San Fernando the densest housing project ever
built in downtown San Jose, and possibly in the entire city.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are densities that are comparable to those in Berlin and
Vienna,'' said Daniel Solomon, a San Francisco-based architect who
designed the complex. With the high densities, civic leaders can
concentrate housing in certain areas of downtown to create a
natural customer base for neighborhood merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The architect and the city collaborated to produce a design for
the apartment building that would not seem imposing or impersonal,
Solomon said. He provided seven separate entrances to the building,
each with its own small courtyard. In this way, the large building
resembles a row of smaller courtyard apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple entrances of 101 San Fernando also have an urban
design role: the street is enlivened with doorways, rather than
deadened by impenetrable walls.
</P>
<P>
   Housing is the ``final ingredient'' needed to make downtown San
Jose successful, Anderson said. The city has ``done a lot, and the
downtown has hotels and restaurants, it has night life, and the
retail is coming along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
