<SLUG> BC-NJ-BODY-FOUND-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOMEOWNER FINDS BODY IN A BARREL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ When Hamid Tafaghodi and his family moved into
their new $455,000 split-level home, they found a rusted 55-gallon
drum. The drum was later discovered to contain the mummified
remains of a pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Tafaghodi asked the seller of the house to remove the drum from
a crawl space in the rear of house at 67 Forest Drive. The seller,
Ronald Cohen, asked his movers to take the drum, which weighed 345
pounds, to the curb. But the garbage men would not touch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garbage men told the owners: `We can't take it because it
might be toxic or noxious. You are responsible for opening it,'''
said Sgt. Robert Edwards, a detective in the Nassau County homicide
squad. ``If they had just taken it and put it in the truck, that
would be it.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday, Cohen and his real estate agent pried the lid of
the drum open with a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   Inside they found another container with a rusted bottom. Then
they saw a hand and a shoe and decided to call the police.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrived at 1:35 Thursday afternoon and removed the
body from the drum. The body was that of a woman who was nearly
full-term pregnant, and was 4 feet, 9 inches tall and 59 pounds,
the police said. She was wearing a skirt, button-down sweater, high
socks and a shoe with a mid-high heel.
</P>
<P>
   Around the neck was a locket with the words ``Patrice, Love
Uncle Phil.'' On her left hand was a wedding band with the
inscription ``M.H.R. XII-59'' and another ring with a green stone.
An imitation leopard-skin coat and a pocketbook filled mostly with
makeup were also found in the drum.
</P>
<P>
   The container was tightly sealed, largely preventing oxygen from
entering and the body from decomposing. The bulk of the drum was
made up of what police call moisture-absorbing grain, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police brought in dogs and searched the rest of the house
and yard, but found no other bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Though the police estimated that the woman had been dead for
nearly 25 years, they said they had leads. ``It's tough, but we do
have some parameters,'' Edwards said, adding that the barrel was
made in 1963 and originally contained pigments used to tint plastic
and paints, which were no longer made after 1972 or 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate records show that the owners before the Cohens were
Frank and Bernadette Salmaggi, who bought the house from Arthur and
Judith Ebbin. The Ebbins lived there from 1972 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Howard B. Elkins sold the house to the Ebbins. Reached by phone
in Boca Raton, Fla., Elkins said Saturday that he knew nothing
about a drum or a body.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving out in 1972, Elkins said, he and his wife, Ruth,
lived there for at least 15 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We built a room off the kitchen to the back of the house,''
Elkins said. ``A big den with a fireplace. It was built up to the
level of the living room and the kitchen, so there was a crawl
space.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had ever gone into the crawl space, Elkins
replied, ``What for?''
</P>
<P>
   Elkins said he could not recall the name of the contractor who
did the work on the house, but remembered that the job went
smoothly. ``It wasn't bad. It probably only took a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of the gardeners and landscapers, and the contractor
who built the addition, I can't think of anyone else who had access
to the house,'' Elkins continued. ``We did have maids on and off
over the years'' who often had keys to the house, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, who would not give her name, said: ``I just can't
understand how this can be undetected for so long. Wasn't someone
declared missing? Wouldn't it smell?''
</P>
<P>
   As the new owners carried out rusty wire hangers and old carpets
to the street on Saturday, cars and children on bicycles slowed to
a crawl while passing the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
