<HEADLINE>
EDWARD BASSETT, 77, ARCHITECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ind., Hawaii, Wash., Mich.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward Charles Bassett, a widely praised architect whose work
ranged from San Francisco's symphony hall to the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow, died Aug. 28 in a San Francisco hospital. He was 77 and
lived in Mill Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke he had suffered 10 days earlier at his
home, said Craig Hartman, a partner in the San Francisco office of
the architectural firm of Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett, known as Chuck, was the partner in charge of design in
Skidmore's San Francisco office for 21 years until he retired in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Temko, the former architecture critic of The San Francisco
Chronicle, said Saturday that for years Bassett (pronounced
BASS-ett) ``was a leader in the efforts of younger modern
architects to seek alternatives to the arid formulas of the
International Style.''
</P>
<P>
   Temko described him as the best architect working in San
Francisco in his time and ``a very inventive architect wherever he
worked.'' His more far-flung projects included the Australian
Mutual Provident Society complex in Melbourne, Australia, the Royal
Dutch Shell headquarters in The Hague, Netherlands, and the Mauna
Kea Beach Hotel in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   He designed a city hall for Columbus, Ind. In 1989 it was
described in The Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky., as ``a not to
be missed, imposing triangular building with a cantilevered front
lintel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said, ``A number of his buildings incorporate in them
very traditional qualities of architecture, especially in the use
of very traditional materials, but generally reinterpreted in the
modernist idiom.''
</P>
<P>
   Temko had particular praise for Bassett's design work early in
his San Francisco years for the John Hancock Building, now called
the Industrial Indemnity Building, in the city's financial
district. He said the structure ``isn't a glass box, but it's
contextual in the best sense: It respects the whole cityscape.''
</P>
<P>
   The elegant corporate headquarters of Weyerhaeuser Co. near
Tacoma, Wash., Temko called ``another beauty: It's so handsomely
sited the building is like a dam overlooking a lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Bassett was born in Port Huron, Mich., served in the Army in
World War II and was wounded on Okinawa. He received a bachelor's
degree in architecture in 1949 from the University of Michigan and
a master's degree in architecture in 1951 from the Cranbrook
Academy of Art, in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., where he was influenced
by the Finnish-American architect Eliel Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 to 1955 Bassett worked with Saarinen's son, the
architect Eero Saarinen, in Eero's office, also in Bloomfield
Hills, before joining Skidmore in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The honors Bassett received included the Brunner Prize in
Architecture from the National Institute of Arts and Letters, the
Maybeck Award from the California Council of the American Institute
of Architects and numerous other awards for the designs of
individual projects.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Doris West, known as
Dory; four children, Christine Carlisle Bassett, Ann Bassett
Wheelock, Joseph and Peter, all of California, and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett and his wife went to elementary school together. ``I had
never thought about marrying him,'' she recalled after his death.
``But when I heard he was wounded, I just fell apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
