<SLUG> BC-ST.-JOHN'S-DORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 129 YEARS, ST. JOHN'S UNIVERSITY ADDS DORMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (rk) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Jayare Lendor moved into his new dorm room,
other students offered to carry his boxes just to get a look at the
place. His friends became so envious that he tried not to make a
big deal about it.
</P>
<P>
   But living on campus at St. John's University is a big deal.
``The buzz around here is amazing,'' said Lendor, 22, who used to
ride two subway trains and a bus from Washington Heights to get to
class. ``It's like when the Knicks are in the playoffs _ everyone
knows about it.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's 100-acre main campus in Jamaica, Queens, threw open
the doors to three shiny new dormitories early Saturday and ushered
out a 129-year-old tradition of educating only students who
commuted from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The residence halls _ named Millennium, Century and Hillcrest
(after a golf course originally located at the site) _ will house
more than 750 students from 28 states and 16 foreign countries
including Cyprus, Japan and Portugal. They cost a total of $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Donald J. Harrington, the university president, said
the dormitories were the latest stage in St. John's evolution from
a local school to a world-class institution. ``We're very conscious
of the fact this is a historic moment for us,'' he said. ``It's
something that will clearly enhance the educational experience of
our students.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, 1,500 applications come from students outside the
New York metropolitan area _ nearly one-quarter of the university's
total application pool, Harrington said. In the past, those
students had to scout out apartments near campus, even though many
of them did not know the area or have family here.
</P>
<P>
   Marcio Ferreira, 18, said the on-campus housing made it easier
for him to leave his home in Portugal to study at St. John's and
try out for its basketball team. He has moved into a six-person
suite in Century Hall that has four bedrooms, two bathrooms, a
living room and a kitchen. ``I want to stay here all four years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some anxious parents, the security of on-campus housing was
one of the university's main selling points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dorms make it a lot more palatable,'' said Gary Blosser,
who drove with his 18-year-old daughter, Emily, from Columbus,
Ohio, in a van crammed with her belongings. ``I don't have to worry
about her walking through neighborhoods at night.''
</P>
<P>
   The dormitories have enabled the university to increase freshman
enrollment by 300 students, for a total of 2,800 freshman this
year, Harrington said. In addition, 100 more upperclass students
transferred from other schools than did last year.
</P>
<P>
   During the next three years, the university plans to add eight
dormitories to bring a total of 2,800 students on campus. The
buildings are part of a $300 million expansion of the Queens campus
that will also include a new university center, a student dining
hall, a church and several athletic centers.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said the expansion was being financed through a bond
sale and donations from alumni and supporters, but he would not
give specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's main campus, which was originally located in
Brooklyn, moved to the site of the former Hillcrest Golf Course in
1955. Other campuses were established in Staten Island in 1971, and
in Rome, Italy, in 1995. The Queens campus is the only one with
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Several St. John's alumni said the dormitories would anchor a
thriving student life on campus and lamented that the change came
too late for them.
</P>
<P>
   Carol A. Gresser, former president of the New York City school
board, said she missed out on an integral part of the college
experience because she commuted to classes at St. John's in the
late 1950s. She encouraged her four children to go away for
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that even if I cry and hang on your leg and beg
you to stay home, pay no attention and go away to school,'' she
said. ``I thought it was an important experience for them to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of volunteers and university workers came out Saturday to
help new students get settled. The multistory residence halls have
been outfitted with cable and Internet connections in every
bedroom, living area and lounge.
</P>
<P>
   And the rent is cheap, for New York City. For a full academic
year, students pay from $4,800 for a 140-square-foot double room to
$6,200 for a 115-square-foot single room.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone has a key to the new hot spot on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Guy, 19, a junior, said she could not afford to move out of
her parents' home in Bethpage, on Long Island. So for now, she has
to be content with watching other students move into the
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may feel like they're in a real school,'' she said with
envy. ``They don't have to leave to go to work like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   But even those students who do not live on campus can still take
advantage of the budding residential life, university officials
said. Library hours have been extended at night, and social
activities are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Lendor, a senior and a residential adviser in Century Hall, is
already making up for all those hours that he spent on subways and
buses. He has cranked up the air conditioning in his room, hooked
up the stereo, and plugged in two television sets so that students
can watch football games with him on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of an 8-to-4:30 school, now we can actually have
midnight movies,'' he said. ``That's a lot different for students
who used to come to class and leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
