<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-TERRORIST-CLEMENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY URGES PRESIDENT TO WITHDRAW CLEMENCY OFFER FOR TERRORIST
GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton called on President Clinton Saturday to
withdraw his offer to commute the prison sentences of 16 members of
a Puerto Rican terrorist organization linked to 100 bombings in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour of Mrs. Clinton's statement, the White House set
a deadline of 5 p.m. Friday for the prisoners to meet the
president's conditions for their release.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's supporters have voiced concern that the issue
could complicate her prospective run for Senate in New York, as
Republicans have attacked the clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's statement, issued as she spent the weekend at
Camp David with her husband, did not quarrel with Clinton's initial
offer, made on Aug. 11, of a conditional clemency to 16 members of
the Armed Forces of National Liberation, or FALN, the initials for
the Spanish rendering of the name. But she noted that the president
had made the offer on the condition that the prisoners _ none of
whom had been directly related to any crimes that resulted in death
or injury _ renounce violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been three weeks and their silence speaks volumes,'' Mrs.
Clinton said in the statement. ``I believe the offer of clemency
should be withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she had not known in advance about her
husband's clemency offer. An aide said she learned about it while
touring New York for her anticipated run for the U.S. Senate next
year. Her spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said that the first lady told
Clinton Saturday morning that she would issue a statement calling
on the president to act.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said Saturday that attempts to draw a
unified response from the 16 prisoners to the offer of clemency had
been complicated by the fact that they were scattered among 11
federal prisons.
</P>
<P>
   But up through Friday evening, the president's advisers had kept
the offer open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential aides said they did not know of Mrs. Clinton's
intentions to release her statement. Wolfson said that the first
lady first informed her husband of her decision Saturday morning at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 prisoners have arranged a conference call with their
lawyer for this week to discuss their response to Clinton's offer.
Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman, said, ``We have always
believed that renunciation of violence was the critical condition
of this clemency offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the White House sent a letter to the prisoners'
counsel Friday afternoon informing them of the deadline. ``We
informed them that if we did not hear from them in writing by 5
p.m. Friday Sept. 10, that would be considered a rejection of the
president's offer and they would continue to serve their
sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican who is likely to run for
the Senate against Mrs. Clinton, and who has been critical of the
president's action, declined to comment on Mrs. Clinton's statement
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement marked the latest, and clearly the most striking,
attempt by the first lady to distance herself from administration
policy since she first began seriously considering the race. This
had proved to be a particularly complicated issue because some
important supporters of her _ among them Rep. Jose E. Serrano of
the Bronx, Rep. Charles Rangel of Harlem and Dennis Rivera, the
head of 1199, the 150,000-member National Health and Human Service
Employees Union _ had backed Clinton's action.
</P>
<P>
   But there had been a wave of criticism of Clinton, from
Republicans as well as Democrats, notably Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, whose decision not to run for re-election created the
opening that is now the subject of the expected contest between
Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of Republicans have asserted that the president, in
taking a step that was not in keeping with the administration's
generally tougher line toward terrorists, was using his position to
try to help his wife's campaign for the Senate. Hispanic voters
make up a growing and increasingly influential segment of New
York's electorate, and Giuliani, in particular, has gone to great
effort to build support among those voters.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, Clinton's aides have refused to
elaborate on the president's decision-making process, even as it
became known that a number of federal law-enforcement agencies who
reviewed the clemency petition filed by the group unanimously
opposed it. Mrs. Clinton has, until now, through a spokesman said
only that the prisoners should not be released until they renounce
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has gathered increasing force both in New York in
Washington. The New York Police commissioner, Howard Safir, held a
news conference with three retired officers who had been injured by
bombs placed outside Police Headquarters in 1982 to denounce the
president. The FALN had claimed credit for placing those bombs.
Giuliani did not appear with Safir, but made clear he approved of
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   It also has appeared increasingly likely in recent weeks that
the issue could be kept alive through congressional hearings in
Washington, which would, no doubt, be an unwanted distraction for
Mrs. Clinton's campaign. Republicans in Congress have begun to
subpoena White House and Justice Department records on the clemency
process in anticipation of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, in her statement, insisted that the White House
had acted on its own in granting the clemency petition. ``When the
administration first offered these prisoners clemency, I made it
very clear that I had no involvement in, or prior knowledge, of the
decision, as is entirely appropriate,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
