<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CONGRESS05-COX     09-04 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congress faces tough issues in a partisan climate
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The big question facing Congress when it returns
this week is whether it can pass enough legislation to escape a
``do-nothing'' branding.
</P>
<P>
   Deep partisan divisions on Capitol Hill may make that an uphill
battle.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the impeachment trial of President Clinton, the
106th Congress has saved most of its tough work for the final
legislative session of this century, prompting political experts to
wonder whether it's possible to adjourn without upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative agenda is crammed with contentious spending
bills as well as thorny issues such as overhauling the campaign
fund-raising system, gun violence, managed care and funding for
Georgia's coveted F-22 fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   And a budget gridlock is predicted as soon as the president's
signature is dry on his promised veto of the Republican Party's
$792 billion tax cut bill.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to that explosive mix are the ferocious campaigns under
way for control of the House and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the looming distraction of more congressional
investigations into the FBI and Justice Department's handling of
the deadly 1993 siege of the Branch Davidian complex near Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want and need some accomplishments so they can inoculate
themselves against the `do-nothing Congress''' label, said William
F. Connelly, a professor of politics at Washington &AMP; Lee
University.
</P>
<P>
   But passing legislation could be more difficult than usual,
Connelly said, because ``both parties are looking for ways to score
points and play politics instead of forming policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood's fight
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Congress will address are the bill introduced
by Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.) to dramatically change the way
managed care is administered across the country. It would give
patients the right to sue their health plan insurers, choose their
doctors and appeal health plan decisions to an external appeals
board.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is strongly opposed by groups such as the American
Association of Health Plans and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce _ not
to mention the elders of Norwood's own party.
</P>
<P>
   But such opposition has served only to energize Norwood, who
crossed the aisle to work with Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.) to piece
together the latest incarnation of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind getting beat,'' Norwood said. ``I'm a big boy. If
you get beat, you get beat. But I do believe in a fair fight, and
so far it hasn't been a fair fight, and it won't be until there is
a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Georgia Republican Rep. Bob Barr will play a pivotal role
in the fall legislative season. Barr, a member of the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, has taken the lead in
demanding more information about why the FBI took six years to
acknowledge using incendiary tear gas canisters in the Branch
Davidian siege. In particular, Barr wants to know more about the
role played by the Army's secretive Delta Force.
</P>
<P>
   And as a member of a special panel of House and Senate members,
Barr will help shape the juvenile violence bill aimed at responding
to a spate of recent shootings in schools in Georgia, California
and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than regulating guns, Barr said final juvenile violence
legislation should bring the Ten Commandments to school classrooms
and ``require federal prosecutors to start prosecuting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that the bill that emerges will focus on the real
problems and real solutions, not cosmetic approaches such as gun
control,'' said Barr, a board member of the National Rifle
Association. ``But I know there will be a lot of pressure from the
gun control advocates to do otherwise and a lot of pressure by some
Republicans to just sort of roll over and avoid the issue and give
in partway.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the dollars go
</P>
<P>
   Locally, few issues rival the importance of the spending battle
set to unfold as soon as Congress returns Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is funding for the F-22 Raptor. Before recess, the
House eliminated $1.8 billion in planned funding for the first six
of the F-22 fighters, saying the plane was too costly and the money
was needed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That created quite a stir among Georgia's congressional
delegation because Lockheed Martin builds the aircraft at its
Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved funding for the F-22 fighters in its version
of the $264.7 billion defense bill this summer. The final outcome
now rests in the hands of a special committee of House and Senate
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Ted Stevens (R-Alaska), chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, has made it clear he will not take the
spending bill to the Senate floor without funding set aside for the
F-22 fighter.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to sell the project, Lockheed Martin has hired
former Republican Sen. Mack Mattingly of Georgia to lobby on its
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 is not the only target of budget cutters.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $40 million in public housing funds slated for Georgia
are in jeopardy. The cuts are part of a Republican proposed trim of
$1.6 billion from the Housing and Urban Development budget. The
proposal, which cleared the House Appropriations Committee this
summer, will be voted on by the full House when Congress resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be devastating,'' said Hattie Dorsey, president of
the Atlanta Neighborhood Development Partnership, a nonprofit group
that builds affordable housing. The cuts, which amount to $9.4
million for Atlanta alone, would dramatically impact the affordable
housing and public housing supply, she said. ``You wonder where the
heart and soul of some of these people are.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) said he intends to fight the HUD cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed cuts are irresponsible and mean-spirited,'' he
said. ``We are trying to balance the budget on the backs of the
people who can least afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
