<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GINGRICH-DIVORCE05-CO     09-04 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-DIVORCE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingriches likely to settle out of court
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lawyers who thrive on domestic cases that make
headlines say there's little chance Newt and Marianne Gingrich will
put their marriage on trial, no matter how bitter their pending
divorce might appear.
</P>
<P>
   The thing to remember, they say, is that in the high-stakes game
of divorce among the rich and powerful, politicians often have the
most to lose.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a week, a Cobb County judge is scheduled
to preside over the first public clash of the couple's attorneys in
a pre-trial hearing over assets. The Gingriches plan to be present.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint courtroom appearance is likely to be a rare event.
This split will probably follow the pattern of most other celebrity
divorces.
</P>
<P>
   Each will threaten and bluff until the other side is ready to
strike a deal. Scandal-hungry Americans will serve as useful
go-betweens, until the judge agrees to seal the settlement and the
public is told to go away. Divorce settlements among average people
are rarely decided by judges or juries, and the trend is even
stronger among people with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart, powerful people want to control their own destiny. They
don't want someone else telling them how they're going to live the
rest of their lives,'' said Sanford Ain, a Washington attorney who
counts dozens of congressmen and senators among his past and
present clientele.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side is expected to roll over easily. Marianne
Gingrich has hired attorney John Mayoue, who also represents
Evander Holyfield's wife in her ongoing divorce case. Newt
Gingrich, once the national leader of the GOP, has hired Thomas
Browning, a Democrat and former law partner of Gov. Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingriches' divorce trial has been tentatively scheduled to
begin around October.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers watching the proceedings from afar say there are two
closely linked reasons to bet on an out-of-court settlement: money
and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's been out of office eight months, Gingrich remains
a $50,000-a-pop speechmaker and a cash magnet in the pass-the-plate
world of Washington fund-raising. Since leaving office in January,
he's raised at least $1.3 million for his new political action
committee.
</P>
<P>
   But a bitter divorce could raise all sorts of personal and
financial details that might have an impact on his future career as
a speechmaker or on any return to politics.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the best example of the damage a divorce can do to a
politician dates back to 1977, when U.S. Sen. Herman Talmadge filed
for the divorce that ruined his political life. During the
proceedings, tales of kickbacks, hidden cash and campaign
contributions converted to private use resulted in a formal
denunciation by his Senate colleagues. Talmadge was voted out of
office in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   So far as the public is concerned, Newt Gingrich's closets are
free of any such clutter. But Mayoue, Marianne Gingrich's attorney,
has said he intends to fully investigate Newt Gingrich's personal
and political business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Gingrich can't afford to tarnish her estranged
husband's image too much _ at least, not without risking her
potential share of his future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the threat of a trial can be a valuable bargaining
chip when it comes to getting the best settlement possible, said
Ain.
</P>
<P>
   The chip is even more valuable in Georgia, which is the only
state where juries can decide alimony payments and how to split a
couple's assets, said Atlanta divorce attorney Shiel Edlin. In
fact, Georgia and Texas are the only two states in the union that
use juries at all in divorce cases. The rest rely on judges.
</P>
<P>
   A divorce by jury in Georgia requires a request from only one of
the parties. Marianne Gingrich made that request in her August
answer to her husband's July 29 divorce petition.
</P>
<P>
   While Ain says judges are fairly predictable in their divorce
rulings, it's a well-known adage among lawyers that juries, on the
other hand, are unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Gingrich's years-long relationship with a
33-year-old congressional aide named Callista Bisek. Proof of an
extramarital affair ``could affect a jury more than a judge,'' said
Atlanta attorney Joe McGee, former president of the Georgia chapter
of the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Pros and cons
</P>
<P>
   Besides keeping dirt out of a public courtroom, settlement
offers a distinct advantage to couples in search of discretion. The
agreements can be sealed or even kept out of the public record
entirely. Once a case goes to trial, however, it's very hard to get
the record sealed, McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   Judges are particularly willing to seal the record when a
divorce includes vast amounts of money or a large alimony payment.
</P>
<P>
   McGee helped represent PC modem entrepreneur Dennis Hayes during
his noteworthy 1988 divorce. Hayes, whose Norcross-based
microcomputer products company was once valued at $500 million,
chose to settle the divorce with a confidential agreement that was
billed as the largest in Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   Like Newt Gingrich, Hayes was accused of having an affair and
the woman in question was forced to give a videotaped deposition.
Callista Bisek's is scheduled for late September.
</P>
<P>
   But even cases destined for settlement often provide an intimate
and sometimes embarrassing look at a couple's life together, as
each attempts to influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich has claimed in divorce pleadings that his wife
``abandoned'' him in 1987. The Gingriches signed a separation
agreement at the time that divided up bank accounts, furniture and
automobiles and gave Marianne Gingrich $12,000 in alimony over six
months, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster his claim that Marianne Gingrich left him first, Newt
Gingrich has filed a letter he attached to the signed settlement
agreement 12 years ago that expressed sorrow over her abandonment.
He addressed it to ``Marianski,'' and signed it ``Merry Christmas,
Newtie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you more than I hate this,'' the letter began,
referring to the notarized agreement, which was not filed in court
at the time. ``... I hope this allows you to relax, heal up, and
truly decide what you want to do with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you decide you want to start a new relationship with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations were in response to charges by Marianne Gingrich
that her husband attempted to hide assets before filing papers to
end their 18-year marriage. Newt Gingrich denies the assets charge.
Divorce lawyers in the know say Newt Gingrich's response is unusual
because it is not required by law. For some, it's an obvious
attempt to play to the media, which is routine in high-profile
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case becomes one of sound bites for the press, rather than
what's likely to influence the judge by the end of the day,'' said
Ain, the Washington-based divorce attorney. ``What they are doing
is trying to influence the public in order to put pressure on the
other side to gain a more favorable settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it works even better than expected. Consider the early
1990s divorce of drug store magnate Herbert Haft, which made the
front page of The Washington Post for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Public interest in one of the pretrial hearings was so intense,
Maryland court officials had to set up a lottery and ticketing
system to dole out the courtroom's limited seats, said Ain, who
represented Haft.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge handed down photocopies of the judge's detailed
ruling on the motion, lawyers in the case couldn't help but notice
that it contained minor facts that had never been introduced at
trial. That judge had apparently been reading the newspapers, just
like everyone else in town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
