<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE_ JERUSALEM _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
sign an agreement in Egypt at 6 p.m. EST that puts the Wye peace
agreement back on track. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) 30. ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-AMD-$ADV05 _ DRESDEN, Germany _ Months of controversy
and millions of dollars later, California-based Advanced Micro
Devices _ whose biggest chip plant is in Austin, Texas _ is about
ready to open another major plant here. The problem is that the new
plant will siphon hundreds of job from the Austin plant. But did it
have to happen in the first place? Is this some harbinger of the
global battle for computer manufacturing dollars, or just bad
judgement on the part of one company? MOVED TUESDAY. (Roughton, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV05 _ LA REALIDAD, Mexico _ Armed with
machetes, the men swarmed the truck ferrying Mexican doctor Lydia
Rangel and two Spaniards out of the Lacandon jungle. ``Tie them
up!'' some of the vigilantes shouted, accusing the three of being
``outside agitators'' and leaders of Mexico's Zapatista rebels.
Bruised and terrified, the three were finally let go. The chilling
incident near this remote rebel stronghold has fueled fear that
anti-Zapatista vigilantes loyal to Mexico's ruling party are on the
rise in spite of a truce. In addition, Rangel, a volunteer doctor,
said Mexican soldiers just 100 meters from where she was attacked
did nothing to help her and the two Spaniards. One soldier, she
said, appeared to have even participated in the mob - an explosive
allegation since the Army is supposed to maintain a truce with
rebels and keep peace in this volatile region. (Ferris, Cox News
Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STATE-$ADV05 _ SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ The question
dominates every political conversation here, peppering the talk of
old men sitting on shady street corners, filling the radio
airwaves, cropping up in news articles on everything from politics
to business and culture. Mainland Americans call it the
``statehood'' issue because they think it's a simple question of
whether Puerto Rico should become the 51st state. For Puerto
Ricans, boiling things down to a simple up or down vote on
statehood doesn't do justice to the complex mix of history,
culture, principles and emotions that most of this vibrant island's
residents bring to the discussion of what they call ``status.''
(Williams, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
