<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YAC-AMERICAS-CUP-575&AMP;     09-04 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-AMERICAS-CUP-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRECY MOUNTING AS AMERICA'S CUP DRAWS NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAITLIN KELLY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months ago, before it moved to New Zealand for the
challengers trials, America One, one of five U.S. entries in the
America's Cup, had an increasingly common problem. It needed to
find a secure spot, away from the prying eyes of competitors, where
its two training boats could be tested.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, America One chose as its U.S. testing ground one of
the least glamorous sites imaginable: a berth at a commercial
shipyard at the end of the road on Terminal Island, the port of Los
Angeles. The site was ideal because the two boats could be quickly
towed into open waters to practice and because local wind
conditions are similar to those in the Hauraki Gulf, the racecourse
site off Auckland, New Zealand, where the America's Cup will be
contested.
</P>
<P>
   But tight security was also paramount. Their site was situated
in a desolate area next to a federal prison, and it was protected
by chain-link fence that was covered with plastic until the boats
were hauled out of the water for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where these million-dollar boats of the America's Cup
series are housed, protecting their unusual design features _ the
culmination of years of testing and refinement _ remains a matter
of serious concern. The New Zealand Herald recently reported that
the America True skipper Dawn Riley was enraged after a local
sports television crew broke into the syndicate's Auckland base and
climbed over its boat.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike America One, which has three boats, America True is a
one-boat campaign, making knowledge of the only craft especially
valuable to potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newspaper's report, three members of the
television crew got into the base with a small boat around 10 p.m.,
climbed onto the keel bulb of their boat and started filming.
``We're worried that this could become the cool thing to do,''
Riley told a Herald reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Breaches like this were not likely at America One's Los Angeles
site. In keeping with America's Cup challenger tradition, the keel
of 49, the team's training boat, was always sheathed from view by
an opaque nylon skirt in and out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Every low-flying plane that approached America One's compound
was photographed and its features were noted.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Billingham, the project manager for America One, who also
worked with Bill Koch on his $100 million A3 campaign in the last
America's Cup, said recently that security concerns were no joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to spend hundreds of thousands of dollars on spying,''
usually from helicopters, he said. ``We'd pass the Italians doing
the same thing and we'd wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Of America One's $32 million budget, $7 million alone represents
the cost of design, an investment Billingham and the skipper Paul
Cayard, not to mention their sponsors, are eager to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Races for the Louis Vuitton Cup, awarded to the winner of the
challengers series, begin in Auckland on Oct. 18. Even until the
last moment boats can be modified based on what a spy discovers in
a competitor's design, Billingham said.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the start date, the more likely this would mean
altering the shape of the keel bulb or the winglets, thin flat
protrusions on either side of the bulb. (Keeping the keel bulb
concealed is therefore an article of faith for most teams.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much information out there now that there are
fewer things to copy, which makes the paranoia and secrecy even
more intense,'' Billingham said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   America One's two training boats are now on their way to
Auckland, stripped of rigging and masts, electronics and deck
hardware. They sit in cradles atop a container ship, the cradles
welded to the ship's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lost 49, we couldn't compete,'' Billingham said.
</P>
<P>
   The entry's newest yacht, 61, which is still under construction
in Long Beach, Calif., her final tweaking and modifications based
on a month of complex data from 49's daily testing, is scheduled to
arrive in New Zealand in November.
</P>
<P>
   While the shore team now starts to arrive in Auckland, its work
being conducted under the aegis of the St. Francis Yacht Club in
San Francisco, Cayard is continuing his own quest: trying to find
an elusive final $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still working on that,'' he said somewhat wearily. He
did manage to drum up $1 million last month _ $250,000 from one
sponsor, another $500,000 from private investors, and the rest as
time, labor and other nonmonetary contributions from Ford, which is
a major sponsor of the program.
</P>
<P>
   What does he need another $6 million for? ``Everything,'' he
said. ``We have to feed and insure and house the crew and the
team,'' some 70 staff members in all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the last one to head down there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
