<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-1     09-04 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HARLEM RALLY, OFFICERS OUTNUMBER PARTICIPANTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (UPDATES throughout with details, Muhammad's speech)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were more police officers than participants as
the second Million Youth March got under way in Harlem around noon
Saturday, after a bitter court fight in which the organizers of the
event won a city permit over Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's vehement
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Many who attended the rally were disappointed by the yawning
expanse of pavement in front of the stage at 118th Street and
Malcolm X Boulevard, and blamed the low turnout on politicians who
condemned the march and media coverage that, they said, scared
people away.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:30 p.m., when a woman kicked off the program with chants
of ``black power,'' and a prayer, there were about 400 people
milling about _ far fewer than the estimated 6,000 who attended
last year's event, which ended in a violent clash with the police.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd barely filled half a block, never mind the six closed
off under the permit. By 2:45 p.m., when Khallid Abdul Muhammad,
the march leader, began his 70-minute speech, the crowd had grown
to more than 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to tell the white man we are too black and too
strong,'' Muhammad told the crowd. Speaking of black politicians
who had condemned his rally, he added: ``We're going to show them
what politics is all about. We're going to use politics as a war
mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad urged black men and women to increase their
self-respect and to love one another, rather than form gangs and
battle over turf. He said ``crackers'' had taken over Harlem,
replacing storefronts with malls, and he led the crowd in chants of
``Teach the youth the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop me from calling the white man a devil,'' he
said. ``That's my religion. There is no devil under the ground,
black man. There is no devil under the ground, there is no hell
under the ground. Heaven and hell are states of mind, states of
being. Your heaven and hell is right here, black man and woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, another speaker, Shaunette Daniels, called for black
militias to protect themselves from the New York Police Department,
saying, ``We must make sure there are no unarmed black men on these
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman said about 1,400 officers, most in uniforms,
were deployed in the area, but only some 300 were visible in
clusters in the rally area, along Malcolm X Boulevard between 118th
and 124th Streets, making it seem like a lighter, and friendlier,
police presence than last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rest were stationed nearby _ including handfuls on top of
buildings _ with a phalanx of mounted units and other special
forces at the ready along the northern edge of Central Park at
110th Street.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 p.m., when the rally permit expired, rap music blared from
the stage and the crowd began to disperse peacefully, with no sign
of the problems that marred the end of last year's event.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before the rally, Muhammad shrugged off the
sparse attendance, saying, ``Our people don't come until the main
speaker. That's the tradition in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, as he shopped at Century 21 clothing store to
celebrate no-tax week, Giuliani was smug. ``I think we have more
people here,'' he said to about two dozen reporters gathered for a
noon question-and-answer session. Earlier, after throwing out the
ceremonial first pitch at the Latin American Little League World
Series in Brooklyn, the mayor indirectly criticized what he has
referred to as a ``hate march.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you want to be doing with children,'' he said.
``You want them to be playing baseball, basketball, you want them
to be reading, you want them to be considering other pursuits, work
in the library, just having fun and learning teamwork rather than
talking about hating other people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, there were precious few children, to whom the
event was supposed to be directed. Instead, there were adults
waving the green, black and red flag of African nationalism and
shooting videotape and photographs of, among other things, the
scores of newspaper and television reporters and photographers on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   A cadre of Black Muslims in matching gray suits and burgundy
ties stood to one side. A group of young men dressed head to toe in
the red regalia of the Bloods street gang hovered a block away,
making machine-gun sounds with their mouths to punctuate the
incendiary remarks broadcast over loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to get a positive message and not worry about the
negativity from the media and the black politicians,'' said Cecil
Payne, 34, who brought his two sons to the march from Hackensack,
N.J. ``I came out here to see what Khallid Muhammad is all about.
I'm not a black Muslim, but I came out because he is the only one
to speak out against injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   Curbside chatter, at some points, reflected the hate-filled
language of Muhammad ``Jews make all the decisions in this
country,'' said one man roaming the area with a megaphone. ``It's
about time for them to be overthrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people said they thought the march was about reparations
_ reimbursing black people for decades of discrimination. Some saw
Muhammad as a role model. ``He's a strong black man who speaks the
truth,'' said a woman who gave her name only as Sarah. ``We need
more black men like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Janita Fitzgerald, 18, a college student, said she thinks
Muhammad can help get teen-agers off the streets. ``It takes a
whole village to raise a child, that's what he's saying,'' she
said. ``Everybody's everybody's parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that they support Muhammad's program of
self-reliance for African-Americans, but worry that his message has
been distorted, in part by the news media, and in part by his own
insistence on using epithets for whites in general and Jews in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``His message is good; it's just that I don't like the way he
gives it,'' said Omotayo Riley, 18, of Jamaica, Queens, part of a
five-man rhythm and blues group, Impact, which was scheduled to
perform later in the rally.
</P>
<P>
   James Udofia, 17, another member of Impact, said, ``Sometimes
you have to be aggressive in the way you speak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's aggressive,'' countered Riley, ``and then there's
threatening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Johnson, a music producer from Teaneck, N.J., said blacks
need ``a rabble-rouser'' like Muhammad. ``We really need somebody
to let them know, hey, we're not content yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the crowd said they came not so much to support Muhammad
but to exercise their rights to free assembly, which were upheld by
two courts last week after the city denied the organizers a permit.
</P>
<P>
   One woman said she had decided not to attend because of the
problems after last year's march, in which 16 police officers and
14 participants were injured, but changed her mind after she heard
the Jewish Defense League asking people to stay away. ``Who are
they to tell us what to do?'' asked the woman, who identified
herself only as Linda.
</P>
<P>
   Others wore buttons reading, ``To Hell with Adolf Giuliani,''
and said they were marching to show opposition to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Malik Shabazz, an attorney for the Million Youth March, held a
picture of Muhammad aloft on the stage and announced, ``White
America, you have created Khallid Muhammad, and now the chickens
have come home to roost.'' Then, he turned to the crowd and asked,
``How to you find Giuliani on the charge of police brutality?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty,'' came the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you find Giuliani on the charge of the murder of
Diallo? How do you find Giuliani on the charge of the sodomy of
Abner Louima?'' Shabazz continued, prompting echoes of ``guilty,
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the perimeter of the rally, people in the neighborhood
were less than lukewarm to the event, although they said they
appreciated that the subways were open, unlike last year, and there
seemed to be more freedom to move about the streets than last year.
At the Salvation and Deliverance Church on 116th Street, about 100
people gathered for a special prayer service, holding hands in
small circles as they chanted, sang and hopped from one foot to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a cause we believe in; we're not advocates of
hatred,'' said Jonathan Graham, 45, a guest minister at the church.
``Jesus is about love. That's what we believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, though, could not stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, just to see the spectacle,'' Ned Burrell said when
asked why he had attended the rally. ``Just the same way I would
come out to watch Hitler or David Duke. It's kind of like watching
a car wreck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
