<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAMP-2TAK     09-04 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAMP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SAY STRONG START IS A MUST
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., also includes reports on Islanders, Devils) 
(rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, the Rangers' latest grand experiment will
begin in Burlington, Vt. And during their weeklong training camp,
coach John Muckler hopes to etch a rough sketch of the team, which
was profoundly altered by Neil Smith, the team's president and
general manager, during a busy and expensive off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine a more productive off-season in Rangers
history,'' Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden,
said last week, as the team formally introduced its new faces at a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The question facing Muckler is how long it will take for all the
players in camp to mold into a cohesive unit. Smith and Muckler are
hoping to have the answer by Oct. 1, when the Rangers open the
regular season in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, even though they were quite familiar with one
another coming in, the Rangers were terrible from the start,
opening the season 0-4-1. They finished 33-38-11. This season, the
Rangers will be much less familiar with each other on opening day.
And like last season, they will not be able to afford a wretched
opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try to have a better start,'' Muckler said.
``That's one of the reasons I want to get to a team concept as soon
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler intends to divide the team into two groups, A and B
squads, after three days of scrimmaging in Burlington, with the A
group consisting of players expected to make team.
</P>
<P>
   The team's core will be familiar. Brian Leetch will be back as
the captain for the third season. Mike Richter will again be in
goal. Adam Graves will return to man a forward line. But there will
be an infusion of new faces, too. Old new faces, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Theo Fleury, the prize addition who played most of his career in
Calgary, is 31. Valery Kamensky, from Colorado, is 33. Tim Taylor,
from Boston, is 30. On defense, Sylvain Lefebvre (Colorado) is 31
and Stephane Quintal (Montreal) is 30. Backup goaltender Kirk
McLean, a free agent from Florida, is 33. And the Rangers were
already aging to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they are hoping that newcomers like 18-year-olds Pavel
Brendl and Jamie Lundmark and 22-year-old Jan Hlavac, along with
19-year-old Manny Malhotra, who is entering his second season, can
contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to see is a good mixture of veterans and younger
people,'' Muckler said. ``And I'd like to see the younger people
pushing the veterans. Because what's going to happen is the
veterans are going to start pushing back.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, young players have not been given many
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the patience is still there for the young players
to be on the team,'' Smith said. ``I think where the patience is
gone is that we missed the playoffs two years in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a mood of guarded optimism among the team's
executive leadership, stemming from all the moves Smith has made.
Checketts proudly noted that there was a 97 percent renewal on
season tickets. And nearly all those ticket holders were
disgruntled by the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't the last game; it was probably the last 10
games,'' Checketts said. ``I knew the patience had run out. If we
had made the playoffs the last year or two, maybe we would not have
felt the same urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rangers went out and re-signed Leetch to a
four-year, $35 million contract. That led to the avalanche of
signings, opening the way, Checketts said, for free agents Fleury
(four years, $28 million), Kamensky (five years, $21 million),
Quintal (five years, $14 million), Lefebvre (five years, $12.5
million), Taylor (four years, $5.8 million plus incentives) and
McLean (two years, $1.7 million plus incentives).
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said he thought the Rangers would be a stronger
forechecking team, that they would be faster overall and improved
on both offense and defense. ``It's not going to be as easy as it
looks on paper, however,'' Muckler said. ``A lot of things need to
be developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are still searching for someone to emerge as the
second-line center behind Petr Nedved. Muckler also pointed out
areas such as mobility to move the puck and team toughness that his
team needs to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll be a feisty team, a gritty team,'' Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
   ISLANDERS
</P>
<P>
   An Uncertain Roster
</P>
<P>
   As the Islanders' training camp opens in Lake Placid, N.Y.,
there's only one thing more uncertain than who will own the team in
two weeks: who will be on the team in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen new players and a new coach were on the
Islanders' roster when the team took the ice at Olympic Center for
the season's first practice Saturday. Still, the new season is very
likely to bring more of the same results.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the fire sale that gutted the Islanders of the few
legitimate stars they had, the young and inexperienced team will
almost certainly struggle to win 20 games under Butch Goring this
season. With a payroll of only $18 million come expectations that
are equally low.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Jonsson, Mariusz Czerkawski, Mark Lawrence and Oli Jokinen
are among the few proven commodities the Islanders have. Most of
the other players listed on the preseason roster represent a mix of
first-round draft picks, veteran journeymen and minor leaguers
hoping to catch a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camp is going to be really open,'' said Mike Milbury, the
Islanders' general manager. ``For a lot of the players, it's an
opportunity to get a toehold in the National Hockey League. We are
very young, and if nothing else, we have that going for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbury must rely on his team's youthful exuberance and hope
that it will be worth something, even if it probably won't help his
team make the playoffs. One of the few bright spots at camp will be
the four 1999 first-round draft picks _ Tim Connolly, Taylor Pyatt,
Branislav Mezei, and Kristain Kudroc _ all of whom have an outside
chance at making the team.
</P>
<P>
   But the first order of business won't be anywhere near the ice.
With the players arriving for photos and physicals Saturday, there
will be one notable absence: center Mats Lindgren, who is expected
to skate on either the first or second line, is still not signed.
The 24-year-old Swede is seeking $1 million a season. Milbury said
he has offered Lindgren a 20 percent raise over the $650,000 he
made last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most deserve a pay cut at this point,'' Milbury said
last week. ``We think a 20 percent raise is more than fair.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TARIK EL-BASHIR
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
