<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- GRAVE-ARTWORK-THIEF-1, 9-4
-- Anthony Casamassima, 40, a career grave robber whose testimony
helped convict a leading authority on Tiffany stained glass on
charges of dealing in stolen mausoleum art, with the bonsai-studded
cemetery tableau he created in his Queens backyard. Casamassima,
who is awaiting sentencing on a variety of charges, including
stealing the window and trafficking in stolen property, sees
himself as a rescuer, stealing Tiffany windows and other treasures,
he says, to ``liberate'' them from vandalism and neglect. (Jeffery
A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK - Sept. 4, 1999 -- TEN-ARATON-COLUMN, 9-4 --
Richard and Oracene, the parents of Serena and Venus Williams, at
the United States open on Friday. Two years ago, more than a few
tennis people were willing to wonder if Richard Williams' girls,
schooled away from the junior tennis grind, faced the possibility
of being colossal flops. Now, every day at the Open is Williams
Family Day. The sisters are energetic, engaging, edgy. They appear
to have it all, except Grand Slam victories, and those are
obviously coming. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LAGUNA WOODS, Calif. -- Sept. 4, 1999 --
FALWELL-GAYS-MEETING, 9-4 -- The Rev. Mel White, right, an
outspoken supporter of gay rights, plans to meet with the Rev.
Jerry Falwell, an outspoken critic of homosexual activity, in
Lynchburg, Va., next month. White is with his partner, Gary Nixon.
White plans take 200 people to Lynchburg to meet with Falwell, and
the 200 people he has invited, for the talks. Such an encounter
will certainly be unusual, perhaps even a first in the long,
contentious debate over gay rights. ``I believe we're going,'' says
White, ``and we're going in love and peace.'' (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SEATTLE -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- KING-COUNTY-DEBATE, 9-4 --
King County Council member Larry Gossett wants the likeness of Dr.
Martin L. King Jr. on the logos of King County, Wash. The county,
originally named for a forgettable Vice President, William King,
was renamed for Dr. King in 1986. The proposal by Gossett to change
the county's logo to include a likeness of King, the civil rights
leader who was slain in 1968, has revived a debate over an unusual
action taken by the County Council 13 years ago, when it officially
voted to change the county's namesake, but not its name. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) VAIL, Colo. -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- VAIL-HOUSING-DISPUTE, 9-4
-- Vail mayor Rob Ford, has been strongly criticized for planning
lower-cost housing in the upscale resort town. The plan is part of
an effort to revitalize the ski resort. Objections over plans to
build affordable housing for people who work in local hotels, shops
and restaurants grew so heated this summer that Ford quit, two
years before his term expires. ``At some of the meetings we had,
things got so bad that I was uncomfortable without an undercover
police officer there to protect me,'' says Ford. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-2, 9-4
-- A crowd barely filling half a block at the second Million Youth
March in Harlem on Saturday. After a bitter court fight in which
the organizers of the event won a city permit over Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's vehement objections, many who attended the rally were
disappointed by the yawning expanse of pavement in front of the
stage at 118th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard, and blamed the low
turnout on politicians who condemned the march and media coverage
that, they said, scared people away. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-1, 9-4
-- Khallid Abdul Muhammad, the primary organizer of the second
Million Youth March, surrounded by bodyguards, in Harlem on
Saturday. Muhammad said he was confident more people would show up
before his speech later in the day. ``What do you mean?'' Muhammad
said when asked about the sparse attendance. ``Our people don't
come until the main speaker. That's the tradition in the black
community.'' Still, for the most part, there were more police
officers than participants and there were precious few children, to
whom the event was supposed to be directed. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- KOOP-ETHICS-FLAP, 9-4 --
Dr. C. Everett Koop, who became one of America's most authoritative
and recognizable public figures on the subject of health during the
eight years he held the post of U.S. surgeon general, preparing to
testify before Senate task force on tobacco legislation in 1998.
More than a decade after leaving office, Koop, now 82, faces
criticism from medical ethicists and consumer advocates. Among the
complaints are that his hugely popular health information Web site,
DrKoop.com, blurs the line between objective information and
promotional content, and that his ties to business have not been
properly disclosed. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MOSCOW -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- RUSSIA-TV-POLITICS, 9-4 --
Yevgeny Kiselyov, a television journalist in the anti-Yeltsin camp,
is facing a media battle with much more at stake than higher
ratings. Kiselyov, a journalist with a studied, ponderous style, is
host of ``Itogi,'' or ``News,'' a long-running weekly program
broadcast by NTV. NTV, an independent channel, is controlled by the
media magnate Vladimir Gusinsky, who in recent months has openly
broken ranks with President Boris Yeltsin's dwindling team and ORT,
Russia's largest TV channel. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Sept. 4, 1999 -- ELDERLY-DEPRESSION, 9-4 -- Dr.
Eran Metzger, a geriatric psychiatrist, with an 81-year-old patient
at the Hebrew Rehabilitation Center for Aged near Boston. ``We're
not trying to make everyone conform to our stereotypes of aging,''
says Dr. Metzger. Some experts on aging worry that modern medicine
may end up trivializing the despair that the elderly feel as they
confront the dwindling of their days by trying to medicate away the
sadness that comes with losses. (Michele McDonald/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
