<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS &LR;      09-04 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SAYS DAGESTAN IS WON, BUT BOMBS RAIN ON REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ For the past week the Kremlin has been declaring
victory over a determined group of Islamic rebels in Dagestan, a
predominantly Muslim province in Russia's volatile Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   But the bombs kept falling Saturday, with Russian jets striking
the village of Chabanmakhi, a separatist stronghold. Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin vowed to stop rebels who ``are trying to break up
that which cannot be broken, our common future and history.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombs fell a day after Russia's military pledged to complete
the Dagestani campaign _ and several days after Moscow said that
federal forces already had captured Chabanmakhi.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has rushed to declare victory before. On Aug. 9, he
predicted the battle would be won in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any claims of victory in Dagestan by the Russian authorities
should be treated with skepticism,'' said Alexander Iskandaryan, a
Moscow-based analyst of the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict began Aug. 7 when Islamic rebels poured into
Dagestan from neighboring Chechnya. Led by Shamil Basayev, a field
commander who helped drive Russian forces out of Chechnya three
years earlier, the rebels occupied several villages in Dagestan's
southwestern Botlikh district. Basayev sought to oust the Russians
and set up an independent Islamic state. Moscow responded with two
weeks of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite holding their ground, Basayev's troops unexpectedly
began retreating Aug. 23, a move analysts say is typical of his
combat strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Defense analyst Pavel Felgenhauer, writing in the
English-language daily The Moscow Times, said Basayev's plan is to
``infiltrate here and there, provoking the Russian military to
`liberate' region after region with bombs and artillery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Dagestanis do not want Chechen warlords to take over
their country and are backing federal troops. But as more towns are
liberated their attitude may begin to change,'' Felgenhauer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Iskandaryan agreed, saying: ``You can't fight extremism by
bombing innocent villagers.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, after declaring victory over Basayev, Russian
forces began bombing Chabanmakhi and Karamakhi, in southeastern
Dagestan's Buinaksk district, where religious leaders had declared
``independence'' and imposed a strict form of Islamic law. Those
caught using tobacco, drinking alcohol, or listening to music faced
public beatings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Basayev surfaced in Chechnya last week, where he
declared a ``holy war'' against Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   During Moscow's war with Chechnya in 1994-96, the Kremlin
repeatedly said victory was just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, for example, President Boris N. Yeltsin said
in a radio address that Russian troops had driven rebels forces out
of Grozny, Chechnya's capital. The only military activity, he
assured listeners, was that of Russian soliders laboring to rebuild
the city.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, a military commander in Grozny told reporters that
he had to crank up the volume on his radio just so he could hear
Yeltsin's speech over the deafening gunfire outside his window.
</P>
<P>
   After bombing Chechnya for 20 months and killing tens of
thousands of civilians, Russia was forced in late 1996 into a
humiliating withdrawal, losing control of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another problem flared for Moscow in the Caucasus
region Saturday when a gunfight broke out in the republic of
Karachayevo-Cherkessia, injuring six people.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, the Cherkess, an ethnic minority in the republic,
have been protesting the results of a presidential election won by
a candidate supported by the rival Karchayev ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   The Cherkess have threatened to split from the republic if the
results are not nullified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANKING-BOS &LR;      09-04 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW'S SPIN ON BANK SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Iron Curtain, the Berlin War, McCarthyism _ and
Monica Lewinsky. These are the images being evoked in Russia, in
response to a Kremlin money laundering scandal that is making
headlines all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations that Russian mob bosses, with Kremlin complicity,
may have laundered as much as $15 billion in pilfered public and
corporate funds, through the Bank of New York, have touched a nerve
here. The matter has insulted this vast country's battered pride _
and has provoked responses of fear, anger and denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so long ago, the phrase `Soviet threat' was born in the
American political lexicon,'' a front-page story read in Thursday's
Kommersant, a popular newspaper among the country's business elite.
``But political fashions change, and today, `Soviet threat' has
been replaced by `Russian mafia.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The paper went on to say that Americans were equating all
Russian business with organized crime, and that US banks may stop
dealing with Russians ``simply because they are Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cold War photograph of Senator Joseph McCarthy, testifying
before Congress in the 1950s during the Red Scare, accompanied the
story, which also reported that the Bank of New York money
laundering case, then being investigated by US and British
law-enforcement bodies, is fabricated. And they vowed to its
readers to unmask those behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the newspaper Izvestia ran a banner headline
reading ``The Iron Curtain,'' over a photograph of the Berlin Wall,
with a menacing soldier peering through a crack. Izvestia's story
warned readers that as a result of the scandal, a possible halt in
International Monetary Fund loans to Moscow could be ``the first
step toward the isolation of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal broke as US media outlets reported that US and
British agencies were investigating an alleged money laundering
scam in which, according to the allegations, as much as $15 billion
in embezzled Russian and corporate funds had been channeled through
the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   These reports linked the laundered funds to Russian organized
crime figures, as well as to past and present members of President
Boris N. Yeltsin's government. Some reports also alleged that
International Monetary Fund loans may have been pilfered, although
the IMF is denying this. The IMF has lent Russia some $20 billion
since 1992, with a new loan installment due this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidates are already picking up on the scandal as a
theme, and the White House has called future IMF loans to Russia
into question. Congressional investigations are also getting
underway, as both the House Banking Committee and the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee are planning to hold hearings this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most original _ and amusing _ take on the scandal in
the Russian media came from the newspaper Vremya MN, which accused
the Republican Party of cooking up the money laundering case as a
campaign tactic _ and in doing so, invoked the name of Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that a whole scandal could be provoked by Republicans
who aspire to occupy the White House would have been unrealistic
prior to the Lewinsky scandal,'' Vremya MN said. ``But now, to use
material like bank transfers, international finance and the Russia
question against the Democrats looks quite respectable and even
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers running the stories are all controlled by banks
and financial institutions with close ties to the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here say that the media-inspired conspiracy rhetoric
will find a receptive audience among most Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accusations that the West is again attacking Russia will
unfortunately have considerable resonance in our society,'' said a
Moscow-based sociologist, Alexei Levinson. ``This scandal reminds
people how dependent Russia is on the West, it makes them angry
about this and it inspires fear that Russia will lose the Western
aid and credits that it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding that ``Russians are sufficiently cynical about their own
public officials, and have no illusions about their honesty,''
Levinson said that most people here believe the corruption
allegations raised in the money laundering scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what people believe to be true is not important,''
Levinson said. ``What is important is emotions and this scandal is
pushing all of Russia's emotional buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   And Russia's journalists aren't the only ones pushing those
buttons; the Kremlin is also getting into the act. Last week,
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said that the scandal was ``an attempt
by certain circles'' to prevent Russia's revival as a great power.
</P>
<P>
   But with elections looming in Russia, some anti-Yeltsin
politicians are themselves trying to take advantage of the scandal.
On Friday, Moscow's mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, a Kremlin foe who hopes to
become Russia's next president, called on Yeltsin and his allies
either to admit that the allegations are true, or to sue the
Western newspapers that are printing them. ``Until this is done, I
am going to believe everything I read,'' Luzhkov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
