<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CARDINAL-SURGERY-A     09-04 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-SURGERY-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUMOR REMOVED FROM BRAIN OF NEW YORK'S CARDINAL O'CONNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this story has been added to NYT Page 1, on the fold)  
(ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A small tumor was removed from the surface of the
brain of Cardinal John O'Connor last week by doctors at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, and a course of radiation therapy is
to begin shortly and continue for several weeks, a spokesman for
the Archdiocese of New York announced late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, the cardinal's spokesman, gave no prognosis and
few medical details in a brief statement, but said that doctors had
determined that ``no other areas of the body were affected.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Zwilling said that the 79-year-old
archbishop of New York had been released from the cancer center
Saturday morning, after a 10-day hospitalization, and that he had
returned to his residence on Madison Avenue at 51st Street, behind
St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling described the cardinal as being ``in good spirits,''
and said that he continues to work, has been celebrating Masses
privately during his hospitalization, and was looking forward to
returning to ``a full and vigorous'' schedule. But he noted that
the cardinal's schedule ``will be somewhat lessened for the
immediately future.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who has been the spiritual leader of 2.3 million Roman
Catholics in the Archdiocese of New York for more than 15 years and
is regarded as Pope John Paul II's most important American ally,
was admitted to the cancer center on Aug. 25 after experiencing
weakness and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said that a team of doctors under the leadership of Dr.
Kevin M. Cahill, his personal physician, and Dr. Thomas J. Fahey of
Memorial Sloan-Kettering, had performed ``a thorough series of
tests over six days,'' the results of which were given to the
cardinal last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, made shortly after 5 p.m. Saturday, said:
``Doctors removed a small tumor from the surface of the cardinal's
brain. They determined that no other areas of the body were
affected. A course of radiation therapy will begin shortly and
continue over the next several weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement did not say when or by whom the operation had been
performed, and it gave no details about the precise size or nature
of the tumor that was removed, its position on the surface of the
brain, or the medical prognosis. Zwilling said he could not release
any more medical information about the tumor, or the operation to
remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said that the cardinal would not celebrate Mass
publicly at the cathedral Sunday, and that he had scheduled no
public events for the remainder of the Labor Day weekend. He noted,
however, that the cardinal had been celebrating Masses in his
hospital room and that, after his release at 10 a.m. Saturday, he
had celebrated Mass in a chapel at his residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the cardinal's schedule will be somewhat lessened for
the immediate future, he is looking forward to returning to the
full and vigorous schedule which he has followed since becoming the
archbishop of New York,'' Zwilling said. ``The cardinal is in good
spirits. He has been celebrating mass privately, and he continues
to work on the business of the archdiocese.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling also said that the cardinal had extended ``deep
personal gratitude'' to doctors, nurses, technicians and support
staff at Memorial Sloan-Kettering who had cared for him, and to New
Yorkers and others who had prayed for him and conveyed their good
wishes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the cardinal entered the hospital last month, Zwilling
said that the choice of Memorial Sloan-Kettering, one of the
nation's most prominent cancer centers, did not necessarily mean
that he had cancer. He also declined to say whether the cardinal
had a history or a family history of cancer, hypertension,
cardiopulmonary illness or other medical problems. The hospital,
citing privacy considerations, also declined to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his health, the cardinal may retire on his 80th
birthday in January. In 1995, when he turned 75, he submitted his
resignation to the pope, in accordance with church law. But the
Vatican declined to accept, ``until other provision is made,''
which was widely interpreted to mean until a suitable successor
could be found.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, no successor has been announced. Church law
prohibits a cardinal who turns 80 from voting for a new pope, and
it has been widely reported that the cardinal might retire in
January, although church officials have said such a decision would
ultimately be up to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal has had a number of minor illnesses in recent
years. In 1991, he was briefly hospitalized for heat prostration.
In 1992, he collapsed at the Alfred E. Smith black-tie dinner, and
was hospitalized at St. Vincent's Hospital for what was later
diagnosed as a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he underwent surgery for an enlarged prostate, and in
April 1998 he had minor surgery to remove a growth from his nose.
The cardinal's last illness was in January, when a bout of the flu
worsened as he accompanied the pope on a trip to Mexico. He was
unable to continue with the pope on a later stop in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the cardinal had undergone surgery for a brain tumor
drew expressions of concern from a number of people at St.
Patrick's Cathedral, where an announcement was read out at a Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's all right,'' said Jim St. John, of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., who had not attended the Mass, but was drawn to
the cathedral by the crowd of reporters waiting outside, fearing it
might mean bad news about the cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the spokesperson of the American church now,'' St. John
added. ``He's brilliant. He's done more for the church than anyone
in this century. I was here for his installation and that makes it
very emotional for me. We're all very interested to find out what's
going to happen to the church with his retirement pending. We're
just praying. We're just waiting. I'm sure the Holy Spirit will
guide what goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Dinan, of Oshawa, Ontario, who attended the Mass at St.
Patrick's, said: ``We didn't realize he was ill, and we're glad
they kept us up to date. It is very important that they inform the
parishioners. Our prayers will be that he has a very speedy
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, David, said of the church: ``It's a close-knit
community. Prayers are being said across North America for the
cardinal. Our parishes will be saying prayers for him as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Skosky, of Collinsville, Ill., said solemnly: ``I hope he
recovers. I pray for his speedy recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
