<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF ISRAEL, PALESTINIANS SIGN PEACE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this story now leads the paper; it replaces ALBRIGHT-SYRIA
on NYT Page 1, which goes inside.) 
 (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARM EL-SHEIKH, Egypt _ Surrounded by a panoply of Middle East
leaders and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the Israeli
prime minister, Ehud Barak, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Saturday night signed a broad agreement that the Clinton
administration hopes will quickly usher in a new era of peace
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, held in a beach hotel aired by cool breezes from
the nearby Red Sea, represented an early victory for the apparently
growing trust between the Israeli and Palestinian leaders, and
crowned a busy day of diplomacy for Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Although her closely watched trip on Saturday to Damascus to
meet Syrian President Hafez Assad yielded no immediate sign that
Israeli-Syrian peace talks can open soon, an administration
official said that the meeting nonetheless laid what he termed an
encouraging basis for negotiations in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Albright then became the first secretary of state in almost 17
years to land in Beirut on an official American government plane,
and held talks with Lebanese leaders on a previously unannounced
stop. Her aides said the negotiations were intended to underline
the administration's desire to see all parties, including Lebanon,
engaged in the search for regional peace .
</P>
<P>
   Many of the principals necessary for achieving that tantalizing
goal were on hand for Saturday night's ceremony, essentially the
signing of a revision of an accord reached last year with the
previous Israeli government, but redolent with hope for a final
settlement. Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and King Abdullah of
Jordan applauded as Barak and Arafat, seated side by side on gilt
chairs, signed the latest accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli and the Palestinian, who do not know each other well
but appear to have forged a certain understanding since Barak took
office in July, acted before a backdrop of Egyptian, Israeli,
Jordanian, Palestinian and American flags symbolic of the shared
effort needed for this and future agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we are paving the way toward the end of a century-old
conflict between us and the Palestinians,'' Barak said. ``I am
committed to Israel's security,'' he stressed. ``I also want the
Palestinians to feel secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who on a brief visit to Italy on Saturday hailed the new
accord as a continuation of the venture for which he said the late
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin gave his life, referred to
Barak as ``my new partner in the peace process'' and pledged to
carry out the accords swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   But he also reiterated that Palestinians are determined ``to
build our independent Palestinian state'' with Jerusalem as its
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Barak, 57, injected energy into a quest for
peace that had been on hold for much of three years and is now
resumed at a time of transition in the Middle East. Both Arafat,
and Assad are 69, and in frail health. Barak is new to power and
comparatively young, while King Abdullah, who is 37, is taking over
from his late father, King Hussein, whose contributions to Middle
East peace were often critical.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ceremony, Israeli, Palestinian and American officials
mingled and chatted easily with each other.
</P>
<P>
   At President Clinton's Camp David, Md., mountain retreat, where
the 1978 framework Middle East peace accords were signed, the
president said the breakthrough ``represents a wonderful
opportunity to move the peace process forward,'' The Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement envisions the end of conflict between the
Palestinians and Israelis a year from now with the emotional issues
of the boundaries of Israel and the Palestinian lands and the
disputed status of Jerusalem solved by then. Other long standing
differences over the return of Palestinian refugees now scattered
through the Middle East and the use of water resources would also
be resolved under this bold strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In the shorter term, the agreement calls for the implementation
of a land-for-security deal signed by the Israelis and Palestinians
at Wye, Md. last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Sept. 13, the Israelis will transfer 7 percent of
the West Bank from its total control to partial control for the
Palestinians. On Nov. 15, another 5 percent of the West Bank will
be transferred to the Palestinians and on Jan. 20, the final
transfer called for in the agreement will be completed, meaning
that 40 percent of the West Bank will then be under partial or full
control of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The longer term goal of a final status agreement between the
Palestinians and the Israelis _ which Barak would like to see
conducted alongside talks with the Syrians _ is now the toughest
business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the ceremony Saturday night, Albright alluded to
the difficulties ahead. ``The obstacles that permanent status
negotiators will face are daunting,'' she said. ``The issues are
tough, laden with emotion, and deeply rooted in the region's
troubled past. They involve life and death issues for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The final status negotiations, which are supposed to start by
mid-February, will help determine Israel's size, its role in the
Middle East and its position as a secure or threatened state. The
agreement signed Saturday night does not mention specifically the
emergence of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials have acknowledged that in essence the
final status negotiations mean that the Israelis and Palestinians
will sit down for the first time to discuss the terms of that
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Following on what is envisaged as a more generalized agreement
on the framework for such talks, the negotiations on final status
will deal with such vital issues as contiguity of the Palestinian
territory and ways of entering and leaving Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday night whether the February 15 date for a
framework agreement was too ambitious _ as officials on both sides
have suggested _ a senior American official said: ``Maybe. But if
you set sights too low, you won't reach that. If you set sights
high, that's good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The way Saturday night's agreement was finally stitched together
boded reasonably well for the broader negotiations, the senior
American official said. In the end, Arafat wanted some assurances
on specific concerns _ including the fact that the final transfer
of land would be completed before the framework agreement was drawn
up.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat reportedly had been concerned that Barak would not follow
through on his pledge to deliver the final portion of land if it
was not transferred before the framework agreement was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Going back over some of the key moments in three days of shuttle
diplomacy, the official recalled that when Albright and top
American officials arrived at Gaza City Friday night, it was
unclear whether Arafat had signed off on the complete document. But
Arafat was relaxed when the Americans walked in and ``optimistic
about the future,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans placed a call to Barak from Arafat's office
for the two leaders to talk on Friday night, Arafat opened the
conversation with the Israeli by saying: ``'Shabat, Shalom,''' one
of the Americans said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at the ceremony Saturday night was in a totally
celebratory mood. ``This marks moving from a frozen process to a
working process,'' said Nabil Shaath, one of the Palestinian
negotiators who worked on the agreement with the Israelis. ``It
promises a happy future but it will be really happy when it is
implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said he was delighted that the United States was back in
the process of trying to agree on peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have been anxious to play down their role. One of
the officials involved in the talks of the last few days said that
in contrast to the Wye document last fall and an earlier agreement
in 1997 dealing with Hebron, the Palestinians and Israelis drafted
and wrote this document themselves. The other two had been drafted
by the Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had made a dozen phone calls during the past few weeks
urging both sides on, the official said. And Dennis Ross, the
administration's senior Middle East negotiator, was on the phone
daily with them, sometimes on conference calls with the two sides.
But this was a qualitatively different role to pushing the two
sides together as was necessary under the former Israeli prime
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, the American official said.
</P>
<P>
   The American official cited as an indication of the trust built
in recent months what he said was a remark by Saeb Erekat, the
senior Palestinian negotiator. He quoted Erekat as saying that he
could now understand, if not always agree with, the Israeli point
of view. ``I am finally able to put myself in their shoes,'' Erekat
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of the tough road ahead, Albright summoned the
Palestinians and Israelis to muster still more courage, and invoked
the example of past Middle East leaders who had done the same. ``If
we were to ask, where will the negotiators find the required
strength and confidence?'' she asked. ``I can only think of the
model provided by Anwar Sadat and Menachem Begin, by Yitzhak Rabin
and King Hussein. These leaders experienced war and understood,
therefore, the need to prevent war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
