<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-04 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOSING PROPOSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The Gambler is a masochist moved by the
excitement of thundering horses and animated jocks. He thinks he
can defy the arithmetic lined up against him, but he never does
even though he vainly keeps trying.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in a perpetual agony because of the maddening
fickleness of his pursuit. There are no certainties in horse races
or games, but he lives with the illusion that he can beat a system
that conspires against him.
</P>
<P>
   He can't resist the dark temptation of making money without
working for it, but inevitably winds up broke for giving in to such
an inane impulse. He knows after a while that his addiction is
self-destructive, but he refuses to change because he enjoys the
emotional jolts he receives during his rare moments of financial
gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Gambler does not fit any stereotypical mold. He is just as
liable to be an erudite college professor as he is to be a
bartender, and I know a one-time professor who's shattered his life
because of his race track forays. He is just as liable to be a
high-priced heart surgeon as he is to be a ticket scalper, and I
knew a doctor, now dead, responsible for the down payment on a
bookmaker's home. He is just as liable to own a lucrative car
dealership as he is to be a liquor salesman, and I know a guy who
blew his lucrative car dealership because of the millions he lost
from his uncontrollable betting urges.
</P>
<P>
   The football season is now upon us, and The Gambler is being
heavily recruited by bookmakers. That in itself should make him
wary, but it never does. He accepts their phone numbers with naive
gladness, and blithely ignores the harrowing fact that the calls
he'll make during the autumn will result in the drastic
diminishment of his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   This is the inevitable outcome because he must lay 11 dollars
for every 10 dollars he bets, and thus the numbers are aligned
against him. It's difficult enough to guess which side will win a
football game based upon a point spread, but this 11 to 10 gimmick
known as the vigorish makes the entire proposition a mathematical
impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't matter to The Gambler, who wallows in a fog of
self-denial, who boasts shamelessly about his winners and lapses
into a silent depression when his handicapping results in losers.
</P>
<P>
   He often doesn't understand he's engaged in a fool's sport until
it's too late, until the creditors foreclose on his properties,
until the car is repossessed, until the wife and kids depart, until
he loses his job or business, until he finds himself having to live
in the den of his best friend, until he realizes he must spend his
evenings attending Gambler's Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Gambler spends wasteful hours studying the form sheets and
listening to the views of pundits, but winds up cursing his
misfortune when a jockey miscalculates or a running back fumbles or
an official blows a call.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps practicing his hopeless art year after dreary year even
though his ultimate fate never changes, and he has nothing to show
for all of his wagering.
</P>
<P>
   He is a likable fellow, quick to pick up tabs on those rare
occasions when his pockets are stuffed with money. He can be fun,
and light up a party with his one liners.
</P>
<P>
   But most of his life is spent curing his misfortune. Oh, if only
I hadn't taken that horse out of the Pick 6 I could have won that
million dollar payoff, oh, if only that quarterback hadn't been
intercepted, oh, if only that receiver hadn't dropped the ball in
the end zone, oh, if, if, if, ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   He so often has a blank expression fixed on his florid face
because his life is an endless roller-coaster of emotions, with the
giddiness from winning never quite matching the horrible gloom that
envelops him from losing.
</P>
<P>
   The Gambler perceives his bookmaker as his friend, but this is a
misguided perception because the bookmaker is an unlicensed
pawnbroker who puts his customers in hock. A bookmaker is a
heartless scoundrel who earns his living from the compulsive
weaknesses of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Betting is a sham that exploits those who pursue it, and even
the government of the states are involved in it with their
lotteries that fleece millions of dollars each week from people who
can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a terrible habit that those addicted can't easily shake,
and I've known too many people ruined by it. I'll defend the right
of a person to make a bet, but I'll also ridicule him harshly for
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   But The Gambler doesn't care about the odds stacked again him,
about the unfortunate events that await ominously on the horizon
for him.
</P>
<P>
   He just cares about getting down, and feeling that wicked
adrenaline rush that one feels when he's punched out a race ticket,
or when he gives a clerk his gridiron selection.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a mean facade, and at the end The Gambler will be broke
because only those taking the action in his endeavor make money.
The bettors never come out on top at the end, but the suckers keep
trying for reasons not even the psycho-babblers have been able to
figure out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
