<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Sept. 5. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
NAVAJO-ELDER _ On the most isolated corners of northeastern
Arizona, what may be the last generation of traditional Native
American people live out their lives alone. Many of their children
have left, but the old people stay on, living in primitive hogans
far from villages or neighbors. It is a beautiful, but dangerous
isolation. By MAUREEN WEST and BETTY REID. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REDISTRICT _ The Justice Department says Arizona has failed to
prove that its plan for redrawing legislative district boundary
lines after the 2000 census wouldn't discriminate against
minorities. Arizona's defense of its redistricting plan for
legislative and congressional seats is ``insufficient,'' the
department's Civil Rights Division said in a July 28 letter to the
Arizona Attorney General's Office. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABORTION _ Profile of the 14-year-old girl in Arizona foster care
who became a symbol of the national debate over abortion. A picture
of her turbulent life emerges through interviews with family
members, people who know her both now and as a younger child, and
from court and police records. By KARINA BLAND. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL (Undated) _ For more than a week, now, grown-ups all
over town have been shouting at one another over a girl. It's not
unusual for adults to argue over children, of course. This
particular discussion got ugly because it concerned a 14-year-old
who was pregnant and wanted to have an abortion. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) _ Nothing dusts up a good argument like sports.
But no one can dispute one thing: When they switched on the cameras
for the first time in Bristol, Conn., on Sept. 7, 1977, no one
dreamed that ESPN would change _ for better and for worse _ the
face of sports forever. The network celebrates its 20th anniversary
Tuesday. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
