<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASECOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR IS THE MAN TO TURN ANGELS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Terry Collins didn't quit Friday. His players got
him fired two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The trick for the Anaheim Angels, who face a winter even more
chaotic than the regular season, is to make sure that never happens
again.
</P>
<P>
   Hire Don Baylor. Hire him now.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem as though getting the playoff-bound Atlanta Braves
batting coach at this point in the season would be like hiring a
coach just before he goes to the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But protocol is out the window at this point. The Angels aren't
going to be able to gut their roster in the offseason. They need
someone who can give them some guts.
</P>
<P>
   They need someone who can get the players _ who mutinied against
Collins before cannibalizing themselves _ to look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   For the modern player, that is so much harder than hitting a
curveball.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor can do that.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Robin Yount what the scariest sight was during his Hall of
Fame career and he'll say it was seeing Don Baylor coming in on him
to break up a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels need more than a metaphor. And in Baylor they would
have one.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was the American League MVP with the Angels in 1979 and
still lives in the area. His leadership led the club to some of its
greatest seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He offers sound managerial credentials, taking expansion
Colorado to three winning seasons in six years.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Baylor offers something Collins, for all his
attributes, never could. A clubhouse presence that turns 25 players
into one.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won four World Series with the team of GM Buzzie
Bavasi and manager Walt Alston, who played one major-league game
between them. But those days are over. Players are bigger, stronger
and faster than ever. They are also more fragile.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excusing how poorly the Angels players acted this
season. They used the team's injuries as their out-clause and when
that wasn't enough they ripped the manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins' playing career, which never reached the majors, is
not much different than Earl Weaver's or Tom Lasorda's. Only the
time in which he managed has changed. The others are in the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is headed home with $450,000 to be paid for next year,
but without the legacy he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   When Baylor was at Dodger Stadium last month with the Braves, he
couldn't say he wanted the Angels job. Collins was still in place,
but the obvious was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, aware that only two of 11 African-American managers ever
have been given a second chance, knows that the odds have not
always been in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   But now he holds the hammer. Baltimore, where he broke in as a
player, wants him desperately. The Orioles have an old, unmotivated
team in need of some fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels need to act now. The last time they waited, they let
Mo Vaughn take their free-agent offer and shop it around for two
months before saying yes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance GM Bill Bavasi and club president Tony
Taveras will be gone by next spring training. So too will Disney,
which is expected to sell the club to Irvine-based billionaire
Henry Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans will still be there. So will most of the team,
underachievers or not.
</P>
<P>
   They need Don Baylor now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
