<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-Mideast-Peace-Cox     09-04 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mideast-Peace-Cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBRIGHT WITNESSES PROGRESS AMONG ISRAEL AND PALESTINIANS,
CONTINUED STALEMATE WITH SYRIA
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM As U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright looked
on last night, two long-time foes, Israelis and Palestinians,
affirmed a plan to settle all their differences within a year. But
her efforts duriing her visit to the Middle East to coax Syria into
settling that country's disputes with Israel still showed little
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Albright witnessed the signing of a new Palestinian-Israeli
peace agreement in the Egyptian resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh,
land once conquered by Israel and then returned under the Camp
David Agreements of 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Israelis and Palestinians negotiated this pact
directly is a rich source of hope for the future,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   The pact signed just after midnight in Egypt is the seventh plan
signed since 1993, the start of the on-again, off-again Oslo peace
process and is acutally a revision of the Wye River Memorandum, an
agreement signed in Washington in October. The plan sets a schedule
for the Israeli withdrawal from predominantly Arab land in the West
Bank, which Israel captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's four-day tour of the region aims at taking advantage
of what American officials believe is a new opportunity for peace
between Israel and all its neighbors: the May election of Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In an another hopeful sign earlier in the day Saturday, she made
a surprise visit to Lebanon to consult with Prime Minister Salim
el-Hoss and she became the first secretary of state since 1983 to
use the public airport in that war-scarred country. In her previous
visit, she had helicoptered directly to the heavily fortified U.S.
Embassy complex.
</P>
<P>
   The signing represents more of a new atmosphere than any
substantive change in the plan for settling the throny issues that
separtate the Israelis and Palestinians . The Wye memorandum was
signed but abandoned by former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are worried that the new agreement will also not be
implemented. But, Albright said the new agreement represents a
return to the mutual trust the parties showed in signing the
original outline for peace, the 1993 Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton, from Camp David, called the agreement a
``new beginning'' and asked Congress to approve $1.6 billion in aid
promised to the two sides for implementing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Barak noted that the agreement sets a
timetable for all issues to be settled within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we are paving the way to the end of the century-old
conflict between us and the Palestinians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his election campaign, Barak had promised to resume the old
Wye process, but then he refused to do so until it was
renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   He won a deal that lets him slow down the land transfers while
speeding up the discussions of the major issues between the two
sides such as whether Israel will share Jerusalem with the
Palestinians or allow the return of millions of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The methodical former general has been apprehensive about giving
away land without knowing how the final issues will be solved. The
agreement sets a new deadline of September 2000 for the resolution
of all issues.
</P>
<P>
   What the Palestinians get in the deal is less apparent. Much of
the new plan is a repeat of the old Wye, but Barak seems more
determined to carry it out than Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement lets the Palestinians start construction on an
$80 million seaport in The Gaza Strip, promised in the old
agreement. It promises to let Palestinians travel, in controlled
caravans, through Israel between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank
anther item promised before.
</P>
<P>
   It also promises the release of 350 Palestinians in Israeli
jails for anti-Israel activity. Palestinians, viewing the prisoners
as political detainees, had sought more, but this would be more
than Netanyahu afforded.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they await to see if this agreement will be implemented,
unlike the last, and they still bristle Barak's insistence on
renegotiating a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He insisted on changing it and called the Palestinians
stubborn for not wanting to go along with him,'' said former
Palestinian cabinet member Hanan Ashrawi. ``With every new
agreement, we have managed to chip away at the substance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, the chances that they will get what was written are
higher than have been,'' said Israeli political columnist Chemi
Shalev.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's dealings on Israel's northern front were not as
productive.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years, Israeli troops have occupied a 9-mile-wide swathe
of land in southern Lebanon, battling forces that have opposed the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon is now controlled by Syria. It is believed that Syria
would rein in the anti-Israeli Hezbollah guerrillas if Israel
returns the Golan Heights, conquered from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   But, talks between the two sides broke off in 1996 and Syria has
asked that Israel agree up-front on the principle of returning the
entire Golan Heights before talks restart. Syrian officials
repeated those conditions Saturday to Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts speculate that progress between Israel and
the Palestinians will put pressure on Syria to also make peace.
Albright, who had helped close Palestinian deal the night before,
hoped it would carry momentum through her trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light that came from yesterday's agreement should also let
us illuminate the whole region,'' she said in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   She was scheduled to go to Turkey Sunday, but possibly return
for a night in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
