<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-IRELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR U.S. SOCCER TEAM, EXHIBITION IS A CORONATION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The American women's soccer team that captured
the fancy of sports fans and the news media this summer returned to
action for the first time Saturday afternoon since winning the
World Cup. The players walked onto the Foxboro Stadium field waving
their arms and blowing kisses to the crowd of 30,564 in an
atmosphere reminiscent of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But because this was an exhibition game against Ireland, a
rather weak team that the Americans demolished by 5-0 despite only
one day's practice, there were no wild celebrations after goals.
Nothing like Tisha Venturini doing a back flip in the World Cup
victory over North Korea or Brandi Chastain shedding her jersey
after her deciding penalty kick against China in the championship
game in July.
</P>
<P>
   After close to two months of endorsements and public appearances
off the field for the American team, this game against Ireland was
a coronation of sorts. It was like raising the banner to the
rafters by a hockey or basketball team, a reunion with the fans who
fell in love with a group of soccer players because they brought a
world championship to this country and recognition for women in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Only three players from the World Cup roster were missing.
Goalkeeper Briana Scurry, who made the crucial save in the shootout
against China in the World Cup final, had a prior commitment.
Defender Lorrie Fair is back in school at the University of North
Carolina. And midfielder Michelle Akers, who has chronic fatigue
syndrome, is still recuperating from the World Cup and will not
return to play until January.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain started in the second half because she joined the team
just before the game and had not practiced. Her place at left
fullback had been taken by Christie Pearce, while Saskia Webber
took Scurry's place in goal and Tiffany Roberts started in midfield
in place of Akers.
</P>
<P>
   The game came 56 days after the Americans' World Cup triumph
before a crowd of 90,185 at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif. This
is in contrast to 1991, when the Americans won the World Cup and
then took nine months off.
</P>
<P>
   Despite only a single practice in preparation for this game, the
Americans orchestrated a great deal of action that excited the
crowd. The Americans played with imagination and creativity in
midfield and finished their efforts effectively, especially in the
second half, when they scored three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffeny Milbrett, the engine for the Americans in midfield in
the World Cup, led the team Saturday with two goals, including the
game's opening goal in the 25th minute. Julie Foudy, Joy Fawcett
and Kristine Lilly had the other goals for the Americans, who
improved their 1999 record to 21-2-2, with the penalty-kick victory
over China in the World Cup counting as a tie in the official
records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-MICHIGA     09-04 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-MICHIGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN BEATS NOTRE DAME, 26-22  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Forget the feud over Notre Dame's adding an
extra game; it was manufactured. Michigan's quarterback
controversy? It was solved early and emphatically. But one thing
remained true to form when the Wolverines and the Fighting Irish _
the nation's two winning-est programs _ renewed their bitter
rivalry Saturday: they played until the final minute and stayed
within a couple points of each other.
</P>
<P>
   For the 11th time in their last 18 meetings, 7 or fewer points
decided the game. This time, with Notre Dame out of timeouts and
desperately trying to line up on Michigan's 11-yard line, a
National Collegiate Athletic Association-record crowd of 111,523
sent a roar of approval reverberating through Michigan Stadium over
the final score: Michigan 26, Notre Dame 22.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen points were scored in the final eight minutes, and with
4 minutes 8 seconds to play, the No. 16-ranked Irish looked as if
they were in command. Lloyd Carr, coach of No. 7 Michigan, had
complained that the Irish had violated a gentleman's agreement by
adding an opening game last week against Kansas. He claimed it was
an unfair advantage. It hardly looked like it Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish's drive to take a 22-19 lead pretty much
captured how a young, talented team can alternately tantalize and
torment. On the seven-play, 65-yard march, there were passes that
accounted for 40 yards, and there were false starts and missed
blocking assignments that gave half of that back.
</P>
<P>
   There was quarterback Jarious Jackson's composure: on
fourth-and-1 from the 19, he faked a handoff, rolled left and threw
across the field to a wide-open Jabari Holloway, who walked into
the end zone for the 20-19 lead. There was Bobby Brown's costly
enthusiasm: after catching a 2-point conversion pass to put the
Irish ahead by 22-19, he and his teammates were penalized for
excessive celebration. It meant Notre Dame had to kick off from its
own 20-yard line, and Michigan started its game-winning drive on
its own 42.
</P>
<P>
   The senior quarterback Tom Brady acted quickly. He passed to
Marcus Knight for a 15-yard gain that became 30 when Notre Dame
safety A'Jani Sanders was penalized for a late hit. He took
Michigan to the Irish 5-yard line with a slant pass to David
Terrell. Two plays later, Anthony Thomas swept left into the end
zone; Jeff Del Verne kicked the extra point and Michigan was ahead,
26-22.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Irish had 1:38 left. They had Jackson and hope but no
timeouts. The senior quarterback took them to the 11. But that
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different Wolverines team that came out in the second
half _ one led by Brady, who had started the game before giving way
to Drew Henson in the second quarter. The senior tri-captain wasted
no time, taking the Wolverines 80 yards in 3:08. He completed 4 of
5 passes for 63 yards before Thomas took it over from the 2-yard
line for a touchdown, giving Michigan a 16-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two more times in the third quarter Brady moved Michigan down
the field: a 32-yard drive ended with Del Verne missing a 26-yard
field goal, and a 29-yard drive saw Del Verne kick a 27-yarder to
put Michigan ahead, 19-14. Brady remained the Wolverines'
quarterback for the remainder of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Brady and Henson each played a quarter as an
audition to be the Wolverines' quarterback in the second half.
Michigan controlled the clock in the first half _ 15:35 to 14:24 _
but failed to convert critical third downs; the Wolverines were 4
for 9.
</P>
<P>
   With Brady at the helm on the opening drive, the Wolverines
marched 41 yards in nine plays to the Irish 9. But the Notre Dame
defense stuffed Thomas on third-and-6, and Michigan settled for a
21-yard field goal by Del Verne.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines stalled again on their next possession. On
third-and-3 from the Notre Dame 18, Brady tried to find Knight on a
square-out pass but the pass was caught out of bounds. This time
Del Verne kicked a 25-yarder for a 6-0 Michigan lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, however, were ready to break free, and they did it on
the first play after the kickoff. On first-and-10 from their own
20, Jackson rolled left and found Tony Fisher, who had circled from
the backfield, alone on the 40-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher caught the pass over his shoulder and raced down the
sideline to Michigan's 25, and another 5 yards was tacked on for a
face-mask penalty. On second-and-9, Jackson turned a near certain
sack into a 9-yard gain down to the 16-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-goal and the Michigan Stadium crowd at full volume,
Jackson and the Irish line rolled right while flanker Joey
Getherall circled back left. Jackson pitched the reverse to back to
Getherall and he scampered into the end zone alone. Jim Sanson
converted the extra point and the Irish were up, 7-6, after an
eight-play, 80-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Then Henson took over for Michigan in the second quarter, but he
had no better luck than Brady in turning a big play into 6 points.
Again, the Wolverines could not convert on third down and Del Verne
came in to kick his third field goal of the first half, a
37-yarder, to give the lead back to Michigan, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:20 left in the half, the Irish got the ball on Michigan's
41. It didn't take Jackson long to torture Michigan with his
footwork. Two of his scrambles picked up half of that yardage and
the last one translated into a spectacular touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the 12, Michigan sent all its linebackers
after Jackson. Fullback Joey Goodspeed blocked one linebacker, but
Jackson still needed to roll left to elude three more blue jerseys.
He then cut back between them, jittered left, shuffled right,
picking up a block from center John Merandi, before twirling into
the end zone to give Notre Dame a 14-9 halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
