<HEADLINE>
METS LOOKING FOR SHORTCUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo went 6 for 6 with
three homers Monday. The defense has a .988 fielding percentage.
Rookie right-hander Octavio Dotel has walked into a pennant race
and put himself in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the New York Mets go far in the postseason, expect
them to use Alfonzo and Dotel as part of a package to acquire
Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also are fascinated with the idea of trading for the
future Hall of Famer. But the Mets, who would also throw in
shortstop Rey Ordonez, have the players to make this a real
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are faced with Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr.
leaving through free agency after next season. Both are seeking
long contracts for well over $100 million. It is expected Seattle
will make a deal with Rodriguez if it cannot re-sign him this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Means nothing in October: If the season ended today, the
wild-card Mets would face the Arizona Diamondbacks in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Right now that doesn't look too good for the Mets, who went 2-7
this year against the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is 8-16 against the other first-round possibilities,
Atlanta, Houston and Cincinnati, but they have outscored the Mets
63-39.
</P>
<P>
   It should be remembered that the last time the Mets made it to
the postseason (1988), they faced a Dodgers team they had defeated
10 of 11 times during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won the NLCS in seven games and went on to beat
Oakland in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get into October, who cares what happened in the
regular season?'' Arizona left-hander Brian Anderson said. ``The
Mets won't come in here intimidated by us by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   First things first: Of course, the San Francisco Giants took a
seven-game lead into Saturday's action and cut the Diamondbacks'
lead to five games with a month to play. Barry Bonds took off
Friday's 12-2 win over Pittsburgh, but he continues his amazing
late-season run. Wednesday he had his fourth two home run game in
his past 13 games. He finished August with 14 homers, the most by a
Giants player since Willie Mays hit 17 in August 1965. ``Thank God
that it's happening now,'' manager Dusty Baker said. ``You've
almost come to expect it. He does it day in and day out. The main
thing now is to win. He wants to win badly and we want to win
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   More problems: Although most of the blame for the Phillies'
decline has been traced to Curt Schilling 's three-week stay on the
disabled list, third baseman Scott Rolen hasn't helped. Rolen, who
missed just eight games in his first two seasons, has missed 24
this season with a sore lower back. Since July 21, Rolen has just
two homers and 14 RBI. In 16 games before the injury, Rolen hit
.317 with nine homers and 22 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bright future: The Pirates' .500 season is already an
overwhelming success. They have not challenged Houston or
Cincinnati in the Central Division, but they have laid the
foundation for future success. Second baseman !bolod!Warren Morris
is a rookie of the year favorite. First baseman Kevin Young became
the fourth player in frachise history to hit 20 homers and steal 20
bases in the same season. Brian Giles, acquired from Cleveland
after the Indians said he could be an everyday player, had 12
homers and 31 RBI in August and is at 34 and 100 for the year.
Giles could challenge for Paul Waner 's club record of 131 RBI set
in 1927.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
