A1013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE05-     09-04 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    50 years of racing at Darlington
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ In the first Southern 500 at Darlington
Raceway, the majority of competitors drove their stock cars to and
from the track.
</P>
<P>
   Few hotels existed near the tiny, rural South Carolina town _
located 72 miles east of the capital city of Columbia _ so many
drivers spent the night in their cars during the 15 days of
qualifying. On race day, masking tape was used for car numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have seat belts, so we had to tie ourselves in the
car with a rope,'' Hall of Fame driver Cotton Owens said. ``And the
doors had handles, so we had to tie them shut with a dog collar.''
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural Southern 500 was Sept. 4, 1950. Today's 1 p.m.
event is the 50th anniversary of the race, which is a bona fide
Southern and NASCAR tradition. The aura of the 1.366-mile banked
oval, once known as ``The Lady in Black'' for its tendency to scar
shiny new cars, has changed little over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much history at Darlington,'' Jeff Burton said.
``To me, it's one of the biggest races of the year. It's a race
that has put Winston Cup racing where it is (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Mantz's claim to fame was winning the inaugural Southern
500, which was the first Winston Cup (then called Grand National)
race to be held on a paved raceway and the first to go 500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mantz's lone Cup victory. He took the checkered flag in
six hours, 38 minutes and 40 seconds at an average speed of 75.250
mph. One of the co-owners of Mantz's car was Bill France Sr.,
founder of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sport's most memorable moments have occurred at the
Southern 500 in the past half-decade:
</P>
<P>
   1962: Junior Johnson drove into the winner's circle, but a
protest by Lee Petty caused a review of the manual scoring cards.
Larry Frank was declared the official winner and was honored in a
ceremony the next day in front of empty grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   1965: Ned Jarrett had one of the most dominating victories of
his career, winning by 14 laps. Rookie driver Buren Skeen was
involved in a collision on the second lap and died nine days later.
Cale Yarborough was knocked over the wall in Turn 2, with a young
college student by the name of Robert Yates watching nearby.
</P>
<P>
   1966: Earl Balmer nearly destroyed the press box after his car
hit the rail and became airborne.
</P>
<P>
   1976: David Pearson claimed the first of three Southern 500
victories. He won the most races (10) at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   1985: In the most famous race of his career, Bill Elliott won
the race and the inaugural Winston Million on national television.
Elliott appeared on the cover of Sports Illustrated for the
monetary feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has just been a good race track for me, for whatever
reason,'' Elliott said. ``The '85 race was big, and I also think
it's ironic that my last (Cup) win came there in '94.''
</P>
<P>
   1998: Jeff Gordon became the first driver to win four years in a
row and trails only Yarborough in career victories (five) in the
Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darlington has turned into one of my favorite tracks,'' Gordon
said. ``It wasn't one of my favorite places in the beginning, but
eventually it became a place where I really enjoy racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough, tough race track _ one of those tracks that no
matter how perfect your day is going, you'll have a situation when
you say, 'Hey, I just barely made it through that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Darlington Raceway is shaped more like an egg than a modern
oval. The turns on the west end are much tighter than the other end
because builder Harold Brasington refused to destroy a minnow pond
on the outside on turn 4. The unusual design has created problems
for drivers since the inaugural race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do everything short of blowing the damned place up,
but Darlington is still the same treacherous old track that it was
15 years ago when I first raced there,'' said Rusty Wallace, who
has yet to win a Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
