<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin to have surgery
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Mark Martin won the Dura-Lube 200 on Saturday
for his fifth Busch Series victory in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the season-long success in the Grand National division,
Martin's victory at Darlington Raceway was a minor surprise. Martin
had said the car was an ``embarrassment'' after qualifying Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never dreamed that we could win the race, but I've got
to give credit to the team and (crew chief) Tony Lambert,'' Martin
said. ``They never gave up. They still thought (we) could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Blaney and Matt Kenseth, who is second in the points
standings, rounded out the top three.
</P>
<P>
   Offseason surgery
</P>
<P>
   Martin canceled back surgery during the the last offseason but
says he will have the operation Nov. 22, the day after the
season-ending race at Atlanta Motor Speedway.Martin's injury has
been diagnosed as a deteriorating disk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm up for the fusion (surgery) as long as somebody will
not guarantee me but really convince me that I'm going to be better
after I have it,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   New millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   Through the Winston No Bull 5 program, five race fans each have
the chance to become a millionaire if their driver takes the
checkered flag in today's race. The eligible drivers are Dale
Jarrett, Tony Stewart, Bobby Labonte, Jeff Burton and Martin. With
a victory by any of the five, the driver and paired fan each win $1
million. The fans were selected at random by a nationwide
sweepstakes program The drivers became eligible by finishing in the
top five at May's Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR rocks
</P>
<P>
   The rock group Blessed Union of Souls is shooting a video this
weekend for its last song ``Rev It Up, NASCAR Rocks.'' Drivers
participating in the filming include Darrell Waltrip, Dale
Earnhardt Jr. and Bill Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Off track
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the day on the feud between Dale Earnhardt and Terry
Labonte came from Jarrett: ``Oh, (Earnhardt) is aggravating as hell
to race with, but that's him. It's aggravating, but it's fun
racing.'' . . . Mike Dillon has signed to drive a Grand National
car for Richard Childress Racing through the 2002 season. . . . For
the second race in a row, Jerry Nadeau is the substitute driver for
the No. 36 Pontiac. Now that Ernie Irvan has retired, Nadeau likely
will remain the car for the final 11 races. ``If things keep going
the way they're going, I could be there the rest of the year,''
said Nadeau, who will start third in today's race. He is under
contract to drive for Hendrick Motorsports next season. Johnny
Benson and Todd Bodine have surfaced as candidates for the No. 36
car next year. . . . A.J. Foyt, who is seeking a driver for his Cup
team next year, confirmed he is not considering Kenny Brack, who is
the defending Indy Racing League Champion and drives for one of the
two Foyt-owned IRL teams. ``I don't think Kenny is ready yet,''
Foyt said. ``He liked the IROC races, but there's a big difference
between that and Winston Cup.'' Foyt's Cup car will apparently be
No. 14, the same number Foyt made famous as driver in open-wheel
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
