<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON COULD RETURN TO RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oakland and Boston each entered Saturday's action
with 27 games remaining. The Red Sox had just a one-game lead in
the wild-card race after losing 2-1 in Seattle on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland has eight games left against teams with .500 records and
the Red Sox have 15, including back-to-back series against the
league's winningest teams, New York and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston might get back closer Tom Gordon, who was feared lost
for the season with elbow problems. Gordon, who converted 46 of 47
save opportunities last season, was clocked at 89 mph during a
workout in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His possible return comes at a time when the Red Sox are
uncertain about former Dodger Ramon Martinez, who struggled
Thursday in his first start since July 1998 elbow surgery. But they
also acquired Grant High product Rod Beck , who is coming back from
elbow problems that ruined his season with the Cubs. Beck arrived
in the fourth inning of Wednesday's game against Kansas City and
earned a save in the ninth. &QL; 
That was some trade: While the Angels are almost forced to re-sign
left-hander Chuck Finley for around $7 million a year, the
potential free-agent they let get away, Omar Olivares , has been
great in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares is 5-0 in seven starts since arriving in Oakland. He
had never won more than four in a row in his career. Randy Velarde,
another pending free agent acquired in the trade, already has had
hitting streaks of 13 and 10 games since joining the A's. More
importantly, the A's are 24-10 since the two players arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Who's in left?: When Orioles center fielder Brady Anderson moved
to left field Wednesday, it might have been a glimpse of the
future. The switch has been talked about much of the season, but
now that Baltimore is so far out of the race, the team would like
to see youngster Eugene Kingsdale. Right now it looks as though
Anderson will be back in center next season, but if Cal Ripken
retires after next year, B.J. Surhoff could wind up at third with
Anderson in left full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming:Some good might have come from Brian McRae 's bad
knee in Toronto. The Blue Jays have called up center fielder Vernon
Wells, a top prospect just two years out of high school. Wells
began the season at Single-A, but sailed through three levels in
five months, batting a combined .334 with 18 homers and 81 RBI. He
went 0 for 7 in his first two games, and an 0 for 5 on Friday night
dropped his average to .150. But Wells felt better when All-Star
Shawn Green came up and said he began his career 0 for 15.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers reload: The Texas Rangers, fearful of New York and
Cleveland's big left-handed bats in the playoffs, acquired
left-hander Jeff Fassero from Seattle at the Aug. 31 postseason
trade deadline. They weren't comfortable going with former Angel
Matt Perisho, a 15-game winner at Triple-A. They obviously worried
about using veteran John Burkett or veteran Mike Morgan, who has a
10.80 ERA in his past six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Runaway: Although it is no guarantee of postseason success, the
lead the Cleveland Indians have in the Central Division is very
impressive. Their 7-6 victory over Baltimore on Friday gave the
Indians a 22{-game lead, their biggest since 1995 when they set a
major-league record by finishing 30 games in front.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have superior talent, the Indians have had nine
players on the DL this year, including regulars Travis Fryman,
Sandy Alomar, Wil Cordero and Kenny Lofton and one-time staff ace
Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   For the stretch, Cleveland acquired Harold Baines from Baltimore
earlier in the week. Baines wants to return to the Orioles to close
out his career, but Baltimore was willing to give him a chance for
one more shot at a World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
