</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LIBERTY-COMETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A TOUCH OF GLASS, LIBERTY STUNS COMETS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Liberty guard Teresa Weatherspoon put a crimp in the
Comets' celebration plans Saturday with a desperation 3-point shot
launched from beyond half court with four-tenths of a second to
play. The shot banked off the glass and into the basket to give the
Liberty an improbable 68-67 victory and force a Game 3 in the
Women's National Basketball Association championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Before this afternoon's game, and even in the first half, it
looked like all the Houston Comets would have to do to pick up
their third straight WNBA championship was to goof around the court
for 40 minutes and then walk to center court of the Compaq Center
and reach out their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty put on a furious rally to overcome a 14-point
halftime deficit with a 19-3 second half run. Then it came down to
the final moments.
</P>
<P>
   Kym Hampton was fouled by Sheryl Swoopes while making a basket
and made the free throw, then hit a 15-footer to put the Liberty in
front by 63-62 with 1 minute 24 seconds left. Swoopes was fouled on
the next trip down the floor and made both free throws with 1:05 to
go to give Houston a 64-63 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, Cynthia Cooper, the league's leading
scorer who was just 1 for 10 Saturday, stole the ball from Vickie
Johnson. Tina Thompson was fouled with 28 seconds left and made one
of two free throws, leaving Houston up by 65-63.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Robinson tied the score at 65-65 with 16 seconds left,
and Thompson hit a jumper with 2.4 seconds remaining that nearly
brought the house down as Houston took a 67-65 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was out of timeouts, and the ball was inbounded
quickly to Weatherspoon. Her improbable shot stunned the crowd of
16,285, who had already started throwing streamers and confetti.
But Weatherspoon's basket insured there will be the final game on
Sunday. And the way things unfolded Saturday, it is no longer a
lock for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching the flight of the ball and the arc of the ball, I saw
that the ball had a chance to go in,'' said Robinson, who score a
game-high 21 points (18 in the second half). ``When it hit the
square on the glass, I thought it was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the shot went in, fans were silent as
Weatherspoon, who finished with 8 points and 5 assists, was mobbed
by her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt pretty good when it left my hands,'' Weatherspoon
said. ``I was just praying that it went in and that we'd have a
chance for Game 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said: ``My thought when the ball was in the air was I
called it a basket. I've never seen a shot like that. I've never
experienced anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon said she had just one thought when she took the
inbound pass. ``I wasn't going to look for anyone,'' Weatherspoon
said. ``I was going to live or die with that shot. I didn't want
any of my teammates to have to live with missing that shot during
the off season. If it didn't go in, I wanted to be the one to have
to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough the desperation shot is something that a few of the
Liberty players work on at the conclusion of each practice.
Weatherspoon said that guard Becky Hammon normally won the shooting
contests.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way that the Liberty started and the way the
game ended, it was truly miraculous that it is alive for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was horrendous from the field in the first half,
shooting 1 of 11 in the first 10 minutes. The Liberty was quickly
trailing by 17-2 against a team that was on fire in a building that
was filled with raucous fans. The Liberty's first basket came at
15:11 on a 16-foot jumper by Johnson. The Liberty didn't get its
second field goal until Sophia Witherspoon hit a driving layup with
9:17 to play. In the interim the Comets, and their fans, began
their stroll toward their third straight coronation as WNBA
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were stifling us in the first half,'' said Liberty Coach
Richie Adubato. ``We were on that 2 points for a long time. I
haven't seen anybody play defense like that ever. I'm glad there
aren't any shutouts in games like these.''
</P>
<P>
   As they had done on Thursday night in Game 1, the Comets were
able to force the Liberty out of their game. This time they did it
with a suffocating full court press.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty came out with more life in the second half, holding
the Comets scoreless for the first 2 minutes and cutting into that
14-point halftime lead with three field goals from Robinson and a
3-pointer from Weatherspoon that made the score 37-29. Robinson
continued to have the hot hand and her teammates kept finding her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't buy a basket in the first half,'' said Robinson,
who was 1 of 6 from the field in the first half. ``I was getting
shots, but they weren't falling. Coach told me to just keep
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing she listened. The Liberty continued their rally and
took its first lead of the game, 42-40, on a 3-pointer by Robinson
with 11:55 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cooper, who had blistered the Liberty for 29 points
on Thursday night, went into a second-half drought. She finished
with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't let me get into a rhythm,'' Cooper said. The
good news is we do have a second chance. We do have a chance to
play a 40-minute game and match the intensity that we showed on
Thursday night and the intensity that the Liberty showed in the
second half today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
