<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE SHADOWS, CAPRIATI SEIZES SPOTLIGHT IN THE OPEN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She has called her reincarnation close to complete.
No longer the distraught teen-ager who turned to darker recreations
when the scrutiny that came with tennis fame began to chafe like a
pair of golden handcuffs, Jennifer Capriati ignored the leaden air
Saturday and jumped for joy following her successful debut in the
Arthur Ashe Stadium at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of self-destruction that segued into three
more of self-help, Capriati, instantly lauded as a big-stadium
player when she made her pro debut at the age of 13, was back in
business in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   As her last passing shot streaked by 11th-seeded Nathalie
Tauziat to seal her 6-3, 1-6, 6-1 upset, Capriati took her cue from
the whimsical lilac and yellow butterfly clips restraining her
hair: she practically levitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excited,'' Capriati said in explaining her post-match
euphoria. ``I'm working hard, being focused, doing all the right
things. Just keep doing it, keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time is a good time to win a Grand Slam. It doesn't matter
whether you're the youngest or the oldest or whatever,'' said
Capriati, who at 23 has studied Andre Agassi's transformation from
141st-ranked has-been to 1999 French Open champion like a
blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the second-seeded Agassi, with Pete Sampras' No. 1
ranking all his if he wins this title, advanced with a 6-1, 4-6,
6-3, 6-4 throttling of Justin Gimelstob of New Jersey. Agassi left
the histrionics, along with an on-court change of shorts, to
Gimelstob, who injured his left wrist with a rotisserie-style
spinning swan dive in the fifth game of the final set but stuck
around for a regulation finish. Gimelstob even performed curtain
calls for his local fans once Agassi was done blowing air kisses in
the general direction of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I needed to do,'' said Agassi, still not convinced
he has a lock on a berth in the final. ``If we could phone in the
results of the highest seed left _ but you can't, you've got to go
out there and play. And win.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, seeded seventh and trying hard to fulfill her
father Richard's prognostications about an all-Williams final,
repaired the damage she did herself with 27 unforced errors in the
opening set by scrambling into a 4-6, 6-2, 7-5 comeback against
16-year-old Kim Clijsters of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Though an Open neophyte, the 98th-ranked Clijsters was not
intimidated by Williams, and it showed. In the final set, their
match was choreographed like a ``West Side Story'' rumble: Williams
mimicked a machete with her racquet after breaking Clijsters'
serve, who slipped, fell and did the splits on the baseline, to
trail by 3-4. Then Clijsters performed a Connorsesque pump-and-roar
maneuver after breaking back with an overhead for a 5-3 lead and a
chance to serve for the upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relates a lot to my mental toughness,'' said the
17-year-old Williams, who responded to the overhead with a 14-point
rampage to win the match. ``That's when my determination really
kicked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Capriati, who validated her phenom label by capturing
a gold medal at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona, Spain, the
Open's defending champion, Lindsay Davenport, a gold medal Olympian
in Atlanta in 1996, reached the Round of 16 with a 6-1, 6-1
demolition of Amy Frazier. Davenport's next opponent, ninth-seeded
Julie Halard-Decugis of France, beat her three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Davenport, still disinclined to do any
celebrating at this Open until she replicates last year's
breakthrough title, Capriati reacted to her third-round success
with uninhibited glee. She has already met her imperative of
improving on three straight first-round losses in the 1996-98 Open.
</P>
<P>
   First Capriati whacked a ball into the stands and accepted a
well-rehearsed ``Well done,'' from Tauziat, a player Capriati has
beaten in all four meetings. Then she waved and blew kisses to her
cheering fans. She was once fearful that her off-court exploits,
including a court-ordered stint in drug rehabilitation that
convinced her she had more in common with tennis phenoms than
substance abusers, would ostracize her supporters. But Capriati
realized in the past year that it was time to return the public
embrace she has received throughout her comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really scared me,'' Capriati said about the years when she
doubted her ability to re-create herself as a contender. ``I just
thought, `God, what if this is it?' Then I just thought: `How
ridiculous. I mean, why not? You have the power in you. Just to do
it if you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there was no better place to solidify her comeback than this
Open. It was in this tournament that she quit tennis after an
opening-round loss in 1993 but in which, as a 15-year-old
semifinalist in 1991, she played and lost the finest match of her
career, a 6-3, 3-6, 7-6(7-3) slugfest against Monica Seles, her
potential fourth-round opponent. For years that defeat gave
Capriati nightmares, but lately it became a reminder of a place she
would like to revisit.
</P>
<P>
   After falling in and out of comebacks, Capriati earlier this
year _ on the verge of turning 23, which is middle age in her
profession _ decided to take her job and herself seriously. She
hired Harold Solomon, a practice courts drill sergeant, to whittle
down her physique and add some strategy to her backcourt repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick of losing, sick of not reaching my full potential
that I think I can reach still,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With Solomon in her corner, and with Tauziat as her quarterfinal
punching bag, Capriati slogged through the draw of her French Open
tune-up at Strasbourg and won her first title in six years. Her
fourth-round exit at Roland Garros was her best progress in a Grand
Slam tournament since her quarterfinal finish at Wimbledon in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Now ranked 40th, Capriati is far from complacent about her place
in the pecking order. After finishing 1991 ranked a career-best
sixth in the world, Capriati, no longer the ``goofy'' teen-ager who
wilted when asked to inherit Chris Evert's mantle as the darling of
American tennis, wants to make her mark on her profession as an
adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very gifted and she kind of forgot that,'' said Solomon,
who used tapes of the Barcelona Olympics to remind Capriati of her
gifts. ``This whole thing has been self-inspired. She finally said,
`I have to do this.' She took a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in a match she said she probably would have squandered
a year ago and in which her attention took a second-set hiatus,
Capriati retrieved her concentration and treated the net-charging
Tauziat like a convenient target in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more determined just to fight back, not give up, and
regroup, just get it back,'' Capriati said. ``Maybe before I didn't
have the confidence to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with her opponent eliminated, her fans rewarded, and the
news media admonished that she would like to stop rehashing her
imperfect past, Capriati made her exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so hungry I can't think,'' she said, and headed to the
lunchroom to correct that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
