u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-KICKER-BOS     09-04 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-KICKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTEBERRY LEFT KICKING HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they filed numbly into the visitors' _ and losers' _ locker
room at Alumni Stadium Saturday, Baylor coach Kevin Steele put his
arm around Kyle Atteberry. The Bears kicker figured he was a prime
candidate for strangulation at that point, and he wasn't about to
launch a self-defense. His shanked extra point in overtime had just
saddled Steele with a 30-29 loss to Boston College in his Baylor
debut, and Atteberry was intent on hogging the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a routine kick, to be honest with you,'' he recalled
mournfully. ``I should get axed for something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   So he was surprised to discover that instead of vengeance,
Steele was offering a valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you,'' he told Atteberry.
</P>
<P>
   A deeply religious sort, Atteberry was relieved to discover that
his coach could forgive the sinner while condemning the sin. Even
more heartening, his teammates turned his misfortune into a revival
meeting of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them came up to encourage me,'' he said. ``We're a
close-knit team.''
</P>
<P>
   They're a losing team, too, as their 2-9 records the past two
seasons prolaim. And they missed a golden opportunity for
redemption largely because Atteberry experienced a kicker's day
from hell _ a blocked extra point in the second quarter after
Baylor seemingly had seized the momentum, a blocked punt in the
third quarter that set up BC's tying touchdown, and the overtime
horror show when he barely got the would-be tying kick off the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ours,'' said a conciliatory Steele. ``And he's one of the
best and we'll take him any time.''
</P>
<P>
   BC took advantage of him this time. After McKinley Bowie's
83-yard interception return for a touchdown late in the second
quarter, Atteberry stepped to the 10-yard line, poised to build the
Baylor lead to 17-7. Not so fast. The Bears were penalized for
excessive celebrating because a player ran onto the field after the
TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had so little to celebrate that I'll take that one,''
said Steele. ``I won't take the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Atteberry now had to take his extra-point
kick from field goal distance _ 35 yards away. And Eagles defensive
tackle Chris Hovan broke through the Baylor wall to knock it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good snap and a good hold,'' said Atteberry. ``I hit
it good. He must have gotten it just as it was leaving the turf.''
</P>
<P>
   BC got him again with Baylor nursing a 16-10 lead midway through
the third quarter. Punting from his 11, Atteberry watched onrushing
Eagles defensive back Ralph Parent swat the ball sky high, and it
wound up on the Bears' 4, where another BC defensive back, Doug
Bessette, recovered. That set up Cedric Washington's tying TD burst
on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to come through clean and you know it,''
Atteberry said, ``you take just one step and kick it. I stayed with
my normal routine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steele didn't hold him culpable for those botches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a kick blocked,'' said the coach, ``there's
obviously a breakdown in coverage. We got soft in protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no doubting the culprit on the climactic calamity.
Perhaps Atteberry wasn't familiar with the assignment _ kicking a
routine extra point _ because after another penalty following
Baylor's go-ahead TD, he'd been forced to attempt the conversion
from an extra 5 yards back, which he did successfully. Perhaps he
was unfamiliar with the holder _ Ryan Chapdelaine, who was pressed
into service because the regular in that role, quarterback Jermaine
Alfred, had been ``dinged,'' according to Steele, while sneaking in
for the TD.
</P>
<P>
   But no, Atteberry wasn't going to invoke any alibis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practice with both holders,'' he said. ``And the snap was
perfect. The hold was perfect. I just mis-hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sideline, Steele couldn't believe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you miss wide right or wide left,'' he said. ``This
one looked like it had no intention of going through.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Atteberry had no intention of ducking the flak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the pressure,'' he said. ``It's a neat situation. A
lot of guys would crawl into a corner and never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Atteberry intend to do?
</P>
<P>
   He looked his questioner square in the eye and said, ``I'll be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   And his coach gladly will let him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
