</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-TRAININGCAMPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS GETTING WHAT THEY BARGAINED FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Training camps opened throughout the National Hockey League this
weekend and there were plenty of name players _ unsigned free
agents and one disgruntled and misguided soul in Ottawa who does
have a contract _ not in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long list _ including Boston's No. 1 goalie Byron Dafoe,
defenseman Hal Gill, and left wing P.J. Axelsson _ and suffice to
say, it's bound to become an annual event, so get used to it. You
want to argue wrong or right? It isn't as difficult a situation to
assess as you might think.
</P>
<P>
   One factor often distorted is that both the Players Association
and the league signed the collective bargaining agreement. It's not
a one-sided document. There was no coercion, no collusion, no
sleight of hand, no fraud. Both sides read it and agreed to sign.
So why now are teams being vilified by players and agents for
utilizing a tool the players agreed they could have?
</P>
<P>
   It's mind-boggling, but predictable. In the midst of
skyrocketing player salaries, teams are finally realizing they have
a tool, one they've had all along but have been ignoring. After a
couple of years of lulling players into a false sense of security
(``Hey, he's a good kid, let's give him the money''), clubs now are
making the most of their power under the collective bargaining
agreement, and it's driving players and their agents crazy. Which
is somewhat understandable. Players have had the upper hand for
several years. A half-dozen years ago, Islanders general manager
Mike Milbury, then the assistant GM in Boston, was saying there was
no one to feel sorry for anymore because there was so much money.
It wasn't all that long ago _ OK, it's been a while _ that players
had to get summer jobs to help make ends meet. It certainly wasn't
that long ago when players regarded $500,000 as a lot of money. Not
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Things are vastly out of whack, and owners faced with
increasingly higher operating costs and a smaller profit share are
saying they now expect to take advantage of the CBA. The exception
is the Rangers. Then again, it's nearly always the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   There was a report out of Calgary that indicated the weekly
conference call among general managers Aug. 27 was a rallying cry
to hang in there in the face of rising salary demands among Group 2
(restricted) free agents. Bruins president/general manager Harry
Sinden said that wasn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody tells us that,'' said Sinden. ``We have a conference
call every Friday, but the league never advises the clubs in the
relationship with players. They often tell us the numbers, we share
information, but we'd never do that. There's always a caution about
your budget, you all have budgets, there's always a caution about
exceeding it, but everyone is free to make up their own minds. Many
people go way over their budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if teams were now, finally, starting to use the CBA
as the tool for which it was intended, Sinden said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was negotiated with the players and they agreed with it,''
he said. ``They should use it for the reasons it was negotiated. If
you have certain rights and you failed to exercise them in the
past, you should use it now. You never, ever have one situation
with a player in which the team doesn't live up to the collective
bargaining agreement that you're not called on. You're called on it
right away. You couldn't get by with five cents. The teams have
been reluctant to take the same position with the players. I think
more and more, they're saying `This is a contract with the
players,' and we have every right to do what it says in there. I
think teams, having tried a lot of other things that didn't work,
are coming around to this.''
</P>
<P>
   It says here that Dafoe deserves a great raise for his stellar
work in goal for the Bruins. That's indisputable. But before
everyone piles on Bruins management for failing to sign him at the
start of training camp, keep in mind that the club is exercising
its rights under the CBA and that Dafoe had the option of
arbitration, which he decided to forgo in order to keep the holdout
option alive.
</P>
<P>
   Take sides if you must, but remember, both sides are right here.
And both sides are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In holding pattern
</P>
<P>
   Another player who has yet to reach contract terms is Edmonton
standout Mike Grier. Grier was a bargain last season at $400,000
Canadian. This season, he's reportedly asking for
$800,000-$900,000. That's certainly not ridiculous for the 20-goal
season he had but it is a big bump from a year ago . . . Patrik
Stefan, the No. 1 overall pick in the June draft, did come to terms
with the Atlanta Thrashers late in the week. The 18-year-old center
will be paid the rookie salary cap maximum of $1.025 million base
salary for three years. That was a given. The stumbling block is
the bonus structure. Neither the team nor the player's agent, Steve
Kotlowitz, revealed details of the bonuses but they are said to be
in line with those of Tampa Bay's Vincent Lecavalier, who can earn
$3 million a year or $8 million total in bonuses over the three
years. Atlanta GM Don Waddell made comments similar to Sinden's
after Joe Thornton agreed to terms two years ago, saying the
measure of Stefan will be in the long haul. ``We're not too
concerned with Patrik Stefan this year or next year,'' Waddell
said. ``We want to bring him along right. I'm more concerned with
where he is four or five years from now.'' . . . The Vancouver
Canucks re-signed forward Todd Bertuzzi to a two-year deal said to
be worth a little more than $1 million per season. Bertuzzi had a
nightmarish season last year, missing 31 games with a broken leg
and then tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee on
March 5, an injury that caused him to sit out the remaining 19
games. Bertuzzi, regarded as a huge disappointment early in his
career with the Islanders, has shown signs with the Canucks of
being the kind of force expected of him when he was taken 23d
overall in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Is all not forgiven?
</P>
<P>
   It has been a big mystery why former Coach of the Year Ted
Nolan, who won the Jack Adams Trophy in 1997 with the Sabres, has
been out of work so long. Robin Burns, cousin and agent of Bruins
coach Pat Burns and Nolan's former representative, offered some
interesting insight into the situation late last week. It was
widely believed that Nolan had been blackballed despite an offer
from the Lightning two years ago. Burns said that, during his two
years behind the Sabres bench, Nolan made many enemies in positions
of power. The other point Burns made was that after Nolan walked
away from a one-year $500,000 extension with Buffalo, he committed
a ``catastrophic error'' in turning down a $2.2 million, four-year
offer from Tampa Bay some four months later. ``I thought it was a
very fair offer and suggested he take it,'' Burns said. ``When he
said, `No,' I was floored.'' Nolan also turned down an assistant
coaching position with the Islanders and though he was interviewed
briefly by the Kings, he was not offered the head-coaching job that
eventually went to Andy Murray. There have been reports that
Rangers coach John Muckler, former Sabres general manager, is
behind some of the negative perception of Nolan. Nolan denies he
was trying to angle for Muckler's job. ``I never did anything
wrong, I don't think,'' said Nolan. Burns came to the conclusion
that Nolan perhaps miscalculated his worth. ``The problem is, if
you say no in the NHL too many times, they stop asking,'' Burns
said. ``I think a lot of people are wondering, `What does this guy
want?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Skate on the other foot
</P>
<P>
   As expected, former NHL superstar Mario Lemieux took over
ownership of the Pittsburgh Penguins after US Bankruptcy Court
Judge Bernard Markovitz approved the $85 million purchase Friday
morning. Lemieux gave up $7.5 million in deferred salary the
Penguins owed him in order to make the deal work. He had been owed
$32.5 million by the former owners and previously agreed to put $20
million into the team. It will be fascinating to see how Lemieux
deals with contracts. He forfeited more money to make this deal
work than some players will ever see in a lifetime . . . The Flyers
took a great many lumps last season for their underachieving
finish. Part of the reason for that disappointing playoff showing
is becoming more clear now. Left wing John LeClair, who suffered
from lower back problems late in the year, doesn't seem to have
received much relief. Now the club is saying LeClair could miss all
or most of training camp. That has to come as a huge disappointment
for Philadelphia's front office _ which weathered the frightening
saga of star Eric Lindros's collapsed lung last spring. If there's
any good news, LeClair's problem appears to be muscular rather than
disk-related . . . As expected, good guy Doug Risebrough has been
named Minnesota Wild executive vice president/general manager.
Risebrough won four Stanley Cups as a Canadien from 1976-79. He was
vice president of hockey operations with the Oilers for the past
three seasons . . . The Senators signed 35-year-old forward Kevin
Dineen to a one-year-plus-an-option contract worth $450,000 this
year and $550,000 next. Dineen won't be a replacement for
malcontent Alexei Yashin but he can certainly add character and
grit that was missing last year as Ottawa went up in flames during
the first round of the playoffs. ``He brings a lot of leadership to
our club,'' said coach Jacques Martin. ``He's an individual who's
been around. He brings some intensity and some fire to the game. He
can spark a team and he's well-respected.'' Reportedly, the
Senators remain interested in defenseman Steve Duchesne . . . There
appears to be little or no progress on the Yashin front. Yashin,
the Ottawa star who thinks he's a free agent but actually has a
full year remaining on his contract, is threatening to head to
Europe to play rather than honor the final year of his deal valued
at $3.6 million. Our suggestion? Go right back to Russia and pump
gas. Maybe that would trigger some perspective. Good riddance . . .
The Lightning have invited 13-year NHL defenseman Zarley Zalapski
to camp on a tryout basis. Last year, he was rehabbing a balky knee
and playing in Europe . . . Speaking of the Lightning, former
coach/GM Jacques Demers will return to Montreal to work as a TV and
radio analyst. Demers coached the Habs from 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling their Oates
</P>
<P>
   Center Adam Oates, who was a prolific scorer during his tenure
in Boston, has been named captain of the Washington Capitals. It's
kind of ironic, isn't it? Oates was vocal to the point of stunning
during the Bruins' stop in Denver in February 1997, getting
stripped of his alternate captain's ``A'' after his outburst.
Oates's frustration at the state of the Bruins _ shared by many _
led to his being dealt to the Capitals on March 1, 1997. Now he's
the spokesman for the team, taking the place of retired forward
Dale Hunter, who didn't say boo his entire career. Hunter preferred
to let his playing do the talking. Oates, a very intelligent man,
isn't shy about offering opinions . . . The Maple Leafs say they'll
move No. 1 center Mats Sundin to left wing for much of the
preseason in an effort to take some of the workload off him and
utilize his substantial skills. It's an experiment worth trying
even if it lasts only a few games . . . This will mark Burns's
third year behind the Bruins' bench. Last year was fascinating.
This year promises to be much more so. Stay tuned . . . 26 days to
opening night. With all due respect to legendary goalie Gerry
Cheevers, here's hoping it's not him in the net when Boston kicks
things off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
