<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESSIVE APPROACH COULD MOVE PATRIOTS OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have all heard of political football, but this is getting
ridiculous. When, exactly, did leading an NFL offense become akin
to leading a conservative think tank? Next thing you know, you'll
be reading quotes from offensive coordinators named Newt Gingrich
and Orrin Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have heard people complain about parity in the NFL.
Parity is not an issue. In fact, it's a myth when you're talking
about players. The problem is that many pro coaches and their
offensive coordinators think alike. It's as if they gather at the
same Cliche Trough and decide what they are going to say _ and run
_ on autumn afternoons. So they run on first and second downs, pass
on third, punt on fourth, and then explain it all by saying,
literally, ``It was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots decide to follow that conservative philosophy
this season, it is only because they want to. The scant offense
they showed during the exhibition season will still be good enough
to win eight games by itself. But the offense they have stored in
the pantry could easily increase that total to 10 or 11.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this about the NFL: It is a league designed for
quarterbacks. History shows that if you've got a quarterback who
can complete a high percentage of passes, you're going to win more
than you lose. And you might even win the Super Bowl. Out of the
top 10 single-season pass-percentage QBs in league history, nine
led teams with winning records. Three made it to the Super Bowl.
One _ Wade Wilson of the '92 Falcons _ directed a losing team.
</P>
<P>
   As I write this, I can hear someone yelping, ``Defense wins
championships.'' Is that you, Clarence Thomas? Show me a great
defense that has supposedly won a Super Bowl, and I'll counter with
Mercury Morris/Larry Csonka ('72 Dolphins), Terry Bradshaw/Lynn
Swann/Franco Harris ('78 Steelers), Walter Payton and his entire
offensive line ('85 Bears), Phil Simms and his line ('86 Giants),
Joe Montana/Jerry Rice ('89 49ers), and John Elway/Terrell Davis
('98 Broncos).
</P>
<P>
   Now, think of the Patriots. You have heard enough of what they
cannot do, but think of what they can do. If I were making a film
about two of my favorite offenses of all time _ the 1980 and '81
San Diego Chargers _ I would hire the Patriots to play the leading
roles. Drew Bledsoe would star as Hall of Famer Dan Fouts, who
threw for 4,802 yards in '81. Ben Coates would play Hall of Fame
tight end Kellen Winslow. Terry Glenn would be Wes Chandler, and
nine-year veteran Shawn Jefferson would have to play a younger
version of legendary receiver Charlie Joiner. There wasn't anyone
like Michael Bishop on the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings me back to the NFL, where the Wing formation has
evolved into right-wingers disguised as coordinators. Maybe Pete
Carroll and Ernie Zampese don't want to tip off the Jets by saying
it, but I am sure they have a role in their offense for the dynamic
Bishop. They have to. Bill Belichick may be a great defensive
coordinator, but imagine what he would tell the Jets in the
following scenario:
</P>
<P>
   It is third and 3. The Patriots are in a shotgun formation, with
Kevin Faulk to Bledsoe's left and Bishop to his right. Will there
be a snap to Bledsoe? Or will there be a direct snap to Bishop, who
has the option of throwing for a first down or running for one?
Maybe Bishop goes from the backfield to the slot. Maybe Faulk goes
in motion, leaving a dangerous Bledsoe-Bishop backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Stumped? Well, I'll tell you what Belichick might tell his
players. He would tell them that blitzing is not an option. He'd
also tell them to pray.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that teams have a hard enough time stopping
Bledsoe, Coates, and Glenn. Put Bishop on the field with all of
them, and you'd have chaos. This would be the natural thing to do
if you were simply picking the most talented players and putting
them in the game. That happens when you are playing sandlot
football. That happens in college, when players who were
linebackers in high school learn to be fullbacks or tight ends,
simply because they want to play. It rarely happens in the NFL. The
Patriots could make themselves indefensible in certain situations
if they did it with Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone can see the Patriots' offense is geared toward passing.
Why frustrate yourself trying to establish an average run game when
you could be passing better than any team in your division, if not
conference? If that sounds like a wild exaggeration, look at the
Patriots' top four receivers and compare them with the Jets', minus
the injured Wayne Chrebet: Glenn, Jefferson, Troy Brown, and Tony
Simmons vs. Keyshawn Johnson, Quinn Early, Dedric Ward, and Dwight
``Hands Of'' Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Asking this team of Patriots to win the Super Bowl is probably
not realistic. But there is no reason they can't win 10 games. No
team in the division is superior, and the only AFC team that should
frighten anyone is Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots should do is pass. They should utilize Bishop.
They should become the '80 Chargers (1-3-1 preseason, 11-5 regular
season). They should remember that this is football and that the
acronym of their league is NFL, not GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
