<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     09-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ JOINS ELITE BOSTON CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's a pretty impressive group, this private club that
includes Cy Young, Babe Ruth, Smoky Joe Wood, Lefty Grove, Jim
Lonborg, Luis Tiant, Dennis Eckersley, and Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above had at least one 20-win season for the Boston
Red Sox, and Saturday at dangerous Safeco Field, Pedro Martinez
earned lodge membership with eight innings of two-hit, 15-strikeout
pitching in a 4-0 victory over the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez becomes the first 20-game winner in the majors this
season and Boston's first since Clemens turned the trick way back
in 1990. It's Pedro's first 20-win season, which means the Martinez
brothers join the Perrys and Niekros as brother combos with 20-win
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was jubilant when he greeted his teammates in the
clubhouse immediately after the game. He could be heard shouting,
``I did it, I did it.'' Later, when he met with the media, he put a
little perspective on the accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really a big deal, but it's the level every pitcher
dreams about,'' he said. ``To me, it's something I will always
remember. I pretty much had the hint that I could get there. After
a couple of years in Montreal, I realized I could get 20 wins. Up
there, I just never had the support, the experience, or the
breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no stopping the Pedro Train in 1999. He was 11-1
by June 4 and 15-3 when he earned the MVP award at the All-Star
Game. He missed three starts with shoulder woes, then got himself
in the blender when his manager benched him for tardiness. But
everything appears back on course, and Friday night at Yankee
Stadium, Pedro will take the mound with a record of 20-4 and an ERA
of 2.26. He has 257 strikeouts and only 34 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that folks in the Dodger organization (Tommy Lasorda in
particular) gave up on him in 1993, fearing that he was too slight
(5 feet 11 inches, 170 pounds) to pitch more than five innings,
Pedro smiled and said, ``Not to mention any names, but they didn't
know anything about baseball. Pick up the newspaper tomorrow and
read that I got 20 wins, and I went more than five innings in all
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday he had to do it without K-cards, Dominican flags, or
Spanish-speaking reporters from the Globe _ and against a lineup
that includes Ken Griffey, Alex Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez, and Jay
Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro was at the ballpark well ahead of Jimy Williams's
deadline. He spent a few moments watching the Boston College
football game on the clubhouse television and said he had visited
with some of the BC players last week. Down the hallway, in the
home locker room, Buhner walked past the lineup card and screeched,
``Oh my god, I am in there!''
</P>
<P>
   Prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the game, Buhner was 0 for 5, all strikeouts, against
Martinez. The streak now stands at 0 for 8, all whiffs. Buhner was
one of four Mariners who fanned in the first two innings, then he
struck out on a 95-mile-per-hour fastball to end the fourth, and
was caught looking in the seventh. Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle starter Paul Abbott was perfect through four but the Sox
broke it open with three runs in the fifth and Pedro knew what to
do to nail down the Magic No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough,'' said Seattle manager Lou Piniella. ``He gets
ahead of you and stays ahead of you. He gets every pitch over the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez seemed possessed. We know he pitches better when he's
angry or inspired, and maybe he got a shot of adrenaline from the
news that brother Ramon had been scratched from the rotation after
one brief outing.
</P>
<P>
   He punched out the side in the seventh, ending the inning with a
95-m.p.h. heater to an overmatched Tom Lampkin. It was 1-2-3 again
in the eighth. His final victim (pitch No. 128) was poor Brian
Hunter, who spent the entire day at the plate looking like a kid
facing a polio vaccine shot, desperately trying not to strike out.
Martinez retired the final 11 batters he faced before yielding to
David Crosby, er, Rod Beck, who struggled through the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Did Martinez want to come out for the ninth?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that,'' he said. ``I don't know pitch limits. I just
have a game to win. I know they are concerned about me down the
stretch, but I felt getting the win was more important than to go
over any limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more positive about our team than ever. We're playing
solid baseball. The playoffs are not here yet, but if we're in the
playoffs, I'll go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he is a Red Sox 20-game winner, just like Young
(21-15) in 1907, Ruth (23-12) in 1916, and Bill Monbouquette
(20-10) in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen, who first accomplished the feat for Kansas City
in 1985 when he was 21 years old, said, ``It's always sweet,
especially the first one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
