<HEADLINE>
AGASSI LOOMS LARGE ABOVE THE REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The metallic cloud with a motor hovered somewhere
above Arthur Ashe Stadium. The sun may or may not shine on the US
Open, but that cloud is omnipresent. It is called the Fuji blimp _
a floating camera position for a bird's-eye TV shot _ and it was
getting on Justin Gimelstob's nerves.
</P>
<P>
   With a blobby airship in his line of vision as he tossed the
ball up to serve, and the gleaming scalp of scalp-hunting Andre
Agassi on the other side of the net, 22-year-old Gimelstob had a
couple of serious reasons to be frazzled. He may have felt like
Mick Jagger warbling, ``Hey, you, get offa my cloud!'' But of
course he couldn't ``get no satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin tried anyway. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get that blimp outa here!'' he demanded of umpire Steve
Ullrich. Ullrich has heard a lot of complaints from distraught
performers, but the request to reroute a blimp from Flushing Meadow
was a first. Since he had no pull with an aerial tow truck, or the
TV networks employing the blimp, Ullrich merely nodded
sympathetically and indicated that Gimelstob, an All-America from
UCLA, should get on with it.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't too easy because Agassi, the heir apparent to
1997-98 champion Patrick Rafter, is no zinc zeppelin. This is a
year in which he is ballooning large on the scene, reaching for his
second major and the No. 1 ranking that injured Pete Sampras will
lose after six years as the caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are maybe two people in New York who can order a blimp
to move and have it happen,'' Agassi was smiling Saturday after his
6-1, 4-6, 6-3, 6-4 victory had elevated him to the fourth round.
``And Justin isn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during the third set that Gimelstob issued his stressed
plea for the umpire to roust, or at least ticket, the dawdling
blimp, parked overtime. He was still in the match then, but needed
all the help he could get. Agassi was behaving like the German
dirigibles that bombed London in World War I. After a second-set
lull, he started exploding again and no longer looked so small
opposite the huge-serving, 6-foot-5-inch Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sampras called in sick with an aching back and Rafter
begged off with a cranky shoulder, this US Open has been Agassi's
to lose. They were going to play it out through Sept. 12 because
that's customary, but how could anybody doubt that Agassi would be
in the winner's circle accepting the trophy from US Tennis
Association president Julia Levering?
</P>
<P>
   Because he looked so good in pulverizing Swedish Davis Cupper
Nicklas Kulti in the first round (6-0, 6-1, 6-3), it was suggested
by some that Levering hand Agassi the prize then, asking only that
he go through the formalities of playing the remaining six matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Open was falling apart around him, the Meadow beginning to
resemble an emergency room. Six of the 1998 quarterfinalists were
gone. Semifinalist Carlos Moya, perhaps catching back pain from
Sampras, said, ``Adios.'' Finalist Mark Philippoussis's gimpy knee
cried, ``Uncle.'' Tom Johansson came down with a heart ailment, and
Karol Kucera was wounded here and there. Of the last eight of '98,
only Magnus Larsson and Jonas Bjorkman ventured past this year's
first round, and Bjorkman got the hook Saturday, courtesy of
Yevgeny Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   After he won, Kafelnikov said that only three possible winners
remain: himself, Richard Krajicek, and, of course, Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi hates to hear that kind of talk. Anybody who concedes him
``or anybody else this championship doesn't know anything about
tennis _ or sports,'' he said. ``You can't mail it in. I feel I'm
getting better with every match, but there are people here who can
beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those is No. 46 Vince Spadea. Agassi is keenly and
painfully aware of what happened at the Australian Open, which also
appeared wired for him. Until the fourth round, where Spadea
intervened. He had labeled Spadea ``just a journeyman'' _ and Vince
sent him on an abrupt journey home. Agassi won't make that mistake
again. Spadea, a peppery Floridian, is still around but only after
surviving a tense five-set duel with Italian Laurence Tieleman with
a backhand passer on the last point of the decisive tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Another who can challenge Agassi is his next foe, the zippy
little Frenchman, No. 52 Arnaud Clement, a semifinalist at the US
Pro eight days ago at Longwood. ``I remember Clement, all right,''
said Agassi, rolling his eyes at the memory. Clement came within
two points of beating him in a second-round match in Paris, early
sabotaging that glorious ascent to the French Open title.
</P>
<P>
   Curioser and curioser this Open becomes, at least in the male
precinct, where the lineup _ other than the three guys owning major
titles, Agassi, Kafelnikov, Krajicek _ seems as recognizable as a
roll call at a Foreign Legion camp. Who are these people?
</P>
<P>
   ``All professionals, all dangerous guys,'' insisted Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   He has to keep himself in that frame of mind. But it's Andre's
to lose, and the only way he will is if the blimp falls on him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
