<HEADLINE>
TO CLUB PROS, CUP RICHNESS ISN'T MONETARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about every 30 years or so, it seems those who play golf
for a living become restless. The PGA of America was once the sole
governing body of men's golf, but the guys who played for pay grew
restless under it. The result was a breakup in 1968 into two
organizations. The PGA of America, with nearly 25,000 members and
apprentices, represents the grassroots of the game. What became the
PGA Tour represents those who now play for big money.
</P>
<P>
   During the breakup, the pros were waiting for Arnold Palmer's
move. His father, Deacon, was a club pro and had taught him the
game, so what would Arnie do? After piloting his plane into
Worcester Airport on the eve of the Kemper Open that summer, Palmer
said he was siding with the play-for-pay guys. The split was now
the split.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to 1999, when the PGA Tour guys want to share the
Ryder Cup wealth, either through their bank books or designated
charities.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that David Duval is one of those who
has proposed that players get access to a sizable chunk of the
receipts that the PGA of America reaps and largely pours back into
the development of the game. Wasn't his father, Bob, a PGA of
America pro until he struck it big this year on the PGA Senior
Tour? Davis Love is also the son of a PGA of America pro, and he
has stood by the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The New England PGA, an organization of 711 members, recently
completed its sectional championship at Winchester CC and Kernwood
CC. These were the guys (and one woman) who have largely been
confined to their pro shops or the lesson tee, with little chance
to play. The New England Open is later this month (Sept. 15-17) at
The Woodlands and Portland CC in Maine; 167 pros and 10 amateurs
are already in the field. It is the second phase of their fall
festival, a fun time and a reunion for most.
</P>
<P>
   So these players could sit around and survey the
share-the-wealth approach to an event that drew only a few of the
curious when the Europeans joined the fray in 1979 at the
Greenbrier in White Sulphur Springs, W.Va. ``There were no
spectators,'' said a reporter friend who covered that Ryder Cup for
the Richmond Times Dispatch. ``You could just walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have certainly changed. There were 30,000 tickets sold for
the 33d Ryder Cup (Sept. 24-26) at The Country Club. The income
generated is expected to be $63 million, with the PGA of America
realizing a profit of about $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The club pros look at the situation with some bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing for your country is worth more than anything, and just
to be selected has no dollar value,'' said Paul Parajeckas of
Woburn, who has twice won the Wogan Award as the NEPGA's top
player. ``I'm from the old school. With everyone going on in life,
things have to change, but our association supports the Ryder Cup.
I think once that flag goes up, it doesn't matter what you're paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does all the money go? No. 1 is PGA charities. To me it
doesn't matter, as long as you're always helping someone out. If
someone is getting better because of the money the PGA of America
is giving out, if you help one individual for life or to further a
life, that means a lot. I always feel the Ryder Cup should be for
charity, and I feel as a player it should be an honor to be on the
team and money should not be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to see the caddies be treated the same as
the players. They're part of the team. They should get expenses.
It's the greatest thing to ever hit New England, and the flag is
more important than anything else when it comes to competition
between countries. They should recognize what the PGA of America
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Carr of Bedrock GC, who played on the PGA Tour and continues
to play in European Senior Tour events, said, ``I feel, in this
case, the players are wrong. I've heard these guys wanted the money
for themselves when they first started. They never have to go in
their pocket. They get wined and dined. They get their families
brought in. I just think the guys are out of line asking to get
paid. The PGA used to foot the bill and nobody was making any
money. Greed's an awful thing, but what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Senior circuit beckons
</P>
<P>
   Mike San Filippo's magical 9-iron second shot to within 3 feet
on the 18th hole earned him his second NEPGA Championship Thursday,
nine years after he won at Ocean Edge. ``I think I'm a better
player now than I was then,'' said San Filippo, 46, who has been a
teaching pro at Nashawtuc CC the past two summers before heading to
Florida, where he has been a dominant player on the PGA club pro
circuit. Is the PGA Senior Tour in his future? ``I don't know,''
said San Filippo. ``It depends on what I'm doing. I'm not going to
quit practicing. I still have three years. That's a long time, and
I'm in no hurry. It's nice that it's out there, but it depends on
how I feel and what I'm doing in a few years.'' The success of
players such as Dana Quigley of Barrington, R.I., and Allen Doyle
of Norwood makes it more tempting. ``We all know how they've been
doing,'' said San Filippo, ``and I have a feeling I'll give it a
go. It depends on a lot of things. It depends on health and my job
situation, but I think if there was an opportunity to go out there,
I'd give it a shot. There've been nine guys who've won for the
first time, so it goes to show you there's a lot of opportunity out
there.'' . . . In 2005, the Ryder Cup will be held in Ireland for
the first time. The announcement was made prior to the matches at
Valderrama two years ago to give Ireland the chance to promote the
event with the official use of the Ryder Cup identity and logo.
There was talk that the matches should set down at one of the
nation's great links courses stretched out from Portmarnock on the
Irish Sea to Ballybunion at the Mouth of the River Shannon. But it
was no great surprise when the man with the money bought them for
the K Club, a parksland course some 17 miles southwest of Dublin
owned and nurtured by Dr. Michael Smurfit, chairman of the Smurfit
Group conglomerate, who brought in Palmer and architectural partner
Ed Seay to create a suitable course for a luxury resort. The K Club
isn't linksland golf, since vast amounts of soil were moved and
lakes were created on the final four holes. It's sufficient for the
Irish to know that, finally, the matches are coming to the republic
. . . The first Cape Cod Senior Open will be contested Sept. 20-21
(Monday and Tuesday of Ryder Cup week) at Cape Cod CC and Hyannis
GC. This is an outgrowth of a suggestion by the venerable Fordie
Pitts, who co-owns Hyannis GC with Joe Keller and has been one of
New England's outstanding amateurs through the past five decades.
``It was his idea,'' said Jim Gaquin, who oversaw the growth of the
Cape Cod Pro-Am league with wife Lois and is helping with plans to
celebrate the league's 50th anniversary next year. The Cape Cod
Senior Open will offer $15,000 in prize money and is open to pros
and amateurs in three age groupings (50-59, 60-69, and 70-plus).
``I think we've got a winner,'' said Gaquin. ``I'd say the
tournament will draw between 100 and 125 players.'' Who knows?
Should the word get around, some Ryder Cup visitors might check in
early for a competitive introduction to New England golf, at a time
when getting access to a local course will be all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Pops to benefit Dad
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy opening day at the Ryder Cup, one way to unwind
Sept. 24 will be at a Boston Pops Ryder Cup concert, a musical
tribute to the game that will salute Palmer's contributions.
Proceeds will benefit the Deacon Palmer Scholarship, a permanently
endowed award distributed by the Francis Ouimet Scholarship Fund.
Tickets for the gala, with John Williams conducting, range from
$250 to $750 . . . The exclusive Carnegie Abbey course on
Narragansett Bay is under construction. The land of rolling hills
was the home of the Narragansett and Wampanoag tribes and site of
the Battle of Rhode Island in 1778 in the American Revolution. The
founder of the parent Carnegie Club, Peter de Savary, has developed
projects at Skibo Castle, Scotland, on the estate of Andrew
Carnegie, Stapleford Park, Leicestershire, England, and Cherokee
Plantation near Charleston, S.C. The course is due for completion
this fall and should be open for play next summer in exclusive and
very private surroundings . . . Parajeckas took note of the
professional manner in which superintendents Dan Higgins of
Winchester CC and the venerable Dean Robertson of Kernwood CC
prepared the courses for the NEPGA. ``These are Tour spec greens
and Tour spec courses,'' said Parajeckas, who oversees the
maintenance of Woburn CC, where he also is head pro. ``A Tour stop
could come in right away. I give credit to the superintendents.
Given the season we've had, with the extreme amount of hot weather,
they've done quite a job. It's been first class. They're the ones
behind the scenes.'' . . . Pairings are set for the NEPGA
Individual Match Play Championship Oct. 5-6 at The Kittansett Club,
in which 16 players tee it up for two full days of competition.
Mike Shoueiry of Bradford CC, who led the NEPGA entering the final
round, earned the No. 1 seed and will meet Mo Guttman of Portland
CC in the first match. Shoueiry, who left his family home in the
surburbs of Beirut so he could pursue university studies in this
country, took up golf at 27 . . . The NEPGA will have 48 members
serving as volunteer marshals at The Country Club's eighth hole for
the Ryder Cup. Is this what they term a necessary evil that goes
with membership in the organization?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
