<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ TAKES 20TH WIN FOR SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The philosophy remains unchanged, from Denton T.
``Cy'' Young, the first to win 20 games for the Olde Towne Team 98
years ago, to the skinny Dominican who Saturday became the Red Sox'
newest 20-game winner. This is what stoppers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important for me to set the tone, to bring the
team back to life,'' Martinez said after he struck out 15, held
Seattle to two hits in eight innings, and combined with Rod Beck to
shut out the Mariners, 4-0, to become Boston's first 20-game winner
since Clemens went 21-6 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't willing to give up anything,'' he said. ``I'll do
anything to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out someone in every inning he pitched, fanned
the side in the seventh, and whiffed each Mariner at least once,
with nine of his last 12 outs coming on strikeouts. Jay Buhner, who
whiffed all three times he faced Martinez, then fanned against Beck
to end the game, has come to bat eight times against Martinez in
two seasons and has whiffed each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're worried about his shoulder?'' said Mariners manager
Lou Piniella, whose team had won five in a row before being shut
out for the seventh time this season, the fourth time in just 29
games at their new playground, Safeco Field. ``Send him over here
to pitch for me, and I'll worry about him.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it isn't as automatic as it looked, said Nomar
Garciaparra, whose leadoff home run in the fifth inning, his second
homer in two games and 20th of the season, jump-started a three-run
rally after the first 12 Sox went down in order against Seattle
starter Paul Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Petey's human,'' said Garciaparra, who had apologized
to Pat Rapp for his own mortality the night before, when his high
throw led to Seattle's first run in a wrenching 2-1 Sox loss. ``We
know he may not have it and that we still have to go out there and
play our game. We can't say, `Guess what, Petey's pitching and we
can sit back.' We've still got to go out there and score some runs.
And for a while there, it didn't look like anybody was going to
score.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was especially happy to get the ball rolling,
considering Friday night's tough loss. ``This game was important
because of the fact that we started our road trip with such an
emotional game, and losing it the way we did,'' said the shortstop.
``We didn't want to lose the next one, so it's a good feeling to
bounce back like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, held to three hits Friday night, doubled that total
Saturday, with five of their hits coming in the fifth inning. Troy
O'Leary singled after Garciaparra's home run and was on the move
when Jason Varitek doubled past first baseman Raul Ibanez to make
it 2-0. Trot Nixon then singled off Ibanez's glove to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Boston added its fourth run in the eighth, when Nixon singled,
stole second, advanced to third on a throwing error by catcher Tom
Lampkin, and scored on Jose Offerman's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit sweet,'' said Martinez, whose locker
contained a bottle of champagne sitting in a tub of ice normally
used to soak tired elbows, ``especially knowing Oakland won last
night. It's up to them to win. We got ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez spoke those words not knowing that the A's had just
pushed across a run in the bottom of the ninth to beat Detroit,
2-1, and remain just a game behind the Sox in an American League
wild-card race that may not end until the season does Oct. 3, four
weeks from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has struck out 15 or more batters five times this
season (Nolan Ryan did it six times in 1974), was dismissed after
the eighth inning, having thrown 128 pitches. That's a total he has
exceeded just four times this season, the last time in an 133-pitch
outing against Tampa Bay just before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days later, after whiffing five batters in two innings in
the All-Star Game, he had the worst outing of his career against
the Florida Marlins and afterward revealed that his shoulder hurt.
So the Sox' precautions were understandable, especially with a
four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, making his second appearance since coming to the Sox in
Tuesday's trade with the Cubs, had no illusions about whether the
Mariners were happy to see Martinez depart. Especially when his
first pitch to Raul Ibanez went no more than 50 feet before
dribbling past catcher Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a spike on my way downhill and screwed up my whole
first hitter, because I worried about grabbing it again,'' said
Beck, who walked Ibanez with Ken Griffey, Alex Rodriguez, and Edgar
Martinez due.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pumped when I first got out there, because I said, `Man,
this is a nice hill,' and I end up screwing up and walking the
first hitter,'' said Beck. ``Fortunately, we had a four-run lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who has done nothing against the Sox this season (.219,
including one infield hit in eight at-bats this series), fouled out
to Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got him with a fastball,'' Beck said. ``Not a Pedro Martinez
fastball, but a Rod Beck fastball. They probably thought it was a
changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck then retired Rodriguez (0 for 8 in the series) on a ground
ball and, after Martinez singled, struck out the beleaguered
Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Beck's neat closing effort, the Mariners couldn't get
Martinez out of their minds. ``He just had one of his days, his
typical days,'' said Mariners third baseman Rafael Bournigal, who
came up with Martinez on the Dodgers and is one of his closest
friends. ``When he's throwing all his pitches like that, he's
almost impossible to hit him. MVP? He definitely should be in that
category. He and Garciaparra have been carrying that team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
