<SLUG> BC-HKN-ONHOCKEY-BRUINSCAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ARE UP FRONT ABOUT CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ Everything hockey begins anew Sunday when all the
Bruins convene here once again, some 52 shooters and booters ready
to divvy up the 20 or so black-and-gold sweaters with the spoked B
on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it began Saturday, with rookies skating, scouts
scribbling, coaches watching, equipment guys unloading, and the
ever-present autograph hounds working the Ristuccia Center parking
lot as if it were the last acre of the '49 Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   A sunny sky. A cold rink. Only the slightest hint of autumn in
the air, summer buckling at the knees as it nears the end of its
scorching three-month shift. In times like these, the Stanley Cup
seems but a mirage. Drop a 9-inch blanket of snow on that tableau,
and call in a 30-mile-per-hour northeast wind, and the dream comes
into much sharper, perhaps harsher focus.
</P>
<P>
   Can these Bruins of 1999-2000 realistically think about winning
the Cup? Assuming that Byron Dafoe gets here soon, yes, they can.
Without Dafoe, it's a decent bunch, but destined to collapse. With
Dafoe, the Bruins easily can win a couple of playoff rounds, would
be a decent bet to win a conference championship, and then it's on
to the finals and hourly updates from the trainers' room. All comes
together easily in one run-on sentence, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe and his dollars will consume far too much newsprint and
air time over the next few days. For now, let's assume he'll be
here soon (i.e. closer to Veterans Day than Labor Day).
</P>
<P>
   That said, if the net's OK, where do the fortunes of the '99-00
Bruins rest? The focus has to be up front, which is always where
the focus is at the back end of the season. It is ultimately up to
the scorers.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of three decades now, we've watched the
Bruins self-destruct in April, May, or June. The rare time they
have appeared to have more than a one-line attack, the second line
has disappeared or the power play has caved. The best of recent
times had Adam Oates setting up Cam Neely, or Craig Janney as
Neely's set-up guy before Oates, but there was never another
twosome that made the Boston offense complete, or at least complex
enough to defeat the likes of the once-mighty Oilers in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   This time around can be different, no matter how impaired the
offense might look now that Dmitri Khristich has been cashiered.
The talk-show callers keep asking about filling the Khristich void.
Who'll get his goals? The newly acquired Dave Andreychuk is part of
that answer, and there are a number of others who'll audition for
that spot on the wing.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get caught up in the patch and spackle of Khristich's
29 goals. The key to Boston's success this season will be the likes
of Jason Allison, Joe Thornton, and Sergei Samsonov, first and
foremost, and to a lesser extent, Anson Carter and _ I can't
believe this is rolling off my fingers _ Landon Wilson. If there is
a Cup to be embraced, the first here since the bell-bottom and
long-sideburn days of 1972, it will be handed over by the arms and
wrists of those four or five forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that most of those guys can be .300 hitters,'' said
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``Now we find out, are
they going to provide more than that? Are we going to see physical
play? Are we going to see strong corner work? Are we going to see
leadership?''
</P>
<P>
   In short, will that group develop en masse, or at least in
substantial part, as complete players? They are just the right age.
All are in their young 20s, precisely where a true contender wants
its core talent _ be it up front, on the blue line, or in net. For
the most part, they've had two full seasons, under the same coach,
wearing the same sweater, learning one another's strengths and
weaknesses, and now is the time for them to shoulder and shape this
team's success.
</P>
<P>
   In back, much the same can be said about Kyle McLaren, about to
enter his fifth season. He turned 22 this summer. This likely will
be Ray Bourque's last sashay. McLaren isn't going to be the
all-purpose Hall of Famer that Bourque has been for two decades,
but he can be the undisputed leader of the blue line for the next
10 years. It's time now, even with Bourque still here, for McLaren
to step forward and truly assert himself. In fact, it will be far
easier for him to do just that with Bourque still in the war room.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when it all fell apart here when the Bruins took up
their new digs on FleetStreet? The model was upside-down. They had
far too many old men wearing younger men's clothes. Some, like
Oates, remained highly valuable and proficient, but there was
virtually no younger cast to work around him and make the Bruins a
true contender. When Oates spoke that obvious truth to the media,
he won himself a trade to Washington. One more messenger shot.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the emphasis has been on the bright future, looking
forward to the day that young, talented players would define the
team and determine its success.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day is here now,'' agreed coach Pat Burns, standing
rinkside, moments before Samsonov was the first of the veterans to
join an informal skate, joined seconds later by Wilson. ``It is _
it's here.''
</P>
<P>
   No more talking about what this team will be. The waiting is
over. It is time for the work in progress to put up, step up, and
play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
