</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-QUARTERBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL MANY TOP QBS IN NFL RANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With John Elway retired, debates about the NFL's best
quarterback don't generate a heated argument anymore. Over the past
three years, Brett Favre always captured most of the votes, anyway,
and he remains the clear-cut choice for the top spot. But after
him, there is debate about how the quarterbacks rank, and there
also is a much-publicized crop of young pups who haven't even
played a regular-season game yet. Here are one reporter's rankings,
excluding the rookies:
</P>
<P>
   1. Brett Favre, Green Bay. Obviously, he has the credentials:
five Pro Bowl selections, two Super Bowl appearances, and an
excitement factor because of his mobility. The Packers have
declined slightly as they've gone through personnel changes, but
Favre, with a lighter frame and a new excitement for the game, may
elevate them again.
</P>
<P>
   2. Steve Young, San Francisco. The precision of this man is
incredible. He's like a throwing machine. He still has mobility,
though the 49ers probably wish he'd stay in the pocket. He also has
the Pro Bowls and Super Bowls to show for a Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drew Bledsoe, New England. In his seventh year, he's got
three Pro Bowls, one Super Bowl appearance, and better statistics
than anyone in history for six years. He settled the
leadership/guts issue last year when he played with the broken
finger and pulled out dramatic victories over AFC East rivals Miami
and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   4. Randall Cunningham, Minnesota. He's got the best receivers in
the game _ Randy Moss, Cris Carter, and Jake Reed _ but part of the
reason they're great is that he throws the ball deep as well as
anyone in the game. The first part of his career was erratic, but
there's no doubt about what he brings to the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   5. Troy Aikman, Dallas. Little by little, his stock drops as he
ages and the team around him erodes. The Cowboys are a star-struck
team, giving most of their money to a few guys while the rest of
the team _ including the receiving corps _ is average. Yet Aikman
is still dangerous and has a glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   6. Doug Flutie, Buffalo. The Flutie bashers will say this is too
high, but we're talking about a guy who has won everywhere he's
been. He is not a one-year wonder. He's a 36-year-old quarterback
who will still have a certain magic about him when he's out there
playing at 44.
</P>
<P>
   7. Mark Brunell, Jacksonville. He is an exciting, fun
quarterback who can run and throw it deep with the best of them.
Unlike Bledsoe, he hasn't gotten his team to the Super Bowl. If he
fails again, the steady buildup of Jacksonville fans who complain
about him so much will continue.
</P>
<P>
   8. Vinny Testaverde, NY Jets. Everyone waits for this guy to
turn into Tony Eason, but he was near-perfect last year, and in
exhibition games this summer, he still was directing the offense
with precision, using his All-Pro receivers deep, short, and
over-the-middle as well as anyone in the league.
</P>
<P>
   9. Dan Marino, Miami. No disrespect intended. He's the best pure
passer there ever was, and there's nobody I'd rather watch direct a
team down the field. The pressure is on Marino this year because he
will likely have a decent running game, a good offensive line, and
_ for the first time since the days of Clayton and Duper _ quality
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   10. Steve McNair, Tennessee. One of these years _ and this may
be the one _ he will be unstoppable. It's hard to find this
combination: strong arm, great runner, and tough.
</P>
<P>
   11. Jake Plummer, Arizona. There's something special about this
guy. He has great field presence, throws well on the run, and has
that Steve Grogan toughness about him.
</P>
<P>
   12. Peyton Manning, Indianapolis. A rookie quarterback hasn't
looked this poised since Bledsoe. The second year may be tougher,
because teams have seen him and scouted him and may understand his
weaknesses. But he also has a nice supporting cast and a team
that's rising.
</P>
<P>
   13. Kordell Stewart, Pittsburgh. Can we call last year an
aberration? After all, why would an offensive coordinator ask
Stewart to stay in the pocket? If he gets back to his old ways and
cuts down his mistakes, he could be very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   14. Chris Chandler, Atlanta. He wins.
</P>
<P>
   15. Jeff George, Minnesota. He has the arm of a No. 1
quarterback, but his head makes him a backup. Too bad, because he
throws a pretty ball and shoulda been a great one.
</P>
<P>
   16. Rob Johnson, Buffalo. Has played enough for everyone to
realize that he's not Doug, but what a future this guy has. He's
big, strong, and can run when he has to.
</P>
<P>
   17. Kerry Collins, NY Giants. We have him rated higher than Kent
Graham, the starter. Collins is one of the few Giant quarterbacks
since Phil Simms who can really throw the football. If he's over
the stupid stuff that got him into trouble in Carolina and New
Orleans, he may do well the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   18. Trent Dilfer, Tampa Bay. The Rodney Dangerfield of the NFL.
This guy gets no respect. He's a former Pro Bowler, and by the
looks of his exhibition performance against the Patriots, he's
capable of getting the ball to some very fast receivers.
</P>
<P>
   19. Brad Johnson, Redskins. He has so much upside if he can get
in a full season. For a tough guy, he is very injury-prone, but he
can move an offense.
</P>
<P>
   20. Jeff Blake, Cincinnati. What happened to this guy? He seemed
to be on his way to multiple Pro Bowls. It looks like he'll be a
decent player somewhere else, because the Bengals are looking to
Akili Smith as the QB of the future.
</P>
<P>
   21. Bubby Brister, Denver. Brian Griese may be better over the
long haul, but we don't know that for sure. Brister has been a good
soldier and won five games for the Broncos last season.
</P>
<P>
   22. Jim Harbaugh, San Diego. Anyone who would spend the year
teaching Ryan Leaf is a saint. Harbaugh used to be a good
quarterback until injuries started to chip away at his
effectiveness. But he's known as Captain Comeback for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   23. Scott Mitchell, Baltimore. Like Blake, another guy whose
brilliant rising career went south. With Brian Billick's help, he
may be perfect for the Raven offense and could jumpstart his
career.
</P>
<P>
   24. Steve Beuerlein, Carolina. A serviceable starter who gets
the Dilfer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   25. Rich Gannon, Oakland. Not bad in spurts, but a full year of
him?
</P>
<P>
   26. Elvis Grbac, Kansas City. He's one hell of a backup
quarterback but he has yet to prove he is special enough to lead a
team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   27. Warren Moon, Kansas City. Moon, on the other side of 40,
still may be better than the guy he backs up. He can still be
exciting and strike with the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   28. Kent Graham, NY Giants. A real pro. He gets the job done
without much fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   29. Neil O'Donnell, Tennessee. If McNair gets hurt, he has the
experience to be a long-term quarterback. He never gets enough
credit for the things he does well.
</P>
<P>
   30. Charlie Batch, Detroit. He'll be heading into a new
dimension without Barry Sanders around. The kid has made a lot of
fans, showing poise beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   Second chance
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders were busting old friend Ferric Collons because he
was a few pounds over his playing weight of 300, and as a result he
incurred a hamstring injury. Then they assigned him to the third
team, and Collons balked, telling his coaches they were wasting his
time. He's now with the second unit on what is a very deep
defensive line. As some Patriot players have wondered, why isn't
Collons still here? Though his salary was going from $575,000 to $2
million, the Patriots could have renegotiated and kept a very good
run stopper . . . Is the era of the two-way player returning?
Linebacker Junior Seau made his debut at tight end Friday, and
defensive end Ebeneezer Ekuban may be used as a short-yardage tight
end by the Cowboys. Add to that Deion Sanders and, likely, Champ
Bailey, Charles Woodson, and R.W McQuarters as guys playing both
sides. The Patriots must evaluate the Ty Law situation. They are
paying him above his market value and he wants to try other
positions. Afraid of injury? Listen, Ted Johnson got hurt reaching
out to make a tackle. You can't be afraid of what the media or the
fans will think if a player gets hurt. If you have great players,
use them, especially in this age of salary cap restrictions when
rosters are thin . . . It would not be shocking to find Damon
Denson on the Patriots' list of final cuts. Denson has been given
every opportunity to showcase himself, but he hasn't taken
advantage. The Patriots played Heath Irwin a lot at both guard
spots in the final exhibition game, and coach Pete Carroll said he
would do that (move Irwin around) in an effort to save a roster
spot. That means they may carry only eight or nine offensive
linemen _ the starters, plus Irwin, Jason Andersen, fifth-round
pick Derrick Fletcher, and possibly Ed Ellis . . . Don't be
surprised to see Jets defensive end Bobby Hamilton wind up with the
Patriots if he's cut. Hamilton played for defensive line coach Ray
Hamilton with the Jets a few years ago . . . The cast on Brandon
Mitchell's right hand is coming off soon, after a procedure on a
finger on his left hand that was largely cosmetic. When Mitchell is
set to go, he'll man the end opposite Willie McGinest . . . When
you win two Super Bowls, your career as a coach is made. You can do
and say anything. But Denver's Mike Shanahan may have done Brister
a great disservice, one that veteran players will note. Brister
bailed the Broncos out of five games that Elway missed with
injuries in 1998, but after a couple of bad exhibition games, he's
out? Griese probably will do very well, because he, like Manning,
has quarterbacking in his blood. He also has a great cast around
him, including the best running back and offensive line in the
business, so Shanahan's move is probably safe. But justified? . . .
The Broncos have another distraction in their camp concerning
linebacker Bill Romanowski, who along with his wife, Julie, and two
others has been accused of prescription fraud in illegally
obtaining an appetite suppressant. Romanowski's attorneys have
denied charges of fraud, conspiracy, and unlawful use of a
controlled substance, but if convicted Romanowski, 33, could face
up to three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He liked Mike
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has loved Michael Bishop from the moment the quarterback
was drafted in the seventh round. In fact, in an interview on Aug.
20, Carroll said, ``I thought we should have drafted him in the
third round. I like this guy. Bobby (Grier) kept telling me, `We'll
have a shot at him. Hang with it.' I love the way this guy plays.
Incredible to me that we could get him. A lot of people paid a lot
of money for some quarterbacks this year and some were drafted way
up high and our guy can give you some problems. I'm excited about
him and he's a terrific draft pick.'' . . . Don't bet the house on
it, but do you think the Patriots are devising some plays for
Bishop? Whether or not they spring them in the opener against the
Jets, they need to get Bishop involved at some point. He's a great
weapon that shouldn't be wasted on the sidelines for 16 weeks . . .
Six more Dolphins were injured in their loss to Green Bay Thursday
night, to go along with running backs J.J. Johnson, Karim
Abdul-Jabbar, and Cecil Collins. Added to the list were safeties
Calvin Jackson (twisted knee), Brock Marion (ligament damage,
hand), Shawn Wooden (broken right thumb), cornerback Pat Surtain
(groin), quarterback Damon Huard (quad), and defensive tackle
Dimitrius Underwood (dislocated shoulder). Underwood is the ironic
one. Jimmy Johnson made a brilliant move to sign him off waivers
after the tug-of-war concerning his future in the ministry or
football got him booted out of Minnesota. Underwood, a good player
at Michigan State who skipped his senior season, has the reputation
of not playing hurt. But after the shoulder dislocation, he piped
up and said, ``I'll put a brace on it and play with it next week.''
Such injuries always lead to questions about whether the regular
season should be expanded to 18 games and the exhibition season
shortened to two. The players would love an 18-game schedule
because it ultimately would mean more money in their paychecks; the
owners wouldn't like it for the same reason. But some owners would
go for an 18/2 arrangement, figuring they've got the same amount of
dates at their home venues. The league would balk because there
aren't as many TV viewers before the kids go back to school.
There's a new theory in NFL circles that injuries are occuring
because of too much training, too much offseason conditioning, too
many two-a-days, and too much practice time . . . The preseason
MVP? Matt Hasselbeck. The former Boston College quarterback, now a
backup in Green Bay, tossed nine touchdown passes in helping the
Packers to a 4-0 record . . . While some assume that the Patriots
will stink based on their 1-3 exhibition record, remember that the
Cowboys were 0-5 last year and won the NFC East . . . The Colts'
Edgerrin James lit it up in preseason: 138 yards on 22 carries . .
. Another BC alum, Glenn Foley, keeps trying to forge a quarterback
controversy in Seattle, where Jon Kitna is the starter. In a 31-28
loss to Indianapolis, all Foley did was complete 19 of 27 passes
for 248 yards and put 19 of the team's 28 points on the board.
``I'm understanding the game plan and understanding what the
coaches want from me,'' said Foley. ``I've been playing this game
for a while and I've got confidence in myself.'' After releasing
Scott Zolak, Bill Parcells may wish he had Foley back in New York.
</P>
<P>
   No swan song yet
</P>
<P>
   Eric Swann, the Cardinals' excellent defensive tackle, told the
Arizona Republic that he bypassed the team's medical staff and had
surgery on his arthritic right knee last year just as the team was
making a playoff run. Swann said he was ``in extreme pain just
doing normal things like walking around.'' The two-time Pro Bowler
is still on the ``physically unable to perform/active'' list, but
it appears he will play this season, perhaps as soon as Sept. 27
vs. San Francisco . . . The Cardinals have other personnel
problems. No. 1 pick L.J. Shelton, an offensive tackle, is still
unsigned. His agent, Lamont Smith, has filed a grievance claiming
the team negotiated in bad faith. The Cardinals also have been slow
in coming to terms with wide receiver Rob Moore, the franchise
player, and defensive tackle Mark Smith, who was offered $325,000
but wants $1 million . . . Steelers coach Bill Cowher says he has
the best offensive line he's ever coached, mainly because of new
tackles Wayne Gandy and Chris Conrad. If Cowher is right, many
holes will be opened for Jerome Bettis and there will be lots of
protection for Stewart. Cowher, incidentally, said he will keep
four quarterbacks on his roster: Stewart, Mike Tomczak, Pete
Gonzalez, and rookie Anthony Wright. He also kept four in 1995:
Stewart, O'Donnell, Tomczak, and Jim Miller . . . Dick Jauron plans
to do something in Chicago that usually doesn't work: He'll use
both rookie sensation Cade McNown and Shane Matthews at
quarterback. The coach is hoping one takes the job, but evidently
the competition is too close to call right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
