<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN TAKE IRELAND TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ It was a class reunion that turned into a tutorial.
The US women's soccer team hadn't been together on a soccer field
since the players were love-bombing Brandi Chastain on the floor of
the Rose Bowl. But they got back into celebratory mode quickly
Satuday afternoon, taking overmatched Ireland to school, 5-0,
before 30,564 at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffeny Milbrett scored two goals, and Julie Foudy, Kristine
Lilly, and Joy Fawcett each added one as the Americans breezed past
their green-clad visitors, who got an unaccustomed taste of life at
soccer's upper level.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Americans had played together since
they defeated China on penalty kicks in the Women's World Cup final
eight weeks ago, and their mood was decidedly more relaxed. ``It'll
be fun,'' Milbrett said. ``No restraints. The reins are off of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, who hadn't even qualified to try to qualify for the
Cup, were happy just to be invited into the same playpen with the
world champions. ``Lambs to the slaughter,'' coach Mick Cooke
joked.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish had played only two international matches this year
and none since June. And they never had performed before 30,000
people. ``These girls have never played in front of more than
10,000,'' said forward Claire Scanlon. ``If we can get over that
initial culture shock, if we can overcome the mind game . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming the experience, skills, and depth of the Americans
was another issue. ``Their starting 11 is amazing,'' said
midfielder Holly Pierce, who used to play for the US under-20 team,
``and the people on the bench are amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Americans probably could have handled the Irish with
their second string, they brought the varsity. All but three of
their gold-medal team (keeper Briana Scurry, defender Lorrie Fair,
and midfielder Michelle Akers) were in uniform, and coach Tony
DiCicco started his regulars _ from defenders Carla Overbeck and
Fawcett to midfielders Foudy and Lilly and forwards Mia Hamm and
Milbrett.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it still took the Americans the better part of a half to
brush off two months' worth of rust and get their legs moving
again. Most of them hadn't arrived until Friday (and Chastain not
until Saturday morning), and they'd had only one practice session
together.
</P>
<P>
   Though the US quickly set up housekeeping in the Irish end, it
took a couple of dozen minutes to get on the board. Tiffany Roberts
put a header over the bar in the second minute. Foudy deflected
Hamm's free kick just wide in the 15th. And Cindy Parlow, alone to
the right of the penalty spot, had the ball taken off her foot by
sprawling keeper Emma Byrne in the 22d.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Milbrett dashed into the area, took a deft cross from
Parlow and lofted the ball over Byrne to put the United States up,
1-0, in the 25th minute. A dozen minutes after that, it was
Milbrett chasing down a loose ball and crossing to Foudy, who
finished easily from the doorstop.
</P>
<P>
   So it was 2-0 at intermission, but the American dominance was
far more pronounced than the score _ 15-2 in shots, 11-0 in corner
kicks. That gave DiCicco the green light to reach deep into his
bench when play resumed. Out came Overbeck, Foudy, defender
Christie Pearce, and keeper Saskia Webber. In went Chastain at
defender, Tisha Venturini in the midfield, Shannon MacMillan at
forward, and Tracy Ducar of North Andover in goal.
</P>
<P>
   There was little risk there. The Americans hadn't allowed a
second-half goal since they'd lost to the Chinese in added time at
the Meadowlands in April. And when play resumed, nothing changed.
The Americans still had the Irish backpedaling and gasping for air.
Natick-born Sara Whalen came in for Parlow in the 58th minute and
within seconds was sprinting down the right flank and feeding
Milbrett for her second goal.
</P>
<P>
   That was far more than enough against an Irish squad that had
made only brief forays into the US end. So the Americans put on an
impromptu clinic for their guests, with Chastain heading a corner
kick to Fawcett, who headed it in for a fourth goal in the 71st
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, after Hamm's bid was kicked out by a supine
Byrne, defender Dolores Deasley cleared the rebound straight to
Lilly, who roofed it to the far right corner, making it 5-0. So
much for the graduate-level course in Football 101. ``We're playing
the world champions,'' said Cooke. ``If you can't learn from that .
. . ''
</P>
</TEXT>
