<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-BULLSMOV     09-04 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-BULLSMOVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO FANS GET MORE OF SAME OLD BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you noticed what's going on with the team formerly known as
the Chicago Bulls? They made two big moves recently, bringing back
former stalwarts Will Perdue and B.J. Armstrong, two fine lads who
are, as they say, gettin' on.
</P>
<P>
   Unless I missed something, wasn't this supposed to be the summer
that the Bulls, who religiously, deliberately, almost haughtily got
well under the salary cap, were going to make their big, bold move
and become a real team again? They had a high draft pick, which
they used on Elton Brand. They had all this salary cap money, which
they used on, er, ah, hmm. But this was their plan and it was as
ill-disguised as it was foolproof. We could expect to see Penny
Hardaway, Ray Allen, Vin Baker, or some other free agent stud
swooping into town and picking up where Michael left off.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course, none of it happened. The Bulls were boring and
bad last year, a lethal mix. It was so much fun, they are doing it
all over again. The Bulls are pushing the consumer fraud envelope
to the limit by asking season ticket-holders to stomach another
horrible team and another horrible season because next summer,
they'll have all this cap room and Tim Duncan, Maurice Taylor, and
Grant Hill may be there and, well . . .
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you'll have Perdue, Armstrong, Brand, and other
Springfield-bound fellows.
</P>
<P>
   You already know this story. It didn't happen this time. It
won't happen next time, either. Duncan, to be sure, will be
coveted, but the Bulls can't pay him more than San Antonio no
matter how much cap room they have. And he has said he's amenable
to staying put if the city comes through with a new arena. The
Pistons similarly can outpay Chicago for Hill, who, by the way,
says he wants to stay where he is. Taylor is another matter. He's a
Clipper, so all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls even managed to unload the one player they did spend
for last year: Brent Barry. If I'm not mistaken, wasn't he going to
be one of the guys around whom the team built? (Gee, did Rick
Pitino take over Chicago while I was on vacation?)
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Bulls have the Duncan drums beating
already. They gave Perdue $5 million and the ex-Spur then said,
``Tim Duncan is not married to San Antonio by any means.'' That is
called being a grateful, loyal, marketing-savvy employee. There has
been nary a syllable from either Duncan or Hill or anyone, for that
matter expressing a desire to play in Chicago along the lines of
what Baker said about Boston this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls are again pointing ahead while asking and hoping
the fans ignore what's right in front of their eyes. That is, of
course, after the fans have shelled out the ransom money ahead of
time to see the sorry show.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on the Bulls, who quickly have lost whatever cachet they
thought they had by winning all those titles. But even worse, shame
on their fans, who, we thought, knew better. What are they both
going to say next summer when the well runs dry again?
</P>
<P>
   Magic touches
</P>
<P>
   Orlando is taking the same approach as Chicago, which doesn't
make the Magic any less culpable except that they are doing it for
the first time, they spent lavishly last year and got smoked in the
first round, their fans don't know any better, and they do have the
important inducements of weather and no state income tax to offer
free agents. Plus, it's closer to St. Croix . . . Last year, after
he got fired by the Nets, John Calipari was mentioned by Larry
Brown as a possible addition to the 76ers' staff. Then Brown ran it
by his boss, Pat Croce, who did a Dikembe Mutombo on the whole
thing. Croce was still steamed that Calipari stood him up at the
Chicago predraft camp in 1996 and said he wouldn't have anything to
do with the guy. Well, Cal got wind of Croce's wrath, put in a
call, said it was all a misunderstanding, and, Croce says now,
``Apology accepted.'' So Cal will be an assistant for the first
time in 11 years, passing up guaranteed TV work for a return to the
NBA. ``Coach Brown cornered me on the golf course at Pinehurst and
we talked and I got excited all over again,'' Cal said. ``I had the
TV stuff lined up, but I decided I wanted to do this.'' Calipari
said he thought he might even enjoy the work because he knows
there's no pressure or expectations. ``He's the coach, just like I
was the coach,'' Calipari said. ``I don't think he's going to be
looking over his shoulder.'' . . . We hear that plans are afoot to
get John Mellencamp to close Market Square Arena with a free
concert and have Bruce Springsteen open the new Conseco Fieldhouse
around the corner. They're negotiating dates in Indy with the Boss.
But on Saturday, Nov. 6, the Pacers will play their first home game
in the building, against the Celtics. ``That's always a tough game
for us,'' Pacers president Donnie Walsh said. But also that night,
the 50 greatest players in Indiana state history _ high school,
college, and pro _ will be honored. The 50 will be announced on a
daily basis beginning Sept. 17 after being chosen by a panel of
media members, players, and coaches chaired by the legendary John
Wooden, who, of course, is a native Hoosier. Among those on the
panel are George McInnis, who played at all three levels in
Indiana, former Pacers coach Slick Leonard, and Billy Keller, who
also played at all three levels in the state . . . Charles Oakley
said he had feelers from perhaps a dozen teams before taking the
money and reupping with Toronto. ``I'm not that young, but I do
have a lot of respect around the league.'' . . . Baker's new deal
with Seattle contains a weight clause, which, given last season, is
not a bad idea . . . Don't be surprised if the Celtics are off to
the Orient in the next year or two. Paul Pierce just came back from
a Nike tour of Taiwan, Japan, and Korea and, according to agent
Aaron Goodwin, was an unqualified smash. ``I've never seen him
interact with kids like he did in Japan,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer case revisited
</P>
<P>
   Ron Mercer has been an ex-Celtic for more than a month and is
still unhappy about the way his exodus is being portrayed. Yes, it
was about the money. But no, it wasn't all about the money. Mercer
revealed that he was told before the end of the regular season, in
the back of the Celtics' locker room in Madison Square Garden, that
he probably would not be re-signed. According to Mercer, Pitino
told him he didn't think the team could meet his market value,
although Mercer said he didn't know what that figure was, nor was
one offered by Pitino. And for good reason. There wasn't any way
anyone could have known what that figure was. ``I knew then that I
wasn't going to be back,'' Mercer said. Then there was the brief
meeting in Boston, at which time the Celtics offered him $7 million
over four years. That's a decent wage. But Antoine Walker is making
$12 million a year. And Mercer thinks his market value is somewhere
in between. ``I know what I'm capable of doing,'' he said. ``I
don't think you understand how much motivation I have for this
season.'' So, based on one offer, and one counter from Mercer that
was not, as is being circulated, for the maximum $71 million, the
Celtics decided they couldn't re-sign one of their top players.
There were no more calls. There were no more offers. There was no
more negotiation. ``We wanted to make something happen,'' Mercer
said. ``I wanted to stay with the Celtics, but I also wanted to be
treated fairly. That's all. But it's being said that I was
money-hungry and that's not it at all.'' Mercer may indeed be
unrealistic about his market value. He'll get what he gets and it
will be a lot. It also may not be close to $7 million. But teams
traditionally overpay for players they want to keep, and Mercer had
every right to expect to be one of those guys, especially when he
sees teammates represented by his former agent, David Falk, signed
up quickly and without fanfare. And a disagreement over
compensation is hardly a novelty in pro sports. ``I don't know what
the reason was,'' Mercer said. ``All I know is that I was going to
be traded and it was that way the entire two years I was in Boston.
That's not good.'' And what kind of message does it send to Danny
Fortson, Tony Battie, and, in a couple years, Pierce? Will they,
too, be told their market value makes them unsignable and become
the latest departees in the Bare Rick Project?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
