<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC GETS POINT IN OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heat had grown stifling. So, too, had the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   As searing, Texas-type temperatures heated up the artificial
turf at Alumni Stadium, Boston College's football team withstood
the conditions and remained calm, cool, and collected when
Saturday's season opener against Baylor threatened to go into
double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bears answered an Eagles touchdown in overtime and
lined up for the extra-point attempt by Kyle Atteberry, nerves on
both sides _ and among the crowd of 39,756 _ seemed to reach a
boiling point.
</P>
<P>
   How much more could the Eagles give? How much more could they
withstand after being victimized by several bizarre plays and
miscues? How much farther could they go?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going all the way,'' said BC senior defensive tackle
Chris Hovan. ``Until we dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, BC didn't have to go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry saw to that when he missed a chip-shot PAT _ hooking
it wide left from the right hash _ that enabled the Eagles to sweat
out a 30-29 victory. BC's first-ever overtime triumph touched off a
delirious celebration on the sideline that spilled onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Cirino, who came crashing off the corner in an attempt to
block the kick, ripped off his helmet and flung it high in the air.
Defensive tackle Mike Willetts, who had plowed into the middle of
Baylor's line, exhaled a mighty sigh of relief. And Hovan, who said
his only view of the kick ``was a wall of white jerseys,'' knew BC
had won it when he saw his joyous teammates rush the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things finally happened to good people,'' said BC coach
Tom O'Brien. ``The kids hung in there and they played extremely
hard. We didn't play very smart and we didn't play very good. We
understand we have a long way to go, but you have to give Baylor a
lot of credit. That's a pretty good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like BC, the Bears were not without their flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor struggled to mount a rushing attack against BC's
senior-laden defense, which held the Bears to 110 yards on the
ground and 14 first downs. Behind an offensive line that plowed
huge holes into Baylor's defensive front, the Eagles amassed 451
yards total offense, almost rushing for as many yards (350) as the
Bears had total offense (354).
</P>
<P>
   Junior running back Cedric Washington did the bulk of the work,
carrying 32 times for 177 yards and scoring three touchdowns.
Washington, a 5-foot-11-inch, 200-pounder from Holyoke, scored in
regulation on runs of 4 and 6 yards and added a 1-yard plunge in
overtime. Senior John Matich, who made one of two field goal
attempts, converted the PAT following Washington's overtime TD that
proved the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry, though, had no such luck after Baylor quarterback
Jermaine Alfred (15 of 18, 244 yards, 2 TDs) scored on a 1-yard
plunge in OT.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, Atteberry's regular holder, was dinged up on the scoring
drive and was on the sideline. There was no trouble with the snap
or the hold. But the kick was off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' said Baylor first-year coach Kevin Steele.
``I should've used a timeout there, that was my mistake and I take
full credit for that, but still (Ryan) Chapdelaine (the reserve
holder) is every bit as good as Jermaine in getting it down. He got
it down just perfect. It was a good snap and a good hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could base it on is what Kyle told me,'' he added, ``And
Kyle said that he mis-hit it, you know? He just mis-hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   It absolved the Eagles of an afternoon of sins.
</P>
<P>
   When BC's first possession stalled at its 42 after three plays,
Baylor took a 3-0 lead on Atteberry's 22-yard field goal after
Samir El-Amin blocked Kevin McMyler's punt. Carlton Rowe, who
rushed 10 times for 47 yards before departing with cramps in the
second half, gave BC a 7-3 lead on a 1-yard plunge that capped an
impressive 15-play, 80-yard drive with 2:33 left in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor then recorded its first TD on a bizarre play when Melvin
Barnett hauled in a flare pass at the BC 3 but fumbled the ball
after Jonathan Ordway's jarring hit. The ball squirted into the end
zone where Lanny O'Steen pounced on it, beating Adam Newman to the
ball for a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck, who struggled in his first
career start by completing 13 of 29 passes for 101 yards (including
the first pass to himself for a 3-yard gain), was victimized by
McKinley Bowie's 83-yard interception return with 25 seconds left
before intermission. Hovan blocked Atteberry's PAT, but Baylor had
a 16-7 lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   BC rallied with a strong second half, overcoming back-to-back
penalties (for delay of game) to get a 21-yard field goal by
Matich. Washington made it 16-10 on a 4-yard run in the third, but
an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty (for excessive celebration) led
to Matich's missed PAT from 35 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, though, made it 23-16 in the fourth when he scored
on a 6-yard run after Bryan Arndt salvaged the drive by pouncing on
a William Green fumble at the 6. However, Baylor came back and tied
it, 23-23, when Alfred beat Ramon Johnson with a 73-yard TD toss to
Andra Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, but we fought through it,'' Cirino said of the
steamy conditions. ``Once again, we couldn't lay down and die. We
had a bunch of opportunities where this team in the past would have
done that and just rolled over. But we weren't having it _ this
game or this year _ because we realized this was a chance to win
our first home opener since we've been here and we wanted to make
it count.''
</P>
<P>
   And they did, by the slightest of margins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
