<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCICIT-EXHIBIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF SCIENCE CITY AT UNION STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science City at Union Station:
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $250 million for entire renovation, including $40 million
held in long-term endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Where the money came from:
</P>
<P>
   - $118 million through bistate -cent sales tax voters passed in
November 1996;
</P>
<P>
   - $30 million from the federal government, primarily the Federal
Transit Authority;
</P>
<P>
   - More than $100 million donated by local individuals,
foundations and businesses, including $20 million from the Hall
Family and the Hallmark corporate foundations, $25 million from the
Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation and $9 million from the Sprint
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Money spent on Science City exhibits:
</P>
<P>
   - $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   Space: Union Station _ 600,000 square feet developed in
995,000-square-foot station.
</P>
<P>
   Science City _ 300,000 square feet, including all offices,
theaters, exhibits space, maintenance and support areas, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit Space _ 76,000 square feet (67,000 in Science City plus
9,000 of temporary exhibit space in Union Station's north waiting
room)
</P>
<P>
   Admission: The price is now 25 percent more than first
predicted. Prices for visitors living in Johnson, Wyandotte,
Jackson, Clay and Platte counties: $9.50 for adults and $6 for
children. The cost for individuals living outside those five
counties: $12.50 for adults, $9 for children.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Science City at Union Station is supposed to
open in two months. Workers are scrambling to finish. Few exhibits
are in place, though planners insist that the museum will still
open Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a just a few highlights people will see, along with the
most basic science lessons they will learn:
</P>
<P>
   - Theater district: Features a 440-seat theater with a 60-foot
screen playing Iwerks large-format films, a 150-seat domed theater
for planetarium and multimedia shows, a 200-seat theater for live
performances and an eight-seat computerized motion simulator,
which, depending on the software, re-creates motion experienced in
an Air Force jet, a roller coaster or a race car.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Science is an enjoyable experience involving body, mind
and emotions.
</P>
<P>
   - Media labs: Create your own newspaper or TV newscast with
up-to-date science news. Prepare and deliver a TV weather forecast
on Science City's weather channel.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Learning from real-world stories and understanding how
media technology works.
</P>
<P>
   - Mister E. Hotel: The rooms in the hotel contain optical
illusions. As you figure out how they work, you gather clues to the
mystery of where a missing fortune is hidden. Entering one room you
feel upright, but the room looks tilted. Lie on the bed, and
suddenly the room looks normal and you feel tilted. You see a gem
in a safe and try to grab it; it's not there. From one angle
objects in a safe look like gold bars, from a different angle they
look like pieces of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding reflection, refraction and optics.
</P>
<P>
   - Crime lab: Given a file on a suspected criminal, you use
autopsy reports, fingerprints, comparative hair samples and other
forensic science techniques to prove guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Learn to gather, analyze, compare and interpret data.
</P>
<P>
   - Helicopter: Grab the controls of the chopper for a simulated
flight; see how difficult it really is.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding the phenomenon of flight.
</P>
<P>
   - Storm Center: Determine the course of an approaching storm
using data from storm watchers, weather maps, satellite feeds and
other information.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding weather phenomenon; gathering data and
making decisions based on your observations.
</P>
<P>
   - Pop Wheelie's Delivery Service: Center of gravity becomes real
when, strapped into a counterbalanced bicycle, you ride it across a
high wire 23 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding balance, gravity and center of mass.
</P>
<P>
   - S.O.A.R. Lab: Enter the Scientific Opportunities in Applied
Research Lab as a research scientist with a specific job. Design a
robot to perform a particular task; engineer a car for style and
efficiency; check your design of a boat, a plane wing or an
automobile in a wind tunnel; go to the drop tower and, with a
high-speed camera, witness what occurs to your sample when dropped
from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding research and design, the process of trial
and error and what it takes to turn an idea into a workable
product.
</P>
<P>
   - Dr. Hugh Mann Torso's Body Tours: This pretend company has
developed body-imaging technology that lets visitors diagnose a
disease by taking a fantastic voyage through a pulsating blood
vessel. Images of blood cells whiz by as you make your way into the
lungs, the brain and on to an operating room, where you suddenly
become part of a surgical team.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding anatomy and body-imaging technology.
</P>
<P>
   - City Golf: Learn the physics of motion as you putt balls on
this four-hole miniature golf course, where the hazards, including
spinning disks and blasts of air, have been designed by physicists.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding how forces influence bodies in motion.
</P>
<P>
   - Farm Environment: Here in a barn you are given data and a
global positioning satellite map on how your crop did in the
previous year. Then you climb into the cab of a combine and on a
computer make decisions on the use of pesticides, fertilizers,
irrigation and plant strains to improve this year's yield. See
whether it works.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding the high-tech nature of farming with its
use of genetic engineering, satellites, etc. Learning to make
decisions based on data collection.
</P>
<P>
   - Music Park: Everything is musical. The fence is a xylophone. A
giant synthesizer keyboard is embedded in the ground. Five
trash-can drums play 10 different tones. Infrared beams shoot
through the branches of a weeping willow ``harp tree.'' Stop the
beams with your hands, and the tree plays different notes.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   - Art Park: Features a 10-foot ball-bearing stream. Create
eddies and waterfalls, and change the course of the stream using
different levers and obstacles. A heat-sensitive liquid crystal
column changes color as you touch it. Using ultrasound, create a
cloud inside a 4-foot diameter bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding the connections between art and science.
</P>
<P>
   - Secret City: Visitors take a trip beneath the streets of
Science City to dabble with electricity, pneumatics, water _ the
kind of systems that help a city operate. Manipulate breakers and
switches on three generators to guide a current and light an alley
sign; make whistles blow, wheels spin, etc., using compressed air;
direct balls to their destinations through a series of pneumatic
tubes; figure out the right pulley system to raise yourself while
sitting on an elevator seat.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Learning how science helps keep a city running.
</P>
<P>
   - Astronaut Training Center: You are training for a mission to
Mars. Use a joystick to guide a model of the Mars rover over a
simulated Mars terrain built behind glass. Try it using on-board
cameras. Enter either of two space station modules. Test a series
of surface samples using ultraviolet light, magnification,
radioactivity detectors. While standing on a tilting disc, you
place your head in a opening filled with flashing lights and
designed to approximate the disorientation one can feel in outer
space. A modified exercise bike helps monitor your fitness for
space travel. Use a satellite dish to get messages from outer
space.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding basic astronomy, the geology of Mars,
balance and effects of minimal gravity.
</P>
<P>
   - Tree-house and canopy: By pointing a parabolic microphone into
a tree canopy, you pick up the sounds of birds and insects. Compare
the sound waves generated by these animals to known sound waves to
identify the bird or the insect you have found.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Learning about life in the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   - Sports Training Center: You are a football player kicking an
extra point. Your kick is taped using a high-speed camera and then
analyzed against a pro's. See what happens to the speed and
accuracy of your best baseball pitch when the shape, size and
balance of the ball is altered.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding the mechanics of motion.
</P>
<P>
   - Dinosaur Films Ltd.: After walking through a prehistoric
landscape, you enter a movie set, where you sit at a computer to
create your own animated dinosaur with the help of a paleontologist
Interactor.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding prehistory and comparative anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   - Old Town: Fourteen historic facades. Create sound effects and
become part of the show at the old radio station; search through
relics and trace genealogy in the attic of Grandma's Boarding
House; help repair a 1950 Ford at a vintage service station.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Understanding the history of Kansas City and early
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
