<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BARRY-LIFESAVER-KAN &LR;      09-04 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRY-LIFESAVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE FAN, THE MUSIC OF BARRY MANILOW MEANS LIFE ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For more than two decades, Rachel Cooke of
Louisburg, Kan., told almost no one the full story of her troubled
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   But now, on the day she will attend the Barry Manilow concert at
Sandstone Amphitheatre, she doesn't care who knows _ especially the
singer.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she said, his music saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1978 in LaVista, Neb., a suburb of Omaha. Cooke, then
Rachel Parker, was an energetic, creative 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   She also had decided to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   At home after school, she put on a nightgown, pulled a
handkerchief-wrapped bundle from a dresser drawer and filled a
glass with water. Then she climbed onto her twin bed and prepared
to die.
</P>
<P>
   This was it, she thought: the end of her fears, the end of her
pain.
</P>
<P>
   She untied the handkerchief and let 27 red-and-white Dilantin
capsules tumble onto her bedspread. She didn't want to die, but
after years of sexual abuse by her father, she couldn't think of a
good reason to live.
</P>
<P>
   She scooped the heart pills into one hand and held the glass in
the other. Then she heard the music by Barry Manilow that would
change her life.
</P>
<P>
   All the time I thought there's only me
</P>
<P>
   Crazy in a way that no one else could be
</P>
<P>
   I would have given everything I own
</P>
<P>
   If someone would have said you're not alone
</P>
<P>
   The words stunned her. She dropped the glass and pills, grabbed
her pillow and began to sob.
</P>
<P>
   - - -
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than 20 years since Cooke, now 36, nearly took
her own life.
</P>
<P>
   With Manilow in town, Cooke wants to share her story to show
others who are suffering abuse that they are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father went blind when I was about 2 years old,'' she said.
``I learned that by touch, my father could see.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was 11, he started touching her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `Come here, so I can see how you are growing.'
Then he would disrobe me and touch me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The touching eventually turned to intercourse. She asked him to
stop. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   And he threatened to kill her, her siblings and her mother if
she told anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd repeatedly mention that he had bullets with our names on
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By several accounts, Richard Parker was a talented but troubled
man with an iron will.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his blindness and health problems ranging from epilepsy
to heart disease, he carved out a living with Radio Talking Book in
Omaha, a service that provided information, ranging from books and
the weather to current events, for the visually impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside the home, my father was an incredible man,'' Cooke
said. ``Made a name for himself in the community, knew the chief of
police, worked with the media, even talked about running for
senator at one point.''
</P>
<P>
   At home he was far different.
</P>
<P>
   One night, when Rachel was 17, he burst into the bathroom, where
he tied her to the toilet and forced himself on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people ask, `Why didn't you run? He was blind,' &UR; ''
Cooke said. ``I could have run. But he would have found me.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, she feared, things would be worse. He might beat her.
Or turn his twisted affections to her sister or brother. Or kill
all of them.
</P>
<P>
   In speech class the next day, Cooke wasn't herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had this big neon sign flashing on my forehead
that said, You've had sex with your father!''
</P>
<P>
   When the teacher teased her about not wanting to give her
speech, Cooke bolted from the room, shattering the glass in the
door.
- - -
</P>
<P>
   In the office, she cried hysterically.
</P>
<P>
   The school called police. For the first time, she told someone
about the abuse. Instead of support, she got accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever walk in front of him naked to entice him?,'' one
officer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's blind!,'' she shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Her father denied the charges. A juvenile court judge ordered
the family into counseling and then sent her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father beat the tar out of me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, the family went to counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' a therapist said. ``Your dad tells me this is all your
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel stared daggers at the therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the problem,'' she said. ``I don't have the problem.
I don't need to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   She walked out. Her parents walked out. They never went back.
</P>
<P>
   Each time officers called to check on her, her father made her
hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Una Kohler, a former reserve officer for the LaVista Police
Department, remembers how hard Cooke struggled to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To begin with, she was a pretty timid girl,'' she said. ``But
as time went on, she gained strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rachel,'' his father yelled after hearing that she had a new
bra. ``Come here so I can see your breast size.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flipped,'' she said. ``I started screaming....`As long as I
live you'll never touch me again!' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   That night she ran away.
</P>
<P>
   Scared, alone and broke, she lived out of her red Dodge Dart for
three weeks. She bathed in public rest rooms. Still in high school,
she got jobs as a telemarketer and at a bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   She saved enough to rent an apartment and graduated from high
school. She was 18. A year later, her father died of congestive
heart failure.
- - -
</P>
<P>
   His death brought back the hopelessness, the pain. And the
memories of the day she almost beat him to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty minutes till the pain is over,'' she thought as she
walked home from school on the day she planned to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened that she still doesn't completely
understand.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a garage sale and went in. With a quarter in her pocket,
she went from table to table, passing glassware, knickknacks, old
books.
</P>
<P>
   She stopped at a box of records. She was drawn to a single by
Barry Manilow called ``All the Time.'' She had never heard of Barry
Manilow.
</P>
<P>
   She bought the record for a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Kneeling on her bed at home, with 27 Dilantin capsules spread
before her, she placed the record on the turntable. Seconds before
swallowing the pills, she heard the single _ from Manilow's album
``This One's For You.''
</P>
<P>
   All the time I thought there's only me....
</P>
<P>
   His lyrics were a revelation. Someone understood!
</P>
<P>
   Sobbing into her pillow, she resolved not to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a reason to keep going, because I wasn't alone,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   From that day, more Manilow records followed. His gentle voice,
his upbeat tunes and positive messages moved her, inspired her.
</P>
<P>
   Saved her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming to hear a story like that,'' Manilow said.
``When I began making records I didn't know what I was doing. I
don't know if anyone really does. All I was getting was a critical
drubbing from the press. `Stop doing what you are doing. You stink
so bad.' I'd get up every morning and... say, `They're wrong.
There's somebody out there who is getting what I am trying to say.'
And there she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cooke has a small shrine to Manilow in a curio cabinet in
her dining room. There's Manilow on a book, on the cover of People
magazine, on playing cards, key chains, clocks, candy dishes.
</P>
<P>
   She has ``Manilow'' personalized license plates on her car. She
recently wrote a sermon about him.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's his music. She has it all. Every song. Every note.
- - -
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, her sister, Renelle, will go with her to Manilow's
concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister is my savior,'' Renelle Ferry said. ``Everything I
have ever wanted to be is related to my sister _ being a good
person, being good with children, being a Christian and a
volunteer....I think one of the greatest things she has done is
help other children through the same things she went through. She
worked with the court system and abused children in Sarpy County
(Neb.) for several years. She's turned it around. She took
something horribly negative and turned it into a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cooke is married and stays home with her boys, Weston, 6,
and Sawyer, 2. She watches children in her home and volunteers at
her church, Redeemer Lutheran in Shawnee, Kan. She and her husband,
Scott, a project manager at Sprint, recently built a large house in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   She credits her recovery to therapy and to friends who have
become a second family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough,'' said her therapist, Sherry Briggs. ``It's been
a long haul for her. She's had a lot of past trauma, and she's
worked very hard to come through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooke plans to become an ordained youth minister.
</P>
<P>
   She met her idol for the first time last November at a taping of
the ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' show in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tongue-tied,'' she said, ``and I am never at a loss for
words. I even gave him a card, because I was afraid I wouldn't
speak articulately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this?'' she remembers him saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thank-you card,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He reached out, took her hand, and said: ``No. I should be
thanking you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he kissed her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Manilow has added ``All the Time,'' to tonight's play list in
honor of Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shaking,'' she said when she heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   All the time
</P>
<P>
   All the wasted time
</P>
<P>
   All the years, waiting for a sign
</P>
<P>
   To think I had it all the time
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have it all the time,'' she said. ``I just had to find
it in myself that I was worth something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
