<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SCICIT-MUSEUM-KAN &LR;      09-04 2118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCICIT-MUSEUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE CITY WILL OFFER LEARNING BY DOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Earlier this summer, the creators of Science
City got a phone call from a man so excited about Union Station's
new science museum that he offered a gift _ a reproduction of
Sputnik, the first satellite rocketed into outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it, he said. Think how great the glimmering herald of
the Space Age would look dangling from the ceiling of the station's
Grand Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Officials didn't think long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' said spokesman Bill Musgrave. ``But it's not what
we have in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the prize had been Apollo 11 itself, a Tyrannosaurus
rex, Archimedes' bathtub or Einstein's brain, the answer would have
been the same: No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the way the creators of Science City see it, the
best way to get excited and learn about science is not by looking,
it is by doing, by becoming immersed in an experience that, in the
case of Science City, has been shaped by extensive market research
and focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission,'' said Steve Snyder, Science City's director of
attraction development, ``is to ignite a passion for discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   So why gawk at Sputnik when you can pilot a helicopter?
</P>
<P>
   Why read about DNA fingerprinting, when you can solve a murder?
</P>
<P>
   Science City is not scheduled to open until Nov. 10. But museum
leaders aware of its concept _ a science world that is more theme
park than museum _ already are identifying it as an exotic species
in their field, although some may question how much science the
visitors will absorb.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, hands-on museums and interactive exhibits have
existed for decades. In Chicago, a Museum of Science and Industry
exhibit that simulates a 1,500-foot descent into a coal mine has
been around since 1933.
</P>
<P>
   And the idea of marketing ``experience'' also is decades old.
Today it is prominent throughout the retail world from Nike Town,
where customers can climb walls as well as buy sneakers, to
Rainforest Cafe, where diners eat amid the mist and sound effects
of a tropical jungle.
</P>
<P>
   But in museums, such thoroughly immersive experiences are still
as rare as a snowfall in the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``By its scale and approach, what Kansas City is planning takes
the idea of being immersed in an environment way out on the
continuum,'' said Bonnie VanDorn, executive director of the
Washington-based Association of Science-Technology Centers.
</P>
<P>
   So how much actual science knowledge will visitors take way from
Science City? The vast majority of educators agree that people
learn best from hands-on experiences. But by relying so heavily on
a theme-park approach, will Science City be exchanging fun for
facts? Theater for theorems?
</P>
<P>
   The response from Science City planners: It depends.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the science is there, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole premise,'' said David Ucko, president of Science
City at Union Station and the Kansas City Museum, ``is that science
underlies everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials proudly boast that Science City's exhibits contain
more than enough to help teachers fulfill nearly all the
kindergarten to 12th-grade goals spelled out in the Missouri,
Kansas and national science standards.
</P>
<P>
   But if visitors hope to come away knowing Bernoulli's Principle
or the standard model of quantum physics _ forget it, they say. And
while visitors will be able to dig fossils at an archaeological
site and walk on a movie set from the Cretaceous period, there will
be no mention of Darwin or the process of natural selection.
</P>
<P>
   Science City's mission is to beguile, to enchant, to inspire, to
make the process of science and scientific inquiry in this world so
delightful that, upon entering the real world, visitors not only
will begin to see science all around them but also hunger to know
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone comes out of Science City and you ask them to name
all the amino acids, they're not going to be able to do that,''
said Lauranne Hess, developer of Science City's educational
programs. ``But that's not what the experience is about.'' Born in
Paris
</P>
<P>
   Simply, when Science City is finished it will be exactly what
its name implies, a mock city under glass. It is a two-level
science theme park built beneath what looks like an enormous
greenhouse that rises the height of Union Station and runs along
the west side.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Science City concept did not come to the attention
of Kansas Citians until 1991, the inspiration goes back to 1987.
That is when Ucko, who was then at the California Museum of Science
and Industry in Los Angeles, attended a temporary film exhibit in
Paris called Cites-Cines.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of just watching movies, visitors to Cites-Cines wore
earphones and walked through a series of faux city facades _ a jail
cell, a rooftop. In moving from one environment to the next, famous
movie scenes related to each environment flashed on the walls.
Music and dialogue came through the earphones.
</P>
<P>
   For years Ucko had felt that science centers were not living up
to their potential. Science and industry museums did a great job
showing technology's dramatic progress. And hands-on museums, like
the Exploratorium in San Francisco, were dynamic laboratories. But
neither, he felt, were great at engaging visitors' emotions or
sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Cites-Cines did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful,'' Ucko said. ``At that point I began to
think of how to take this kind of emotional engagement, which
science museums had not been creating, and translate it into
something educational.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ucko moved here in 1990, he came with the understanding
that he would corral support for a science museum. His idea was
Science City. When the museum opens as part of the $250 million
renovation of Union Station, the space beneath the glass ceiling
will feature $21 million worth of exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits are housed among elaborate sets. People will see
stone, wood and brick buildings. There will be streetlamps,
sidewalks, bridges, curbs, sewers, parks, billboards, fountains, a
four-hole miniature golf course, a Missouri cave, a waterfall and a
tree-house canopy. There will be an eatery, a skyscraper
construction site, a crane, a barn, a combine, a helicopter, a
movie set, a historic neighborhood, an archaeological dig site, an
astronaut training facility, a robot design lab and more than 25
other environments, each designed to launch visitors on separate
scientific adventures.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's hospital, visitors will tour the human body by
walking through a reproduction of a pulsating blood vessel. At the
Mister E. Hotel (get it? ``mystery'') the mission will be to gather
clues to a lost fortune while wandering through rooms of different
optical illusions. Tornadoes are tracked at the severe storm
center. Bad guys are nabbed using forensic science at the crime
lab.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever explanatory text each exhibit requires will blend into
each environment. Instead of reading signs, visitors will find
information on blueprints, memos, wall posters, golf score cards,
Post-it Notes, medical charts, an archaeologist's notebook.
Throughout, as in Cites-Cines, there will be film and sound
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Science City will even have residents _ 23 costumed
``interactors'' meant to entertain and help visitors understand the
science behind their jobs, from a crime-lab worker (forensics) to a
make-up artist who changes the appearance of visitors using
filtered light (optics).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have an ice-cream vendor,'' said Steve Snyder, ``who at
the base of it deals with the science of hot and cold. One idea
we're playing with is to have him branch out; he's looking to
create a flower Popsicle.''
</P>
<P>
   By dipping a flower in liquid nitrogen, Snyder said, people will
see what happens at a very low temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The object, Snyder said, is not to give a science sermon, but to
help create ``a rich, exciting, emotionally engaging experience
that, at its heart, is educational.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Ucko said, is exactly what people want.
</P>
<P>
   How is he sure?
</P>
<P>
   Focus groups. Focus groups. Focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   Like it, don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Like other things served under glass, Science City has been
prepared to order. The effect of focus groups in helping guide the
facility's design has been enormous.
</P>
<P>
   When focus groups said they did not like the idea of a
science-of-arson exhibit because it brought up feelings of loss,
the idea was nixed.
</P>
<P>
   When focus groups said they liked the idea of a Secret City
exhibit, allowing visitors to explore underground systems like
power and water, the exhibit was added.
</P>
<P>
   And when focus groups clearly stated that their top four
interests were medicine, space, the history of Kansas City and
dinosaurs, Old Town became part of Science City. It is an area of
14 buildings modeled after well-known Kansas City businesses, from
an 1868 J.H. Adami Hardware, Cutlery store to a 1940s Jones Store
to a 1964 Jack Boring appliance shop.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, Ucko said, is how focus groups confirmed what
he and other museum officials have long known:
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to read lots of stuff,'' he said. ``They
want hands-on. They want to do things they don't normally do,
whether it's going up in a tree house or down in a cave. These are
places and experiences people don't normally have.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Internet, television, movies and theme parks,
``the public has just grown to expect a higher level of fun in the
museum experience,'' said Joe Shacter, director of exhibits at
Chicago's Museum of Science and Industry.
</P>
<P>
   If giving visitors what they ask for gets them excited about
science, so be it, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more people than ever are going to museums of all sorts:
art, science, natural history. Attendance is at a record high with
860 million visits a year _ more than 2 million a day. One big
reason, said Ed Able, president of the American Association of
Museums, is the hard work all sorts of museums have put into
shedding their elitist images and becoming more accommodating to
the people who walk through their doors. In short, making the
experience exciting or, at least, personal and easy to relate to.
Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   - At the Maryland Science Center in Baltimore, part of a recent
women's health exhibit used a life-size Barbie doll to show bizarre
and unrealistic that symbol of femininity is when compared to real
women.
</P>
<P>
   - In October, Chicago's science museum will mount an interactive
``Star Trek'' exhibit, with props and sets from the movies, to show
how fiction has come to pass in the form of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   - A traveling Whodunnit exhibit at the Fort Worth Museum of
Science and History, in Texas, plunges visitors into a murder at
Memory Diner, complete with police lights, crime tape, recorded
witness reports, film of a mannequin autopsy and 14 other clues,
allowing visitors to use ballistic, toxicology and other forensic
tools to solve the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it work,'' said Charlie Walter, vice president of
the Fort Worth museum, ``is that it provides a real context. It
engages you. If you've really experienced it, it's easier to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   At Science City then, will visitors come away understanding
angular momentum or the laws of aerodynamics when they putt a ball
over spinning discs or blasts of air on the miniature golf course?
</P>
<P>
   On the Dinosaur Films Ltd. movie set, will visitors _ walking
through a tunnel beneath a projection of an animated mosasaur _
learn the distinction between Cretaceous, Triassic and Jurassic
dinosaurs?
</P>
<P>
   When visitors at Pop Wheelie's Delivery Service are strapped
onto a counterbalanced bicycle and ride it along a cable 23 feet in
the air, will they suddenly know how to calculate center of mass?
</P>
<P>
   No. But they will learn firsthand how bodies in motion act;
they'll see a type of underwater beast that scientists say swam
millions of years ago in the great inland sea that became Kansas;
they'll obtain a visceral understanding of center of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The hope, then, is that visitors will begin to ask questions:
</P>
<P>
   What kind of skin might the animal have had? Fur? Scales? How
would it have stood and moved? What evidence is there to make a
conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this thought out there,'' said Snyder of Science
City, ``that science is this big book somewhere, where you turn to
the right page and you find the right answer. But what it really
is, is this adventure, this process of investigation and discovery
that is the thrilling heart of science.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the stuff, he said, that fires the intellect.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what we're looking to do,'' said Ucko, ``is create the
spark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
