<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITHOUT A 70-TON TANK, TOWN'S PARADE IS HEAVY WITH MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTON, Kan. _ Never mind that KDOT KO'd the M1A1 battle tank.
</P>
<P>
   The PRIDE Committee can be proud of its 1999 Jubilee Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot we had to do this year,'' said Wilda Carswell,
a PRIDE member. ``We wanted this parade to be special.''
</P>
<P>
   That was because it celebrated veterans, especially those of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing them all the time,'' said Deanna Roach, a
committee member.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a good opportunity to finally say goodbye to one of
its sons who grew up here, found the wife who became the mother of
his two children, and then disappeared into the maelstrom of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Only to be found again.
</P>
<P>
   But first, more about that tank. In order to make last weekend's
parade even bigger than recent ones for Russell Stover, the candy
man who was born here, or the Alton football team, which won 51
consecutive games in the 1960s, the PRIDE Committee set its sights
on an M1A1 main battle tank, the kind that dominated the
battlefields in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those really big ones,'' said Carswell. ``It was all
set. We'd called the Army at Fort Riley. They were going to send
one over on a trailer. Then along came the darn KDOT.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been something. A low-slung Abrams tank sporting a
120-mm cannon rumbling down the main drag.
</P>
<P>
   But with the M1A1 weighing in at almost 70 tons and its
transport trailer and truck coming close to half that, it was the
Kansas Department of Transportation that trembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were worried about the highways and bridges,'' said
Carswell. ``I could see their point.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Riley did send over a cavalry troop with soldiers wearing
19th century uniforms. There was also a Humvee; a couple of old
jeeps were scrounged up locally, and the parade went off without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   How big a parade?
</P>
<P>
   Try 140 entries. Not bad on a hot August afternoon for a
100-plus town in Osborne County.
</P>
<P>
   The theme was ``The Troops March On.'' First, down Mill Street,
came the military vehicles, the blue-clad troopers on horseback,
jeeps carrying elderly veterans, the American Legion and a float
recalling the home front _ scrap metal, victory gardens, bundled
newspapers, tin foil, even Rosie the Riveter.
</P>
<P>
   Past the estimated 800 onlookers came the rest _ farm machinery,
antique cars, wagons, motorcycles, riding mowers, a milk truck,
18-wheelers, dune buggies, more horses, bicycles and just about
anything else that could be pushed or pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was a more poignant side.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was the old photographs of Thomas Taylor and Floyd
Taylor, uncle and nephew and soldiers in the Philippines. They died
on or as a result of the Bataan Death March.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was Clarence Gregory, 75, who landed at Normandy's
Utah Beach on D-Day, June 6, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to hit Omaha Beach,'' said Gregory. ``Lost a
whole company there. Our landing craft ended up at Utah. I
guarantee I wouldn't be standing here talking to you. I'd have been
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   There was Carl Nonamaker, 79, who went ashore at Normandy on
D-Day-plus-nine, fought in five major battles and never even got a
scratch. After all these years, though, Nonamaker still has a gripe
_ not about people trying to shoot him, the counterbattery fire or
the wretchedness of war itself.
</P>
<P>
   No, his complaint is that the Army allowed him only a 10-day
furlough for the 1943 Kansas wheat harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Took two days to get here on the train and two days back,''
Nonamaker said. ``That left me just six days, and my daddy didn't
have any help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go back. Back at the base all we did was piddle
around. Instead, I could have been in the fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally there were the three persons sitting under the awning of
the old Odd Fellows Hall, now boarded up: Violet Sparks Mertz of
Salina; her daughter, Karen Sparks Hendrickson of Rancho Mirage,
Calif.; and her son, Doug Sparks of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Violet's first husband and Karen and Doug's father was Edward
``Mack'' Sparks, an Alton boy who, from his photograph, was almost
movie-star handsome.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, five weeks after they met here, Violet and Mack were
married. The war came. Mack joined the Army Air Corps. He'd be
safer in the air than on the ground, he told Violet.
</P>
<P>
   Karen was born in 1942; Doug in 1944. When Doug was 3 days old,
Mack shipped out to the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Mack was the co-pilot of a B-24 nicknamed ``Cold Steel,'' which
did not return to base on March 5, 1944. The crew of 10 was first
declared missing and then presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946 Violet married Lester Mertz, a friend of Mack's. Lester
died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In March, almost 55 years to the day since that first War
Department telegram came here, Violet was visiting Karen in
California. Doug had also gone west for the get-together.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang in Karen's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me if I was sitting down,'' said Karen, ``so I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The news was that the plane had been found in the
all-but-inaccessible interior of New Guinea. Among the wreckage
found on a mountainside were scattered bones and some dog tags. One
of the tags belonged to her father. Testing, through DNA, will take
another year, said Doug.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the remains can be separated, we'll bury him here,'' Doug
said. ``Mom bought a marker for him right after the war that's been
out in the cemetery all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not, they'll all be buried together, maybe in Arlington.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Doug looked north along Mill Street. The parade was
wrapping up. Still to come was the dedication of a new park, an
antique and stationary engine show, basketball, a pony pull, a
barbecue and a dance.
</P>
<P>
   The street was crowded. People were visiting each other,
smiling, having a good time. For a moment, Alton looked as it must
have 50 or 60 years ago, perhaps on the day Mack Sparks left for
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a real little kid, I remember, this town used to
fill up with people on Saturdays,'' said Doug. ``Just like today.''
</P>
<P>
   Alton used to be Bull City, named after its founder, Hiram C.
Bull, who put down roots here in 1870, then, unwisely, established
his own personal zoo. That decision proved fatal in 1879 when a
``pet'' elk gored him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was those were more genteel times, and a lot of
the town's ladies here thought Bull City was just a little racy,''
said Roach, a PRIDE Committee member. ``So in 1885 they changed the
name to Alton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bull City is beneath the word Alton on the sign out on U.S. 24.
The riding club, naturally, calls itself the Bull City Saddle Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name another town in Kansas,'' added Roach, ``that's had two
centennials. We had one in 1970, another in 1985. We're small, but
we think big. The tank, for instance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
