<HEADLINE>
MANUFACTURERS TOUT LOWER-COST VERSION OF B-2 STEALTH BOMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE McGRAW  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Builders of the B-2 stealth bomber, which President
Clinton lauded for its performance in Kosovo, think they can
produce a lower-cost version of the $2 billion plane that some are
already calling ``B-2 Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress, wary of the price tag for development and production
of the heavy long-range bomber, had earlier limited the fleet to
21, all of which will be based at Whiteman Air Force Base near Knob
Noster, Mo. Total cost so far has been $44.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Updated manufacturing methods and other savings could drive down
the price of each bomber to $500 million or less, defense industry
officials said last week. And some hope that could lead to
reopening the B-2 production line in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The newest version of the current B-2 Spirit stealth bomber is
referred to as the ``Block 30.'' The new lower-cost plane would be
referred to as a ``Block 50'' or B-2X. Some industry observers call
it ``B-2 Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking into it, but we have not yet begun a formal
study,'' said Jim Hart, a spokesman for the plane's manufacturer,
Northrop Grumman Corp. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop said savings would result from enhanced and
computerized manufacturing methods. Some B-2 backers say builders
also would have to install lower-cost components, such as a cheaper
radar system, to achieve such significant savings.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force and Defense Department officials declined to comment
or did not respond to questions about whether a lower price would
prompt them to change their long-held perception that 21 B-2s were
enough. A recent Air Force study was based on assumptions that 184
bombers, including 21 B-2s, were sufficient to win ``two nearly
simultaneous major-theater wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ike Skelton, a Missouri Democrat who has spoken glowingly
of the plane and its performance in 30-hour Kosovo bombing missions
launched from Whiteman, was noncommittal about buying more planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see if we can afford it to begin with. Half a
billion dollars is a lot of money,'' Skelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton added that he was also a strong supporter of using
limited federal funds to build additional ``smart bombs,'' like
those dropped by the B-2 over Kosovo, only smaller. He said he also
was interested in reinstituting federal aid for the F-22 fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norman Dicks, a Washington state Democrat and longtime
backer of the B-2, ``would not in any way oppose'' more purchases
of the bomber, his spokesman said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The B-2 is partly made by Boeing Inc., based in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks' spokesman, George Behan, said trying to buy more B-2s
would not be a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does have a chance,'' he said, ``especially with the Air
Force and the president saying how capable these planes really
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Loren Thompson, a longtime B-2 backer and defense industry
analyst: ``Norm Dicks is a tenacious advocate. If he wants money
for a study of more B-2s, he will get it, because no one will care
as much as he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are willing to say it or not, Thompson said, the
Air Force wants more B-2 bombers if it can get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing is what they have to give up to get them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, however, anti-B-2 pressure in Congress is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mere half-billion dollars for more B-2s?'' Winslow Wheeler,
senior defense analyst for the Senate Budget Committee, asked
mockingly. ``That remains a totally outrageous cost for any
airplane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
