<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS START TRAINING CAMP TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For nearly three months Andy Murray has prepared
for this day, fine-tuning the highly organized theories that in
June convinced general manager Dave Taylor he was the right coach
to revive the moribund Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the start of training camp at the Iceoplex, the
theories _ and the players _ go onto the ice for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season begins in 27 days in Nashville. It ends 31
weeks from today in Anaheim. And if Murray is successful, the Kings
will continue playing beyond that April 9 visit to the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are hoping to advance to the playoffs for just the
second time in seven years, and they are looking to win a playoff
game for the first time since taking a 1-0 series lead over
Montreal in the 1993 Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's first training-camp move will be to start with three
days of practice, with no scrimmages scheduled until Wednesday
afternoon, when Team A (led by Ziggy Palffy and Luc Robitaille)
faces Team B (led by Donald Audette and Bryan Smolinski).
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes with a new coach, there's no time for him to put his
stamp on a team, and then you're into the exhibition games and
you're playing catch-up,'' said Murray, whose team begins
exhibition play Saturday against the Phoenix Coyotes at the MGM
Grand in Las Vegas. ``I want three solid practices before we
scrimmage to show them how hard we're going to work this year and
to give them a basis for tactical play.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a summer of change for the Kings, beginning with
Taylor's decision to replace Larry Robinson with Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he plans to carry 22 players when the season begins
(13 forwards, seven defensemen and two goalies), and Taylor has
spent the summer signing new players who either are likely to make
the team, or who at least have a decent chance.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's signing this week of 22-year-old defenseman Aki Berg
completed a busy summer of acquisitions. The additions of Palffy
and Smolinski were the flashiest, but the Kings also sought to add
depth.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for this season, Taylor added defensemen Jere
Karalahti and Frantisek Kaberle, centers Jason Blake and Len
Barrie, and Finnish forward Marko Tuomainen, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti, Kaberle, Blake and Tuomainen have little or no NHL
experience, so it is unrealistic to expect all of them to have an
immediate impact, though any or all could make the opening-night
roster. The new players, however, definitely should increase the
competition for jobs at training camp, especially with a number of
returning Kings coming off extremely disappointing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some positions up for grabs,'' Murray said.
``We know right now certain guys are going to make the team. But
some guys could play themselves onto the team, and some could play
themselves off it. The biggest factor in the equation is that the
Kings weren't very good last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
