A1248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      09-04 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT ANGELS, 9-6  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When Joe Torre arrived here early Saturday
morning, Bernie Williams already was in the trainer's room, shirt
off, his left shoulder under treatment, and Torre knew the news was
not going to be good.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was out of the starting lineup Saturday and may miss
more games on this road trip. Although Williams and Torre are
certain the Yankees' center fielder will play in the post-season,
his left shoulder _ his nonthrowing shoulder _ is gradually feeling
worse, weakening. ``This is just something I have to get through,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He contributed a pinch-hit single Saturday, in the midst of the
Yankees' ninth-inning rally. They blew a 6-3 lead over Anaheim in
the seventh inning, but Ricky Ledee smacked a two-run triple in the
ninth off the Angels' Troy Percival to break the tie. Williams
added a run-scoring single as the Yankees won, 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (83-52) reduced their number for clinching the
American League East to 19, and in that sense, this was just
another victory in their methodical journey through the regular
season. But when Don Zimmer, the Yankee bench coach, retires and
entertains friends with his megabyte memory, he will recall bizarre
episodes from Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led by three runs in the seventh inning; Hideki
Irabu was pitching effectively, finishing off hitters with the best
split-fingered fastball he had had in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There had been a strange moment in the first inning. With a
runner at first, catcher Jorge Posada returned a ball to Irabu
after Irabu had thrown a pitch and it went maybe a foot over
Irabu's head; it sailed into center field, and Darin Erstad took
second. ``I jumped for it, but I can only jump that high,'' said
Irabu, holding his forefinger and thumb about two inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu faded in the seventh, however, two walks quickly leading
to a pitching change and three game-tying runs. The rally was
capped by Mo Vaughn's two-run double off Mike Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had a chance to move ahead in the eighth when the
Angels' Jeff Huson singled off Allen Watson with one out and stole
second. Seeing Huson edging off second, Watson rapidly stepped off
the mound and turned to throw. He tried stopping when he thought
Chuck Knoblauch was not looking at him, but lofted the ball into
short center field, a soft throw to nobody. ``It was a screen
pass,'' Torre joked later. ``He had somebody in the flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Huson charged for third base while Ledee, playing center field
in Williams' absence, sprinted in to recover Watson's throw. He
heard the Edison Field crowd roaring and assumed that Larry Bowa,
Anaheim's third-base coach, was waving Huson home. He grabbed the
ball and instinctively hurled it homeward, without eyeing his
target.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting at the plate, Posada could see that Bowa was windmilling
his arm, and Huson, who represented the go-ahead run, was running
home. Ledee's throw bounced in front of home plate; Posada caught
and held the ball as Huson knocked him over. Out. Zimmer turned to
a fan behind the Yankees' dugout and said, ``We worked on that in
spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez walked to lead off the ninth against Juan Alvarez.
Chili Davis was waiting in the on-deck circle to pinch-hit for
Darryl Strawberry, but before Davis was officially inserted, Joe
Maddon, Anaheim's interim manager, called for Percival, a mistake
in timing. Strawberry batted instead and drew a walk, and Clay
Bellinger pinch-ran for Martinez at second. Nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Sheets, the Anaheim shortstop, then broke in behind
Bellinger on the pitch to cover second as part of the bunt defense.
Angels catcher Matt Walbeck burst from his crouch and threw to
second, and without hesitating, Bellinger sprinted for third and
was safe with a slide. If he had been thrown out, he admitted
later, Torre would have chewed him out.
</P>
<P>
   Posada popped out. Ledee was next, straining to see Percival's
dynamic fastball. In the shadows, he said later, it appeared as if
Percival was throwing 200 miles an hour. But Ledee fought back from
a two-strike count and ripped a triple off the right-field wall,
driving in two runs. Williams pinch-hit and singled through the
middle. ``Go figure,'' Williams said later, laughing at the
craziness of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He may play Monday. Or he may not. Williams, the switch-hitter
whose right-handed prowess has been the counterweight to the
left-handed batters in the middle of the Yankees' lineup, is
hurting _ the pain will wake him at night, he said _ and his
shoulder is affecting his hitting. ``It's definitely affecting my
swing,'' said Williams, before elaborating on how his approach at
the plate has been poor lately.
</P>
<P>
   Williams feels that in some ways the pain has forced him to
focus better at the plate. But the weakness in his shoulder is
evident in his production: Williams has just two doubles in his
last 27 games and just one home run in his last 20 games. He is
getting his hits, just not many extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who initially hurt his shoulder diving for a ball in
June, has been examined repeatedly and treated with
anti-inflammatory medication that has eased his pain. He will
probably be examined again in the off season, and he could undergo
surgery at that time, to explore possible rotator-cuff problems.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, he will try resting his shoulder and reducing
his batting practice, saving his swings for when they are needed.
Williams' .343 average ranks third in the league, and in the
context of the Yankees' deep and patient lineup, they do not
require home runs from him. They just need him to continue getting
on base, with singles and walks, if need be, through October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make it through,'' Torre said. ``It's just a matter of
how much he can endure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
