<P>
   &QL; 
UPSCALE _ Wal-Mart is installing cappuccino bars. Oprah is hawking
haute literature. TV is fine, but Bose home theater is very much
the dream screen. For the first time in American economic history,
there is what cultural analyst David Frum has dubbed a ``mass upper
class,'' and popular taste is leaning toward the ritzy, glitzy and
generally costly. By JAIMEE ROSE. Story will move in the ``L''
category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
