<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT ROCKIES, 4-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a Bart Simpson doll hanging in the locker of
Edgardo Alfonzo, incongruous decoration for one of the most polite
men on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, Alfonzo has been a Bart-like pest to pitchers, who
seem to be, unwittingly, adorned with a ``Kick Me'' sign when
Alfonzo comes to the plate. Saturday night's victim was Colorado's
Brian Bohanon. Alfonzo drove him to distraction, launching a
two-run home run in the fifth inning that gave the steely and
superb Al Leiter a lead he would not relinquish in pitching eight
and two-thirds innings for the 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Atlanta's loss to Arizona, the Mets picked up a
game in the National League East to trail the Braves by three and a
half games. The Mets remain four ahead of the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's home run _ his 24th of the season _ gave the Mets a
3-2 lead in the fifth and Robin Ventura's 30th homer of the season
in the bottom of the eighth gave Leiter the comfort run he needed.
After Leiter allowed two two-out singles, the hard-throwing Armando
Benitez, pitching upwards of 94 miles an hour, struck out Terry
Shumpert on three pitches to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter and Bohanon were like two beginning dance students for
much of the night, holding the other at arm's length, tiptoeing
gently to avoid a pratfall. Leiter, at first, seemed more unsteady
on his feet. He gave up a single to the first batter he faced,
Neifi Perez, who later came around to score on Kurt Abbott's
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies had another opportunity to score in the third inning
when Bohanon hit a leadoff double. After getting the next two
batters to fly out, Abbott sent a grounder into shallow center
field. Charging to the ball, Shawon Dunston threw so hard to home
that he fell face first to the ground. But the ball made it to home
on one hop, and Mike Piazza grabbed it as he blocked home plate
with his left shin. The husky Bohanon came lumbering toward the
plate but Piazza's leg held and Leiter escaped.
</P>
<P>
   When he was on the mound, Bohanon seemed to be tap-dancing,
nibbling away at batters, using a fastball that was clocked at 85
miles an hour with one pitch only to follow it with a changeup at
65.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the first 10 batters he faced were retired on
groundouts, and he allowed only four hits in the first six innings.
But in the fourth inning, Bohanon slipped just slightly. He walked
Alfonzo to start the inning, then hit John Olerud just above the
right elbow. He threw a hanging first pitch up to Piazza, but
Piazza just missed hitting a home run and had to settle for a
warning-track out that sent Alfonzo to third. Ventura's first-pitch
single to right scored Alfonzo to tie the score at 1-1, but the
Mets, despite having only one out, could score no more in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies then rallied after Leiter struck out the first two
batters in the fifth inning. Then Terry Shumpert stretched what
looked like a simple bloop into short left center into a double and
he came around to score when Vinny Castilla roped a single to left
to tie the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   In his last outing against Arizona, Leiter had struggled with
his control for the entire six and a third innings he lasted,
giving up seven hits and walking six while allowing six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Leiter allowed more hits _ there were nine by the
end of the seventh _ but there were just two walks and Leiter
seemed to get stronger as he went along, challenging the batters he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the side in the sixth and, after allowing a leadoff
single to Bohanon in the seventh, induced the next eight batters to
fly out or pop out. But with two out in the ninth, Leiter allowed a
pinch hit single to Larry Walker and another single to Neifi Perez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
