<SLUG> BC-CAR-STREET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST DRIVERS HOPE TO STAY ON COURSE IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Greg Pursley sat on the pole for the NASCAR
Featherlite Southwest Series race in last year's Ford L.A. Street
Race, but that accomplishment is now little more than a happy
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course is entirely different,'' Pursley said Saturday.
``The fact that I won the pole last year was pretty cool, but it
really isn't going to help me at all this time around.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two drivers will have to contend with the new course in
Monday's race, the featured event in the three-day L.A. Street Race
at Exposition Park. Saturday was practice day for drivers in the
three other divisions, the American IndyCars, the Ultra Wheel SPEC
trucks and the PRO racing series, and most Southwest Series drivers
won't get their first look at the track until this morning's
practice and 1:15 p.m. qualifying runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That course is really tight,'' said Pursley, who tested in a
SPEC truck Saturday to get a feel for the course. ``Passing is
going to be really difficult, and you're just going to have to pick
your spots. I'm just going to try to drive smart and stay out of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The new course features two hairpin turns just before the
start-finish line to the south of the Sports Arena. The 1-mile
track has eight turns total, leaving drivers few opportunities to
get up to speed before making passing attempts in the straightaways
during the 125-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's track had a lot more straightaways, so I'm sure
the speeds will be a lot slower this year,'' said Nick Joanides of
Woodland Hills, one of the top candidates for Rookie of the Year on
the Southwest Series. ``But since it's a brand new track, everybody
will be on equal ground. Nobody will have an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes Pursley, who led part of the race last season but
crashed late, giving the victory to Steve Portenga. Pursley says
patience on the track will be most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is very green, very slick, because it doesn't have
any rubber down on it now. But it will once cars practice more and
run more laps,'' Pursley said. ``Winning the pole is going to be
big, because if you get out ahead and run good, it's going to be
hard for anybody to get past you.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no clear-cut favorite to win today's pole or Monday's
race. The series' 12 races this season have been won by 11
different drivers. The points leader, Kurt Busch, is the only
driver to win twice this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great series, very competitive,'' Joanides said.
``Out of the 20 drivers who are out here regularly, 15 of them
always have a shot at winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
