<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MU-GAME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MU GRINDS OUT VICTORY OVER UAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE DeARMOND  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ When all the
laughter threatened to turn to sorrow, Missouri did what Missouri
has done best since rediscovering the game of winning football. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Just shoving it down their throats,'' said quarterback Kirk
Farmer, who capped an 80-yard, 12-play drive that featured 10
rushes by tailback DeVaughn Black with a 12-yard scoring pass to
fullback Joe Chirumbolo with 2 minutes, 12 seconds to play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Alabama-Birmingham roared back, going 80 yards in two
shots to the gut of Missouri's defense. But that late touchdown,
with 98 seconds to play, only made it close. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri won its 1999 season opener 31-28 on Saturday because
the Tigers _ who threw a little, played a little defense, blocked a
punt for a touchdown and saw two of its own punts blocked for
touchdowns _ ran and ran and ran some more when it counted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up just 24-21 with 7:57 to play, Missouri set up shop at its 20.
Ten times Farmer turned and put the ball in the gut of his
tailback. And in those 10 carries Black gained 69 of his 140
rushing yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the ninth straight run by Black, a 4-yard dive play that
gave MU a first down at the UAB 16, the Blazers called a timeout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie,'' Black said, grateful for the brief
rest. ``I was tired.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next play, Black ripped off left tackle for 7 more yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Farmer was dumped for a 3-yard loss trying to get out on the
option on the next play, leaving Missouri with a third and 6 from
the UAB 12. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Farmer _ a redshirt freshman who played the
entire second half because of starter Jim Dougherty's dinged-up
knee _ rolled left and hit Chirumbolo, a freshman fullback, with
the first TD reception of Chirumbolo's career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Missouri's defense let down at that point. UAB running
back Percy Coleman took the first handoff from scrimmage after the
MU kickoff and roared 69 yards on a draw play from his 20 to the MU
11. On the next play, tailback Carl Fair ripped through three
would-be tackles and into the end zone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That pulled UAB within the final score. But the Blazer's onside
kick then sailed out of bounds at the UAB 44. And quite naturally,
MU killed the clock on two more runs for a combined 20 yards by
Black and two kneel downs by Farmer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Black, playing in the shadow of All-American Devin West a year
ago, rushed for just 115 yards all last season. But center Rob
Riti, who once blocked for Black at Hazelwood West High, didn't see
Black's big game as the emergence of an unknown quantity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Missouri football,'' Riti said of an offensive strategy
that produced 245 yards in 56 rushes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done that a dozen times since I've been here. You need
to do it in key moments in certain games.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the path MU followed to victory last December in the
Insight.com Bowl, when West gained 46 yards on a critical late-game
drive that put away West Virginia in a 34-31 MU triumph. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly a key, critical moment,'' Riti said of the
Black-driven drive on Saturday in front of 50,356 at Faurot Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line and wide receivers and tight ends had to
block. The quarterback had to hand the ball off. And the running
back had to run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a system here. It's not like the tailbacks are
dramatically different personalities from year to year. They're all
coached to be north and south runners, to be powerful runners. And
I think that's what we had here today.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, certainly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brad Hammerich's 40-yard field goal and Justin Smith's punt
block and John McPherson's 9-yard return put Missouri up 10-0
midway through the first quarter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But UAB's Chris Brown returned the favor with a 16-yard scoring
return off a block of a Jared Gilpin punt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farmer hit Dwayne Blakley with a 4-yard scoring pass, putting MU
up 17-7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman answered with a 15-yard run that capped an 11-play,
73-yard drive in which UAB used screen passes and draw plays to
take advantage of MU's defensive aggressiveness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zain Gilmore made it 24-14 with a 1-yard plunge. But Adrian
Abrams returned the second UAB punt block 18 yards, pulling UAB
within 24-21. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys think you get 10 points ahead and the other guy is
going to fold,'' MU coach Larry Smith said. ``They didn't.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
