<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; kan-z
r s BC-SENIOR-GOLF-KAN &LR;      09-04 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-GOLF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR PGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD RICHMAN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed Dougherty leads the TD Waterhouse Championship, but nothing
more than a smattering of spectators stayed around to see him
finish Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two inches of rain, accompanied by lightning, soaked Tiffany
Greens Golf Club, causing a delay that lasted 4 hours, 3 minutes.
The majority of the announced crowd of 31,271 was long gone by the
time Dougherty completed his round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty shot 6-under-par 30 on the front side on his way to a
6-under 66 and a two-round total of 12-under 132. He led Gil Morgan
and Allen Doyle by 1 stroke entering today's final round. Forty-two
players broke par Saturday. That's two fewer than in the first
round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the good news for those who held on to their ticket stubs
and want to see the final 18: They can bring them back today and
enter for free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the severity of the storms and the parking problems we
had getting people out of the lot, we'll make this exception,''
said tournament director Jerald Andrews, who also noted refunds
won't be given. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several vehicles got stuck as they tried to exit the grass
fields that are being used for parking. Even one of the wreckers
that was brought in to pull cars out of the mess got stuck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The entire ESPN telecast was canceled because the delay began 18
minutes before the cable network was scheduled to begin its 90
minutes of coverage. That was a downer for TD Waterhouse executive
vice president Randy Miller. TD Waterhouse is making its first
major pitch nationally to a sports audience, and losing an entire
telecast hurt its momentum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Miller said, ``but that's the chance you
take with an outdoor event. All in all, though, this has helped our
name. We're delighted. We just hope it doesn't rain (today).'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unless you were one of the brave few who endured the delay,
here's what you missed: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morgan eagled the par-5 11th and moved to just 1 stroke behind
Dougherty when play was interrupted. But Morgan bogeyed No. 13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graham Marsh was within 4 strokes of Dougherty until he
triple-bogeyed the par-3 15th. That was his first hole after the
delay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it in the water,'' said Marsh, whose only PGA Tour
victory came in 1977 when he edged Tom Watson by 1 stroke at the
Heritage Classic. ``You try to stay loose physically during a
delay, and a lot of guys got a massage, and I got that. Sometimes
the delay hurts you, like it did to me today.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Mahaffey eagled the par-4 18th from 182 yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a 4-iron as high as I could. It hit right in front of
the pin and rolled in,'' said Mahaffey, who shot 72 and was at
4-under 140. ``I had to hit it high to make it land soft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of going south. This brings things into a little
better perspective.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty was on No. 11 when the delay hit. He played the
remainder of the round 1-over and sounded thrilled to get done
without any more damage. He bogeyed No. 18 after he popped up his
tee shot, then hit his second shot from 220 yards into a
collection-area pin high left of the green. He had to take a drop
and eventually missed an 8-footer for par. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard seeing the ball. I have a hard time with depth
perception,'' Dougherty said. ``I wish the rain had never come
because I was on a roll.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Dougherty birdied Nos. 3, 4, 5 and 6. On the 210-yard,
par-3 No. 6, he hit a 6-iron shot to 20 feet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty, who made his senior tour debut here a year ago, has
fond memories of Kansas City because of that. But he's not
completely happy with the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mad at the Chiefs because Rich Gannon is my cousin,''
Dougherty said, referring to the former Chiefs quarterback now with
Oakland. ``So I'm not a Chiefs fan anymore.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty likes the spot he's in starting today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be where I'm at,'' he said. ``Let it rain. I just
want to play good golf.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
