r s BC-POSNANSKI-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSNANSKI-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE EARLY AND OFTEN FOR BRETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ OK, folks, we've all worked too hard to let
this happen. Let's face it, we've named half the town after George
Brett. George Brett Bridge. George Brett Highway. George Brett
International Airport. Bonner George. Excelsior Brett. On Thursday,
I went to a local Brettbuster to rent a movie, passing Westgeorge,
the Pine Tar Liberty Memorial, and The Number Five Plaza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all summer long, we've gone way overboard for George _ even
George is sick of himself _ and yet now we're all about to sit
back, relax and let Brooks Robinson get named to the major-league
baseball All-Century Team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yep, they are taking two third basemen to the team. Mike
Schimidt is a lock. And right now, Robinson leads Brett by more
than 50,000 votes for second place. The deadline approaches. This
is ridiculous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's not a knock on Brooks Robinson. He was a great player. A
brilliant defensive third baseman. A clutch hitter. A class act. I
would have voted him first ballot into the Hall of Fame. I wish the
guy was my uncle. I might name my first son after him. But I'm
going to tell you right now there is no way on George Toma's green
earth that Brooks Robinson was a better third baseman than George
Brett. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These All-Century teams are ridiculous, of course. There's no
reasonable way to judge whether Greg Maddux is better than Carl
Hubbell, no legitimate way to tell if Wee Willie Keeler was a
better hitter than Not So Wee Tony Gwynn or if Three Finger Brown
would be able to strike out Luis Aparicio. Times change, people
change, the game changes. In the end, the whole thing is a lot like
arguing who is stronger, Superman or Tarzan (by the way, Superman
is stronger). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this Brett-Robinson thing is easy to figure out. They
played, more or less, in the same era. They played about the same
number of games _ Robinson played 189 more games than Brett, a
little more than one full season. They both played for winning
teams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And it's no contest. Robinson was a better defensive third
baseman than Brett, we'll give you that. The guy won 16 Gold
Gloves. Robinson had the knack of playing his best defense when the
cameras were on _ everyone remembers that he was sensational in the
1970 World Series _ but day-in, day-out, he was tough, dependable,
he charged bunts well and he often made great plays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fine. You can have that. Truth is, though, Brett was a pretty
good defensive third baseman himself. His arm was erratic,
especially in his early years, but he also made more than his share
of great plays. And, as former Royals pitcher Al Fitzmorris said:
``He got to more balls than almost anyone else in the league,
including Brooks Robinson, because, you've got to remember, George
was an athlete.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hitting is no contest. Period. Brett has many, many more hits,
runs, doubles, triples, homers, RBIs and walks than Robinson. His
batting average is 38 points higher. His slugging percentage is 86
points higher. Hey, pay attention, this took actual research. He
struck out less, stole 173 more bases, and over his career hit
better in the clutch. Robinson had that glorious 1970 World Series
where he hit .429 and slugged two home runs, but Brett pounded the
ball in the postseason every year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See, this is the dirty little secret of Brooks Robinson; he
really wasn't much of a hitter. Offensively, Gary Gaetti was
better. Ken Boyer. Ron Cey. Tim Wallach. Robinson had one fine
year, 1964, where he hit .317 with 28 homers, 118 RBI and won the
Most Valuable Player award. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, his average year was: .264, 13 homers, 69 RBI. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would somebody please take this calculator away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The point is, there's no way he should be knocking George Brett
off the All-Century Team. Not a chance. And yet, there he is on
top, thanks to those loyal, intense, Camden-Yards loving,
crabcake-eating, ``Diner''-watching, Art-Modell-sheltering
Baltimore fans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Something has to be done. Go to the ballpark and vote. If not,
go on the Internet (www.majorleaguebaseball.com). This is an
emergency, people. If Brett doesn't make the team, we'll have to
name more stuff after him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your neighborhood might be next. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0249 </DOCNO>
