r s BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN     09-04 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN HAS SHOT AT 20 WITH SIX STARTS LEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Kevin Brown would have preferred to win his 20th game
during a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   But with six starts remaining he could reach 20 anyway,
especially after Brown limited the Chicago Cubs to two Jeff Reed
singles in Saturday's 6-0 Los Angeles Dodgers victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't have much meaning,'' said Brown, who now has
won seven straight decisions. ``It is much better when doing
something like that gets you to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who last won 20 in 1992 with Texas, has been to the
Series the past two seasons, with Florida and San Diego. But he
seldom has pitched better than this.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first shutout with the Dodgers and it came after
taking one into the ninth inning in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today he threw strikes on the first pitch,'' pitching coach
Claude Osteen said. ``That forces hitters to become more aggressive
and swing at pitches out of the strike zone. Earlier this year it
seemed like every batter was a 2-2 count. That hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in the first year of a seven-year, $105 million contract,
was flopped in the rotation Saturday to give him a better chance of
reaching 20. Some think it is a publicity stunt to make the
disappointing Dodgers look good after making a huge free-agent
signing.
</P>
<P>
   By flopping him from today's start, Brown will be able to pitch
every fifth day with his final start on the last day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Happens every year: Before the game, manager Davey Johnson met
with outfielder Devon White and later with the club to discuss
White's remarks that there is a communication problem between
players and the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who met with the players for 15 minutes, said he was
surprised that White, critical about his lack of playing time
during a 6-for-56 slump, would pop off.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added that the frustration of a disappointing season is
bound to bubble over at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had four managers since I've been here,'' Eric Karros
said. ``It is the job of the player to learn the manager's style.
That is the way it's always going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy hitters: With his fourth-inning homer, Karros reached 30
for the fourth time in his career. That tied him for third with Roy
Campanella and Mike Piazza on the all-time Dodgers list. Duke
Snider and Gil Hodges each did it six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can control your preparation and the way you react to
things,'' said Karros, who now has 94 RBI. ``You can't control the
results. I prepare myself and if I'm healthy I've proven I can be
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: White had two singles and a run Saturday.... An MRI
on Carlos Perez's right shin showed only a contusion. It is
uncertain when Perez, who was struck by a line drive at Triple-A
Albuqerque, will pitch again.... After hitting homers in the first
two games, Sammy Sosa went 0 for 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
