u a BC-FINANCIER-ARRESTED-1S     09-04 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIER-ARRESTED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE FINANCIER CAPTURED IN GERMANY AFTER LONG HUNT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new top; new details, rewriting throughout)   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin R. Frankel, the Connecticut money manager suspected of
defrauding insurance companies of hundreds of millions of dollars
before fleeing overseas, was captured in his hotel room in Germany
Saturday, federal law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   German police officers accompanied by an agent of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation entered Frankel's room at the Hotel Prem in
Hamburg and seized the fugitive financier and a female companion,
exactly four months after he fled his Connecticut mansion. They
also found a computer, documents and an undetermined quantity of
diamonds and cash, Michael J. Wolf, an FBI special agent, said
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got me,'' Frankel said when they entered the room,
according to Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Suspected of siphoning as much as $350 million from Southern
insurance companies, Frankel was charged with money laundering and
wire fraud. He is in custody in Germany awaiting extradition to the
United States, a process that could take several months even if
Frankel does not fight to avoid repatriation, Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   The German authorities also took into custody Cynthia Allison, a
35-year-old American citizen using the alias Susan Kelly. Friends
and associates of the suspect have said that Ms. Allison, who
worked as an office assistant for Frankel, flew to Italy to join
him on the run in late June. She has been detained for questioning
but has not been charged with any crime, Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   The capture ended what the FBI acknowledges was a long and at
times frustrating manhunt for Frankel, whose brazen and at times
bizarre activities captured headlines in the United States for
several months. In exile, Frankel, whom associates traveling with
him described as having no evident talent for international
intrigue, lived in apartments and hotels arranged by contacts in
Rome. He was accompanied by several female companions and at times
seemed to live large, dining in outdoor cafes and phoning friends
and business partners in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, just as the FBI felt it had come close to
tracking his whereabouts in Italy, Frankel disappeared. The law
enforcement agency followed numerous tips that put Frankel in
France and Brazil as well as Germany, but Wolf said Saturday that
the trail went cold for many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators' luck changed Saturday. Acting on a tip, the
authorities tracked him to Hamburg. A team of local and federal
German police officers found Frankel in his hotel room shortly
before 9 p.m. German time.
</P>
<P>
   Though the last tip proved good, the search was hampered by a
stream of misinformation, said Wolf, who spoke at a news conference
Saturday night in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We responded to various tips, and a lot of them were
fruitless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agent also lamented limited help from international law
enforcement authorities, though he praised German officials for
their efforts Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the trail went cold, and without the cooperation of other
law enforcement agencies, it's very difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's lawyer, Hugh F. Keefe, was unaware that his client had
been apprehended when he was reached for comment Saturday evening.
The Connecticut-based lawyer added that he had spoken to a federal
prosecutor in the case as recently as Saturday morning. ``He asked
me if Frankel was still alive,'' Keefe said. ``I have a feeling he
knew more than he was letting on.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have described the case as one of America's
largest and most bizarre incidents of insurance fraud.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For eight years, Frankel lived a sybaritic life on the money he
claimed to be managing for a string of Southern insurance
companies, federal law enforcement officials and prosecutors
charged.
</P>
<P>
   His operation grew to depend on scores of other people,
including prominent lawyers, insurance industry executives, private
detectives, a coterie of women, and priests with ties to the
Vatican, all of whom say that they were innocent dupes of a man
that they thought was a brilliant speculator in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   If official accounts are accurate, Frankel, 44, also had
remarkable success in fooling state insurance regulators. His
strategy was to buy small, troubled insurance companies through
intermediaries, then manage the sometimes considerable investment
assets those companies held against future policy claims.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Frankel claimed to be earning returns that were well
above industry norms, but he was not exposed as a fraud until after
he fled the country, leaving behind smoldering documents in one of
his several houses in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Toledo, Ohio, Frankel first ran afoul of financial
regulators in the early 1990s, when a small investment fund he ran
generated steep losses for retirees who entrusted their savings to
Frankel. After an investigation, the Securities and Exchange
Commission reached an out-of-court settlement with him in early
1992. He agreed to a lifetime ban from the securities business.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that agreement was final, however, Frankel had begun
a new operation in Tennessee. Using the names of several friends
and acquaintances in Ohio, Frankel set up a Tennessee trust and
began buying insurance companies, first in Tennessee and later in
Mississippi, Missouri, Arkansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   He also moved his base of operations to Greenwich. He rented and
later bought a multimillion-dollar, four-acre estate on Lake
Avenue, surrounding the area with elaborate security. He later
rented other upscale homes in the area, using one as his office and
another to house some of the women he recruited through the
Internet and help-wanted ads as personal assistants and full-time
companions.
</P>
<P>
   By early 1998, Frankel began to fear that insurance regulators
would sooner or later catch on, he told friends and associates. It
was then that he apparently decided to rapidly expand his insurance
holdings in hope of growing big enough and involving enough
well-known people that the authorities would consider his business
unassailable.
</P>
<P>
   He hired many insurance consultants and retained several
prominent law firms, including Robert Strauss and his well-known
firm, Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld. Frankel persuaded a
high-level retired priest at the Vatican to back a charity that
Frankel used as a holding company for his insurance assets.
</P>
<P>
   The gangly and unkempt Frankel persuaded people that he was a
genius in stock picking. He had walls of computers and trading
equipment installed in his home, though associates say he rarely
executed trades.
</P>
<P>
   By spring of this year, insurance regulators were asking pointed
questions. By late April, Frankel prepared to flee the country.
Like his operation, his flight to safety abroad was highly
disorganized. A last-minute purchase of diamonds turned into a
fiasco when Frankel decided to leave early and security officers
fought over control of some diamonds that remained behind.
</P>
<P>
   While he eluded a dragnet, the authorities were gradually
confiscating assets he stashed in numerous bank accounts, forcing
him to live on valuables and cash that he carried on his person.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were limiting assets in various accounts and following
leads, I think that we expected sooner or later that he would be
apprehended,'' Wolf said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
