<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN MAKES BIG STOP AT THE BIG HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Tommy Hendricks gets asked about it when he
returns home to Houston. People want to know how it feels to play
for Michigan against Notre Dame in Michigan Stadium, with an
NCAA-record crowd of 111,523 making The Big House a crowded house.
``It's hard to put into words,'' said Hendricks, a senior safety
who had a team-high 10 tackles and an interception for the
Wolverines. ``It's a game that you put all your emotion and effort
into. It's one of the biggest rivalries in college football. We
both left it all out there on the field.'' It's hard to describe it
even when you make the big tackle that seals the victory. Hendricks
stuffed Notre Dame receiver Raki Nelson a yard short of a
game-extending first down that sealed No. 7 Michigan's 26-22
victory against the 16th-ranked Fighting Irish. This is a
blue-blooded rivalry. Michigan has the most Division I-A victories;
Notre Dame is tops in best winning percentage. Even though most of
America might hate both teams equally, this is a game the nation
watches. It's rarely disappointing. Seven of the past 10 games have
been decided by five or fewer points. Three of the past four games
have been decided in the final two minutes. Not that it was
necessary, but the pregame fires were stoked by Michigan coach
Lloyd Carr. He was angry that Notre Dame scheduled Kansas in the
Eddie Robinson Classic last week. That, Carr said, gave the Irish
the advantage of five to six more days of practice. ``You want to
call me a whiner, good,'' Carr said. ``Call me anything you want.''
But it was Notre Dame that played like it was opening the season.
The Irish lost three fumbles and committed 10 penalties for 81
yards. A celebration penalty on Notre Dame's Bobby Brown after a
two-point conversion that put the Irish ahead 22-19 gave Michigan
good field position. And a late-hit penalty on the Wolverines'
second play moved the ball to the Notre Dame 28. ``We didn't play
smart,'' Notre Dame coach Bob Davie said.''You don't come up here
and beat Michigan with silly mistakes.'' Michigan's Anthony Thomas
scored on a 1-yard touchdown run with 1:38 remaining for the
winning points. The 225-pound Thomas ran through 233-pound Anthony
Denman to nudge the ball over the goal line. Thomas, who carried a
career-high 32 times, did not meet with the media. He was in the
training room with an IV stuck in his arm. ``That game took its
toll on a lot of guys,'' Carr said. ``That's the hardest-hitting
game I've ever been involved in.'' Notre Dame quarterback Jarious
Jackson, who passed for 302 yards, tried to pull a Joe Montana. The
Irish drive ended with his pass to Nelson, who gained 19 of the 20
yards needed for a first down that would have stopped the clock and
let Notre Dame try one more play. ``The most disappointing thing is
seeing the clock wind down, knowing we were about to score,'' said
Jackson, who was 18-of-29 and was sacked four times. Michigan,
which started defense of its 1997 national championship with a
half-hearted second-half effort in a 36-20 loss to the Irish last
year, had a sweet season-opening victory. The Wolverines defenders
wanted the chance to win the game. ``We kept 'em out. That's all
that matters. It's real emotional, man,'' Hendricks said, minutes
after his hit had won the game. ``I knew it would come down to the
last play. It always does.'' Notre Dame's Brown, a senior whose
bunny ears celebation signal had turned into goat horns, was
face-down flat on the ground. Michigan's Grady Brooks and DeWayne
Patmon were prostrate. Hendricks was on his knees, sobbing. Just a
glance at the postgame carnage and you wondered who had won.
Michigan linebacker Dhani Jones celebrated the game by screaming
and jumping like a little kid and screaming like a baby _ his
words. ``I was just letting my body vent its emotions,'' Jones
said. ``You had to interpret what I was feeling by looking at me.
But that's what the feeling is like, like being on the playground.
Today's game was like a soap opera, big plays, back and forth,
mistakes. ``This is a game you're going to tell everybody about
when you're old and gray and slow. There are some things in life
where the only way you'll feel the entire emotion of it is to be
involved in it.''
\Nsubheds:Extra points The announced attendance of 111,523 at
Michigan Stadium broke the NCAA single-game record of 111,238 set
at last year's Michigan State-Michigan game. ... These teams take a
break in their series for two years; they'll play again in 2002.
Notre Dame opens with Texas A&AMP;M and Nebraska in South Bend next
season. ... Michigan running back Anthony Thompson finished with
142 yards; Michigan rushed for 124. In his last three games, he has
nine touchdowns. ... Notre Dame's first touchdown was scored by
junior flanker Joey Getherall on a reverse. It was his first points
for the Irish. ... Michigan's Jeff Del Verne, a former walk-on,
converted four of five field-goal attempts. ... Michigan had eight
drives that penetrated the Notre Dame 35, but only converted two
drives into touchdowns. ... Sophomore David Terrell, who committed
to Notre Dame before signing with Michigan, led the Wolverines with
eight receptions for 115 yards. ... Notre Dame has lost its first
road game each of its three seasons under coach Bob Davie.
</P>
</TEXT>
