<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HAVE MADE CHANGES, BUT ARE THEY GOOD ONES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ignore the sobs. It's just Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, still
shedding tears.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that persistent whine, please observe a moment of
silence in honor of Pat Verbeek and Dave Reid and Craig Ludwig. Win
a war, lose some good soldiers. Life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, a short and sweet off-season ends for the Dallas
Stars. The summer-long kissing of Stanley Cup silver gives way to
the first training camp practice in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only last week when Brett Hull stuck both a toe in
the crease and the puck past ... .
</P>
<P>
   Well, you know all about the endless local celebration. And the
river of tears from the Buffalosers.
</P>
<P>
   But with this ultimate NHL success, what came next for the Stars
was change. And because change followed success, that leads to
questions for this new season.
</P>
<P>
   Did general manager Bob Gainey tinker too much? Or did owner Tom
Hicks go totally out of character and suggest budget trimming to
his GM?
</P>
<P>
   On the team depth-chart, the Stars will be only somewhat
different from the championship class. It is a younger, faster and,
yes, financially-cheaper club that coach Ken Hitchcock calls to
order today in Vail.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen on the ice is one thing. But without the
veteran locker-room presence of a Verbeek, a Reid, and particularly
a Ludwig, how are the tough and turbulent times dealt with
internally?
</P>
<P>
   Gainey doesn't claim to have definite answers. ``Any of those
players who are no longer with us, there will come a time this
season when all of us will be talking about how we miss them,'' he
said Friday, preparing to depart for Vail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a risk or gamble in the decisions we made,''
Gainey added, ``then the reward has to be in keeping the nucleus of
a championship caliber team together for a long period of time. In
the league's financial climate, that is the challenge for
management. You've got to beat the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey noted that Hicks didn't stress with him the necessity for
budget cuts, ``although costs were obviously discussed,'' he said.
Plus, it's not like the Stars will be dealing with a reduced
payroll for 1999-2000. The $3 million of Verbeek salary, for
instance, will be absorbed in contractual raises due other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the issues Bob faced in putting the team together were
budgetary,'' said Hicks. ``But it was also his desire to go with
fresh blood _ that means a cheaper player, of course. But it does
keep the resources flowing for the bigger stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the off-season moves, the one most haunting to the Stars
_ both now and for an expected eternity _ is the giveaway of backup
goalie Roman Turek. The St. Louis Blues stole Turek for a
third-round draft pick because the Stars were caught in an
expansion-draft deadline 24 hours after the Stanley Cup Finals had
ended. Worst still, the Blues are in the same conference.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Gainey carefully charted his off-season course, and
stuck to it. Asked Friday what would happen if the still-unsigned
Verbeek would agree to a $1 million Stars' contract for this
season, Gainey had a ready answer. ``We would go ahead with the
plans that were put in place, and the decisions that were made,''
he said. In other words, no deal.
</P>
<P>
   Compare Gainey's approach, however, with the
season-after-a-championship-season strategy of Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones. Hindsight now has Jones being criticized heavily for
sticking too long with his veteran cast. The Cowboys had a true
dynasty going in the NFL, but when the end came, and high-priced
veterans were liabilities, the thud was loud.
</P>
<P>
   One Stanley Cup doesn't make the Stars an NHL dynasty, but it's
a team that has had the league's best regular-season record two
consecutive seasons, and the second-best record three seasons ago.
It could be a dynasty in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought is that younger guys trying to elbow their way into
the mix, along with the increased speed factor, enhances our
team,'' said Gainey. ``How it all works out, remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Reaugh was once an Edmonton prospect, although he's more
famous now as a Stars broadcaster than his days of backup
goaltending with the Oilers. This was a franchise, however, that
was winning four Stanley Cups in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Edmonton theory was no matter what, change out 15 percent
of the team for each season,'' said Reaugh. ``And that was an era
when it was very easy to keep a team together forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Change has come to the Stars. With change comes questions. But
first comes training camp, starting today in Vail.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
