<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CUBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN, KARROS LIFT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Does playing well when you're playing out the string
do more harm than good?
</P>
<P>
   For the Los Angeles Dodgers, it's a question that goes well
beyond Kevin Brown, who pitched a brilliant two-hit, 6-0 shutout
against the Chicago Cubs on Saturday in front of 39,048 at Wrigley
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is having a Brown-like season, winning his seventh
straight and 16th overall. He has six more starts to reach 20.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't about Eric Karros, whose fourth-inning home run
marked the fourth time in his career he has reached 30 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Those guys always seem to hit their marks.
</P>
<P>
   It's others, such as Todd Hundley and Mark Grudzielanek, who
have played better in the second half of a lost season. Both hit
home runs Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers have now won 11 of 15, momentum remains
elusive. Five times in the second half they have won the first two
games of a series and lost the finale.
</P>
<P>
   This season is now about evaluating players for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Dodgers were mesmerized by Carlos Perez's four
straight complete games in September.
</P>
<P>
   Perez hasn't pitched well since signing a four-year,
$15.5million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both Grudzielanek and Hundley figure to be part of the Dodgers
next season. Karros, who may or may not be, said the two are part
of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are playing the way they are capable, not some
two-week thing,'' Karros said. ``People talk a lot about breaking
up this team in the winter. I think the best thing that could
happen is keep most of it intact. You don't want to go through that
transition again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley homered for a second straight day and now has 21 this
season. His average is just .223 and he still has trouble throwing
out runners behind the plate. But it was not a problem Saturday,
since Brown allowed just two singles _ both by catcher Jeff Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who raised his average to .321 with three more
hits, is convincing manager Davey Johnson that he might be a
capable No.2 hitter in an offense that has stumbled at the top of
the order.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek has hit safely in 11 straight games (.449, 22 for
49) and 21 of his past 22 (.371, 36 for 97). It is no coincidence
that No.3 Gary Sheffield has 22 RBI in his last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I feel I've been capable of all along,'' said
Grudzielanek, the former Expo who had 201 hits in 1994 and 54
doubles the next year. ``I think these games are important because
they can answer questions. How you perform when things aren't going
well can be harder than the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek also has committed just nine errors at short after
making 92 in his previous three seasons. But it's his improved
offense that will earn him a sizeable raise from this year's
$1.9million salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has such great hand-eye coordination,'' Johnson said. ``He
might never be as patient as you'd like, but right now he is as hot
as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Hundley, who always has hit well in Wrigley Field. His
home run off Kyle Farnsworth (3-8), who defeated the Dodgers last
Sunday, was his 10th in his adopted home. His father Randy played
10 years with the Cubs and is now a part-time broadcaster with the
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been an easy season by any means,'' said Hundley,
who is still recovering from reconstructive elbow surgery that was
performed two years ago. ``But I think we are building something
here for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Others agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what he has done and he has only played half a
season,'' said Raul Mondesi, who also hit a home run. ``He is
getting better every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-04-99 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990904.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1282 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LA     09-04 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' BIG RALLY FALLS FLAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Even when things go well for the Anaheim
Angels, eventually they start to go bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied from a 5-0 deficit against the New York
Yankees, tying the game at 6 on Mo Vaughn's two-run double in the
seventh inning. But Ricky Ledee's two-run triple in the ninth off
Troy Percival broke the tie and sent the Angels to a 9-6 loss
before 30,589 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Percival began this season having never given up an earned run
to the Yankees in 181/3 innings. That streak ended earlier this
season when he gave up one run, but still he had four saves in four
appearances this year and a lifetime ERA of 0.40 (one run in 221/3
innings) against New York going into Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   But in a season such as this for the Angels, that trend was
bound to change. Percival was charged with two of the Yankees'
three ninth-inning runs. Juan Alvarez (0-1), who began the ninth by
walking Tino Martinez, got the loss.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter which team Percival is facing these days,
though. In his previous nine appearances, he was 1-2 with an 11.05
ERA, one save and four blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   His problems came to a head last week in Cleveland when the
Angels blew an eight-run lead to the Indians, and Percival was on
the mound for seven of the 10 runs the Indians scored in their
eight-inning comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really struggling with the ball running on me,'' he said.
``I try to throw the ball in and it comes back over the plate.... I
try to throw the ball down and away and it goes up and in. I'm four
feet off on some occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I have to fight through. Everybody comes to a
point in their career when you have problems, and you can either
fight or give in. I'm going to fight through it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game had twists and turns before Percival lost it. The
Angels trailed 5-0 in the second but battled back. Down 6-3 in the
seventh, Tim Salmon drove in one run with a single and Vaughn's
double scored two more to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Jeff Huson walked and stole second with one out.
And when Yankees reliever Alan Watson's pickoff attempt sailed into
center field, Huson headed to third. Third-base coach Larry Bowa
waved Huson home, but Ledee's throw from center nailed him at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Angels catcher Matt Walbeck had Yankees
pinch-runner Clayton Bellinger picked off second base. But
Bellinger was caught so far off the bag after a missed bunt attempt
that he broke for third and made it.
</P>
<P>
   Percival walked Darryl Strawberry, struck out Jorge Posada and
yielded Ledee's two-run triple. Bernie Williams followed with an
RBI single to make it 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our guy, he's our man,'' Angels interim manager Joe
Maddon said. ``Everyone in this game struggles at some point
regardless if you're a hitter or pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ramon Ortiz struggled in his fourth start, going
only four innings and giving up six runs and six hits. But Ortiz
said his problems Saturday had nothing to do with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was the Yankees, the only thing that hurt me
was my location of pitches,'' Ortiz said. ``The Yankees are the
Yankees but I didn't pitch the way I usually pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
