<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SIGNING-1STLD     09-04 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SIGNING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF ISRAEL, PALESTINIANS SIGN PEACE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to fix time element in 1st graf; rewriting throughout)   (Eds., this story now leads the paper; it replaces ALBRIGHT-SYRIA
on NYT Page 1, which goes inside.) 
 (HLW) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARM EL-SHEIKH, Egypt _ Surrounded by a panoply of Middle East
leaders and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of Israeli and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
signed a broad agreement early on Sunday that the Clinton
administration hopes will quickly usher in a new era of peace
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, held in a beach hotel aired by cool breezes from
the nearby Red Sea, represented an early victory for the apparently
growing trust between the Israeli and Palestinian leaders, and
crowned a busy day of diplomacy for Albright.
</P>
<P>
   On a closely watched trip on Saturday to Damascus to meet
President Hafez Assad of Syria, Albright won no immediate signal
that Israeli-Syrian peace talks can open soon. But an
administration official said the meeting nonetheless laid what he
termed an encouraging basis for future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Albright then became the first secretary of state in 16 years to
land in Beirut, Lebanon, on an official American government plane,
and held talks with Lebanese leaders on a previously unannounced
stop. Her aides said the negotiations were intended to underline
the administration's desire to include Lebanon in the search for
regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the principals necessary to achieving that tantalizing
goal were on hand for the late-night ceremony, essentially the
signing of a revision of an accord reached last year with the
previous Israeli government, but redolent with hope for a final
settlement. President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and King Abdullah of
Jordan applauded as Barak and Arafat, seated side by side on gilt
chairs, signed the latest agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli and the Palestinian, who do not know each other well
but appear to have forged a certain understanding since Barak took
office in July, sat before a backdrop of Egyptian, Israeli,
Jordanian, Palestinian and American flags symbolic of the shared
effort needed for regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we are paving the way toward the end of a century-old
conflict between us and the Palestinians,'' Barak said. ``I am
committed to Israel's security. I also want the Palestinians to
feel secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat referred to Barak as ``my new partner in the peace
process'' and pledged to carry out the accords swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Barak, 57, injected energy into a quest for
peace that had been on hold for much of three years and has now
resumed at a time of transition in the Middle East. Arafat is 70
and Assad is 68; both are in frail health. Barak is new to power
and comparatively young, while Abdullah, at 37, is taking over from
his late father, King Hussein, who made crucial contributions to
Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ceremony, which began late Saturday night and ended
early Sunday morning, Israeli, Palestinian and American officials
mingled and chatted easily with one another.
</P>
<P>
   At President Clinton's Camp David, Md., mountain retreat, where
the 1978 framework Middle East peace accords were signed, the
president said the breakthrough ``represents a wonderful
opportunity to move the peace process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement envisions the end of conflict between the
Palestinians and Israelis a year from now, with the emotional
issues of the boundaries of Israel and the Palestinian lands and
the disputed status of Jerusalem solved by then. Other longstanding
differences over the return of Palestinian refugees now scattered
through the Middle East and the use of water would also be resolved
under this bold strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In the shorter term, the agreement stipulates how to carry out a
land-for-security deal signed by the Israelis and Palestinians at
Wye River, Md., last fall.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Sept. 13, the Israelis will transfer 7 percent of
the West Bank from its total control to partial control for the
Palestinians. On Nov. 15, 5 percent more of the West Bank will be
transferred to the Palestinians. And on Jan. 20, a third transfer
should be completed, meaning that 40 percent of the West Bank will
then be under partial or full control of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The longer-term goal of a final-status agreement between the
Palestinians and the Israelis _ which Barak would like to see
concluded alongside talks with the Syrians _ is now the toughest
business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the ceremony, Albright noted that ``the obstacles
that permanent status negotiators will face are daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are tough, laden with emotion, and deeply rooted in
the region's troubled past,'' she added. ``They involve life and
death issues for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The final-status negotiations, due by mid-February, will help
determine Israel's size and its role in the Middle East. The new
agreement does not specifically mention the emergence of a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials have acknowledged that in essence the
final-status negotiations mean that the Israelis and Palestinians
will sit down for the first time to discuss the terms of that
possibility, and tackle such vital issues as contiguity of
Palestinian territory and ways of entering and leaving Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Feb. 15 date for a framework agreement was too
ambitious, a senior American official said: ``Maybe. But if you set
sights too low, you won't reach that. If you set sights high,
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the new agreement was finally stitched together boded
reasonably well for the broader negotiations, the American official
said. In the end, Arafat wanted some assurances on specific
concerns _ including that the final transfer of land would be
completed before the framework agreement was drawn up.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat reportedly had been concerned that Barak would not follow
through on his pledge to deliver the final segment of land if it
was not transferred before the framework agreement was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Going back over key moments in three days of shuttle diplomacy,
the official recalled that when Albright and other top American
officials arrived at Gaza City on Friday night, it was unclear
whether Arafat had signed off on the complete document. But Arafat
was relaxed when the Americans walked in and ``optimistic about the
future,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans placed a call to Barak from Arafat's office
for the two leaders to talk, Arafat opened the conversation with
the Israeli by saying, ``Shabat, Shalom,'' one of the Americans
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at the late-night ceremony was in a totally
celebratory mood. ``This marks moving from a frozen process to a
working process,'' said Nabil Shaath, one of the Palestinian
negotiators.``It promises a happy future, but it will be really
happy when it is implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said he was delighted that the United States was back in
the process of trying to agree on peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have been anxious to play down their role. One
official said that in contrast to the Wye document last fall and an
earlier agreement in 1997 dealing with Hebron, the Palestinians and
Israelis drafted and wrote this document themselves. The other two
had been drafted by the Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had made a dozen phone calls during the last few weeks
urging both sides on, the official said. And Dennis Ross, the
administration's senior Middle East negotiator, was on the phone
daily with them. But this was a qualitatively different role
compared to pushing the two sides together as was necessary under
the previous Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, the
American official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official cited as an indication of the trust built in recent
months what he said was a remark by Saeb Erekat, the senior
Palestinian negotiator. He quoted Erekat as saying he could now
understand, if not always agree with, the Israeli point of view.
``I am finally able to put myself in their shoes,'' Erekat was
quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
