<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-04 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1301 &Cx1f; kan-z
r s BC-WHITLOCK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-04 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITLOCK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM COLBERT STILL HAS LOTS TO OFFER KC AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JASON WHITLOCK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You talk to Jim Colbert long enough, and you get the feeling
he'd rather be playing football than golf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lightning struck the TD Waterhouse Championship at Tiffany
Greens Golf Club, causing a four-hour suspension of play. Colbert,
the former Bishop Miege High quarterback and Kansas State F.O.B.
(friend of Bill Snyder), went straight into the clubhouse and
caught up on the college football scores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the delay, Colbert was in the process of
scorching the course. He was 5 under par with two holes to play. He
was tied for seventh and positioning himself for a run today at the
leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With his 16-year-old grandson as his caddie, Colbert was playing
his best round of golf this season. He was throwing darts at the
flags. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have shot 30 on the front nine,'' Colbert said. ``I
missed an 8-foot and a 5-foot birdie putt.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what did Colbert want to talk about when he strolled into the
press tent? Football, of course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here,'' Colbert said waving me a little closer. ``What's
going to happen to the Chiefs? It looks to me like Warren Moon
should be the quarterback.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Grbac skeptic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, Colbert brought up the subject, so I went straight for his
purple jugular. How bad did Kansas State's loss to Texas A&AMP;M in the
Big 12 championship game hurt? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad. Real bad,'' Colbert said with a frown. ``I was shocked. I
spent the whole night with Snyder. It was a terrible, terrible
thing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Snyder asked for the score not to be announced,''
Colbert continued, referring to the score of the critical
UCLA-Miami contest that concluded in the middle of K-State's
eventual loss to the Aggies. ``If you watch the game _ before the
score was announced _ we were supposed to beat A&AMP;M 42-17.It started
with the guys calling the defensive plays. (Defensive coordinator
Mike) Stoops had never coached in a big game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colbert held court in the press tent for close to 30 minutes. He
told stories about Snyder's golf game. He said the Wildcats have a
300-pound Samoan defensive tackle who will destroy everybody. He
updated us on the progress of all the K-Staters on NFL rosters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chiefs need to play Kevin Lockett,'' Colbert said. ``He
only dropped two passes in five years at Kansas State.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd bet anything that Colbert would give up golf to coach the
Wildcats or the Chiefs. Well, maybe not. Life is good on the Senior
PGA Tour. Colbert has won more than $8 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He puts his money and celebrity to good use in this area. He's
building golf courses in Spring Hill, Kan., and Manhattan, Kan. And
beginning next year, ``Colbert Hills'' in Manhattan will be the
first national golf academy for the First Tee Program, which
promotes golf mostly among inner-city kids. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually 1,000 kids will come there each summer to learn
everything there is to learn about golf,'' Colbert said. ``I'm very
excited about this. I'm building a townhome right on the course, so
I can be there to help.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why Colbert is so popular around here. He keeps giving
back to this area. Whenever Colbert comes to Kansas City, Mo., you
can just about bet he'll be close to the top of the leader board.
The large, boisterous galleries inspire his play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here is my one weekend a year to be like Arnold
Palmer,'' said Colbert, a winner twice in Kansas City. ``If I'm in
contention, the fans cheer and kind of go crazy when I walk up
18.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, weather permitting, the fans will get an opportunity to
go crazy. Ed Dougherty is 13 under _ 7 strokes ahead of Colbert,
who bogeyed 18 after the weather delay and finished with a 68 for
the day and a 6-under 138 for the tournament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything within 10 strokes is reasonable,'' Colbert said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
